<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets     04-01 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices rallied after two days of consecutive
declines in Tokyo Saturday, boosted by favorable prospects for the
new trading week, traders said.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which lost 156.04 points Friday, gained 177.90
points, or 0.68 percent to end the week at 26,282.12.
   Participants appeared optimistic about the market situation next
week, although many of them sidestepped trading in the absence of
direction, said an official of a major securities firm in Tokyo,
who spoke on the condition of anonymity.
   He attributed the lackluster trading to the Easter weekend
holiday observed in other Asian markets.
   Share prices were mixed with the volume of trade in the first
section totaling 520 million shares during Saturday's half-day
session.
   Popular issues were major chemical, steel and metal. Automobiles
and machineries also rose. Department store, some construction and
foostuff shares lost ground, traders said.
   The Tokyo foreign stock exchange market is closed on Saturdays.
</TEXT>
