<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersStrike     04-01 0310</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contracts Sought By `Several Dozen' Production Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Production companies responsible for such
programs as Johnny Carson's ``Tonight Show'' have opened direct
talks with the striking scriptwriters' union rather than wait for
their own union to end the walkout.
   Several dozen production units formally notified the Writers
Guild they want to bargain, Guild spokeswoman Cheryl Rhoden said
Friday.
   Among those are Carson Productions and the Academy of Motion
Picture Arts and Sciences, which hopes to gain a few days of help
from the scriptwriters before the Oscar awards ceremony is
broadcast April 11.
   The Guild's 9,000 film and TV scriptwriters went on strike
against the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers on
March 7, seeking higher residuals and greater creative control.
   Some of the companies seeking a contract include members of the
alliance, Rhoden said.
   ``We are compelled by law to bargain with them if they notify us
that they want to,'' she said. ``These are companies which
represent some projects that need to move forward immediately, or
they could lose it.''
   Alliance spokesman Herb Steinberg said the talks were
potentially embarrassing for the writers. ``It will result in some
writers working, while others are still on the bricks,'' he said.
   Steinberg and Rhoden said that both sides are far apart and that
there is no immediate prospect of returning to the bargaining table.
   Meanwhile, representatives of the striking radio and TV
commercial actors belonging to the Screen Actors Guild and American
Federation of Television and Radio Artists prepared to talk with
negotiators representing advertisers.
   The two sides will meet under the auspices of a federal mediator
in New York on April 6.
   The actors went on strike March 21 seeking more compensation
from commercials shown on cable television and rejecting a
management bid to eliminate a cost-of-living clause from their
contract.
</TEXT>
