<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ShipRaising     04-01 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ship Raising,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historic Three-Master Raised from Murky Waters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salvage crews used three giant cranes to hoist a
114-foot sailing ship from the murky waters of Boston Harbor in a
delicate operation some feared could destroy the historic square
rigger.
   The 80-year-old barkentine Regina Maris was successfully
refloated on the second attempt Friday, 11 weeks after it sank at
dockside in 30 feet of water.
   ``The knot left everybody's stomach'' as the ship came up, said
David Kenny, field superintendent of Cashman Co., which raised the
ship.
   An early morning effort to lift the three-masted ship with
cables around its hull was halted out of concern that one of the
cables could damage it.
   ``With a ship this age and it being a wooden ship, we were
concerned that if it wasn't lifted uniformly ... we would pull one
of the lifting cables through the ship, so it was important that we
lifted it evenly,'' said Jim Frye, managing director of the
vessel's owners, Marina Bay of Quincy. ``It was a little dramatic,
to say the least.''
   Debris cluttered the deck and hung from the rigging, but the
Regina Maris was free of visible damage.
   The $50,000 operation to refloat the ship took six weeks of
planning, Frye said.
   While in dry dock, the Regina Maris will be examined to try to
determine what made it sink, he said. The ship sank Jan. 15 in
subfreezing temperatures.
   The Danish-built former cargo vessel also has been used as a
training and research ship. The owners plan to turn the vessel into
a floating restaurant, said Frye.
</TEXT>
