<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Pope     04-01 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pope,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Carries Cross in Re-creation of Jesus' Walk to Crucifixion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the Colosseum, where tradition says ancient
Romans threw Christian martyrs to the lions, Pope John Paul II
symbolically retraced Jesus' walk to his crucifixion. The pope
carried a black wooden cross.
   Heading a torchlight procession in Friday night's ceremony, the
Polish-born pontiff wore a white skullcap and gold-trimmed cape
over a white cassock.
   Vatican Radio and Italian state-run television carried the event
live and people gathered by the tens of thousands to watch the Via
Crucis, the Way of the Cross ritual that ends the saddest day of
the Roman Catholic year.
   Television said the spectacle was beamed to 27 countries on five
continents.
   John Paul pressed the cross, which weighed but one pound, to his
forehead as he marked the 14 Stations of the Cross representing the
physical suffering and mockery Jesus endured on his way to death.
   The stations include the three times Jesus fell under the weight
of the cross, the placing of the crown of thorns and whipping by
jailers.
   The pope began the walk inside the Colosseum, climbed the
cobblestone steps and ended at the Roman Forum, the ancient meeting
place of the leaders of Rome.
   Thousands read from prayer booklets illuminated by candlelight
as the procession took place.
   The pontiff earlier in the day heard confessions from 11
pilgrims and tourists in St. Peter's Basilica, a Good Friday
tradition he began during his first Easter Week as pope in 1979.
</TEXT>
