<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 2352EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     04-01 0830</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USDA Plans System to Trace Chemical Residues in Pork</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Agriculture Department plan to require the
identification of hogs so that illegally high traces of drugs in
their meat can be traced back to the farm has the support of a
national consumer group.
   Ellen Haas, executive director of the Washington-based Public
Voice for Food and Health Policy, said in comments filed with the
department this week that the proposal is in the best interest of
consumers.
   ``Improved methods to control and monitor dangerous chemical
residues in the swine supply are sorely needed, and this measure
will help meet this demand,'' she said.
   The proposal was announced a month ago as part of a program to
strengthen USDA's inspection and monitoring of pork for illegally
high traces of drugs, particularly sulfamethazine used to treat or
prevent swine disease. The drug also has been used as a feed
additive for many years in low doses to boost weight gains.
   A stricter monitoring program already has been put into effect,
and the identification proposal is said by USDA officials to be on
a fast track for approval.
   The proposed rule would require all swine in interstate commerce
to be individually identified by a tag or other approved means, and
producers would have to maintain appropriate identification records
on each animal for two years.
   Ms. Haas cited USDA records for 1987 showing that levels of
sulfonamides as a group _ which include sulfamethazine _ exceeded
Food and Drug Administration maximum levels in 4 percent of the
total samples.
   ``But in certain states, the problem was dramatically worse: in
North Carolina, the violation rate was 10.2 percent; in Alabama, 8
percent; and in Georgia, 7.8 percent,'' she said.
   According to department figures cited by Haas, violation
percentage rates for sulfonamide residues in pork tested in 1987
included these states of origin:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>MIDWEST</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Illinois, 4.8; Indiana, 6.7; Iowa, 2.2; Michigan, 3.9;
Minnesota, 2.1; Nebraska, 6.7; Ohio, 7.5; and Wisconsin, 3.3.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NORTHEAST</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Virginia, none; and all others (not specified), 2.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOUTHEAST</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Alabama, 8; Florida, none; Georgia, 7.8; Kentucky, 6.3;
Mississippi, 2.9; North Carolina, 10.2; South Carolina, none; and
Tennessee, 6.9.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WEST</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   South Dakota, 2.4; and all others (not specified), none.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOUTHWEST</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Kansas, none; Missouri, 4.4; Oklahoma, none; Texas, none; and
all others (not specified), none.
   
   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng has set
the 1988 honey price support at an average of 59.1 cents per pound,
down 6 percent from last year's level.
   Actual honey support prices will vary between about 48 cents to
62 cents per pound, depending on the color or class of honey
offered by producers, Lyng said Friday. The price supports will be
carried out through loans on honey stored on or off the farm.
   Under the 1985 farm law, honey supports are being gradually
reduced. Last year's average loan rate was 63 cents per pound and
the 1986 rate was 64 cents.
   Lyng also said the 1988 program will retain the ``marketing
loan'' provision to help reduce inventories held as surplus by the
department's Commodity Credit Corp.
   In earlier years, producers could redeem their honey only by
paying off the full amount of the CCC loan, plus interest. They had
the option of not repaying the loan at all, allowing CCC to assume
ownership of the honey which had been offered as collateral.
   Consequently, because of large supplies and low market prices,
CCC inventories of forfeited honey increased rapidly.
   But since the 1985 law, a honey producer can take out a loan and
then repay it at the prevailing market rate. In effect, this allows
the beekeeper to sell honey to the government at a specified price
and then buy it back at a lower price.
   Currently, producers who obtained price support loans averaging
63 cents per pound for 1987 honey can pay off the loans at 34 to 40
cents per pound, depending on quality.
   Lyng said the lower buy-back rates ``will be established at
levels that will minimize loan forfeitures, reduce honey stocks and
storage costs, and maintain the competitiveness of domestic honey
in U.S. and export markets.''
   
   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Cigarette use per adult expected to decline
again this year after a 2 percent drop in 1987, says the
Agriculture Department.
   ``Domestic cigarette consumption is likely to decline this year
because of further price hikes, continued antismoking activity, and
increased restrictions on where people can smoke,'' the
department's Economic Research Service said Friday.
   Consumption averaged 3,201 cigarettes per adult last year, down
from 3,274 in 1986, according to the preliminary figures. That was
the lowest since World War II. The peak was 4,345 cigarettes per
adult in 1963.
   Officials caution that the figures measure the average
``disappearance'' of cigarettes among those 18 years and older,
including smokers and non-smokers alike. It is used to show changes
from one year to another and does not indicate actual use among the
smoking population.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
