<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CasinoScam     04-01 0219</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Casino Scam,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tour Bus Driver Passes Off Homeless As Junketing Gamblers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tour bus driver rounded up homeless people in
San Francisco and took them to Nevada casinos, from which he
collected money by passing them off as gamblers on a junket, police
said Friday.
   Nevada casinos routinely pay tour bus operators to bring in
gamblers.
   The driver, Gilbert Gonzado, had duped the two dozen street
people into thinking they were getting a free vacation, police
said. The alleged victims said they slept on the bus for seven days
and had no money to buy food.
   Gonzado was arrested at Cactus Kate's Casino near Jean before
dawn Friday after the manager became suspicious of the passengers
who were being touted as legitimate gamblers, said Las Vegas Metro
police.
   Police said Gonzado had asked for $400 to bring the people to
the casino. Earlier, he apparently obtained money from clubs in
Lake Tahoe and Reno, police said.
   Police said the driver was held on charges of obtaining money
under false pretenses.
   The street people were picked up at Cactus Kate's in police vans
and taken to Las Vegas, 35 miles away, where they were put in a
downtown shelter. Police said the people would have to find their
own way back to San Francisco.
</TEXT>
