<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Amnesty     04-01 0439</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Amnesty,0454</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mrs. Thatcher Outraged At Amnesty Probe Into Killing of IRA Trio</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher has angrily
criticized a planned investigation by Amnesty International into
the killing of three unarmed Irish Republican Army guerrillas by
British commandos in Gibraltar.
   Amnesty shrugged off her comments, saying it gets the same
response when it lists human rights violations in South Africa, the
Soviet Union and Chile.
   ``I hope Amnesty has some concern for the more than 2,000 people
murdered by the IRA since 1969,'' Mrs. Thatcher told the House of
Commons Thursday, to cheers from rank-and-file legislators of her
Conservative Party.
   Conservative lawmaker John Carlisle fumed, ``These are
interfering do-gooders ... it (the Amnesty probe) will be deeply
resented by the British people.''
   In Belfast, Northern Ireland, Paddy McGrory, the lawyer for the
families of the three guerrillas killed _ Mairead Farrell, 31,
Danny McCann, 30, and Sean Savage, 23 _ said the relatives welcomed
Amnesty's concern.
   The London-based human rights organization, winner of the 1977
Nobel Peace Prize, announced Thursday it is investigating whether
the March 6 shooting of the woman and two men was an
``extrajudicial killing'' and called on the British government to
provide a ``full and public account.''
   Amnesty said the circumstances suggested the three were
``deliberately targeted'' and killed without challenge or attempt
at arrest. It said one was shot repeatedly while lying ``helpless
and incapacitated on the ground.''
   In the House of Commons, Mrs. Thatcher agreed with Conservative
legislator Ian Gow, who said the ``three terrorists, mercifully now
dead'' belonged to a terrorist organization which breached ``all
decent standards relating to human rights.''
   The guerrillas were shot in front of witnesses in Gibraltar, a
British colony on the southern tip of Spain.
   British and Spanish authorities said the three planned to
detonate a bomb during a changing of the guard ceremony and that
the attack would have killed more than 100 people.
   Spanish police recovered an explosives cache in a car linked to
the guerrillas.
   The IRA acknowledged the three were in Gibraltar on ``active
service.''
   The British government said after the shooting that the three
were challenged by commandos and made moves as if they were
reaching for arms or bomb detonators.
   Mrs. Thatcher said Thursday an inquest in June was the ``proper
occasion for the matters in question to be examined.''
   The killings set off new violence which killed nine people in
Northern Ireland, where the mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting
to end British rule. It wants to unite the province, which has a
Protestant majority, with the Catholic Republic of Ireland under a
leftist administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
