<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0235EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WhiteHouseFacelift Bjt   04-01 0583</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-White House Facelift, Bjt,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers To Remove At Least 30 Layers Of Paint In Refurbishing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The White House, which has had at least 30
coats of paint slathered on it since it was first whitewashed in
1797, is getting a facelift for its 200th birthday.
   Scaffolding went up along the north wall and part of the south
wall of the president's home this week as workers began the job of
removing paint preparatory to repainting.
   The elaborate sandstone carvings on the window pediments,
balustrade and roofline cornice of the building also will be
repaired in time for the bicentennial in 1992.
   The White House has been the home and office of every president
since John Adams, but the cornerstone was laid Oct. 13, 1792, in
the administration of George Washington.
   Five years later the building was first painted white.
   Until 1980, the building was regularly painted every five years.
Because of persistent paint failure, the White House and National
Park Service asked the National Bureau of Standards in 1976 to make
a study and recommend corrective action.
   Scientists recommended in 1980 that the 30 or more layers of
paint be removed. They said this would improve the building's
appearance and make it easier to maintain.
   The National Park Service says records show that the building
became a white house for the first time when laborers working on
its newly laid walls used whitewash as a sealer.
   The original walls were damaged when the White House was burned
by the British during the War of 1812. During reconstruction from
1815 to 1817, portions of the walls were replaced.
   The interior of the White House was renovated from 1948 to 1952,
during the Truman administration, but the new project is the
largest exterior refurbishing since it was reconstructed.
   Repair of the sandstone carvings is being overseen by Vincent
Palumbo, master carver for the National Cathedral in Washington.
Some of the stones will be replaced with stone removed from the
Capitol during a recent renovation.
   William Seale, in his authoritative book, ``The President's
House,'' writes that the sandstone, quarried from nearby Aquia
Creek in Virginia, ``was shaped to magnificence'' by the hands of
the Scots carvers who worked on it.
   ``The Ionic capitals on the colossal pilasters are carved in
high relief with rich scrolls surmounted by acanthus leaves,''
Seale says. ``From the center of each cap bursts a cabbage rose in
stone, great in size and fanciful in conception beyond the flowers
usually found on column capitals.''
   Roses also appear again as an ornamental feature in a carved
swag over the northern door of the residence. Chains and fish-scale
designs decorate the windowsills.
   Seale, who wrote his book after completion of a previous project
in which the North Portico was repainted, said the intricate
designs had long been obscured by paint.
   ``Stripped bare, the pale stone with its smooth surfaces and
rich carving attests to the skill of those who dressed it,'' he
said.
   The current project involves the exterior north walls and part
of the south walls.
   They will be kept bare until the spring of 1989 to allow the
porous sandstone to dry so the paint will adhere to the walls
better when they are repainted.
   The paint is being removed by brushing chemicals on the walls
and then flushing them with a stream of water.
   The work is being done by Ramco Technologies of Harford, Conn.,
under a $384,200 contract.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880401-0020 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0241EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson-Voters Bjt   04-01 0816</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson-Voters, Bjt,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wisconsin's Open Primary Makes For Varied Possibilities</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WAUSAU, Wisc. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ask Roger Timm who will get his vote in
Tuesday's Wisconsin primary, and his answer sums up the confusing
possibilities: ``I'm looking at Jackson _ or Bush.''
   In this state with a reputation for political independence and a
primary system to match, Jackson's strategy is to stitch together a
coalition of blue-collar workers, farmers and college town
residents. There are indications he is having some success.
   ``Jesse Jackson touches you where your heart is on economic
issues,'' said Gary Heiser, a Wausau real estate agent and Marathon
County Board member.
   ``To win, farmers and workers, rural and urban, black and white,
must come together,'' Jackson told about 700 people gathered in the
parking lot of the labor temple in Wausau.
   As in Michigan a week ago, Jackson is drawing big, enthusiastic
crowds from the housing projects in Milwaukee to almost all-white
Cudahy, Sheboygan and Wausau.
   At the University of Wisconsin at Oshkosh on Thursday, Jackson
drew 5,000 to a nighttime rally. And campaign staffers said he has
strong support in Madison, where the big state university campus is
located.
   But while Heiser is certain Jackson will do well in Wausau, he
isn't sure he can carry it against Massachusetts Gov. Michael
Dukakis.
   Kevin Keeffe, Marathon County Democratic chairman in Wausau,
said Jackson ``will do well among these guys'' _ that is,
blue-collar workers locked in a wage giveback dispute with a big
manufacturing company.
   However, ``Dukakis has a very good organization in town,''
Keeffe said, mentioning the American Federation of State, County
and Municipal Workers, which backs the Massachusetts governor.
   One of the complications _ pointed out by Roger Timm's
Bush-or-Jackson comment _ is that Wisconsin has an open primary.
Republicans can vote in the Democratic primary and vice versa.
Since George Bush has the Republican race all but wrapped up, GOP
voters might be tempted to weigh in with a Democratic ballot on
Tuesday.
   Jackson does generate the enthusiasm. Linda Pribanich, a Wausau
activist, was literally jumping up and down as she cheered him.
   ``I would like to think he could win here. This is as white as
it gets in this country,'' she said of the Wausau area.
   Wisconsin has a small black population _ less than 4 percent.
But Jackson campaign staffers say that doesn't worry them, pointing
to Jackson's improving showing in white areas in the Michigan
caucuses on March 26 and in Connecticut last week.
   ``We're going to do well in Wisconsin, because we are expanding
our base,'' said campaign manager Gerald Austin. ``We got 22
percent of the white vote in Connecticut.''
   In Wisconsin, blue-collar workers are a major Jackson target.
   ``When I put on my worker's hat, I am not jesting. It is my
regular hat,'' Jackson said in Oshkosh.
   ``I'm a working person person,'' he told the Wausau crowd.
   At stop after stop, Jackson delivers the same message of ``jobs,
peace and freedom.''
   ``We do not need Star Wars in outer space, we need jobs for
workers in Cudahy,'' he told 1,000 people there.
   ``The little people are really hurting,'' added Adele
Iwaskiewicz as she watched Jackson emerge from a neighbor's home in
Cudahy where he had spent the night.
   Mrs. Iwaskiewicz said she wouldn't have any problem voting for
Michael Dukakis if he's the nominee. She voted Republican in 1984.
   Timm, a Milwaukee policemen, also said he voted for Reagan in
1984, but he is attracted to Jackson's message.
   ``I like his pro-labor stands. He's talking about the working
people,'' said Timm, who is a neighbor of Mrs. Iwaskiewicz.
   In appealing to blue-collar workers, Jackson is tapping a sense
of obligation from his work on the behalf of striking workers in
this state and others tossed out of their jobs in years past.
   Jackson has a television ad featuring his talk to workers in
Kenosha, where Chrysler closed a plant after promising to keep it
open for several years.
   He returned to Cudahy on Wednesday to talk to workers who went
out on strike in January 1987 at the Patrick Cudahy meatpacking
plant.
   Local union president Mark Rosenberg said of Jackson: ``He's
going to do something about the system and make it work.''
   On Thursday, Jackson picked up the endorsement of Richard
Congdon, a Waukesha lawyer who headed Richard Gephardt's campaign
in the state.
   Congdon said he backs Jackson because they have ``overlapping
constituencies'' of workers and farmers.
   Asked if Jackson is electable, Congdon said: ``If he's not
electable, why does he keep winning elections?''
   Then there is the view of Chris Black, an industrial engineer
who was holding his 2-year-old son at the Wausau rally. Black said
he is undecided although he likes Jackson's message.
   Asked which other candidates he would consider, he answered:
``Pat Paulsen,'' the comedian known for his mock campaigns for
president.
</TEXT>
