<DOCNO> AP880401-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0250EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-France-Hostages     04-01 0434</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-France-Hostages,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Speculation Persists On French Hostage Deal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new report in a Beirut newspaper has fed
speculation in Paris that France freed a terrorist suspect as part
of a deal with Iran to secure the release of three French hostages
held in Lebanon.
   Premier Jacques Chirac denied any connection, saying the release
of Mohamed Mouhajer on March 24 was purely up to the judge.
   ``The release ... is linked neither closely nor remotely,
neither directly nor indirectly, to the problem of French or
foreign hostages in Lebanon,'' Chirac said in a radio interview
Thursday.
   The leftist paper As-Safir said Thursday ``secret negotiations''
were under way to free three Frenchmen _ diplomats Marcel Fontaine
and Marcel Carton and journalist Jean-Paul Kauffmann _ being held
by pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems.
   The Beirut newspaper said an Iranian clergyman and a Lebanese
businessman were involved in negotiations in the Ivory Coast. It
said President Amin Gemayel of Lebanon was told of the negotiations
``aimed at obtaining the release of three French hostages.''
   Interior Minister Charles Pasqua was in the Ivory Coast this
week, but broke off his African tour Monday to return to Paris. He
said he was needed in the campaign now under way for the April 24
presidential elections.
   An investigating magistrate cited insufficient evidence in
freeing Mouhajer, a Lebanese arrested a year ago during the
investigation into bombings in 1986 that left 13 people dead and
250 injured.
   Several newspapers immediately linked the move to the hostages.
   In Washington, State Department spokesman Charles E. Redman said
Thursday, ``We want all the hostages released, but we oppose making
deals. Making concessions to terrorists only encourages more
terrorism.''
   He noted that France and other participants in a 1987 summit
involving the seven major industrialized deomcracies ``committed
themselves to the principle of making no concessions to terrorists
or their sponsors.''
   Nineteen other foreigners are missing in Lebanon, including a
Frenchman whose killing was announced by his captors in 1986,
though no body was found. Those held include nine Americans, three
Britons, a West German, an Italian, an Irishman, an Indian and two
unidentified men.
   American Terry Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of The
Associated Press, is the longest held. He was kidnapped on March
16, 1985.
   Fontaine, Carton and Kauffmann also were abducted in 1985.
   In Geneva, Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran told a
news conference Thursday that negotiations had been going on
between France and Iran for 1{ years now on improving relations. He
said the French also asked Iranian help in the hostage situation.
</TEXT>
