<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0252EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Teamsters-Truckers     04-01 0625</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Teamsters-Truckers,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teamsters, Trucking Industry Beat Deadline On Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 200,000 Teamster drivers and warehouse
workers will begin voting in two weeks on a new three-year
nationwide freight contract with the nation's major trucking
companies.
   After two months of negotiations and several hours before the
midnight expiration of their old contract, the union and the
industry's collective bargaining arm reached tentative agreement on
a new accord Thursday.
   Terms of the pact were not disclosed. But Teamsters President
Jackie Presser said it ``addresses the economic needs of our
members and advances their legitimate claims for job security.''
   Under the expiring contract with Trucking Management Inc., the
base rate for drivers who had been on a carrier's payroll for three
or more years was $14.71 an hour. Including fringe and pension
benefits, the industry had calculated its total labor costs at $23
an hour.
   Dissidents in the union said negotiators reportedly had agreed
earlier to keep hourly wage increases within a range of around 30
cents a year with annual benefit improvements amounting to about
another 20 cents an hour.
   But they emphasized that they had no firm knowledge if that is
what occurred.
   ``I really don't know what's in it,'' said Ken Paff, an
organizer for the small dissident Teamsters for a Democratic Union
faction. ``They're keeping it real quiet.''
   Chip Roth, a Teamsters spokesman, said the union will not
announce the terms of the tentative contract until April 7, when
negotiators are to present it to local presidents at a meeting in
Chicago.
   Ballots for the ratification vote will be mailed to Teamster
freight members in about two weeks, Roth said.
   The union's schedule calls for counting the ballots and
announcing the results in mid-May. Under the Teamsters'
constitution, rejecting a tentative contract requires a two-thirds
majority.
   Going into the negotiations, Teamster officials were under
pressure from two directions after giving up automatic
cost-of-living adjustments and allowing lower wage rates for new
hires and part-time ``casual'' workers in the 1985 contract.
   Some large carriers are enjoying fairly healthy profits
following a shakeout of the industry from deregulation in 1980
despite competitive pressures to undercut one another's freight
rates. However, a large number of smaller unionized companies are
having financial troubles.
   At least 78 Teamster-organized carriers have declared
bankruptcy, been swallowed up in mergers or acquisitions or have
gone out of business in the past eight years, according to union
figures.
   Union officials acknowledged their members employed by the
larger carriers were most interested in wage and benefit gains,
while those working for smaller companies wanted more emphasis put
on job security in the bargaining.
   The Teamsters also fared poorly under deregulation, losing
120,000 members between 1979 and 1985 to new non-union companies,
many of them subsidiaries of unionized carriers party to the Master
Freight Agreement. But the union appears to have stabilized its
trucking membership the past two years.
   ``Negotiations were difficult because the industry is in
financial chaos,'' Presser said in a statement Thursday,
encouraging support for ratification.
   Arthur Bunte Jr., the chief management negotiator in the
bargaining, indicated that turmoil is likely to continue.
   ``In the outcome of these talks, we do not feel we were
successful in convincing the union of the harsh competitive
realities facing our members in the marketplace,'' Bunte said.
   But there was little evidence of rancor between the two sides in
the two months of negotiations, held both here and in Arizona,
where Presser spends most of his time while recovering from cancer
treatments.
   Neither side ever mentioned the possibility of a strike. The
last time there was a labor disruption over a nationwide trucking
contract was in 1979, when the Teamsters struck selected carriers
for 10 days.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
