<HEAD>Gore Calls For Meese Resignation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILL LESTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COCONUT GROVE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential contender
Albert Gore Jr. called for the resignation or firing of Attorney
General Edwin Meese III, saying: ``It is time to remove the cloud
over the Department of Justice.''
   Gore, at a fundraiser here, used his criticism of Meese for an
indirect attack at George Bush, the nearly certain Republican
presidential nominee.
   ``How long will it take this administration to understand the
importance of integrity in government?'' the Tennessee senator
asked a crowd of about 100 supporters at the posh Grove Isle
resort. ``We cannot tolerate a situation where the nation's chief
law enforcement officer is constantly testifying as a suspect
before grand juries, constantly operating under a cloud of
suspicion.''
   Gore noted the resignations of two top Justice Department
officials this week, a move that department sources said was aimed
at pointing up the problems Meese is causing by staying on.
   ``President Reagan and Vice President Bush say ``Oh, it's no big
deal. There are resignations all the time,''' said Gore. ``What
insensitivity! What contempt for the American people!''
   The Tennessee senator was heading to Wisconsin today for
campaigning in advance of Tuesday's primary.
   ``I think we are going to exceed expectations in Wisconsin,'' he
said, but wouldn't predict where he would finish.
   About $108,000 was raised at Thursday's event, said Mitchell
Berger, a Fort Lauderdale attorney and co-chairperson.
   Gore told the crowd that despite a lack of success since Super
Tuesday, his candidacy is in a good position to gain momentum with
a win in a large Northern state like Pennsylvania or New York.
   During the fund-raiser, Gore told reporters he is not singling
Jesse Jackson out for unfair criticism.
   ``I am treating each of the candidates equally. I have strong
differences of opinion with Jesse Jackson and I have strong
differences of opinion with Mike Dukakis, and neither one of them
has a single day of experience in the national government. I think
that's relevant in the choice faced by the voters,'' he said.
   Gore, who turned 40 on Thursday, said it was a relief for him.
   ``All those people who thought 39 was too young to run for
president, I've solved their problem,'' he said with a smile.
</TEXT>
