<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-LandPrices     04-01 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Land Prices,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tokyo Acre Costs $6.7 Billion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Land prices skyrocketed in Japan last year, with
the choicest piece of commercial real estate selling for more than
$6.7 billion per acre, the government reported today.
   Japanese newspapers bemoaned the record price jump in Tokyo,
where residential real estate land rose 68.9 percent last year,
nearly twice the previous high of 35.9 percent in 1973 and almost
triple the increase in 1986 of 23.8 percent.
   ``If the (Japanese) people work diligently all their lives and
find that they are unable to even purchase a house of their choice,
then we can expect them to question the signficance of economic
development,'' the nationally circulated daily Asahi Shimbun said
in an editorial today.
   It called on the government to convert more public land into
housing sites and on industry to build residential complexes near
workplaces.
   The National Land Agency released the 1987 statistics Thursday,
the last day of Japan's fiscal year. The agency said land prices
soared abnormally due to speculative buying, money surpluses and
lowered interest rates.
   The land agency said the highest land price was 34 million yen
per square meter, registered in the Chiyoda ward in central Tokyo's
main Marunouchi business district. At the exchange rate of one
dollar to 125 yen, that price translates to $272,000 dollars per
square meter or $6.72 billion per acre.
</TEXT>
