<1ST_LINE>r i PM-ModelUNSession     04-01 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Model UN Session,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Find Nations Not So United</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boris Karlov will return to the Soviet
Union a little wiser about the world's woes, a little more certain
that there are no simple answers to the issues that separate the
superpowers.
   Karlov is among 1,500 students taking part in the National Model
United Nations session, an annual forum for students to dabble in
diplomacy, play a little poltics and tackle the same dilemmas that
confront the real U.N.
   In a nifty bit of role reversal, however, Karlov is playing the
part of the U.S. ambassador.
   ``It is not easy to represent other views,'' he said, ``but it
is extremely important to help us understand each other; to help us
understand how the United States thinks, for the United States to
understand how the Soviets view the world.''
   He wasn't the only student thrust into an unfamiliar role.
   One of the most outspoken delegates this year has been Betsy
Snider of West Virginia's Bluefield State College, who was the
delegate from the Palestine Liberation Organization's observer
mission.
   Snider, who described her politics as ``Republican,'' said that
``at one time I felt that the United States was always right, but
when I started (attending model U.N. sessions) I started to have
pro-Arab sympathies.''
   The model U.N. was set up in the same structure of the real U.N.
The Security Council groped for a solution to the war between Iran
and Iraq. Meanwhile, delegates to the General Assembly launched
scathing denunciations of Israel's occupation of Palestine.
   The students _ from the United States, Soviet Union, West
Germany, Canada and Japan _ were asked to assume roles that
challenged their national perspectives.
   ``By the end of the week, you come to accept your role,'' said
Brian Hayden, an American acting as secretary-general this year.
   ``One of the better learning experiences is coming up against
the United States in a debate. I remember thinking, `Are we (the
United States) really that difficult to work with?'''
   The students are required to follow the national policies of the
countries they represent, so they soon learn the limits of the
United Nations system: bloc voting, lack of enforcement power,
vetoes by the permanent members of the Security Council _ the
United States, Soviet Union, China, Britain and France.
   ``What we simulate is frustration,'' said Thomas Becker of
Westport, Conn., who is playing the undersecretary-general for
economic and social affairs. ``Students come away exhilarated by
the experience but with understanding of the restraints and
frustrations under which delegates must operate.''
   The National Model United Nations Conference dates back to 1923,
when its predecessor organization simulated the League of Nations.
It changed its name in 1946 after the founding of the United
Nations.
   The organization is organized by a non-profit committee
affiliated with the U.N. Department of Public Information, and
funded by fees paid by students attending the sessions.
   But don't expect any simple answer to the world's ills this
week. The real U.N. doesn't operate that way, and neither does its
student model.
   ``There is room for creativity, and exciting things happen in
caucuses, but if there were a breakthough it would probably mean
the students hadn't done their homework,'' said Becker.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880401-0035 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0301EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Nofziger     04-01 0651</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nofziger,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Says Nofziger Should Be Sentenced For Ridiculing Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former presidential aide Lyn Nofziger is still
worth more than $2.8 million despite his pleas of financial
hardship and should be imprisoned for illegally lobbying the White
House, a prosecutor says.
   Independent counsel James C. McKay said Nofziger deserves
imprisonment for flouting and belittling the Ethics in Government
Act.
   Nofziger also should be fined because he was ``unjustly
enriched'' by lobbying then-presidential counselor Edwin Meese III
and other White House aides on behalf of Wedtech Corp. and two
other clients, McKay said in a sentencing memo filed Thursday in
U.S. District Court.
   The former White House political director is scheduled to be
sentenced next Friday by U.S. District Judge Thomas Flannery.
   McKay, noting a probation office report that Nofziger's
``current net worth exceeds $2.8 million,'' rejected the
defendant's argument that the ``public humiliation and serious
financial reversals'' resulting from his indictment and trial
should spare him further punishment.
   Nofziger has said his legal bills total $1 million and friends
have started a defense fund to help pay his lawyers.
   McKay said ``virtually all'' of Nofziger's wealth was
accumulated after he left the White House.
   ``It cannot fairly be concluded that defendant Nofziger's
reduced financial situation supplants the justifications for
judicial punishment for his offenses,'' the prosecutor said.
   McKay noted that Nofziger's lobbying of Meese, now attorney
general, on behalf of Wedtech helped the Bronx, N.Y. company win a
$32 million Army no-bid contract.
   ``The transfer to defendant Nofziger of many thousands of
dollars worth of Welbilt stock would not have occurred if that
contract had not been awarded to Welbilt,'' McKay said, referring
to Wedtech by its previous name, Welbilt Electronic Die Corp.
   Nofziger and his partner, Mark A. Bragg, eventually sold their
Wedtech stock for more than $600,000, according to court records.
   Nofziger's remarks after his conviction showed ``a total lack of
remorse or contrition,'' McKay said.
   Minutes after he was convicted on Feb. 11, Nofziger told
reporters his crime was like ``running a stop sign.''
   He called the ethics statute ``a lousy law.''
   ``That intransigent attitude is a consideration arguing in favor
of a sentence that includes a period of incarceration,'' said
McKay, who did not specify the length of the prison term he sought.
   Nofziger could be sentenced to up to two years and fined as much
as $10,000 for each of three felony convictions for lobbying former
colleagues within a year of leaving President Reagan's staff in
early 1982.
   Defense attorney E. Lawrence Barcella said for McKay to
``request jail time for a 63-year-old man with a spotless record of
public service who did not intend to violate the law is ridiculous,
unnecessary and totally lacking in compassion.''
   But McKay argued in his brief that Nofziger ignored advice about
complying with the Ethics in Government Act from lawyers he
retained when he left Reagan's staff in early 1982.
   The prosecutor recalled an episode during which Nofziger uttered
a profanity when advised by one of his lawyers not to make any
White House contacts without first consulting his attorneys.
   The incident was described at a bench conference during the
trial by associate independent counsel Merrick Garland out of
hearing of the jury and spectators, according to the transcript.
   When Nofziger attorney Martin L. Artiano gave the advice,
Nofziger uttered the profanity and said ``these are my friends and
I am going back to them if I want to,'' Garland told the judge.
   ``Lyn doesn't recall having such a conversation,'' Barcella
said. Artiano only recalled such an incident after ``a lot of
prompting'' during ``repeated interviews with the independent
counsel and numerous sessions with the grand jury,'' the defense
lawyer said.
   ``Even Artiano said Lyn was joking when he said it and
thereafter Lyn came and asked for their advice about Ethics in
Government Act matters,'' Barcella said.
</TEXT>
