<1ST_LINE>r w PM-RocketPlant     04-01 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rocket Plant,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Subcommittee Chairman Says NASA Being ``Hamstrung'' By
Administration</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WX7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA says two areas in Mississippi and one
near Cape Canaveral in Florida are prime candidates for a $1
billion plant to build the next generation of space shuttle rocket
boosters, but that plans are being held up by the White House.
   Two officials of the National Aeronautics and Space Agency
indicated to Congress on Thursday that a requirement for the site
might be that it be accessible by rail and water. That would
eliminate the Morton Thiokol Inc. plant in Utah, the sole source
for current booster rockets.
   Adm. Richard Truly, head of the shuttle program for NASA, and
J.R. Thompson, director of the Marshall Space Flight Center in
Alabama, testified they expect to decide on a site before June when
requests are issued for proposals to build and operate the plant.
   They had been expected to present a comprehensive plant
acquisition plan to the space science subcommittee of the House
Committee on Science and Technology. But they said the plan was
being held up by the White House's Office of Management and Budget.
   The March 30 deadline was spelled out in legislation last year
that was signed by the president. The delay caused Rep. Bill
Nelson, D-Fla., the subcommittee chairman, to say that NASA was
``being hamstrung by the administration, specifically by OMB.''
   He called it ``another example of an administration that's got
such a mixed-up policy, a lack of direction, that it is going
several different ways and not holding itself accountable by
Congress.''
   But OMB, through a spokeswoman who said she didn't want to be
named, said that a technical report of the kind submitted by NASA
normally takes five days for review and that it had been received
only two days earlier. ``They knew that,'' she said. ``We are
taking the full five days.''
   The facility will cost $200 million to $300 million to build and
$1 billion to get into production, Truly said.
   Thompson said a number of sites had been looked at, mostly
around the Gulf coast and some in Florida. He said the Cape
Canaveral area, Bay St. Louis, Miss., and Yellow Creek, in
Mississippi near the Alabama-Tennessee border ``would be among the
three more attractive'' places.
   Thompson said five firms have expressed an interest in making
the Advanced Solid Rocket Motors, which are planned for flights
beginning in mid-1993 that need the extra lifting power the new
boosters will have. Morton Thiokol will continue to make the
current boosters, which gradually will be phased out by mid-1997.
   Thompson said four of the firms, United Technologies, Atlantic
Research, Aerojet and Hercules, are interested in operating a
government-owned plant, while Morton Thiokol wants to upgrade its
facilities in Utah.
   ``A new facility, in our opinion, is needed,'' Truly said. ``It
needs to include more automation, cleaner facilities.''
   The two officials would not commit themselves to whether the
NASA plan rules out a contractor-owned, contractor-operated
facility as is the case with Morton Thiokol.
   But Thompson said, ``We just do not want to get ourselves tied
to one contractor for the long haul.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
