<DOCNO> AP880401-0040 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0327EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Immigration     04-01 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Immigration,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Schumer Says Extension Has Good Chance Of Clearing Full House</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan to give illegal aliens an additional
seven months to apply for amnesty has won committee backing, and a
key supporter says the plan has a good chance of passage in the
House.
   After the House Judiciary Committee voted 22-12 Thursday to
extend the current May 4 deadline to Nov. 30, Rep. Charles Schumer,
D-N.Y., said the margin ``bodes well for passage in the House.''
   The legalization plan applies to aliens who came to the United
States illegally but have lived in the United States continuously
since before Jan. 1, 1982.
   Schumer said he was encouraged by support in committee from
three Republicans, including ranking GOP member Hamilton Fish of
New York and Dan Lungren of California, who was instrumental in
passage of the landmark 1986 immigration law that established the
amnesty program.
   Rep. Michael DeWine of Ohio was the third Republican to support
the extension, while Rep. Harley Staggers, D-W.Va., was the only
Democrat to oppose it. The remainder of the vote was along party
lines.
   ``The margin was higher than expected,'' Schumer said. ``While
we have a long way to go, I'm more optimistic than ever it will
reach the president's desk.''
   Schumer said he expected the bill to reach the House floor soon
after next week's congressional recess. The legislation still faces
heavy opposition in both the House and the Senate _ where it could
be subjected to a filibuster. In addition, the Reagan
administration opposes the bill.
   Legalization was a cornerstone of the landmark law signed in
November 1986 to slow massive illegal immigration. The program was
included as a balance to the legislation's enforcement provision:
financial penalties against employers who knowingly hire
undocumented workers.
   Alan C. Nelson, commissioner of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service, said this week that even talk of an
extension was ``a major threat to the program'' because aliens
would become confused and delay their applications.
   But the majority of committee members, while praising the INS'
current attempt to publicize legalization and the May 4 deadline,
contended the media campaign began too late to reach all those who
might apply.
   INS figures show that through March 29, some 1.1 million
applications have been received under the general amnesty program.
More than 300,000 have been received from a special program for
agricultural workers.
   The agricultural program already has a Nov. 30 deadline.
   Of applications that have reached the decision stage, only
12,700 have been rejected, a rate of 2 percent. Another 782,000
have been approved and the remainder are in the pipeline, the INS
says.
   Applicants receive a temporary work permit when they apply for
legalization, and therefore can stay in the country while awaiting
a decision. If the applicant gains temporary residency, he or she
is then on the road toward permanent residency and citizenship.
   INS figures show the number of applicants has been increasing as
the May 4 deadline approaches. For instance, 16,800 people applied
the week ending Jan. 22, while there were 30,620 applicants in the
week ending March 11. The total was 36,830 for the week ending
March 18.
   The leading committee opponent of the extension, Rep. Patrick L.
Swindall, R-Ga., told colleagues that the amnesty program was
barely approved by the House in 1986.
   ``Now we're going back and changing that delicate balance,'' he
said. ``Now we are coming through the back door and extending it.
It leaves the door wide open to come back again.''
   Rep. Romano L. Mazzoli, D-Ky., chief sponsor of the new
deadline, said the ``one-shot'' extension would continue to be
``self-sustaining,'' paid for by fees charged to applicants.
   He pointed out that some of the INS legalization offices would
stay open until Nov. 30 anyway to receive applications for the
agricultural program, which was established for 18 months.
</TEXT>
