<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-BusCrash     04-01 0195</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Bus Crash,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bus Plunges into River; At Least 14 Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALLE DE BRAVO, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A passenger bus ran off a highway
and plummeted more than 160 feet into a river outside this central
Mexico town, killing at least 14 people and seriously injuring 26,
authorities said.
   Rescuers searched into the night for survivors of the Thursday
afternoon crash, but feared the death toll would rise, said
Wenceslao Garcia Martinez, a Mexican Red Cross spokesman.
   The bus, belonging to the Zanacatepec y Ramales line, split in
half when it plunged into the Rio Paraje el Salto, Garcia Martinez
said in a telephone interview, adding that the cause of the crash
was not immediately known.
   The bus had just departed Valle de Bravo, about 70 miles west of
Mexico City, for the Mexico state capital of Toluca. The trip had
originated in Ixtapa del Oro.
   Red Cross and other emergency personnel were taking the injured
to hospitals and emergency clinics in Toluca, Ixtapan and Valle de
Bravo.
   Hospital officials said they could provide no information about
the condition of the victims and the names of the dead and injured
were not immediately available.
</TEXT>
