<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0335EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Bush-Baker     04-01 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Baker,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sources Hint Treasury Secretary Could Quit To Oversee Bush
Campaign</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III may
resign his post this summer to oversee Vice President George Bush's
general-election campaign, administration and Bush campaign sources
are hinting.
   But the officials, who spoke only on the condition of anonymity,
said that such a move is unlikely to occur before the August 15-18
Republican convention in New Orleans and could depend on the
condition of the U.S. economy.
   Meanwhile, President Reagan may actively campaign for Bush even
before the GOP convention, according to presidential spokesman
Marlin Fitzwater.
   Fitzwater told reporters on Thursday that the president is
reconsidering his original vow to remain neutral until after the
convention now that Bush's only remaining opposition is a token
challenge from former television evangelist Pat Robertson.
   ``We could see the president involved in some political
activities before the nominating convention _ activities that are
directly associated with the nominee,'' Fitzwater said.
   The withdrawal this week of distant rival Sen. Bob Dole gave
Bush a virtual lock on the GOP nomination.
   Bush strategists are now focusing their attention on the fall
elections, and Baker may play an important role in that campaign.
   If Baker does come aboard, it won't be until around the time of
the convention, even though Bush is now certain to be the party's
nominee, said administration officials who spoke on the condition
of anonymity.
   There long has been talk that the treasury secretary, who
managed Bush's 1980 presidential bid and was senior advisor to the
1980 Reagan-Bush campaign, might step aside to help run his
longtime friend's campaign.
   Peter Teeley, a Bush campaign spokesman, said a discussion of
what role Baker might play in the Bush campaign, if any, was only
speculative at this time.
   But, Teeley added, ``Jim is very close to the vice president and
has been for a quarter of a century. There's no secret what their
relationship has been.''
   In the past, Baker has discouraged talk of an early resignation,
saying he was happy with his job as treasury secretary, one he has
held since 1985.
   However, on Thursday a Treasury spokesman, who refused to be
identified by name, would only say that there was no truth to
reports that Baker would quit by Aug. 1.
   Baker intends to go ahead with plans to participate in the
seven-nation economic summit in Toronto in late June,
administration officials said.
   Baker, who has built an international reputation in his current
post, is an experienced political tactician. The former Houston
attorney served as Reagan's chief of staff for four years before
becoming treasury secretary and in 1976 was chairman of President
Ford's re-election effort.
   Baker's role in the Bush campaign, and the timing involved in
such a move, could depend on how the economy performs over the next
few months.
   A deterioration in the economy could persuade Baker to stay on
as treasury secretary to oversee policies designed to head off an
election-year recession, some administration sources involved in
economic policy-making suggest.
   However, recent economic data have shown an economy rebounding
strongly from last October's stock market plunge.
   Baker could probably have any job in a Bush presidency that he
wanted, and there have been rumors for some time that he would like
to be secretary of state.
   Bush on Wednesday told reporters he intended to ``have a new
Cabinet'' if elected. The answer responded specifically to a query
on embattled Attorney General Edwin Meese III but might also be
taken as a signal that there would be a new treasury secretary in a
Bush presidency.
   Bush, back in town for several days following a three-day swing
through Wisconsin, met with Reagan for their regular weekly working
luncheon. Fitzwater said he did not know if campaign plans were
discussed.
   The president's spokesman said a decision on any presidential
campaign activity by Reagan in Bush's behalf before the convention
``has not been finally made, although ... the vice president is
very close to having the nomination.''
   ``Pat Robertson is still a candidate, in a declared sense, but
he too recognizes the realities of the situation,'' Fitzwater said.
   Bush is continuing with plans for campaign appearances in states
that have upcoming primaries and that will also be important in the
general election _ including New York, New Jersey, Ohio and
Pennsylvania.
   He also is planning fund-raising trips late next week to Texas
and Florida, states where he has already won primaries.
</TEXT>
