<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Congress-Mideast     04-01 0382</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Mideast,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senators Urge Shultz Not to Meet with PLO</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 21 senators is writing Secretary of
State George Shultz asking him to refrain from meeting with members
of the Palestine Liberation Organization during his upcoming trip
to the Middle East.
   The bipartisan group, including presidential hopeful Albert Gore
Jr., D-Tenn., still was collecting signatures on the petition and
planned to send the letter today. A similar letter was planned by
House members.
   Shultz left Washington on Thursday for Rome, and will continue
Sunday to the Middle East to lobby for acceptance of a U.S. plan
for Arab-Israeli peace talks.
   The senators slammed Shultz's meeting last Saturday in
Washington with two American university professors who are members
of the Palestine National Council, the PLO's parliamentary arm.
   Defending the meeting, Shultz said he wanted to hear the views
of Edward Said and Ibrahim Abu Lughod about Palestinian
representation in Mideast talks. He denied his meeting violated
U.S. law, which forbids negotiating with the PLO, saying that not
all members of the council are also members of the PLO.
   ``We see no distinction between the PLO and the PNC,'' the
senators wrote. ``We believe your action sets a dangerous
precedent.''
   Congress passed a law in 1985 banning talks with the PLO until
that organization recognizes Israel's right to exist and renounces
acts of terror. The law was based on U.S. assurances to Israel in
1975 that the United States would not deal with the PLO.
   ``If U.S. agreements are breached now, how can we expect the
government of Israel to accept future U.S. assurances concerning an
international peace conference?'' the letter said.
   Shultz has proposed giving Israel written assurances that an
international conference would only serve as an advisory forum for
direct Israeli-Arab talks and would not have the power to impose
solutions.
   The senators who signed the letter were: Christopher Bond,
R-Mo.; Quentin Burdick, D-N.D.; Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.; Alan
Dixon, D-Ill.; Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.; Gore; Bob Graham, D-Fla.;
Charles Grassley, R-Iowa; John Heinz, R-Penn.; Gordon Humphrey,
R-N.H.; Daniel Inouye, D-Hawaii; David Karnes, R-Neb.; Bob Kasten,
R-Wis.; Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.; Howard Metzenbaum, D-Ohio; John
Melcher, D-Mont.; Larry Pressler, R-S.D.; Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va.;
William Roth, R-Del.; Richard Shelby, D-Ala.; and Pete Wilson,
R-Calif.
</TEXT>
