<1ST_LINE>r w PM-US-JapanFoodstuffs     04-01 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-US-Japan Foodstuffs,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S.-Japan Talks On Removal of Orange and Beef Import Quotas Fail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States says it will pursue a formal
trade complaint against Japan after a four-year agreement covering
Japanese import quotas on beef, oranges and orange juice expired
and talks produced no new accord.
   ``I am deeply disappointed that the Japanese did not come
forward with their proposal to liberalize trade on beef and
citrus,'' U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter said after
three days of talks here with Takashi Sato, Japanese minister of
agriculture, forestry and fisheries.
   Thursday was the last day of the agreement. As a result of the
failure, the United States will challenge the quotas as illegal
under international trading rules, opening the way to possible
trade penalties or other sanctions against Japan, Yeutter said.
   The United States has requested an emergency meeting of the
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade council next Friday in
Geneva, where it will request ``an independent GATT panel to be
formed to review our complaint,'' Yeutter said.
   Sato told reporters he and his delegation explained the
difficulties of liberalizing beef and citrus imports and ``tried to
obtain the understanding of the U.S. side for a more realistic
position but our efforts were not successful.''
   Talks on the issue will continue but no time or place was set,
Japanese spokesman Toshiyuki Takano said, and Sato plans to leave
Saturday for Japan.
   Under the 1984 quota agreement, Japan agreed to admit 141,000
tons of American beef that year, rising to 177,000 tons this year,
and to a 1,100-ton annual increase in the 1984 quota on U.S. orange
imports of 82,000 tons.
   The quotas are demanded by citrus and beef farmers who are
influential in Japan's governing Liberal-Democratic Party. U.S.
officials argue that Japanese consumers would benefit greatly from
cheaper U.S. oranges and meat and that the domestic producers
should adjust to imports just as several U.S. industries have had
to cope with Japanese competition.
   Yeutter said he is confident the Japanese quotas will be found
in violation of international trading rules because an earlier GATT
panel recently ruled Japanese quotas on 12 processed foods were
GATT-illegal. Japan at first ignored the ruling but it was
announced during Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita's January visit to
Washington that the country would abide by the decision.
   Officials of Takeshita's governing Liberal-Democratic Party said
recently Japan could not agree to further liberalization of beef
and citrus imports because it would threaten producers' livelihood.
   Although Japan is the largest purchaser of U.S. farm products,
the United States has been arguing that the country's remaining
import barriers cost Japanese consumers unreasonably high prices,
with beefsteak four times the U.S. price and citrus fruit at least
double the American cost.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880401-0047 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0359EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-EasternAirlines     04-01 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Eastern Airlines,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Sues Texas Air, Says Eastern Being Dismantled In Anti-Labor
Move</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The owners of Eastern Airlines are trying to
dismantle the financially troubled passenger carrier in an effort
to break its unions, the union representing 13,000 Eastern workers
alleges in a federal lawsuit.
   The International Association of Machinists and Aerospace
Workers, AFL-CIO, filed the lawsuit in U.S. District Court here
Thursday. The 81-page complaint alleges that Frank Lorenzo's Texas
Air Corp. was trying to undermine the union's legal right to
represent Eastern employees by transferring the airline's assets to
other subsidiaries of the parent.
   The complaint charged that the transfer of some Eastern air
routes, planes and airport gate rights to other subsidiaries such
as Continental was part of a scheme to weaken the IAM's power to
represent Eastern employees.
   Such transactions violated the terms of a 1984 agreement that
the old Eastern Airlines management made with the IAM under which
union members received 20 percent of the company's stock in return
for wage concessions, the union said.
   Texas Air took over Eastern in 1986, but the union contends that
the airline's new owner is bound by the collective bargaining
agreement that set up the stock ownership plan.
   The lawsuit also charges a campaign of harassment of IAM members
as well as ``widespread and blatant'' violations of the labor
contract.
   Eastern spokeswoman Karen Ceremsak said the company would not
comment on the lawsuit until officials had a chance to read the
complaint.
   The union last month obtained a contempt citation against
Eastern for taking steps to sell its Northeast shuttle operation to
another subsidiary of Texas Air.
   The new lawsuit was assigned to U.S. District Judge John H.
Pratt, who last month ruled that the attempt to transfer the
shuttle operations flouted an earlier injunction he had issued
directing Eastern to maintain the working conditions of its
unionized employees.
   The IAM and Eastern are negotiating changes in the union
contract before federal mediators.
   The company was also ordered this week by another judge here not
to lease its planes to an independent cargo carrier to train
non-union pilots in the event Eastern's unionized pilots honor a
possible IAM strike this spring.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
