<HEAD>Police Scatter Protest in Front of Presidential Palace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile, (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police used water cannons and clubs to
scatter scores of dissidents protesting lack of progress in the
investigation of the killing three years ago of three communist
activists.
   Reporters and witnesses saw at least 30 protesters being
detained during the demonstration Thursday.
   The protesters gathered at a plaza across the street from the
government palace in downtown Santiago, carrying signs and chanting
anti-government slogans. The group included the widows of the three
slain communists.
   Jose Manuel Parada, Santiago Natino and Manuel Guerrero were
abducted on March 29, 1985. Their bodies were found with their
throats slit two days later near the Santiago airport.
   Four months later, a civilian judge indicted 12 members of the
national police, including two colonels, in the kidnappings but not
in the killings. The charges eventually were dropped by the Supreme
Court and the case remains open.
</TEXT>
