<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Brazil-Indians     04-01 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil-Indians,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunmen Invade Indian Reserve; At Least Three Dead And 20 Wounded</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty gunmen attacked an Indian
reserve in an Amazon jungle area claimed by wealthy landowners,
killing at least three Indians, wounding 20 and leaving 15 missing,
the National Indian Foundation reported.
   The official report Thursday was disputed by the National
Indigenous Council, an Indian rights group associated with Brazil's
National Catholic Bishop's Conference, which set the number of dead
at 12, including some children, and 21 injured.
   The foundation said the attack took place Monday on the Tikuna
Indian reserve in Benjamin Constant, a town 3,700 miles northwest
of Rio de Janeiro near the border with Colombia.
   Foundation president Romero Juca told reporters Thursday that
the federal police had been called in to investigate the attack.
   The shootings appeared linked to a dispute between the
foundation and landowners for control of the region, which is rich
in mineral deposits and timber.
   According to Juca, the foundation marked off 298,870 acres as
Tikuna territory in 1984, but white landowners have not accepted
the compensation paid by the government and stayed in the area.
   The National Indigenous Council said about 20,000 Tikuna Indians
live in and around Benjamin Constant.
   There are about 220,000 Indians in Brazil, most of whom live in
the Amazon jungle.
</TEXT>
