<HEAD>Former Congressman Wants Cuomo Candidacy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ROCHELLE, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former New York congressman says the
uncommitted delegate slate he's part of for the state's April 19
Democratic presidential primary hopes ``to persuade the (national)
convention to go for Mario Cuomo.''
   ``We think he would be, by far, the strongest, most inspiring
candidate that we could put up,'' Democrat Richard Ottinger said of
the New York governor during an interview Thursday with WVOX and
WRTN radio stations.
   The uncommitted slate of delegates was put together by a group
of upstate New York elected Democratic county clerks, many of whom
hoped Cuomo would join the race.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gore Sr. Says Candidate Son Shouldn't Settle For VP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAUSAU, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Albert Gore Sr. says he almost got the
Democratic vice presidential nomination more than three decades ago
_ and he hopes his son won't settle for the No. 2 spot because it
is ``dead-end street.''
   Gore, 80, said he would not recommend that his son, Tennessee
Sen. Albert Gore Jr., flirt with the vice presidency even if he
fails to become the Democratic presidential nominee.
   ``It's a dead-end street,'' the elder Gore, who recalled
unsuccessfully seeking the 1956 vice presidential nomination, told
the Wausau Daily Herald in an interview Wednesday.
   ``And I have serious doubts that ... the other contestants for
the presidency can win, and who would want to be second on the
losing ticket?''
   The elder Gore also had doubts about the vice presidential job
for his son even if the Democrats win because it would be ``a
do-nothing position.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Study: Married Voters Favor Republicans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Married voters tend to vote for
Republicans in presidential elections, a study by an Ohio State
University political science professor concludes.
   The research by Herbert Weisberg showed that 10 percent to 15
percent more married people than unmarried ones favor Republicans,
partly because Republicans in recent years have emphasized family
issues.
   ``The Republicans have been holding the edge in the marriage gap
for some time,'' Weisberg said. ``The question will be whether
either party finds a way to exploit it.''
   Married people are in the majority and are more likely to vote
than unmarried people because more people vote once they have a
bigger stake in the community, Weisberg said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Carter Praises Jackson's Campaign Style</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Jimmy Carter has praise for the
campaign style of Jesse Jackson, but he isn't saying which
candidate he hopes will win the Democratic presidential race.
   Carter, speaking Thursday with reporters following a conference
on South Africa, was asked what he thought about Jackson's recent
strides in the race.
   ``I think Jesse Jackson has run as near a perfect campaign as I
have ever seen in this country,'' said Carter. He declined to take
further questions about politics.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Elizabeth Dole Says Slick Advertising Won Super Tuesday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Transportation Secretary
Elizabeth Dole says the South's Super Tuesday primaries were won on
the ``slick advertising'' of Vice President George Bush.
   Her husband, Sen. Bob Dole, fell behind in the Republican
presidential nomination race during those primaries.
   Mrs. Dole, in Colorado Springs to speak at the El Paso County
Lincoln Day dinner, told reporters that so many states held
primaries on March 8 the candidates were unable to get their
messages to voters.
   ``The Super Tuesday idea was not at all a good one,'' she said.
``I don't think we'll ever see that concept again.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Clerks May Amend Ballot For New Jersey Primary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clerks in 17 New Jersey counties who
claimed an overcrowded slate for the state's June 7 primary would
force them to spend $4.1 million for additional voting machines won
court approval to change the ballot's design.
   ``In my 21 years as county clerk, this is my greatest
accomplishment,'' Union County Clerk Walter G. Halpin said of the
ruling Thursday. ``I'm saving my county half a million dollars
alone.''
   The ruling by Superior Court Judge Burrell Ives Humphreys means
that a voter casting a ballot for a candidate seeking the
Republican nomination for president will select simultaneously
those convention delegates pledged to the candidate.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Montana Senator Endorses Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., is endorsing
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis to be the Democratic
presidential nominee, citing Dukakis' stands on the economy.
   ``Our nation needs leaders who are committed to rebuilding our
economy,'' Baucus said Thursday. ``Creating good, lasting jobs for
Americans is the key to our future. I believe Michael Dukakis is
best qualified to achieve this goal.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Mexico Congressman Endorses Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Bill Richardson, D-N.M., is endorsing
Democrat Michael Dukakis for president, saying he hopes to help the
Massachusetts governor with a large number of Hispanic voters.
   ``What is significant here is that there is a perception that
minorities in this country are going toward one candidate,''
Richardson said Thursday, referring to minority support for Jesse
Jackson.
</TEXT>
