<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC--AIDS-Measles     04-01 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC--AIDS-Measles,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC Recommends Measles Vaccine For All AIDS-Infected Kids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal health officials say children infected
with the virus that causes AIDS should receive measles vaccine,
since their risk of severe measles is worse than their risk of
complications from the vaccine.
   The Immunization Practices Advisory Committee of the U.S.
Centers for Disease Control said Thursday that children infected
with the virus that causes AIDS should receive the common
measles-mumps-rubella vaccine, whether or not they show signs of
the devastating symptoms of AIDS itself.
   Previously, the committee had recommended that children showing
AIDS symptoms should not be vaccinated, because their immune
systems might be too severely harmed to tolerate the live-virus
measles vaccine.
   The new CDC recommendation, consistent with recommendations by
the World Health Organization, is an ``approach to protect the
HIV-infected child,'' the Atlanta-based agency said in its weekly
report.
   Complication from measles vaccine in children infected with HIV
_ human immunodeficiency virus, the virus that causes AIDS _
``hasn't happened,'' said Dr. Lauri Markowitz, a CDC measles
specialist.
   However, she noted, ``We have had several cases of measles in
these children, and it's felt that the benefit of getting the
vaccine outweighs the risk.''
   In 1986 and '87, at least six cases of measles occurred in
children infected with AIDS virus, the CDC reported; two of those
children died, in the first U.S. measles deaths reported to CDC
since 1985. The other four measles cases were severe.
   None of the six measles cases was believed linked to measles
vaccine. Only one of the six children had received measles vaccine,
and that was five years before he became ill.
   It is hoped measles vaccinations will be effective in
HIV-infected children, although new studies seem to show that those
children, with their weakened immune systems, may not respond to
the vaccine as well as healthy children, Ms. Markowitz said.
   The CDC has reported 913 cases of AIDS itself in children under
13. Researchers believe that more are infected with the virus that
causes AIDS, but have not yet developed the disease _ and may never.
   AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, cripples the boy's
immune system, leaving victims susceptible to a wide spectrum of
infections and cancers. The CDC has recorded 57,024 AIDS cases of
the disease since 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
