<DOCNO> AP880401-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0541EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pulitzers-Bios-Journalism     04-01 1121</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pulitzers-Bios-Journalism,1173</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bios of Pulitzer Winners in Journalism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thumbnail sketches of the 1988 Pulitzer Prize
winners in journalism:
   Dean Baquet, William Gaines and Ann Marie Lipinski of the
Chicago Tribune, winners for investigative reporting.
   Baquet, 31, joined the Tribune's metropolitan staff as an
investigative reporter in December 1984 and was promoted to
associate metro editor-chief investigative reporter in 1987. He
also worked for The Times-Picayunem _ The States-Item from 1978 to
1984. He attended Columbia University.
   Gaines, 54, won a Pulitzer Prize for investigative reporting in
1976 for his work exposing conditions at two Chicago hospitals. He
joined the Tribune in 1963 after working in radio and television
stations in Michigan and Indiana. He also was a correspondent for
The Chicago Daily News, did news documentaries for the U.S. Army in
Germany and did public relations. He graduated from Butler
University.
   Lipinski, 32, joined the Tribune staff as a summer intern in
1978 after being a summer intern the year before at The Miami
Herald; she stayed at the Tribune as a reporter in the features
department. She has won the Detroit Press Club Award and the 1981
Illinois Associated Press Editors Association Award for public
service reporting. She attended the University of Michigan.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Daniel Hertzberg and James B. Stewart of The Wall Street
Journal, winners for explanatory journalism.
   Hertzberg, 42, began his career with the Buffalo (N.Y.) Evening
News in 1968 and moved to Newsday in 1971. He joined the Journal in
1977 and in 1987 was named deputy news editor. Also in 1987, he won
a Gerald Loeb deadline-writing award with James B. Stewart for
coverage of the Ivan Boesky insider-trading scandal. He received a
bachelor's degree from the University of Chicago.
   Stewart, 36, who received a bachelor's degree from DePauw
University and a law degree from Harvard, was a lawyer and
executive editor of American Lawyer magazine before joining the
Journal in 1983, where he is a special writer. He is the author of
``The Partners'' and ``The Prosecutors.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Walt Bogdanich of The Wall Street Journal, winner for
specialized reporting.
   Bogdanich, 37, a reporter, received his bachelor's degree from
the University of Wisconsin and a master's in journalism from Ohio
State University. He was a reporter and then managing editor at the
Compass in Hammond, Ind. He also reported for the Dayton (Ohio)
Daily News, the Cleveland (Ohio) Press and the Plain Dealer
(Cleveland, Ohio). He joined the Journal as an investigative
reporter in 1984. He also has won a George Polk award and an
Overseas Press Club award.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Tim Weiner of The Philadelphia Inquirer, winner for national
reporting.
   Weiner's work for The Kansas City Times was part of the package
that garnered a general news reporting Pulitzer in 1982 for the
Times and The Kansas City Star. He joined the Inquirer in 1982. He
also has worked for The Associated Press, the Soho News and
Fairchild News Service. Weiner, 31, graduated from Columbia College
in 1978 and from Columbia University's graduate school of
journalism in 1979.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Thomas L. Friedman of The New York Times, winner for
international reporting.
   Friedman, the Times' bureau chief in Jerusalem, won a Pulitzer
Prize for international reporting in 1983 for his coverage of the
Israeli invasion of Lebanon the year before. Friedman, 34, joined
the Times in 1981 as a business reporter and was named bureau chief
in Beirut in 1982. Before the Times, Friedman worked for United
Press International. He graduated summa cum laude from Brandeis
University in 1975 and was elected to Phi Beta Kappa. He received a
master's degree from Oxford University in 1978.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jacqui Banaszynski, of the St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch,
winner for feature writing.
   Banaszynski, 35, is a special projects reporter and feature
writer for the newspaper and was a finalist for the 1986 Pulitzer
Prize in foreign reporting. She joined the paper in 1984 after
stints with the Pulaski News, the Janesville (Wis.) Gazette; the
Duluth News-Tribune & Herald; the Eugene (Ore.) Register-Guard and
the Minneapolis Star and Tribune. She won the Minnesota Press
Club's 1986 Gene O'Brien Award for Excellence in Journalism. She
graduated magna cum laude in 1974 from Marquette University.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Dave Barry of The Miami Herald, winner for commentary.
   Barry, 40, a syndicated columnist for the Herald since 1983, won
the American Society of Newspaper Editors distinguished writing
award for commentary in 1986. He was a reporter and editor at the
Daily Local News of West Chester, Pa., and was a reporter for The
Associated Press. In 1980, he began a nationally syndicated humor
column. Barry is a graduate of Haverford College.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Tom Shales of The Washington Post, winner for criticism.
   Shales, 44, the chief television critic and television editor of
the Post, joined the newspaper in 1972 as a writer in the Style
section. Before that, he was entertainment editor of the
(Washington) D.C. Examiner. He has written two books, ``The
American Film Heritage'' and ``On the Air!'' He graduated from
American University.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Jane Healy of The Orlando Sentinel, winner for editorial writing.
   Healy, 38, associate editor of the Sentinel, was a Pulitzer
finalist in 1985 for editorial writing. Healy, who has been at the
Sentinel since 1973, has won the Sigma Delta Chi Southeast first
place award for editorial writing in 1985 and 1986 and the Florida
Society of Newspaper Editors first place award for editorial
writing in 1986. She graduated from the University of Maryland.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Doug Marlette of The Atlanta Constitution and The Charlotte
Observer, winner for editorial cartooning.
   Marlette, 37, joined the Constitution in March 1987 after 15
years as editorial cartoonist for the Observer. Marlette, who has
been drawing newspaper cartoons since he was 16, also draws the
``Kudzu'' comic strip. He has won the 1986 Fischetti Award, and has
received National Headliner, Robert F. Kennedy and Sigma Delta Chi
awards.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Scott Shaw of The Odessa (Texas) American, winner for spot news
photography.
   Shaw, 24, has been a staff photographer at the Odessa American
since 1986 after working at the Paragould (Ark.) Daily Press, the
Southern Illinoisan (Carbondale, Ill.) and the Commercial News in
Danville, Ill. He has a journalism degree from Southern Illinois
University.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Michel duCille of The Miami Herald, winner for feature
photography.
   DuCille, 32, won a Pulitzer for spot news photography in 1986
and won a photojournalism award for his photo essay on the drug
crack from the National Association of Black Journalists in 1987.
He graduated from Indiana University.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Pulitzer Prize for public service was awarded to The
Charlotte Observer and the Pulitzer for general news reporting went
to the staffs of The Alabama Journal and the Lawrence (Mass.)
Eagle-Tribune. The winners were announced Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
