<DOCNO> AP880401-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0711EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pulitzers-Bios-Arts     04-01 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pulitzers-Bios-Arts,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sketches of Winners in Arts Categories</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thumbnail sketches of the 1988 Pulitzer Prize
winners in the arts:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Toni Morrison, winner in fiction for ``Beloved.'' Morrison, 57,
was born in Lorain, Ohio, attended Howard University and Cornell
University and lives in Rockland County, N.Y. An editor at Random
House, she is the author of four other novels, ``The Bluest Eye,''
``Sula,'' ``Song of Solomon,'' which won the 1978 National Book
Critics Circle Award, and ``Tar Baby.'' She wrote a play,
``Dreaming Emmett,'' produced in 1986.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Alfred Uhry, winner in drama for ``Driving Miss Daisy.'' Uhry,
51, a native of Atlanta, worked previously in the musical theater,
writing lyrics for ``Here's Where I Belong'' and lyrics and book
for ``The Robber Bridegroom,'' both collaborations with Robert
Waldman. He and Waldman had worked for Frank Loesser's publishing
company as a ``score team,'' and Uhry worked for the Goodspeed
Opera House in Connecticut restoring early musicals to their
original states. ``Driving Miss Daisy'' is the first play he wrote
alone.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Robert V. Bruce, winner in history for ``The Launching of Modern
American Science 1846-1876.'' Bruce, 64, lives in Madbury, N.H.,
and is professor emeritus at Boston University, where he has taught
since 1955 and still teaches each fall. He is author of three other
books: ``Lincoln and the Tools of War,'' ``1877: Year of
Violence,'' and ``Bell: Alexander Graham Bell and the Conquest of
Solitude.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   David Herbert Donald, winner in biography for ``Look Homeward: A
Life of Thomas Wolfe.'' Donald, 67, won the Pulitzer Prize for
biography in 1961 for ``Charles Sumner and the Coming of the Civil
War.'' Educated at Millsaps College in Jackson, Miss., and at the
University of Illinois, Donald has taught at Columbia University in
New York, Oxford, Princeton University and Johns Hopkins, where he
founded the Institute of Southern History. He lives in Lincoln,
Mass.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   William Meredith, winner in poetry for ``Partial Accounts: New
and Selected Poems.'' Meredith, 69, a professor at Connecticut
College in New London, has published six volumes of poetry. He has
been a chancellor of the Academy of American Poets since 1964 and
from 1978 through 1980 was the Consultant in Poetry to the Library
of Congress. A graduate of Princeton, he has also taught there and
at the University of Hawaii, Middlebury College and Carnegie-Mellon
University.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Richard Rhodes, winner in general non-fiction for ``The Making
of the Atomic Bomb.'' The 50-year-old Rhodes was born in Kansas
City, Kan., and educated at Yale University. He has worked as
editor at Harper's and Playboy and is the author of ``The Inland
Ground,'' ``Looking for America,'' ``The Last Safari,'' and ``Sons
of Earth,'' among other books. He has been a Guggenheim fellow, a
National Endowment for the Arts fellow and a Ford Foundation fellow.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   William Bolcom, winner in music for ``12 New Etudes for Piano.''
Bolcom, 49, was born in Seattle and now lives in Ann Arbor, Mich.,
where he is professor of composition at the University of Michigan.
He attended the University of Washington, Mills College and
Stanford University. A solo and concert pianist, his music ranges
from ragtime to the theater and from chamber to symphonic works.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Pulitzers in arts and journalism were announced Thursday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880401-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0710EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pulitzer-Finalists     04-01 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pulitzer-Finalists,0713</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Non-winning Entries Recommended by Panels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a list of non-winning finalists for the
1988 Pulitzer Prizes. Under the rules, Pulitzer juries in each
category make three recommendations without listing them in order
of preference. The Pulitzer board, which awards the prizes, can
choose a winner from outside the recommendations.
   ARTS:
   Biography _ ``Hemingway,'' by Kenneth S. Lynn; ``George
Santayana: A Biography,'' by John McCormick.
   Drama _ ``Boys' Life,'' by Howard Korder; ``Talk Radio,'' by
Eric Bogosian.
   Fiction _ ``Persian Nights,'' by Diane Johnson; ``That Night,''
by Alice McDermott.
   General non-fiction _ ``Setting Limits: Medical Goals in an
Aging Society,'' by Daniel Callahan; ``Chaos: Making a New
Science,'' by James Gleick.
   History _ ``The Fall of the House of Labor,'' by David
Montgomery; ``The Care of Strangers: The Rise of America's Hospital
System,'' by Charles E. Rosenberg.
   Music _ ``Concerto for String Quartet and Orchestra,'' by
Gunther Schuller.
   Poetry _ ``Good Woman: Poems and a Memoir 1969-1980'' and
``Next: New Poems,'' by Lucille Clifton; ``Flesh and Blood,'' by
C.K. Williams.
   JOURNALISM:
   Commentary _ Ira Berkow of The New York Times for sports
commentary; Molly Ivins of the Dallas Times Herald for columns on
social and political issues; and Michael Kinsley of United Features
Syndicate for political columns.
   Criticism _ Michael Skube of The News and Observer, Raleigh,
N.C., for book reviews; and Allan Temko, San Francisco Chronicle,
for architecture criticism.
   Editorial cartooning _ David Fitzsimmons of The Arizona Daily
Star and Don Wright of The Miami News.
   Editorial writing _ Bernard L. Stein of The Riverdale Press,
Bronx, N.Y., for editorials on a variety of issues; and Joe Dolman
of the Atlanta Journal and Constitution for editorials on the
rights of jailed Cuban refugees.
   Explanatory journalism _ Tim Weiner of The Philadelphia Inquirer
for his series on a secret Pentagon budget; and Athelia Knight of
The Washington Post for her story on a year in the life of an urban
high school.
   Feature photography _ George Widman of The Associated Press for
his photo of a homeless man in Philadelphia; and Barbara J. Ries of
USA Today for a photo taken at the Vietnam Veterans Memorial in
Washington.
   Feature writing _ Lynne Duke of The Miami Herald for her story
about a housing project overrun by crack; and John Dorschner of The
Miami Herald for stories about a neighborhood feud, police tensions
and Holocaust survivors.
   General news reporting _ The Atlanta Journal and Constitution
staff for coverage of an 11-day riot by Cuban inmates; The
Charlotte (N.C.) Observer staff for misuse of PTL ministry funds;
and Sam Stanton of The Arizona Republic for his reporting on Gov.
Evan Mecham's first year in office.
   International reporting _ Larry Olmstead of the Detroit Free
Press for reports from South Africa about the African National
Congress; and Randall Richard of The Providence (R.I.)
Journal-Bulletin for his series on Americans adopting Latin
American children.
   Investigative reporting _ Larry Copeland and Tracy Thompson of
the Atlanta Journal and Constitution for reporting on racial
injustice in Georgia's Toombs Judicial Circuit; and Carlton Smith
and Tomas Guillen of The Seattle Times for their reports on the
investigation of the Green River murders.
   National reporting _ The Atlanta Journal and Constitution staff
for its series on segregation in schools; George Anthan of The Des
Moines (Iowa) Register for stories about contaminated poultry; and
Mike Masterson, Chuck Cook and Mark Trahant of The Arizona Republic
for articles on mismanagement in federal Indian programs.
   Public service _ The Alabama Journal for its investigation of
the state's infant-mortality rate; and The Courier-Journal of
Louisville, Ky., for reporting on vote-buying and
influence-peddling in state elections.
   Specialized reporting _ Natalie Fobes of The Seattle Times for
stories and photos on the Pacific salmon's struggle to survive
man-made hazards; and the Lexington (Ky.) Herald-Leader staff for
its report on the rise and fall of a horse-breeding farm.
   Spot news photography _ Paul Vathis of The Associated Press for
photos of a Pennsylvania official who shot himself at a news
conference; and Carol Guzy and Brian Smith of The Miami Herald for
photos of the turmoil in Haiti.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
