<HEAD>Price Tag For Honduras Exercise To Top $5 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price tag for last month's deployment of
more than 3,100 American troops to Honduras is likely to be
somewhere between $5 million and $10 million, the Pentagon says.
   Spokesman Dan Howard gave the estimate Thursday but said final
figures won't be available for 30 to 60 days.
   Howard said the last soldiers from the 82nd Airborne Division
had returned home to Fort Bragg, N.C., Thursday morning and that
some ``logistical support people'' would be returning today.
   Soldiers from the 82nd Airborne and the 7th Light Infantry
Division at Fort Ord, Calif., were airlifted on March 17 and 18
after Nicaraguan troops crossed into Honduras to mount an attack on
U.S.-backed Contra guerrillas.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hospitals Won't Get Higher Medicare Payments For Anti-Clotting
Drug</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hospitals won't be getting bigger Medicare
payments to help offset the costs to treat heart attack victims
with the expensive new anti-clotting drug called TPA.
   The decision was made public Thursday in a letter from Medicare
chief William L. Roper to the American Hospital Association.
   ``There is a question as to whether the circumstances involving
TPA are so unique as to justify some special accommodation,'' Roper
wrote. ``We have concluded that they are not.''
   Hospitals have been pressing the Health Care Financing
Administration to take into account the high cost of TPA _ which
runs about $2,000 a dose _ in paying for the treatment of heart
attack victims.
   Medicare pays hospitals a flat, predetermined amount for
treatment of various illnesses rather than reimbursing hospitals
for itemized expenses used on a particular patient.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vietnam To Return More Remains Next Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The remains of 27 Americans missing since the
end of the Vietnam War will be turned over to U.S. official in
Hanoi next week and then flown to an Army identification laboratory
in Hawaii, the Pentagon says.
   The planned return of American remains is largest repatriation
by the Vietnamese government since the end of the war. Previously,
the largest turnover of remains was 26 on Aug. 14, 1985.
   U.S. officials in Hanoi will receive the remains on Wednesday.
Then they will be moved to the Army's Central Identification
Laboratory in Honolulu, Hawaii, for identification, Pentagon
spokesman Dan Howard said Thursday.
   There are currently 2,404 Americans still listed as missing in
Indochina as a result of the Vietnam War, of whom 1,767 are listed
as missing in either North or South Vietnam. Up to now, the remains
of 152 Americans have been repatriated to the United States and
subsequently identified by the laboratory.
</TEXT>
