<HEAD>USDA Employees Accuse Agency Of Racial Bias</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A racial discrimination complaint filed by
more than 100 black Agriculture Department employees alleges bias
in promotions and merit awards and claims top agency officials
ignored earlier complaints.
   The complaint, filed Thursday with the department's Equal
Employment Officer, involved grievances in the Foreign Agricultural
Service, said John Franke Jr., assistant agriculture secretary for
administration.
   The complaint, signed by a large majority of the foreign
service's fulltime black professional and clerical staff, charged
top department officials with ignoring earlier complaints regarding
placement of whites over blacks in coveted positions. The employees
said blacks continue to be denied career advancement, choice
overseas assignments and to be underrepresented in merit awards.
   USDA's foreign service promotes agricultural exports through
trade development programs and sales.
