<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Mainly on the Plains; Light Snow in Rockies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm that whipped up a tornado, hail and wind gusts up to 59
mph in Texas and New Mexico spread rain and snow today across the
Great Plains.
   A tornado touched down Thursday evening northwest of Hobbs,
N.M., damaging an unoccupied barn and house trailer.
   In northwest Texas, golfball-size hail fell near Woodrow,
Brownfield, Post and Denver City. Two inches of penny-size hail
covered the ground at Odonnell late Thursday. Lubbock recorded a
wind gust of 59 mph.
   The southerly flow of moist air from the Gulf of Mexico brought
heavy rain to some areas. More than 2.5 inches fell late Thursday
near Walnut and Cherryvale, Kan.
   Forecasters posted flash flood watches for much of southeast
Kansas, parts of Oklahoma and parts of Mississippi.
   The rainfall at Wichita Falls, Texas, brought the total rainfall
for March to 5.24 inches, its wettest month on record. The previous
record was 4.71 inches set in 1905.
   Omaha, Neb., however, had its driest March since 1910 with just
.07 inches of rain, but forecasters said substantial rainfall was
expected through Saturday.
   Snow continued this morning in parts of the southern Rockies.
Albuquerque, N.M., had 4 inches of snow on the ground by midnight
and Edgewood, N.M., had 7 inches.
   In Colorado, the storm began easing after dropping 20 inches of
snow at Rye, 15 inches at Buelah, 13 inches at Silver Cliff and 9
inches east of Salida. Seven inches fell on the Denver area.
Forecasters predicted another 1 to 4 inches of snow in Colorado
today.
   A snow advisory was posted for northwestern Kansas, and a freeze
warning was in effect in southeast Arizona above elevations of
4,000 feet.
   Today's forecast called for widespread rain and thunderstorms
across Kansas, Oklahoma, parts of Texas and the Mississippi and
Tennessee valleys; showers and a few thundershowers from the Ohio
Valley to the middle Atlantic Coast and across southern Michigan
and New York state; thunderstorms from Alabama into the western
Carolinas; snow across Colorado, northern New Mexico, parts of the
Texas and Oklahoma panhandles and northwest Kansas.
   Highs will be in the 50s or 60s in much of the nation; 30s and
40s from the central High Plains and the Texas panhandle across the
central Rockies to northern Arizona, and Michigan to northern
Minnesota; 70s and low 80s from California to the desert Southwest,
and from southern and eastern Texas across the lower Mississippi
and Tennessee valleys and the southern Appalachians to the south
Atlantic states.
   The high for the nation Thursday was 91 degrees at Presidio,
Texas.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 9
degrees at Yellowstone Park, Wyo., to 75 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 62 cloudy; Boston 44 cloudy; Buffalo 44 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 61 fair; Cincinnati 53 rain; Cleveland 41 cloudy;
Detroit 41 cloudy; Miami 72 fair; New York 45 partly cloudy;
Philadelphia 49 cloudy; Pittsburgh 53 foggy; Portland, Maine, 31
partly cloudy; Washington 53 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 30 partly cloudy; Chicago 41 partly cloudy;
Dallas-Fort Worth 65 cloudy; Denver 20 cloudy; Des Moines 47
cloudy; Indianapolis 48 rain; Kansas City 45 rain; Minneapolis-St.
Paul 30 fair; Nashville 57 rain; New Orleans 64 partly cloudy; St.
Louis 50 foggy.
   _West: Albuquerque 31 snow; Anchorage 32 cloudy; Las Vegas 46
fair; Los Angeles 58 fair; Phoenix 55 fair; Salt Lake City 35 fair;
San Diego 58 fair; San Francisco 55 fair; Seattle 46 partly cloudy.
   _Canada: Toronto 34 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
