<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FarmBurning     04-01 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Burning,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Driscoll Farmer Asks FmHA For Farm Back</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BISMARCK, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government foreclosed on his farm,
evicted him from the land and burned down his home, but Albert
Schumaker wants to buy back the place.
   ``There was just poor judgment on somebody's part'' to burn the
house down in January, Schumaker said Thursday as he asked the
Farmers Home Administration to rebuild his home and let him buy
back part of the 2,460-acre farm.
   The 58-year-old farmer, wearing a western hat and accompanied by
10 supporters, made his application at the FmHA's Burleigh County
office here.
   Schumaker said he could raise the $25,000 to $30,000 he
estimates he'll need to buy back his farmstead and 10 acres in
Driscoll, about 30 miles east of Bismarck.
   ``There (are) people pretty disgusted about the whole thing and
will put the money out,'' he said. In addition, a petition is
circulating calling for the ouster of some state and local FmHA
officials, Schumaker said.
   Schumaker, a farmer since 1959, said he hopes to eventually buy
back all the acerage he lost through foreclosure. ``I have two
boys, (ages) 32 and 36, and they were with the operation. My boys
might be eligible for a loan.''
   The FmHA acquired Schumaker's farm in March 1986 in a
foreclosure, said Burleigh County FmHA Supervisor Sterling Breuer.
Schumaker was evicted from his home in December.
   The home, a corn crib and a garage were burned Jan. 30, Breuer
said. Two barns and six steel grain bins were left standing. Breuer
said the house was destroyed because repairs to bring it in line
with agency standards would have cost too much.
   Schumaker said he didn't learn about the fire until three days
after it happened. ``That's about the last kick they can give you
after you lose a farm,'' he said.
   Schumaker said the kitchen had been remodeled, and new windows,
a furnace and water heater had been installed. ``All the neighbors
knew it was livable and a good house,'' he said.
   These days he lives in a mobile home near Driscoll, and works
for Farmers Livestock Exchange as a cattle consignor.
   Schumaker made his application under the Dwelling Retention
Program, part of the Agricultural Credit Act that Congress passed
in December calling on FmHA, the lender of last resort for farmers,
to go easier on growers behind in their payments.
   Schumaker claims the agency violated his rights to retain the
farmstead when it burned down his home.
   Bob Zimmerman, head of FmHA farmer programs in North Dakota,
said the agency would consider Schumaker's application, but said he
was unsure whether the agency was liable for rebuilding the home.
   At the time of the burning, one law was being phased out and
another was being phased in, Zimmerman said.
   FmHA had not received regulations for the dwelling retention
program, he said. The agency was told Jan. 7 to stop certain
foreclosures and liquidations, but received no instructions on
situations like Schumaker's, where land was already in FmHA hands,
Zimmerman said.
   However, Don Vig, vice chairman of the Dakota Resource Council,
an advocacy group for farmers and landowners, said FmHA should have
known about the new law when it burned Schumaker's buildings.
   ``How is it possible for employees of a federal agency to be
totally ignorant of the laws that they are supposed to be
implementing?'' asked Vig.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
