<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Motorola Overcharges,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Motorola Disciplines 59 Employees in Defense Overcharge Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCHAUMBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorola Inc., fined $16.7 million for
allegedly overbilling the government on defense contracts, said it
is disciplining 59 employees involved in the incident.
   The company notified the employees last week when the $16.7
million settlement with the government was announced, spokesman
Mario Salvadori said Thursday.
   The company said 20 managers were dismissed or had their
salaries frozen or were denied promotions. The other 39 employees
were told that if they failed to follow company rules they would be
fired.
   The $16.7 million in civil and criminal penalties and
restitution stemmed from charges that the company's Government
Electronics Group in Scottsdale, Ariz., had mischarged the
government $2.5 million on three programs in 1983.
   All of the employees investigated in the case work in Arizona.
Salvadori said he did not know how many of the managers were
dismissed. The government has said that criminal charges against
individuals are still possible.
</TEXT>
