<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0629EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NorthKorea     04-01 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-North Korea,0603</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Rejects Claims United States Planning Nuclear Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANMUNJOM, Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. Command rejected North Korean
claims today that the United States is preparing to launch a
nuclear attack from South Korea and accused the North of trying to
wreck the 1988 Olympic Games.
   United Nations representatives at a meeting of the Military
Armistice Commission ridiculed North Korean claims that U.S. forces
are using military exercises in South Korea to prepare for a
nuclear attack against the communist North.
   U.S. Navy Rear Admiral William Pendley, chief U.N. delegate,
said North Korea was trying to increase tension on the divided
Korean peninsula to undermine the Olympic Games in Seoul in
September.
   ``We can understand your need for tension _ it is part of your
effort to undermine the Olympics,'' said Pendley as the two sides
traded charges and taunts in Panmunjom, a village in the neutral
Demilitarized Zone separating the two Koreas.
   Chief North Korean delegate Maj. Gen. Li Tae Ho started the
meeting by demanding U.S. and South Korean forces halt annual
``Team Spirit'' exercises in the South involving about 200,000
troops.
   Li claimed the United States was using the exercise as a mask to
build up its forces to attack North Korea. He asserted U.S. forces
introduced a large number of nuclear weapons in recent weeks.
   ``Your wreckless war promotion has created a serious situation
on the Korean Peninsula and war could break out at any time,'' Li
said.
   North Korean military forces had been placed on alert to counter
a U.S. attack and were in ``a full combat mobilization posture .. .
to cope with the extremely dangerous situation created by your
reckless military provocations,'' Li said.
   North Korea announced the alert last week.
   Pendley said the United States had no intention of attacking
North Korea and that ``Team Spirit'' was a legal and reasonable
exercise to ensure the defense of South Korea. He repeated an offer
to let North Korean delegates observe the exercises and said the
North has always rejected the offer.
   North Korea routinely charges the United States is preparing to
launch an attack. It has also placed its forces on alert during the
``Team Spirit'' exercises in past years.
   The United States has about 40,000 troops in South Korea under a
mutual defense pact against the North. U.S. forces are reported to
have some nuclear weapons, but Washington will neither confirm nor
deny the reports.
   Pendley told reporters after the meeting that the U.N. Command
was making every effort to safeguard the Olympic Games. But he
warned the North may resort to terrorism to frighten other nations
into staying away from the Games.
   ``They may take actions to increase that tension,'' he said.
   The United States and South Korea charge North Korea was behind
the Nov. 29 bombing of a South Korean airliner in which all 115
people aboard were killed. A woman who confessed to being a North
Korean agent said she put a bomb on the plane to wreck the Olympics.
   North Korea, which denied it had anything to do with the plane
attack, is demanding to co-host the Olympics. The International
Olympic Committee and South Korea have rejected the demand, but
offered to let the north stage some events.
   The U.N. Command, consisting of the United States and 15 nations
that aided South Korea during the Korean War, meets with North
Korean and Chinese delegates to police the cease-fire signed in
Panmunjom that ended the war in 1953.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
