<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0630EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Biaggi-Wedtech     04-01 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Biaggi-Wedtech,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wedtech Witness Says Company Plotted Problmes for Competitors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Wedtech Corp. executive says he plotted
with a onetime aide to then-presidential counselor Edwin Meese III
to cause legal problems for the defense contractor's competitors.
   Under cross-examination by defense attorneys Thursday,
ex-Wedtech Vice Chairman Mario Moreno conceded that the now-defunct
company used Reagan administration connections to have the
government investigate rivals for no-bid contracts.
   However, Moreno denied getting Wedtech competitors indicted
through political connections.
   Moreno testified at the trial of Rep. Mario Biaggi, D-N.Y., and
six others charged with turning the Bronx defense contractor into a
racketeering enterprise that paid millions in bribes. The trial was
recessed until Monday.
   Moreno testified about James Jenkins, who was a top aide to
Attorney General Meese when Meese was counselor to President Reagan.
   When defense attorney Dominic Amorosa asked whether Jenkins had
told him a Wedtech competitor ``was also going to run into some
serious legal difficulties,'' Moreno said he had.
   ``In fact, you testified on prior examination here that you and
Jenkins sat down and agreed to come to limit the competitors to
two, to get a particular contract, and whoever the other one was,
was going to end up in serious investigative problems, correct?''
asked Amorosa.
   Moreno hesitated, then replied, ``Yes.''
   Jenkins, who became a Wedtech consultant after leaving the White
House, has not been charged with wrongdoing.
   Wedtech grew from a small machine shop into a
multimillion-dollar manufacturer through a federal program that set
aside non-competitive contracts for companies controlled by
minority group members.
   Prosecutors contend that Biaggi and others helped Wedtech
falsely portray itself as a minority concern eligible for the
program.
   Defense lawyers are trying to show that Wedtech officials
corrupted numerous administration officials, and didn't the help of
Biaggi, a Democratic congressman from the Bronx, to obtain
government contracts.
   Amorosa ticked off a list of politically connected people who
got jobs with Wedtech: E. Robert Wallach, Meese's former attorney;
Jenkins; former Reagan political adviser Lyn Nofziger and
Nofziger's business partner, Mark Bragg.
   ``These people,'' asked Amorosa, ``had the ability to get people
indicted, didn't they?''
   ``I believe so,'' Moreno replied.
   But he repeatedly denied asking Bragg to have Wedtech
competitors indicted.
   ``We asked to have them investigated _ for any skeletons in
their closet,'' insisted Moreno, one of four ex-Wedtech executives
who pleaded guilty to state and federal charges and agreed to
testify for the prosecution in exchange for leniency.
   Pressed by Amorosa, Moreno conceded that Bragg, while not a
member of the Justice Department, knew a Wedtech competitor would
be indicted before the indictment was made public.
   Moreno said only one competitor was indicted and that was for
matters unrelated to Wedtech.
   Nofziger was convicted in February in Washington of illegal
lobbying for Wedtech. Bragg was acquitted on related charges.
   Meese has not been charged with any wrongdoing, although a
special prosecutor in Washington continues to investigate his
dealings with Wedtech.
</TEXT>
