<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0640EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Ethiopia-Rebels     04-01 0508</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ethiopia-Rebels,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Mengistu Says Troops Fighting ``Grim Battles'' With
Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebels claimed they captured three
towns in northern Ethiopia and state-owned radio quoted President
Mengistu Haile Mariam as saying his troops were fighting ``grim
battles'' with the insurgents.
   It was believed to be the first time Mengistu has conceded
publicly that the secessionist rebels are in any way effective.
   Radio Ethiopia on Thursday quoted him as saying rebels had
launched a ``systematic and highly destructive campaign'' in the
Tigre and neighboring Eritrea provinces, disrupting transport and
communications networks.
   It was the first comment by the Marxist government on reports of
a new rebel offensive, which also resulted in the capture last week
of three Soviet military advisers to the Ethiopian army.
   The fighting has aggravated relief efforts in the north, the
worst-hit drought region of Ethiopia. Most of the 6 to 7 million
Ethiopians threatened with starvation this year live in the north.
   Because of rebel activities, the Soviet-backed government often
closes roads in the region, cutting off truck convoys.
   Assesa Mamo, North American representative of the Tigre People's
Liberation Front, claimed the rebels took the towns of Axum and
Adowa on Thursday after a three-day battle. He spoke from
Washington in a telephone interview with The Associated Press
bureau in Nairobi, Kenya.
   Axum is 110 miles south of Asmara, Eritrea's provincial capital,
and Adowa is 30 miles from Axum.
   Eritrean rebels said Sunday they captured the town of Afabet,
killing or capturing 18,000 Ethiopian troops. The rebels said one
Soviet officer was killed and three taken prisoner. Afabet is 100
miles north of Asmara.
   The rebels claimed to have wiped out three government divisions
and captured tanks, weapons and other military equipment worth
millions of dollars.
   There was no way to verify the rebels' claims. But Western
diplomats in Addis Ababa said the figure of 18,000 troops, a third
of troops stationed in the north, sounded preposterous.
   The Soviet Union confirmed three of its advisers were captured,
but said nothing of a fourth officer being killed.
   Mengistu made his comments about the rebels in a report to the
eighth regular meeting of the Central Committee of his Marxist
Workers' Party of Ethiopia.
   Western diplomats, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
Mengistu's statement indicated the fighting must be serious. They
said there were reports the Ethiopian leader is preparing a huge
counteroffensive against rebels of the Eritrea People's Liberation
Front and the Tigre rebel group.
   Mengistu inherited the insurgencies 13 years ago when, with a
group of army officers, he dethroned Emperor Haile Selassie and
helped set up a Marxist government.
   Eritrean rebels have been fighting for 27 years in Africa's
oldest civil war.
   The U.N. World Food Program reported Thursday that a relief
convoy reached the town of Wukro in Tigre province, bringing the
first major food delivery to the drought-stricken area since
January.
   The emergency shipment of 1,500 metric tons, enough to feed
100,000 people for a month, arrived March 24, said David Morton,
the U.N. representative in Ethiopia.
</TEXT>
