<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-GoodFriday 1stLd-Writethru a0501 04-01 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Good Friday, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0501,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pilgrims Crowd Old City For Good Friday, Though Attendance Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with Israeli police sergeant
stabbed in Old City. Picks up 5th graf pvs ```We planned... </NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Smaller than normal crowds of Christian
pilgrims today carried wooden crosses and sang psalms in the Old
City's Via Dolorosa to commemorate Good Friday, the anniversary of
Jesus' crucifixion.
   Twenty yards away from the street, an Arab attacker stabbed an
Israeli police sergeant in the stomach. The officer was
hospitalized in fair condition. Police apprehended a suspect and
cordoned off the area.
   Arab unrest in the Israeli-occupied territories has prompted
many pilgrims to stay away this year.
   The Greek Orthodox Patriarch of Jerusalem canceled three
pre-Easter processions scheduled for today and Saturday out of
concern for the pilgrims' safety and due to an expected sharp drop
in the number of tourists.
   But the Old City was more alive than it has been for weeks and
many of the hundreds of tourists visiting the 12th century Church
of the Holy Sepulchre said the event was a special one. The church
marks the spot where Jesus was crucified and, as Christians
believe, resurrected.
   ``We planned to come here for a long time and nothing could stop
us, even friends who said we were crazy,'' said David Reid of
Mountain Lakes, N.J. ``There are lots of police around and we are
as safe here as we are in New York City.''
   Dozens of Israeli riot police stood guard along the route, some
munching the unleavened matzoh crackers Jews eat during the week of
Passover, which begins today.
   The Via Dolorosa, or Way of Sorrow, marks the path where Jesus,
wearing a crown of thorns, was forced to carry the cross on which
he was later crucified. The tradition of following the devotional
walk was started in the 14th century by the Franciscans, a Roman
Catholic order.
   Today, the via is a narrow cobblestone street crowded with shops
which passes by several Moslem mosques. Christians singing and
praying walked down the street, along with priests who carried
ornate silver and gold crosses and burned incense.
   The Church of the Holy Sepulchre was built on the site where
Jesus is believed to have been crucified and buried, and where he
is said to have risen from the dead two days later, an event
commemorated on Easter.
   The spot of the crucifixion is marked on the church's second
floor by an ornate gold table and a figure of Jesus, lit only by
candles.
   Downstairs, pilgrims kissed and threw water on the rock marking
the spot where Jesus's body was washed before burial. Sixteen choir
boys in long black robes sang prayers.
   Arab merchants opened their shops for the three hours permitted
by the Palestine Liberation Organization and did brisk business
selling solid olive-wood crosses.
   But Christian church officials were predicting the violence in
the occupied territories would trigger a sharp decline in tourism.
   The Rev. Timoteus Margaritis, a spokesman for the Greek Orthodox
Christian Church, said 1,500 pilgrims were expected to attend his
church's April 10 Easter Service, instead of the usual 10,000.
   Tourism figures, however, have also become part of the
Arab-Israeli conflict, with Israeli officials reluctant to
acknowledge an adverse impact of the conflict in the territories.
   Tourism Ministry officials said more visitors came to Israel in
January and February as compared with the previous year, but said
13 percent fewer tourists entered the country during the first week
in March.
   ``We are concerned about the coming months, April, May and June,
when we do expect a slight drop,'' said Micha Dedron, who added
that the most serious decline in tourism was among U.S. Jews.
</TEXT>
