<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     04-01 0448</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A high school football coach chose the
50-yard line of Capital Studium to marry a former cheerleader _ but
before the nuptials were over he was called offsides for making a
premature pass at the bride.
   When Steve Ash, 38, an assistant football coach at Rickards High
School, asked Lora Kyle to marry him on Valentine's Day, he had
more than one proposal to make.
   ``I'm a coach, she was a cheerleader, we both love sports, and
we both think that a marriage should be fun and make you laugh, so
why not have a wedding that does the same thing?'' Ash said.
   ``I never thought it would get this big,'' Ms. Kyle, 35, said
through clenched teeth moments before her wedding.
   ``Good evening ladies and gentlemen, and welcome to Capital
Stadium,'' Jeff Duke announced over the public address system.
After introducing all the second-stringers who helped, Duke gave
the starting lineup.
   ``Direct your attention to the south end zone, where standing
tall at 5-feet-9-inches and weighing in at 195, starting at groom
from Steer Creek, W.Va., Steve Ash.''
   Ash then burst through a paper banner with a pink tuxedo painted
on it and ran to the 50-yard line.
   ``And now, in the north end zone, a 5-3, 130-pound former
cheerleader from Smith Creek, Fla., starting at bride, Lora Kyle.''
   Ms. Kyle then jumped through a similar banner with a pink hat
painted on it.
   But as the knot was being tied an overzealous Ash tried to steal
a kiss from his bride and the Rev. Chuck Groover objected.
   ``That's offsides. You're supposed to wait,'' Groover said.
``You're not supposed to kiss her until I say so.''
   A five-second penalty followed after which the real kiss was
exchanged as hundreds of blue and white helium balloons were
released.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MONTESANO, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pssst, wanna buy a bridge? Grays Harbor
County has one for sale and it's a bargain. It's free.
   There's just one catch: the purchaser has to take the 120-foot
span apart, move it and repair it, according to county records.
   Among other things, the bridge on the Olympic Peninsula needs
new deck planks, the metal truss work needs paint and the new owner
should know the wooden stringers have a life expectancy of 10-15
years.
   The 14-foot-wide bridge, built in 1915, cannot support current
legal loads and is to be replaced next year by a two-lane bridge.
   The span was placed on the National Register of Historic Places
in 1980, preventing the county from simply tearing it down without
trying to find the bridge a new home.
   So far, there have been no takers.
</TEXT>
