<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Pulitzers-Weekly 1stLd-Writethru a0509 04-01 0609</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pulitzers-Weekly, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0509,0623</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>For Second Year, Weekly Co-Publisher Falls Just Short Of Pulitzer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to restore dropped word; SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT,
three finalists sted two, since winner was also a finalist, and
that finalists were not `chosen' Thursday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE NEUMEISTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The co-publisher of a small Bronx weekly
newspaper finished as a finalist for a Pulitzer Prize this year for
the second time and conceded it's getting ``a little frustrating.''
   ``I'd like to win it,'' said Bernard Stein after learning
Thursday he had been one of three finalists for the Pulitzer in
editorial writing for his work on The Riverdale Press, circulation
14,000.
   He credits some of his success to what he learns through daily
reporting, a necessity for even the bosses at a paper with a news
staff of six.
   When he's not solving problems faced by weekly newspaper
publishers, such as choosing what computers to buy or deciding how
to patch a hole in the roof, he might be found at the Wedtech
trial, where he was Thursday when Pulitzers were passed out.
   ``I report a lot, walking with my own feet, seeing with my own
eyes and talking to people. I think a good editorial writer has to
be a good reporter,'' he said.
   Last year, Stein entered the contest ``on a whim.''
   ``This year, I thought maybe there was some serious possibility.
It still feels wonderful,'' he said.
   Stein's editorials on a variety of issues earned him a spot as a
finalist along with Joe Dolman of the Atlanta Journal and
Constitution for his editorials on the rights of jailed Cuban
refugees.
   Jane Healy of The Orlando Sentinel won the prize for editorials
protesting overdevelopment in Orange County, Fla.
   Stein has a love-hate relationship with some of his neighbors
for controversial stands he has taken, including one that so irked
Mayor Edward I. Koch that Koch invited him to lunch to discuss the
subject of housing with him.
   In February, Stein criticized Israel's policies in the occupied
territory and drew plenty of hate mail from his readers, many of
whom are Jewish.
   ``I think you have to take a stand,'' said the 46-year-old
Riverdale community resident who was arrested along with more than
800 others on Dec. 3, 1964 during a free speech rally in the
administration building at the University of California at Berkeley.
   Tom Watson, the paper's deputy editor, said he is ``somewhat in
awe'' of Stein, who has helped train journalists who now work at
The New York Times, the Los Angeles Times, USA Today and the
Detroit News, among others.
   ``He basically is a great teacher,'' Watson said. ``He likes to
call this the best graduate journalism program in New York state.''
   Stein, who helped found Students for a Democratic Society at
Berkeley, said he fights for ``the principle that ordinary people
can make the decisions that affect their lives.
   ``I try to give them the information they need to do that. I
have an absolute commitment to free speech. That's why I published
every letter I get, including racist and sexist letters, as long as
they're not libelous,'' he said.
   And, he said, the readers showed their appreciation after he was
named a finalist last year.
   ``Neighbors, people I'd meet at the shopping center, would stop
me at the street to say they felt it was their prize too,'' he
recalled. ``Hundreds of people wrote me letters to say they felt
they had a share in it and they were immensely proud to live in
Riverdale because The Riverdale Press came so close to a Pulitzer.''
</TEXT>
