<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-AprilFool's     04-01 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-April Fool's,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>April 1 Story Says Baseball Stadium Sits on Burial Ground</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's leading English-language newspaper reported
today that Tokyo's new baseball stadium would have to be moved
because it sits on an ancient Shinto burial ground. Failure to
relocate the 56,000-seat stadium would cause the Yomiuri Giants to
finish last this year, it warned.
   April Fool.
   But officials in the office of the just-opened Tokyo Dome,
Japan's first covered stadium, weren't laughing. They were busy
advising callers the story was an April Fool's Day joke.
   Callers weren't amused either. Japanese take baseball seriously.
And the Yomiuri Giants just don't expect to finish in last place.
   The story in the independent Japan Times said a Shinto priest
had discovered after the stadium opened in March that the
oval-shaped ``Big Egg'' was built partially on a Shinto burial
ground.
   The priest predicted the Giants, which share the stadium with
the Nippon Ham Fighters, would finish last in their division if the
stadium were not moved 40 yards to the north.
   Engineers had offered two solutions, the Times said. Some
preferred filling the domed stadium with helium gas and letting it
float the 40 yards. Others suggested that with the Japanese
tradition of hard work and with lots of and with lots of overtime,
the stadium could be dismantled and rebuilt on safe ground in time
for the April 8 season opener.
   A Times staffer told The Associated Press only that the
newspaper had received numerous inquiries, including a call from
the company that built the stadium, asking if the story were true.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
