<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AmtrakIndictment     04-01 0333</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Amtrak Indictment,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Conrail Engineer Indicted By Federal Grand Jury</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VALERIE MEEHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury has indicted a former
Conrail engineer involved in an Amtrak crash that killed 16 people
on charges including lying to investigators about taking drugs the
day of the accident.
   Rick L. Gates, 33, of Essex, was charged Thursday with one count
of conspiracy, one count of obstruction of an agency investigation
and two counts of making false statements, U.S. Attorney
Breckinridge Willcox said.
   Gates missed a track signal while operating a string of three
Conrail locomotives and drove them into the path of a speeding
passenger train.
   The accident, the worst in Amtrak's history, also injured 175
people.
   The indictment alleges Gates lied under oath to National
Transportation Safety Board investigators on Jan. 7, 1987, three
days after the crash in suburban Baltimore County, when he said he
had not consumed any drugs that day.
   Gates, however, shared a marijuana cigarette with brakeman
Edward Cromwell that day, according to the statement of facts read
into the record when Gates pleaded guilty to a state charge in
Baltimore County Circuit Court Feb. 17.
   The new indictment also alleges Gates falsely testified about
the status of the signals in the locomotives and along the tracks
and about what pre-departure tests he conducted.
   The conspiracy count alleges he joined with Cromwell to
fabricate a story about what happened.
   Cromwell cooperated in the state investigation and is expected
to testify against Gates at the federal trial, Willcox said.
Cromwell was granted immunity from prosecution by state and federal
prosecutors, Willcox said.
   Gates was the only person named in the indictment. If convicted,
he faces a maximum of five years in prison and a $250,000 fine on
each count.
   On Tuesday, Gates was sentenced to five years in prison and
fined $1,000 on a state misdemeanor charge of manslaughter by
locomotive.
   The NTSB had no comment on the indictments, an agency
spokeswoman said.
</TEXT>
