<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DJ-AprilFools'     04-01 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-DJ-April Fools',0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disc Jockey's Joke Results In Flurry Of Calls</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCIA DUNN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A disc jockey's April Fools' Day joke about a
mysterious rumble and flash of light in a popular suburban park
resulted in a flurry of calls today from listeners claiming to have
witnessed the event.
   ``People are seeing it. But it ain't there,'' said Fred
Honsberger, news director for Pittsburgh's KDKA-AM.
   ``We just had a lady call who said she saw a bunch of gray
trucks go in led by a jeep. These people are claiming to have seen
that thing. But we started it all,'' Honsberger said, chuckling.
   Another caller, he said, wanted to know, ``Who's going to pay
for the military going out there? Who's going to pay for all this?'
''
   Morning disc jockey John Cigna jolted some of his sleepy
listeners when he said his house shook early today and dishes
rattled. He said he saw a flash of light in North Park, noticed a
lot of activity and wondered what was going on.
   ``The place is cordoned off. You can't get into the park,''
Cigna said in a calm voice, introducing a man on the telephone as
Colonel Charles Bradshaw.
   ``Is that a UFO? Is that a saucer that's down?'' Cigna asked.
   ``I can't divulge any information,'' the man replied, saying
only that it was an ``item.''
   Dozens of nervous listeners called the Pennsylvania Association
for the Study of the Unexplained in nearby Greensburg to learn
more. After an hour of checking, the association determined it was,
indeed, an April Fools' Day joke.
   ``Unfortunately, when things like this happen, it takes away
from the legitimacy of the callers who see things that are unusual
and can't be explained. It helps to bring back the ridicule
problem,'' said Stan Gordon, the association's director.
   Honsberger said none of the morning news reports included the
so-called emergency.
   ``That should be a clue to anybody,'' Honsberger said. ``If
anything was happening, it would be our lead story. We'd have
reporters there.''
   Despite the incongruity of it all, callers swamped the
switchboard at the radio station as well as its television
affiliate.
   ``It's all because of April Fools','' Tom Trukula, an intern at
KDKA-TV, explained as he fielded telephone calls.
   ``They are not really mad,'' he said.
   But Allegheny County police officers stationed at the park
weren't laughing. They, too, spent the morning responding to
queries, mostly from reporters wanting to know if anything really
was happening.
   ``There's nothing going on,'' assured Sgt. William Wolverton,
``so nobody should be frightened.''
   Last year on April Fools' Day, Cigna said on the air that an
alligator was lurking in Pittsburgh's sewer system. To solve the
pesky problem, he asked listeners to flush their toilets at the
same time.
   ``A lot of people did,'' Honsberger said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
