<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Obit-Minne     04-01 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Minne,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Joris Minne, Belgian Sculptor, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANTWERP, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joris Minne, the Belgian engraver and
sculptor credited with helping revive the art of engraving, has
died, his family announced today.
   Minne died Thursday at 91. The cause of death was not announced.
   Minne and four other Flemish graphic artists, Frans Masereel,
Henri Van Straten, Jan-Frans Cantre and Joseph Cantre, founded the
art magazine ``Lumiere'' in the 1920s. The magazine was a key force
in generating new interest and techniques in wood engraving.
   The five artists were credited with popularizing in the early
20th century the art of wood, copper and linoleum engraving.
   Minne was considered a pioneer of modern wood and copper
engraving. He was also a gifted drawer and painter.
   His sculpting career began in 1939, but he only won widespread
recognition in 1950 with an exhibition in Antwerp's Middelheimpark.
He mainly sculpted wood.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
