<DOCNO> AP880401-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0944EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-India-Sikhs 1stLd-Writethru   04-01 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Sikhs, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0465,0628</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sikh Attacks Take 33 Lives</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede AMRITSAR</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to ADD detail on attacks with executions,
women and child killed. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DEEPAK SHARMA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANGOTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh militants lined up and executed
people in a courtyard near this Hindu village, police said today.
They were among 33 killed in the Punjab state's worst outbreak of
religious violence this year.
   Thursday's attacks came hours after an umbrella organization
spearheading the movement to establish a Sikh homeland in the
northern Punjab state called for an end to killings of moderate
Sikhs.
   It was the bloodiest single day of such violence this year and
brought the number of people killed in such attacks this week to
more than 80. Most of the killings have been near Amritsar, the
site of the Golden Temple, the Sikhs' holiest shrine and a center
for militants.
   Authorities blamed the latest spate of violence on differences
within militant groups and attempts to sabotage government moves to
reach an accord with militants.
   Authorities said 25 people died in three separate attacks near
Pangota, 25 miles north of Amritsar, and eight died elsewhere in
the Punjab violence.
   Eighteen people died in a hamlet outside Pangota, when 12
militants stormed the huts of a Hindu work commune, local police
officer S.S. Virk said. Most of the victims were dragged out of
their homes at gunpoint, lined up in a courtyard and shot, he said.
   The gunmen also killed a pregnant woman, her 6-month-old
daughter, and her 80-year-old mother-in-law at their home, Virk
said. The militants had wanted to drag the family away like the
others but found they could not walk, he said.
   Seven militants fired Chinese-made AK-47 rifles at a family
sleeping in the courtyard of their home, local Police
Superintendent Izhar Alam said.
   At least six other victims were women. The victims, migrants
from neighbouring Haryana state, were all related, Virk said.
   At Shaeed village, six miles west of Pangota, another group of
militants gunned down five Hindus, including three women and a
two-year-old boy. The militants entered the homes of the victims
and shot them in their beds, Virk said.
   The militants then shot and killed a Sikh couple in nearby
Verowal town, Virk said.
   Elsewhere in Punjab, three members of a Sikh family were killed
in the central Kapurthala district, said a police officer in the
state capital of Chandigarh, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
The United News of India news agency said the victims were
militants killed in factional rivalry.
   Two deaths each were reported from Gurdaspur and Bhatinda
districts and one person was shot and killed in Ropar district in
the east, the officer said.
   Earlier Thursday, the underground Council of Khalistan had
called on militant groups to cease random killings of Sikhs. At
least 330 of the 616 people killed this year in attacks blamed on
the Sikh extremists have been Sikhs who oppose the demand for a
separate state.
   Khalistan is the name militants give to the homeland they want.
   Sikhs form 2 percent of India's 800 million people but are in a
majority in Punjab state. The militants have been agitating for a
separate state since 1983, claiming discrimination by the Hindus,
who comprise 80 percent of India's 750 million people.
   The government last month released 12 Sikh leaders jailed for
sedition and dissolved the Punjab state assembly in what was seen
as an attempt to enroll the militants in political processes.
   But sources in the Golden Temple, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said some militants opposed the peace plan since it
would not give the Sikhs total autonomy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
