<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1000EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Thai-Border     04-01 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thai-Border,0337</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Aid Officials Take Precautions Following Attack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ENG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western officials helping refugees on
the Thai-Cambodian border will travel only with armed escort after
a British nurse was held hostage and a firefight killed two people,
an aid official said today.
   Officials of the U.N. Border Relief Operation and cooperating
voluntary agencies made the decision Thursday night, said Stephen
Goode, director of the aid agency Youth With A Mission.
   He said workers would travel to and from refugee camps with Thai
security escort until the measure was reviewed Saturday. Also, all
non-essential services to the camps were suspended until that
review, he said.
   During the attack Thursday, an assailant hijacked an UNBRO truck
and forced the driver to stop a pickup truck belonging to Youth
With a Mission, according to Goode and Western aid officials.
   The assailant held an automatic weapon to the head of Sally
Rymer, a 29-year-old midwife from Yorkshire who has been working
for Youth With a Mission on the border since 1985. Three defense
volunteers who had been alerted by other aid workers pursued the
pickup in a motorcycle, and a shootout followed.
   The attacker killed one Thai village defense volunteer and
injured two others before a Thai driver for the agency shot and
killed him.
   The assailant remained unidentified, but was thought to be
Cambodian since he didn't speak Thai well, Goode said. At one
point, the assailant asked for money, but the motive for the attack
remained unclear.
   Thai and Cambodian bandits roam the border, but few attacks have
involved Western aid workers. Unlike most previous incidents, this
one occurred in broad daylight, on the main road to Site Two camp.
   Site Two is the largest border refugee camp, housing 162,000
Cambodians who fled economic hardship and a guerrilla war against
occupying Vietnamese troops. It is in Thailand's Prachinburi
province and about 50 miles north of the key Thai border town of
Aranyaprathet.
</TEXT>
