<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BikiniFuror     04-01 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bikini Furor,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bikini Contest Canceled After Angry Women Protest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sponsor's withdrawal following protests
by women students caused the cancellation of a fund-raising bikini
contest planned by a University of Massachusetts fraternity.
   The makers of Miller Lite beer withdrew their sponsorship hours
before the contest was to begin Thursday night, said Joe Giarusso,
assistant general manager of the off-campus Pink Cadillac bar.
   ``There are no prizes and the event has been canceled,'' said
Giarusso, who refused further comment.
   Thirty-four students had signed a petition denouncing the
contest, which protester Becky Lockwood called dehumanizing.
   But fraternity brothers at Delta Upsilon said they didn't
understand the furor.
   ``It's ridiculous,'' said fraternity President Paul Kearney.
``Why should they be upset if it's a fund-raiser? They do it
everywhere else. If they go to the beach, are they going to call
that sexist too?''
   Robert O'Brien, chairman of the fraternity's fund-raising
committee, said proceeds of the contest were to be used for the
fraternity's yearly beer keg roll, a charity event that raised
$3,000 for the Jimmy Fund last year.
   The Jimmy Fund, the official charity of the Boston Red Sox,
raises money to fight cancer in children.
   The fraternity circulated fliers last week announcing, ``Delta
Upsilon & The Jimmy Fund in association with the Amherst Police
Dept. present First Annual Bikini Contest.''
   But Jimmy Fund associate director Michael Rafferty said he knew
nothing of the contest and asked the fraternity not to use its name
for the event.
   Amherst police Chief Donald Maia had accepted an invitation to
be master of ceremonies at the contest but changed his mind over
the weekend, saying the contest was no longer a beauty pageant and
his presence would be inappropriate.
</TEXT>
