<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Carlucci     04-01 0154</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Carlucci,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Defense Secretary In Morocco</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARRAKECH, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci said
today the United States would continue its close cooperation with
the moderate Arab government of Morocco.
   Carlucci began a three-day visit that was to include tours of
Moroccan military bases. On Sunday, he will fly to India and then
visit Pakistan and Tunisia before returning to Washington.
   On arrival, he praised ``the close links that have united our
two countries in the course of the past two centuries.''
   ``I am convinced that this cooperation with continue in the
future in the interest of our two countries and our two peoples,''
he said.
   American aid to Morocco in 1987 was $131 million, $35 million of
which was to help the government in its 13-year-long war against
Polisario guerrillas fighting for the independence of the former
Spanish Sahara.
   The defense secretary is to return to Washington on April 9.
</TEXT>
