<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1042EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mother'sSuit     04-01 0269</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mother's Suit,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Sues Bank In Credit Card Hassle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman is suing the Bank of Boston for more than
$2 million, claiming the bank's refusal to honor her credit card
caused a hotel in the Philippines to seize her baby son until the
bill was paid.
   A judge earlier this week turned down the bank's motion to
dismiss the claims by Maria Luz Delulis, 39, of Lynn, said her
lawyer, Benjamin Glosband.
   Bank officials say Delulis had asked them to stop use of the
card.
   According to The Boston Herald, Delulis and her two children
were staying at the Royal Palm Hotel in Manila in December 1986.
   ``When it came time to check out, I presented my card from the
bank,'' she told the newspaper. ``After a delay, the clerk told me
it was invalid and refused to accept it.''
   She said hotel officials confiscated the card and took her to a
local police station.
   ``When I got back, the hotel manager told me my children could
not leave the hotel until the ($260) bill was paid,'' she said.
   Delulis said the manager later agreed to turn over her older
boy, but held onto her youngest son, William, then 7 months, as
collateral.
   She said she eventually got her children back after tourism
officials and the U.S. Embassy intervened.
   ``I became very traumatized and was unable to take care of my
business,'' Delulis said in the court papers. ``I was depressed and
am still under the treatment of a psychologist.''
   Bank spokesman Wayne Taylor said Thursday bank lawyers believe
Delulis' claims are groundless.
</TEXT>
