<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan House, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0547,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nancy Reagan Tours Bel Air `Gift' Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with first lady's press
secretary saying Mrs. Reagan had seen the house before. Picks up
3rd graf, `The house ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First lady Nancy Reagan toured the $2.5
million home she and the president will share when the couple
leaves the White House.
   Mrs. Reagan, her press secretary, Elaine Crispen, and others in
her entourage didn't stop to meet with reporters when they visited
the mansion Thursday afternoon.
   Mrs. Reagan, who arrived in Los Angeles on Wednesday, checked
into the Beverly Wilshire Hotel. She was in town to see the house
and to take care of ``some business and tasks that she has to
perform,'' said Wendy Toler, the first lady's deputy press
secretary.
   Ms. Crispen said the first lady had seen the house before but
was taking another look while in town.
   The house has three bedrooms, six baths, guest room, living
room, family room, sun room, butler's pantry and three servants'
rooms. It's tucked away on a 1\-acre estate in exclusive Bel Air,
12 miles northwest of downtown Los Angeles.
   The Reagans' future home sits next door to the Kirkeby estate,
where the ``Beverly Hillbillies'' was filmed. Television producer
Jerry Perenchio recently bought Kirkeby for more than $13 million.
   The Reagans also will be neighbors to such entertainers as
Elizabeth Taylor, Joan Rivers, Zsa Zsa Gabor, Mac Davis and Burt
Bacharach.
   The president and his wife signed a three-year lease on the
ranch house within the last two weeks, Elaine Crispen, the first
lady's press secretary, said earlier this week. The house is owned
by Wall Management Services, a group of about 20 friends of the
Reagans who bought it with them in mind, she said.
   The three-year agreement gives the Reagans the option to renew
the lease or buy the property. The identity of the Wall Management
individuals and the amount of the lease payments were not disclosed.
</TEXT>
