<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Rebels     04-01 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Rebels,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Rebels, Two Soldiers Killed In Clash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist rebels and soldiers fought
a four-hour battle that left four rebels and two soldiers dead, the
government-owned news agency reported today.
   The Philippine News Agency said three other rebels were wounded
and captured during the battle Thursday near the town of Guagua,
about 40 miles northeast of Manila. Two other soldiers were wounded.
   The encounter began around noon when some 30 New People's Army
guerrillas opened fire on a government patrol sent to verify
reports that rebels had been sighted in the area, the agency said.
   On Wednesday, security forces captured seven top communist
leaders in raids on two rebel hideouts in suburban Manila. Those
arrested included Romulo Kintanar, the alleged guerrilla commander;
Rafael Baylosis, secretary general of the Communist Party of the
Philippines; and Central Committee member Benjamin de Vera.
   President Corazon Aquino hailed the arrests as a major victory
and said it showed her government had turned the tide against the
rebels in their 19-year insurgency.
</TEXT>
