<DOCNO> AP880401-0101 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1115EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan 2ndLd-Writethru a0571 04-01 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0571,650</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs pvs graf 6, Fitzwater outlined, with six new grafs to
include IRS statement.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan left today for a 10-day
Easter holiday after ordering new steps to force the ouster of
Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega by tightening the
economic screws on his government.
   Shortly before departing for his California ranch, Reagan also
signed a $48 million humanitarian aid bill providing supplies to
Nicaragua's Contra rebels and medical care to war-injured children.
   The measure received final approval in the Senate on Thursday on
an 87-7 vote. Reagan signed the bill in his residence with no
fanfare. The signing was announced by a brief executive order
delegating responsibilities to various agencies to carry out
provisions of the law.
   Reagan, dogged in recent days about his embattled attorney
general, Edwin Meese III, and resignations at the Justice
Department, did not make any appearance in public Thursday and will
remain largely out of sight until April 10.
   His only appearance will be at a fund-raising event Monday in
Newport Beach, south of Los Angeles, for the Ronald Reagan library.
Construction on the library is expected to begin this summer at a
site in Ventura County.
   As part of the economic pressure against Noriega, the Internal
Revenue Service said today that American corporations' tax payments
to the government of Eric Arturo Delvalle, whom the United States
recognizes as president of Panama, will qualify for the U.S.
foreign tax credit.
   The announcement cleared the way for U.S. firms that operate in
Panama to pay taxes into a special account at the Federal Reserve
Bank of New York without jeopardizing the tax credit. The credit is
designed to avoid taxation of the same dollar of income by the
United States and a foreign country.
   The action cuts off a source of cash to the financially strapped
Noriega regime. The Reagan administration has expressed concern
that a recent infusion of cash, some of it from U.S. corporate tax
payments, may have temporarily strengthened Noriega's hold.
   Delvalle issued a decree on March 25 directing that income taxes
due the government of Panama be paid only to a New York Federal
Reserve Bank.
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, who outlined the series
of actions against Panama on Thursday, said he did know how much
money would be involved by the IRS step, but estimated it could
deprive Noriega of ``millions and millions.''
   The IRS announcement was one of a series of measures to deprive
Noriega's government of money from American companies and
individuals. Fitzwater said the administration would consider
making the measures mandatory if voluntary action proves
insufficient.
   The action follows the disclosure that some American firms _
including Texaco Inc. and Eastern Airlines _ paid taxes and fees
owed to Panama for doing business there, undercutting the economic
sanctions imposed by the United States on Panama.
   Announcing the new action, Fitzwater said, ``we are giving U.S.
companies and persons an incentive and opportunity not to provide
financial support to the Noriega regime.
   ``Should these measures prove insufficient, we will review
additional legal steps that may be necessary to deny transfer of
funds to the Noriega regime from U.S. companies and persons,''
Fitzwater said.
   Noriega is under indictment in the United States on drug
trafficking charges. As chief of the 15,000-member Defense Forces,
he is the power behind Panama's civilian government, although the
United States recognizes Eric Arturo Delvalle _ who is in hiding _
as the legitimate leader.
   Fitzwater said U.S. government payments owed the government of
Panama will be deposited in the Federal Reserve Bank in New York.
The United States already is withholding canal fees, toll payments
and other funds. Fitzwater said withholding taxes for U.S.
employees in Panama and rental payments also will go in the new
account.
   He also said the Justice Department will take part in legal
cases by private parties who owe debts to Panama, declaring
Delvalle the legitimate leader of the country. The U.S. Treasury
will help establish an account for payments in these cases.
</TEXT>
