<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua 1stLd-Writethru   04-01 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0575,0491</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cease-fire Between Sandinistas and Contras Begins</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: LEADS throughout to ADD details. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RODOLFO GARCIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The leftist Sandinista government and
the Contra rebels today began a formal 60-day cease-fire in their
6{-year war, but details remain to be negotiated next week.
   A spokesman for the Defense Ministry, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said there were no initial reports of violations of the
truce, which began at midnight.
   The cease-fire was worked out last week during peace talks
between the rebels and government negotiators in Sapoa, a post on
Nicaragua's southern border with Costa Rica.
   It was arranged to give both sides time to arrange a permanent
truce to bring an end to the fighting that has battered the country
since late 1981.
   The cease-fire is an extension of a temporary truce that began
March 21 during the peace talks.
   In technical discussions earlier this week at Sapoa, both sides
agreed in general terms on the size and location of five zones
where the rebels are to gather in the first 15 days of April.
   Two zones are in the northern part of the country, two on the
Caribbean coast and one in the south. Their exact locations have
not been disclosed.
   The two sides will resume talks next week, apparently to
determine details of the cease-fire, including what supplies the
rebels may receive and whether they must lay down their weapons.
   Technical discussions are to resume Tuesday in Sapoa, while
high-level negotiations between Sandinista and Contra leaders are
set for Wednesday in the capital of Managua.
   Under the peace agreement signed March 23, the Sandinistas will
grant freedom of expression and amnesty to political prisoners and
will allow rebel leaders to take part in national talks.
   The Contras, in turn, agreed to gather in the cease-fire zones
and accept only humanitarian aid from a neutral organization, such
as the International Red Cross.
   In Washington, President Reagan signed today a $48 million
non-lethal aid package for the Contras, but it probably will be at
least two weeks before the rebels begin receiving supplies under
the new legislation.
   ``There certainly is an urgent need among the (rebels) for
medical supplies, food, clothing, the basic commodities of life,''
said White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater. ``This bill is very
welcome in that regard and we support it.''
   U.S. aid to the Contras ended on Feb. 29.
   On Thursday, Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega expressed
concern that the measure called for the U.S. Agency for
International Development to deliver the aid to the rebels. He said
the Organization of American States should determine how the help
will be turned over to the Contras.
   Government offices and most stores were closed today to mark the
long Easter weekend. Many Nicaraguans went to the beaches on the
Pacific coastal for the holiday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
