<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1136EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Taxes-Scholarships     04-01 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taxes-Scholarships,230</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service has ordered its
agents to ignore more-restrictive court rulings in determining
whether certain stipends paid graduate students are subject to tax.
   The agency said it will rely instead on a 1975 revenue ruling
that allows some stipends to be excluded from taxation.
   The IRS announcement is aimed at clearing up confusion that
apparently has resulted in thousands of students being billed for
back taxes on their stipends because the district where they filed
returns decided the issue on the basis of court rulings.
   The announcement applies only to stipends earned before 1987. A
new law taxes most such post-1986 payments to the extent they
exceed the cost of tuition.
   Under the IRS announcement, pre-1987 stipend income is not taxed
if:
   _The student was a candidate for a degree,
   _The student performed research or other services for the collge
to satisfy requirements for the degree, and
   _Similar services were required of all degree candidates.
   Students who have been assessed additional taxes and who meet
those requirements should apply for a refund, if they have paid, or
an abatement, if they have not paid the extra amount, the IRS said.
Any such filing should note that it is being done for
reconsideration of whether the stipend is taxable.
   The agency promised to give quick attention to any such claims.
</TEXT>
