<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Meese 4thLd-Writethru a0576etal 04-01 1143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0576 et al,1150</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Combines pvs; inserts 1 graf Reagan comment after 5th graf
pvs, Meanwhile, Justice. Trims thruout. McKay's announcement at
noon EST</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Independent counsel James McKay today was
preparing to issue a statement in the criminal investigation of
Attorney General Edwin Meese III that is somewhat favorable to the
attorney general, sources familiar with the probe said.
   However, McKay, who has been investigating Meese's involvement
through his longtime friend E. Robert Wallach with scandal-plagued
Wedtech Corp. and a $1 billion Iraqi oil pipeline, will continue
his criminal investigation, said the sources, who spoke on the
condition of anonymity.
   It wasn't immediately known what the independent counsel's
expected one-page statement would say, but one Justice Department
source said that ``on balance'' it is favorable to Meese.
   ``I'm not concerned about it,'' one of Meese's lawyers, James
Rocap, said when asked if the statement were favorable to Meese.
Rocap said the defense lawyers would have a statement of their own
later.
   Meanwhile, Justice Department sources said that later today
Meese was likely to announce the names of two, or possibly three,
nominees for now-vacant Justice Department posts.
   President Reagan, asked as he left the White House for an Easter
vacation in California, ``What about Meese. ... Should he quit?''
responded, ``I think you'll be hearing from him later today.''
   The department's top ranks were decimated Tuesday by the protest
resignations of Deputy Attorney General Arnold Burns and Assistant
Attorney General William Weld, head of the criminal division.
   In addition, the No. 3 Justice Department official, Stephen
Trott, is leaving to become a federal judge.
   Meese is expected to announce replacements for Trott and Weld,
and possibly Burns, said one Justice Department source, who
requested anonymity.
   The replacement for Weld is James I.K. Knapp, a deputy in the
Justice Department's tax division who previously worked in the
criminal division.
   The replacement for Trott is Francis A. Keating II, now the
assistant Treasury secretary for enforcement, a position that
involves overseeing criminal investigations of money laundering and
other crimes. Keating oversees the Customs Service, the Secret
Service and the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms.
   The swift appointments by Meese are an attempt to quell mounting
calls for his resignation.
   Earlier in the day, the Justice Department's fourth-ranking
official, who reportedly tried but failed to get Meese to resign,
said he would stay on the job so long as he can work ``with
integrity and effectiveness.''
   The statement by Solicitor General Charles Fried was devoid of
any other expression of support for Meese other than to say that
the solicitor general would stay on for the time being.
   In a prepared statement, Fried said he had had a private
conversation with Meese on Wednesday ``to tell him clearly what
course of action I thought he should follow.''
   Fried refused to tell reporters what that recommended course
was. The New York Times, however, said that Fried had urged Meese
to quit but that Meese had rejected the suggestion.
   ``I have concluded that while I am able to lead the office of
the solicitor general with integrity and effectiveness in its
special responsibilities to the law, to the United States and to
the Supreme Court, I should continue to do so,'' Fried's statement
said.
   Fried said pointedly that ``I will not accept any other
positions in the Department of Justice,'' which was rocked Tuesday
by the resignations of Burns and Weld.
   Fried's statement referred to the special, almost autonomous
nature, of the solicitor general's office in connection with the
rest of the Justice Department. Fried's office is responsible for
arguing the government's positions before the U.S. Supreme Court.
His statement referred to ``the two departments'' _ his office and
the Justice Department.
   ``As course, I serve only at the pleasure of the president,''
said the solicitor general. ``As for the attorney general, I felt
it was my duty to him and to the two departments to tell him
clearly what course of action I thought he should follow.
   ``I did that Wednesday in a private conversation.''
   Retired Associate Justice of the Supreme Court Lewis F. Powell
Jr. said Fried had called him Monday evening, ``very upset and
concerned, and very perplexed about what he should do,'' according
to the Times.
   Monday was the day that Burns and Weld made their decision to
quit out of concern that Meese's continued tenure as attorney
general was hurting the operations of and undermining public
confidence in the Justice Department. The resignations were
announced the next day.
   Powell said that Fried had indicated to him that ``once he found
out what the facts were, he'd have to keep in mind that he had an
obligation to the Court,'' according to the Times.
   Meese has been under criminal investigation for nearly 11 months.
   Meanwhile, Meese is facing growing pressure from Republicans as
well as Democrats to resign.
   Meese met Thursday with Republican Sen. Strom Thurmond, who said
a number of people on Capitol Hill have expressed ``deep concern
about the problems at the Justice Department.''
   Thurmond is the ranking Republican on the Senate Judiciary
Committee and the discussion was the strongest sign to date of
growing bipartisan concern in Congress over whether the attorney
general's mounting legal problems are dragging down his department.
   Thurmond said he was not making any judgments, but that he would
not ``countenance any corruption in any way, shape or form in the
Justice Department or any other department.''
   Wallach, a San Francisco attorney who is now under indictment in
the Wedtech scandal, is at the heart of the criminal investigation
of Meese that began last May 11. The independent counsel has been
trying to determine whether Wallach or others paid off Meese in
exchange for his official acts on behalf of Wedtech or the pipeline
project.
   In an interview published Thursday in the San Jose (Calif.)
Mercury News, Wallach said he should have been more sensitive to
the appearance of impropriety in helping Meese set up a financial
partnership with investment manager W. Franklyn Chinn, who later
joined Wedtech's board. Both Chinn and Wallach have been indicted
on racketeering charges related to Wedtech.
   Wallach also said in the interview that Meese had ``nothing
absolutely'' to do with a $150,000 payment Wallach received from
Swiss financier Bruce Rappaport in connection with the Iraqi
pipeline plan.
   Rappaport, a partner in the pipeline project, had been scheduled
to give a deposition about the case to McKay last month but backed
out and has apparently decided not to cooperate with the
investigation, The Washington Post reported today.
   The newspaper, quoting unidentified sources in Washington and
abroad, said Rappaport changed his mind at the last minute because
he was afraid he might not remember everything accurately.
   Rappaport was to have been given immunity from prosecution in
the case.
</TEXT>
