<1ST_LINE>u i AM-China-Baldness Bjt   04-01 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Baldness, Bjt,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bald Japanese Seek Miracle Cure in China</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For about $3,000, Japanese tourists can see the
Great Wall, eat Peking duck and grow hair with Zhao Zhangguang's
mysterious, magical hair-restoring tonic.
   A tour bus arrived Friday carrying 98 bald and thin-haired
Japanese for their first treatment with 101 Hair Liniment, a liquid
made from a secret recipe of about 30 medicinal herbs.
   It is the second Japanese group, following 20 who arrived in
February, to come to China on a package tour that includes
treatment at Zhao's clinic at the Jinsong hospital in eastern
Beijing.
   Among the first 20, ``some have already started to grow hair,''
said Kenichi Morita, president of China-Japan Treatment
Headquarters, a private Tokyo medical firm sponsoring the tours.
   Most of the Japanese said they signed up for the trip after
reading in newspapers of the miraculous results of 101, which Zhao,
a former farmer with only six years of formal education, developed
after 10 years of private research.
   Dr. Liu Qirong, the chief of 12 dermatologists at Zhao's clinic,
said about 2,700 Chinese have been treated in the past year, with
92 percent showing some new growth of hair. For people who have
lost hair in patches, the success rate is 100 percent, she said.
   According to the official news agency Xinhua, more than 100,000
people have been treated with 101 since production began a year
ago, with an improvement rate of 97.5 percent and a cure rate of 84
percent.
   Zhao's results haven't been independently verified.
   By comparison, the anti-baldness drug minoxidil, recommended for
approval by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration, had a success
rate of 26 percent of men in the 40-49 age group. For those under
30, the growth rate was 54 percent, and it was 41 percent to 45
percent in the 31-39 age group.
   Zhao's liniment, Liu said, works by stimulating circulation of
the blood and cleaning out hair follicles. A second medicine, 102,
is available to ensure that the new hair will not fall out.
   One slightly balding 40-year-old man from Osaka, Japan, said he
read about the cure in a magazine and decided to join the tour
because ``it's better to have hair than not to have hair.''
   For some, it is more serious. Yuji Matsuishi, a 6-year-old from
Fukuoka, lost all his hair 18 months ago, and Japanese doctors have
had no success in either identifying or solving the problem, said
his grandmother, Yoshie Kuga.
   ``We have high hopes. Nothing else has worked,'' she said.
   Doctors said the tonic works better on people whose hair loss is
fairly recent, and they were optimistic Yuji's hair could start
coming back after a month or two of treatment.
   They said treatment generally consists of dabbing the liquid
onto the scalp several times a day for about six months or as long
as it takes for hair to grow back.
   The only side-effect, Liu said, is that the scalp often turns a
brownish color before the hair returns.
   One bottle of 101, which lasts for about a month, sells for
about $12 in China, but Morita said the price will soon shoot up to
about $30. The Chinese government, which has not given official
approval to the medicine, has given Zhao the go-ahead to cash in on
his drug.
   The treatment is undergoing clinical tests in China and cannot
be sold in stores or hospitals here or in any other country. It
can, however, be purchased directly from Zhao's clinic for personal
use.
   Zhao, who once had to sell his only pig to obtain money needed
to continue his research, now operates two factories, one in
central China's Zhengzhou and the other in Beijing. The Beijing
plant earned profits of about $135,000 in its first year, the
official China Daily reported.
   Liu said people from Japan, West Germany, Hong Kong, Singapore,
the United States and other countries have written about the
treatment or come to the clinic, and they hope to begin exporting
it once the medicine is approved by various health agencies.
   ``We're not in this for profit,'' Liu said. ``We're trying to
cure people, and when people are cured, it makes us happy.''
</TEXT>
