<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0437 04-01 0564</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0437,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede MILWAUKEE</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 5 grafs new with Dukakis appearance today; pick up 3rd
graf pvs bgng ``I want...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RACINE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis said today that corporate greed has left ``the average
working men and women of America holding the bag'' while the rich
get richer.
   Dukakis, injecting a note of populism into his campaign speech,
struck out at corporate greed he said was fostered by the Reagan
administration.
   ``Wall Street pirates and corporate hit teams aren't the model
for a new America,'' Dukakis said.
   ``If we're serious about winning the battle for our economic
future, we've got to get control of the merger and acquisition
binge that's gobbling up capital, tearing corporations apart like
erector sets, making millions of dollars for a few ... and leaving
the average working men and women of America holding the bag,'' he
said.
   On Thursday, Dukakis said his experience as Massachusetts
governor would make him a better president than Jesse Jackson, but
he refused to criticize the rival who is running neck-and-neck with
him in Wisconsin primary polls.
   ``I want to win this nomination and unite this party at the same
time,'' he said at a news conference.
   Dukakis also called for the resignation of Attorney General
Edwin Meese III, a call made earlier in the day by Jackson, who
also was campaigning in Wisconsin.
   ``The Justice Department is still in turmoil and I guess (that)
will continue until we have a new attorney general and it's about
time we did,'' Dukakis said. ``I would hope at long last the
attorney general would resign _ it's long overdue _ and the
president would appoint somebody as attorney general we could be
proud of.''
   Dukakis' remarks followed a speech at Serb Hall, a traditional
rallying point for presidential candidates in Wisconsin, where
Dukakis said the Reagan administration ``has walked away from the
American dream.''
   Asked why he considered himself more qualified than Jackson,
Dukakis said, ``I think I am going to be a better president because
I think I've got the strength, the experience and the values to
lead this country; because I'm somebody who not only believes in
good jobs and good wages for people, I've helped to create them.''
   Dukakis also cited his efforts in Massachusetts to combat
homelessness and drug abuse in schools.
   ``That's why I'm running. That's why I think I would be the best
nominee and the best president. I respect the other candidates.
They have their strengths and weaknesses as all of us do. We all
share a lot of common values and goals, but if there is one
strength I believe I bring to this campaign it is as a proven chief
executive and leader who has done these things.''
   Dukakis said he is the candidate ``who understands how you take
hopes and dreams and transform them into action.''
   Dukakis' speech, in which he accused the Reagan administration
of embracing programs for the rich and of excessive military
spending at the expense of working men and women, was new.
   He denied it was a response to criticism that he lacked passion
in his campaigning.
   ``I just thought it was time. You guys' eyes were glazing over a
little bit and I just thought it was time to give you something
new,'' Dukakis told reporters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
