<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MilitaryMoves     04-01 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Military Moves,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Taps Three Officers for New Assignments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has nominated Maj. Gen.
Donald L. Cromer for promotion to lieutenant general and assignment
as commander of the Air Force Systems Command's Space Division, the
Pentagon said Friday.
   Assuming Senate confirmation, Cromer, 52, will replace Lt. Gen.
Aloysius G. Casey, who will retire on July 1 after 34 years'
service.
   Cromer, a native of Grand Junction, Colo., now commands the Air
Force's Space and Missile Test Organization.
   In another personnel move, Maj. Gen. Clifford H. Rees Jr. would
be promoted to lieutenant general and named vice commander of the
U.S. Air Forces in Europe. Rees, 51, would replace Lt. Gen. Thomas
G. McInerney, who was recently nominated to assume command of the
Alaskan Air Command.
   Rees, from Newport News, Va., now heads the Tactical Air
Command's Air Defense Weapons Center.
   Reagan also nominated Rear Adm. Everette D. Stumbaugh to become
the judge advocate general of the Navy. Sumbaugh, 50, a native of
Clarksville, Ark., now is deputy judge advocate general.
</TEXT>
