<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MissingMarshal 1stLd-Writethru a0561 04-01 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Missing Marshal, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0561,0507</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manhunt Ends When Officer Believed Kidnapped Turns Up Safe</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with marshal telling father he
escaped from four men who held him captive. Picks up in 3rd graf,
`Officers are ...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BLUE MOUNTAIN, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A town marshal who was believed to
have been kidnapped told his family today that he managed to escape
from four men who had held him captive in an abandoned house and in
a car trunk, officials said.
   Police had launched an intense manhunt for Gary Stokes after he
disappeared early Thursday while investigating an apparent burglary
in this tiny northeast Mississippi town.
   Stokes ``told his father that they let him out of the trunk
early today to go to the restoom and, as he walked over some
railroad tracks figuring he had a 50-50 chance to live, he ran into
the woods,'' said Mayor Robert P. Godwin.
   Stokes was unharmed and resting at his family home, state and
Tippah County authorities said.
   ``About all I can tell you is that he is back and we are
investigating,'' said Tippah County Sheriff Leroy Meeks said today.
   Officers ``are treating this as a kidnapping,'' said Deputy
Sheriff Carl Gillard. Meeks, however, declined to confirm that
Stokes had been abducted.
   Stokes disappeared early Thursday and authorities feared he may
have been taken captive by someone trying to break into a storage
room behind a store in Blue Mountain, a northern Mississippi town
of about 860 residents.
   City Clerk Billie Morgan said today her office was told that
Stokes, the town's only full-time policeman, had walked to a house
in the town of Myrtle in neighboring Union County ``and called in
about 3 a.m. I understand he told officers that he was abducted.''
   Police had used tracking dogs in the rain as they searched for
Stokes in rural areas around Blue Mountain all day Thursday and
well into the night. A helicopter search had been planned today.
   Meeks had said officers from surrounding counties, firemen and
civilians had helped deputies in the search.
   Meeks said Stokes, 35, radioed the nearby Ripley Police
Department for backup while investigating the possible burglary
early Thursday.
   ``When the units arrived, he was nowhere to be found,'' the
sheriff said.
   Morgan said officers found Stokes' car with the engine still
running, the lights on and his radio microphone hanging outside the
door.
   ``The officers reported they found his police pistol on the
ground, with one bullet fired, and his empty billfold nearby,''
Morgan said.
   However, Meeks said investigators were uncertain when the bullet
was fired. He said no evidence was found that anyone had been
wounded at the scene.
   Authorities issued a bulletin for a car with four occupants that
apparently was seen in the area about the time Stokes radioed in.
   ``We are checking every possibility and we don't know if those
men had anything to do with all this,'' the sheriff said.
</TEXT>
