<1ST_LINE>r a AM-OldBones     04-01 0466</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Old Bones,0482</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leader Of Ceremonial Militia Wins OK For Burial Among Historic
Graves</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Cremens isn't ready to leave this world. But
when the time comes, he hopes to settle his bones among famous
early Americans in one of the city's two 300-year-old cemeteries.
   During the nation's 1976 bicentennial, the 65-year-old trial
lawyer commanded the Ancient and Honorable Artillery Company, a
now-cermonial militia that marks its 350th anniversary June 1.
   He hopes to make his last stop with John Winthrop, the state's
first governor; William Dawes, who rode with Paul Revere; the first
woman to get off the Mayflower, and the woman some say was
Nathaniel Hawthorne's model for Hester Prynne, who wore the scarlet
letter.
   Cremens wants to be buried in the King's Chapel Burying Ground
tomb of Capt. Robert Keayne, the militia's first commander. Cremens
said Thursday he belongs there as the bicentennial commander.
   An ordinance the City Council passed last week permits Cremens'
burial in the tomb or across Tremont Street in the Granary Burying
Ground, where he would join Paul Revere, John Hancock, Samuel
Adams, and, some say, ``Mother Goose.''
   But the cemeteries are full.
   And some other militia members say it's not clear Cremens
belongs there.
   A real militia established to protect colonists, the Ancient and
Honorable lost its orgininal purpose before the Civil War. But it
was never disbanded and remains the world's third-oldest surviving
militia, exceeded by its English counterpart and the papal Swiss
Guards.
   Nowadays, the group mainly raises money for charity.
   Cremens's request is expected to be discussed Monday, at the
next militia meeting.
   Member Bert Caldwell said opening Keayne's tomb, already jammed
with 36 coffins, would undo two years and $7,500 of restoration.
   ``You effectively have to make an archaeological dig. I don't
know if it's worth it. ... It's best to let sleeping patriots lie.''
   Although the city's 16 historic cemeteries are full, title
holders to underground tombs can open them for more bodies with the
city's permission.
   Ellen Lipsey, preservation planner for the city parks
department, said a new body is buried every 20 years or so.
   If Cremens doesn't get into the Keayne tomb, he must find
another tomb and get the titleholders to let him in, then get the
park department's permission.
   Parks Commissioner William Coughlin said if the militia is
reluctant to open the tomb it's unlikely the department will
approve.
   Cremens said that whatever happens, he's pleased for the
opportunity to be buried among heroes of the past.
   ``It's a great honor. I'm very happy to be there in that great
company, to be part of the history of this country and to be
remembered in the prayers of people passing by ... I hope it
doesn't happen soon.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
