<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Holidays Bjt   04-01 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Holidays, Bjt,0736</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Passover, Good Friday Celebrated Under Tight Guard</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jews celebrated the first night of Passover and
Christians carrying crosses marked Good Friday under heavy military
and police guard that was mobilized to prevent violence after four
months of Arab protests.
   Fewer tourists than usual filled Israel's hotels, normally
packed to capacity during Passover week. Tourism officials blamed
it on the fear among foreigners, mainly U.S. Jews, because of the
fatal riots.
   Police commissioner David Kraus told Israel army radio extra
units of officers patrolled cities and holiday sites.
   In Jerusalem's walled Old City, hundreds of Christian pilgrims
carrying crosses and singing psalms traced the route Jesus walked
to his crucifixion, but the crowd was thinner than usual.
   An Arab attacker stabbed an Israeli police lieutenant in the
stomach just 20 yards from the processional route. The soldier was
in fair condition.
   The Greek Orthodox Church canceled two pre-Easter processions
due to security concerns and an expected drop in tourism. Western
Christians celebrate Easter on Sunday, while Orthodox Christians
observe it this year on April 10.
   The original Good Friday occurred during Passover, but the
holidays don't usually coincide because the two religions use
different calendars.
   Friday also was the Moslem Sabbath, which in recent months has
been a catalyst for violent demonstrations.
   In Jewish west Jerusalem, few signs of recent tensions were
evident as Israeli shoppers jammed stores buying flowers and candy
to give relatives, a Passover tradition. Children, on a two-week
school holiday, filled the streets eating ice cream and candy.
   Passover, which commemorates the liberation of Jews from slavery
in Egypt, derives its name from the biblical Book of Exodus. The
book recounts that God ``passed over'' the homes of the Israelites
when meeting out the worst of 10 plagues, killing the first-born of
every Egyptian.
   The plagues finally forced the Egyptian Pharoah to let the Jews
leave Egypt.
   The story of the exodus is recounted every year in the seder,
the traditional holiday meal. Participants take turns reading
excerpts from the Hagadah, a book of stories, rabbinical sayings
and lively songs of thanksgiving.
   Symbolic foods are eaten, including bitter herbs to remind Jews
of the harshness of their enslavement and haroset, a brick-colored
mixture of apples, nuts and wine to recall the bricks laid by
Jewish slaves.
   But the best-known symbol is matzo, the unleavened bread eaten
during Passover week. Matzo reminds Jews that when they departed
Egypt, they had no time to let their bread rise and so had to take
unleavened bread into the desert.
   In Israel, stores are forbidden to sell leavened bread during
Passover. But many secular Jerusalemites circumvent the
restrictions and buy pita, the pocket-shaped Middle Eastern bread,
from Arab merchants in east Jerusalem.
   The practice was expected to be more difficult this year with
virtually every Arab merchant there on a partial strike.
   Life returned to the Old City on Friday when hundreds of
Christian pilgrims crowded the Via Dolorosa, or Way of Sorrow,
tracing Jesus' steps to his crucifixion. Priests carried ornate
silver and gold crosses and burned incense.
   ``We planned to come here for a long time and nothing could stop
us, even friends who said we were crazy,'' said David Reid of
Mountain Lakes, N.J. ``There are lots of police around and we are
as safe here as we are in New York City.''
   The procession ended at the Church of the Holy Sepulchre, built
in the 12th century on the site where the faithful believe Jesus
was crucified, buried and raised from the dead on Easter Sunday.
   Pilgrims kissed and threw water on the rock marking the spot
where Jesus' body was washed before burial, while 16 choir boys in
black robes sang prayers.
   Arab merchants opened their shops for the three hours permitted
by the Palestine Liberation Organization to sell olive-wood
crosses, doing brisk business.
   Tourism officials said more visitors came to Israel in January
and February as compared with the previous year, but 13 percent
fewer tourists entered the country during the first week in March.
   The Rev. Timoteus Margaritis, a spokesman for the Greek Orthodox
Christian Church, said 1,500 pilgrims were expected to attend his
church's April 10 Easter service, instead of the usual 10,000.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
