<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--AIDS-Embezzlement     04-01 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--AIDS-Embezzlement,0176</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Banker Pleads Guilty in Embezzlement Scheme</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former banker who went on a spending spree with
funds from his thrift after learning he had AIDS has pleaded guilty
to misappropriating more than $1 million.
   William Patrick Debenport, 27, said he gave some of the money to
gay charities after being told he had acquired immune deficiency
syndrome.
   Debenport pleaded guilty Thursday to three counts of
misappropriation, admitting he illegally used his position as
manager of First Texas Savings and Loan's Oak Cliff branch to
misappropriate $1.1 million from it.
   Documents filed with Debenport's plea show he established fake
accounts, transferring money to them and then removing the funds by
writing cashier's checks.
   He faces up to 15 years in prison and $3,000 in fines at
sentencing May 5.
   His lawyer, Steven Cooper, said earlier that Debenport used most
of the money to buy luxuries for himself and gifts for friends, but
also donated some to charities, including $175,000 to a Dallas home
for AIDS sufferers.
</TEXT>
