<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1247EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson-HighSchools Bjt   04-01 0768</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson-High Schools, Bjt,770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Teaches History Lesson</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson the politician often becomes
Jesse Jackson the history teacher these days, taking his
presidential campaign to high schools as often as to union halls or
churches.
   From the inner city school in Inkster, Mich., to Pulaski High in
the heart of southside Milwaukee, the Democratic presidential
candidate delivers his sermon of self-respect, a drug-free and
violence-free life and the need to achieve.
   ``I go to four or five high schools a week in the course of
every week, because I love our children, because I care, because
their lives are at stake,'' Jackson told students in Inkster, near
Detroit. ``You are our energy.''
   In the high school speeches there is always a political message
_ ``Come alive, April 5'' was the chant he taught at Pulaski, in
advance of the Wisconsin primary on Tuesday.
   But Jackson has other goals as well, for in 1988 he emphasizes
the course of the fight for equal rights for a generation that
looks at the 1950s and 1960s as ancient history.
   Jackson tells the story of Rosa Parks, whose refusal to go to
the back of the bus in Montgomery, Ala., sparked demonstrations
that pushed Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. to prominence in 1955.
   Jackson, a King protege, talks of the role young people played
in the civil rights struggle, saying that King was only 26 when the
Montgomery bus boycott began and that college students led the
lunch counter sit-ins in Greensboro, N.C. that inaugurated a new
tactic in the fight for desegregated public accommodations.
   ``In 1960, four student in Greemsboro, N.C. sat at a lunch
counter to get hamburgers. They got handcuffs,'' Jackson said at
Pulaski High School. ``They were threatened with expulsion from
school. They chose dignity over degrees. They kept fighting to make
America better.''
   Some Pulaski students may have had family members who had
personal experience with the civil rights movement. It is in the
heart of Southside Milwaukee, an all-white neighborhood that was
the scene of ugly, sometimes violent confrontations during open
housing marches of the 1960s.
   Jackson also talks in sometimes brutal terms of the price that
was paid in the civil rights movement, reading down the list of
those who were killed in the fight. Often his images are harsh, as
in his description of one civil rights marcher's death.
   ``Her brains were blown out at point-blank range by a shotgun,''
he told students at Stevenson High School in Sterling Heights, Mich.
   After recounting how far the nation has come, Jackson turns to
the problems of today.
   ``Each generation must face the challenges of its own time,'' he
told Pulaski students.
   At Inkster, the message was more direct to an audience of about
1,500 mostly black students.
   ``After years of struggle, we have obtained equal protection
under the law. You have opportunity. When I went to school, we did
not have equal opportunity,'' said Jackson, who grew up poor in
South Carolina.
   ``Obviously opportunity is not enough. ... What does it matter
if you have equal opportunity if your players are drunk on the
court? What does it matter if you have a new book or an old book if
you never open either?''
   This theme Jackson uses to launch into his crusade against drugs.
   ``The No. 1 threat in your lifetime is not lack of opportunity _
it is concession to the No. 1 killer in the country today _
drugs,'' he said at Inkster.
   Then Jackson repeats a litany to bring home the pervasiveness of
the problems he is attacking. He asks how many students know
someone who has died from drugs. Usually, a scattering stand up.
   Then he asks how many know someone who is in jail because of
drugs. More stand. Then the question is, how many know someone who
uses drugs. In most schools, everyone stands.
   He repeats the question and response pattern about knowledge of
young people who have brought guns to school and knowledge of
contemporaries who contemplated suicide. In each case, a remarkable
number of students stand.
   The preacher-turned-politician is quick to issue a reminder that
this is not a limited problem.
   ``Lest you forget, members of the press, whether we are in the
heart of rural Iowa or in Inkster, Mich., or Seattle, Wash., or
Pasadena, Calif., this is the scene all over America every day,''
he said in the Detroit suburb. ``So I reach out to young America
today to provide positive and creative energy to keep America
strong and to make America better.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
