<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FugitiveArrest     04-01 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fugitive Arrest,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arrest Could Lead To Break In `French Connection' Theft Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fugitive arrested recently in Florida could
shed light on the celebrated but still unsolved ``French
Connection'' drug theft case, a federal prosecutor says.
   Anthony Dominick Passero, 53, was arrested Feb. 10 in Florida on
an outstanding money laundering indictment filed in New York in
1984 that named one of his many aliases, Anthony Paris, U.S.
Attorney Andrew Maloney said Thursday.
   It was not until Tuesday, when authorities received a report on
a fingerprint check, that they realized Paris was Passero.
   He ``may be the last living guy who could solve the French
Connection thefts,'' Maloney said.
   Passero was identified by Maloney as an alleged partner of the
late Vincent Papa, who was suspected of being the mastermind of the
theft of $70 million worth of heroin and cocaine from the property
clerk's office in city Police Headquarters from 1968 to 1972.
   Much of the heroin had been seized in the ``French Connection''
drug case, the basis for the movie of the same name starring Gene
Hackman and Roy Scheider.
   Papa, who had alleged ties to the Luchese organized crime
family, was stabbed to death in 1977 while in an Atlanta prison on
other drug charges.
   Maloney said no one had ever been arrested for the drug thefts,
allegedly committed by a group of police detectives.
   In addition to the money laundering charges, Passero faces
charges from a 1975 heroin trafficking indictment. He also was
charged in 1975 with perjury and criminal contempt in connection
with the investigation into the French Connection thefts,
authorities said.
   Passero, focus of an Internal Revenue Service investigation for
many years, had been living in a $475,000 home at Pompano, Fla.,
under the alias of Anthony Caruso. Five IRS agent and two Pompano
police officers arrested Passero and his common-law wife, Marie
Barbieri, 45, at their home Feb. 10.
   Both waived extradition.
   Both were named in the money laundering indictment, which
alleges they laundered about $750,000 from January 1980 to March
1981. Passero told authorities he was a retired truck driver and
scrap metal dealer, Maloney said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
