<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1324EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SpaceShuttle     04-01 0304</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Space Shuttle,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insulation Problem With Space Shuttle Booster Rocket Is Minor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Technicians will be able to repair a
minor insulation problem on a booster rocket without delaying the
space shuttle flight planned for August, NASA said Friday.
   During an inspection Wednesday, workers found four small areas
where insulation had separated from the rocket casing on the bottom
edge of one of four segments that make up the right solid fuel
rocket. The largest was 1.4 inches.
   There was concern that if the separation extended deeper into
the insulation, the segment would have to be replaced, which could
cause a launch delay of several weeks.
   Ultrasound devices were used overnight Thursday to thoroughly
inspect the segment and no additional separation or ``debonding''
was discovered.
   ``There was no evidence the debonding extended beyond the
edge,'' said NASA spokeswoman Lisa Malone. ``It can be repaired
here with no impact on the schedule.''
   Malone said similar debondings had been found on other rocket
segments in the past and they were repaired here in parallel with
other work. Severe debonding could lead to the breakup of a rocket
in flight and destroy the shuttle.
   Various technical problems have caused two lengthy delays from
the original February 1988 launch date. The target date now is Aug.
4.
   The shuttle fleet has been grounded since Challenger exploded
Jan. 28, 1986, killing the seven crew members. That accident was
caused by another booster rocket problem _ a faulty joint between
segments that allowed flames to escape and ignite the external fuel
tank for the main liquid fuel engines.
   The joint has been redesigned and has successfully passed
several test firings.
   On the first post-Challenger mission, Discovery is to carry five
crew members who will deploy a communications satellite and conduct
experiments during a four-day mission.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
