<1ST_LINE>r a AM-DrugStamps     04-01 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drug Stamps,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Selling Drugs? Don't Forget Official State Stamp</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beginning Friday, drug dealers operating
in Utah must visit the State Tax Commission and buy an official
drug tax stamp created just for them, or else they'll face
additional charges when they're arrested.
   ``This is not the case of a state agency or the state
Legislature condoning the use of illicit drugs,'' said Tax
Commission spokesman Lee Shaw. ``The drug stamp program is actually
a law enforcement tool, not a Tax Commission initiative. The drug
stamps are just another means of applying legal pressure in the
prosecution of drug dealers.''
   When a dealer is arrested, law enforcement officers will check
to see if his drugs have the stamp. If they do not, the dealer
faces a third-degree felony in addition to any other charges, Shaw
said.
   That could prove helpful in punishing dealers who evade a
distribution conviction because of some technicality, said the
law's sponsor, state Sen. Ivan Matheson.
   The law stipulates that if stamps are not attached permanently
to drug packages, a dealer could be required to pay the full cost
of the tax plus a fine of not more than $10,000.
   The stamps cost $3.50 for each gram, or portion of a gram, of
marijuana; $200 for each gram of a controlled substance sold by
weight; and $2,000 for each 50 ``dosage units,'' such as pills, of
a controlled substance not sold by weight.
   ``I cannot see a major drug dealer going in there to buy a
stamp,'' said attorney Gilbert D. Athay, who has defended a number
of alleged drug dealers.
   But that doesn't mean there won't be a market for the stamps.
   ``Stamp collectors will buy them. They'll probably be the only
people in town who will own them,'' Athay said.
   Anyone can buy the stamps. Purchasers do not have to identify
themselves, Shaw said, but must pay with cash or a cashier's check.
   The Tax Commission ordered 4,000 stamps from the state printing
office.
   All three stamps are plain. The marijuana stamp doesn't have a
picture of a leaf, just the title ``Marijuana'' at the top, and
several lines printed over the state seal where commission
employees can fill in the quantity and their initials.
</TEXT>
