<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MallChapel Bjt   04-01 0478</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mall Chapel, Bjt,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Worshipers Flock to Shopping Mall Chapel</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NR2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARAMUS, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Brice Riordan sensed a bargain in
the air one day recently while he prepared to celebrate Mass.
   ``Dear friends, it's encouraging to see such a great number of
you,'' Riordan said, looking out over his congregation. ``There
must be a sale at Stern's or something.''
   The 18-yea-old Carmelite chapel in the Bergen Mall is one of the
few in the country to be located in a shopping center. It is billed
as The Chapel on the Mall, devoted to St. Therese.
   The Rev. Ferdinand Schaefer, the chapel's pastor, said the idea
for a place to worship amid the materialism of a mall comes from
the age-old directive to ``get Christ in the marketplace.''
   ``You have to go where the people are, and the people are in the
malls,'' Schaefer said.
   The chapel is run by four priests of the Carmelite Order of the
Roman Catholic Church, which helped set up the first known mall
chapel more than 25 years ago in Peabody, Mass.
   The reason the Bergen Mall was chosen for a chapel site was a
link to the Peabody chapel _ Allied Stores, which in 1970 owned
both shopping malls, Schaefer said.
   Attendance was poor in the early years but it has gained
steadily, and today, especially during Lent and on Saturdays, it is
standing room only in the 150-seat chapel, Schaefer said.
   Year round, the chapel attracts about 200 people a day for three
Masses daily on weekdays and four on Saturday, he said. The chapel
doesn't offer Sunday Masses, because the mall is closed.
   Schaefer and steady chapelgoers credit the solid turnout to
convenience and the strong sermons of the four Carmelite priests.
   ``We just love these priests,'' said Kathleen Tappen of Maywood.
   Mrs. Tappen and her husband, Frank, have been chapel worshipers
for eight years.
   ``It's like a family,'' added Marge Wohlrab of Rochelle Park, a
10-year chapel-goer. ``Each (priest) gives a different perspective.
We always get another reason for carrying on.''
   The priests, ranging in age from 66 to 71 years old, have drawn
their wisdom from experience, said Schaefer.
   ``These guys have 40 to 45 years of priesthood behind them,''
Schaefer said. ``They have sort of mellowed. They are not out to do
anything except minister the sacraments and be kind to people. That
makes a difference.''
   The chapel is a no-frills religious experience. There are no
baptisms, funerals or weddings. Priests hear confessions, celebrate
daily mass and provide counseling when needed.
   Schaefer believes its success will continue as long as there are
shoppers.
   ``You see an awful lot of people going by and stopping and
looking and they are amazed,'' Schaefer said. ``Then, what do you
know, another day or two and they will be in.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
