<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--SeizureProfits     04-01 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Seizure Profits,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Officials Seize $4.5 Million From Suspects In Three Months</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAND O' LAKES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Law enforcement agencies in Florida
seized more than $4.5 million in property and cash from suspected
criminals in the last three months of 1987, according to a state
report.
   State law lets police seize property when authorities believe it
was used in a felony. The law has sparked criticism because some
agencies confiscate property without making an arrest.
   While they must return the property to innocent owners,
authorities often charge fees to do so. Legislation is expected
this session to prohibit the fees.
   Metro-Dade police seized $1.04 million in cash and $34,000 in
property _ mainly older cars _ and earned $55,000 in interest.
   ``This is home base on the U.S. side to the major traffickers
... people who will have bags and boxes of money,'' said George
Aylesworth, commander of the Metro-Dade legal unit. ``We just bump
into them most often.''
</TEXT>
