<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-AIDS     04-01 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-AIDS,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Surgeon May Have Contracted AIDS Perfoming Operations in Africa</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LON2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A surgeon who died of AIDS may have contracted the
disease while performing surgery in Africa and didn't know he had
been infected until six days before his death, his superior said
Friday.
   The doctor, David Collings, performed 338 operations in Britain
after returning last year from five years in his native Zimbabwe.
Health officials are trying to find the patients to offer them
counseling and, if necessary, a free blood test. Officials are
warning them not to panic.
   Collings, 30, thought he had a bad dose of flu when he became
ill on March 16, but his condition dramatically worsened. A blood
test on March 21 showed he had AIDS, and he died six days later at
Royal Devon and Exeter Hospital in Exeter.
   ``He just shrugged his shoulders and said, `That is one of the
risks of doing surgery in Africa,''' said his superior, consultant
surgeon Bruce Campbell.
   Collings, who was trained in Edinburgh, Scotland, was married
and had an 18-month-old child. He worked in Mpilo and Marondera,
Zimbabwe, for five years before returning to Britain last year, the
Exeter Health Authority said.
   He worked at the Alexandra Hospital at Redditch for a few months
before starting a one-year contract in Exeter on July 1.
   Collings mainly operated on patients suffering from complaints
such as appendicitis, hernias or varicose veins.
   A list of his patients was drawn up and general practitioners
will contact them in the coming days.
   The officials stressed that they were being contacted to give
them reassurance, not because they believe there is any real risk
of infection.
   Acquired immune deficiency syndrome is a fatal disease that
breaks down the body's natural defenses against disease. There is
no known cure.
</TEXT>
