<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ConstructionSpending     04-01 0322</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Construction Spending,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Construction Spending Falls For Third Consecutive Month</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending fell for a third
consecutive month in February, a 0.3 percent decline which
reflected weakness in the housing sector, the government reported
Friday.
   The Commerce Department said that construction spending declined
to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $391.5 billion in February
following a 2.8 percent drop in January. In addition, the
department revised the December figure to show a small decline of
$100 million instead of a 0.4 percent increase.
   The February decline pushed construction spending 2.5 percent
below where it was a year earlier. Analysts are forecasting further
cutbacks in 1988 because of high vacancy rates in apartments and
office buildings.
   Michael Sumichrast, an economist and editor of a construction
newsletter, said that he was predicting a 7 percent decline in
private non-residential construction this year following a drop of
8.1 percent in 1987.
   ``Much of the strength in the past few years was in
over-building driven by tax breaks rather than building for the
existing market,'' he said. ``As a result, we don't have much
strength anywhere.''
   Residential construction fell by 1.1 percent in February to an
annual rate of $188.1 billion. This included declines of 1 percent
in construction of single-family homes and a drop of 4.3 percent in
construction of multi-family units.
   Non-residential construction posted a 1.2 percent increase to an
annual rate of $92 billion. The biggest source of strength came
from an 18.8 percent surge in hospital construction which offset
drops in office, hotel and shopping center construction.
   Sumichrast said that construction of hospitals and private
schools would show increases this year although both sectors
represent only a small fraction of the total industry.
   Public construction edged up 0.4 percent in February to an
annual rate of $74.7 billion with the biggest category, highway
building, posting a 0.4 percent increase.
</TEXT>
