<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1330EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-CurfewLife Bjt   04-01 0835</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Curfew Life, Bjt,0863</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bread, Not Bullets, Concern of West Bankers</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   An AP correspondent entered Ramallah hours
before the Israeli army set up roadblocks Tuesday and left Friday
morning, after the curfew was lifted. Here is his report:
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMALLAH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Please! Please! A kilo of
bread!'' shouted women outside a bakery off Ramallah's main square.
   The flustered bakery owner held out empty hands. ``That's all! I
can't sell anymore!'' the stocky man shouted back, locking his shop
door to obey the demands of gun-toting Israeli soldiers who had
confiscated his identity papers.
   The shop shutters that crashed shut at gunpoint throughout
Ramallah on Tuesday began three days of what residents called a
siege by Israeli troops determined to crush a 4-month-old Arab
uprising.
   But Palestinians are hoarding food and launching a grassroots
campaign to endure tougher measures some say they expect to come.
   Israeli troops closed off the occupied territories for three
days this week, hoping to prevent massive demonstrations on
Wednesday, a Palestinian commemoration of efforts to fight Israeli
land confiscations. The military ordered all 650,000 Arabs in the
Gaza Strip to stay in their homes for three days, and severed
telephone links.
   On the West Bank, Israel blocked the 850,000 Arabs from leaving
their towns.
   Journalists were forbidden to enter or travel without military
escorts. An Associated Press reporter entered Ramallah, eight miles
north of Jerusalem, hours before the army set up roadblocks, and he
left Friday morning, after the curfew was lifted.
   On the first day, troops in riot gear moved through the hilly
streets of Ramallah and neighboring El Bireh, forcing shops to
close. It was punishment for the merchants' nearly universal
acceptance of a Palestine Liberation Organization demand they open
in mornings and close in afternoons.
   The shutdowns left the twin cities, home to about 55,000
Palestinians, still. Men unable to reach jobs hoed their gardens.
Women chatted while shelling almonds in front of their limestone
houses.
   Shrieking children scampered around vacant lots kicking soccer
balls or hurling rocks at one another. It was a game they called
``Jews and Arabs.''
   ``If I see the soldiers, I run,'' said a pushcart vender named
Bassam, who glanced nervously up a street near Ramallah's main
business district while cutting off bananas for customers.
   The conflicting demands of Israel and underground Arab leaders
have imposed similar, longer closures in Bethlehem, Nablus, Jericho
and Jenin.
   Abded Hamouri, co-owner of a fleet of commuter buses, said the
Israelis ``are talking to the people who do not have the solution
in their hands. The solution is not in the hands of the people who
own shops.''
   ``I'm not afraid of the military governor. I'm afraid of the guy
I don't know who he is or what he is going to do,'' he said,
referring to masked young men who tell shopowners when to open or
close.
   Israel has tried to mop up those youths since December by
arresting more than 4,000 Arabs, by government count. Palestinian
lawyers insist the toll is much higher.
   Yet protests continue, and walls throughout the town carry
spray-painted slogans: ``Long live the uprising!'' ``Up With the
PLO!''
   Arabs said Jewish settlers were responsible for a grim reply
stenciled on a few walls: a hand holding a club over a broken bone,
reference to Israel's use of beatings to quell disturbances.
   The three-day closure was Israel's broadest effort yet to stifle
protests against military occupation. But most Palestinians
interviewed in Ramallah's streets said it was little worse than
existing restrictions.
   ``To the boys here, it doesn't matter,'' said a young man named
Suleiman, trying to evade the soldiers who had imposed a curfew on
the crowded El Amiri refugee camp. He said most young men sleep
outside the camp to escape the army's midnight raids.
   Israel earlier severed international telephone connections to
the West Bank and Gaza, blocked deliveries of gasoline and fuel oil
to Arab dealers, and imposed a tight limit on the West Bank's
crucial foreign currency imports.
   It now demands proof of tax payment to obtain a driver's license
or exit visa.
   Despite the scramble for bread, Arabs throughout the area
insisted they were ready for tougher Israeli pressure.
   Reporters saw huge bags of flour and stacks of powdered milk
cans in two houses. Many people said they had stockpiled essentials.
   ``We are ready for anything,'' said Ramallah Chamber of Commerce
President Khader Kasis. ``We can exist just on bread and zatar,''
he added, referring to a popular green spice.
   An El Bireh shopowner who spoke on condition he not be
identified said his neighborhood this week formed a self-reliance
committee.
   He pointed out vacant land the group planned to fill with crops,
and said it had arranged for merchants to sell goods when stores
are closed.
   ``I think that's happening a lot, especially for security and
self-sufficiency,'' said attorney Raja Shehadeh, a human rights
activist. ``People are experiencing a siege.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
