<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Saudi     04-01 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Saudi,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Envoy Recalled After Only 6 Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hume Horan, the U.S. ambassador to Saudi
Arabia, is being reassigned after only six months on the job
because of personality differences with King Fahd, a State
Department official said Friday.
   Horan is expected to be succeeded by the man he replaced last
September, career diplomat Walter Cutler, the official said.
   Horan, who is fluent in Arabic, has been in Washington on
consultations and will return to Saudi Arabia shortly for a brief
stay to tend to personal matters, according to the official,
insisting on anonymity.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley confirmed that Horan
is being reassigned but provided no further details except to say
that he is being considered for a new post.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz will stop in Saudi Arabia
next week as part of his effort to win acceptance for his Middle
East peace proposal.
   Both Saudi and American officials denied a Washington Post
report that the Saudi government had asked that Horan be replaced.
A U.S. official also denied that Horan's reassignment was related
to a U.S.-Saudi dispute over that country's acquisition of missiles
from China.
   Horan had a ``personality conflict'' with King Fahd, the
official said. ``The decision to recall him was made here, not in
Saudi Arabia. They did not specifically ask us to withdraw him,''
he said.
   This is the second abrupt departure by an American ambassador to
Saudi Arabia during the Reagan administration.
   Former ambassador Robert G. Neumann was forced out in 1981 by
Secretary of State Alexander M. Haig after only two months on the
job.
   Cutler, since leaving Riyadh last year, has served as
diplomat-in-residence at Georgetown University here.
   Saudi Arabia's purchase of Chinese missiles, which have a range
of more than 1,000 miles, has been a contentious issue in
U.S.-Saudi relations.
   Israel is within easy reach of the missiles, which are capable
of carrying nuclear warheads. The Saudis have said the missiles
won't be fitted with such warheads.
   A group of 32 senators has written a letter to Shultz asking
that the United States reconsider further arms sales to Saudi
Arabia until the missiles are withdrawn. The administration has
been expected notify Congress shortly that it intends to sell $450
million worth of support equipment for surveillance aircraft the
Saudis acquired recently.
</TEXT>
