<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Iran-Prayers 1stLd-Writethru a0624 04-01 0787</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Prayers, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0624,0806</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iranians Gather for Friday Prayers, Wary of Missiles</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf ``Iran launched ...'' with 1 graf to UPDATE
with number of missiles fired.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten thousand Iranians shook their fists
while chanting of death to Iraq and the ``Great Satan'' America at
Friday prayers, glancing nervously skyward now and then for the
vapor trails of incoming missiles.
   A Western diplomat described the weekly ritual at Tehran
University, where unarmed students defied the imperial army when
the late Shah Mohammad Reza Pahlavi was deposed in February 1979,
as ``the beating heart of the Islamic revolution.''
   Iraq said it would stop firing missiles into Tehran and other
Iranian cities during a three-day visit to Baghdad of the Turkish
prime minister, Turgut Ozal, beginning at midnight Thursday.
   Iran said it launched seven rockets Friday into Kirkuk, the oil
center in northern Iraq, and the southern port of Basra, but did
not report firing any at the Iraqi capital. The last report of a
missile explosion in Baghdad was March 27.
   Turkey maintains good relations with both Iran and Iraq, which
have been at war since September 1980, and has tried to act as
mediator.
   Despite the apparent lull in the month-long ``war of the
cities,'' in which hundreds of civilians have been killed on both
sides, no one in Tehran was taking anything for granted on this
Moslem sabbath.
   Two long-range Iraqi missiles landed in the capital during
Friday prayers in mid-March.
   ``We saw the vapor trails, but nobody at the prayers moved,''
said a translator from the Islamic Guidance Ministry who
accompanied visiting Western correspondents to the university.
``Everyone stayed seated when the missiles exploded some distance
away.''
   Weekly prayers on the campus and elsewhere in Iran, to Western
eyes a cross between a revival meeting and political rally, are the
main platforms for mobilizing mass opinion and stoking fervor for
the war.
   Shiite Moslem fundamentalists beat their chests with fists in
unison, chant slogans and listen to leaders exhort them to victory,
condemn the ``Great Satan'' America and preach Ayatollah Ruhollah
Khomeini's revolution.
   Hashemi Rafsanjani, the parliament speaker, is a regular prayer
leader at the university but this week it was President Ali
Khamenei.
   He urged Iranians to vote in parliamentary elections April 8
``even if there are missiles and bombs falling,'' echoing remarks
the revolutionary partriarch had made the day before.
   Khamenei praised the current thrust by Revolutionary Guards into
northeastern Iraq and said Western media had not given enough
coverage to alleged chemical warfare in the region.
   Iran claims the Iraqis dropped chemical bombs March 16-17 on
three Kurdish towns in Iraq that had been captured by Iranian
troops, killing 5,000 civilians and wounding an equal number.
   At prayers, the pattern is the same each week: calls for
sacrifice interrupted by such chants from the crowd of ``War, war,
until victory!'' and ``Death to America!''
   ``Death to Russia!'' has joined the lexicon since missiles began
demolishing homes, schools and hospitals Feb. 29. Iraq is believed
to be using Soviet-designed Scud-B missiles fitted with boosters so
they can reach Tehran, which is nearly 300 miles from the border.
   Among the estimated 10,000 people at the campus prayer meeting
were about 60 Iraqi prisoners of war Iranian officials said had
volunteered to fight on Iran's side.
   They squatted in an enclosure in front of the covered podium,
which bore photographs of Khomeini and other religious leaders. All
wore white T-shirts emblazoned with the image of Imam Bakr Sadr, a
Shiite cleric executed by Iraq as a subversive in 1980.
   The imam was a cousin of Mohammad Bakr al-Hakim, leader of the
Supreme Islamic Revolutionary Council of Iraq, a group of dissident
Iraqi factions supported by Iran.
   Another enclosure held men wounded in the war _ without limbs,
in wheelchairs _ not far from ranks of teen-aged volunteers for the
front wearing red headbands with Islamic slogans.
   Security was tight and foreign correspondents were frisked twice
before being allowed onto the campus from the surrounding streets,
where thousands more people had gathered to hear the sermons
through loudspeakers.
   A bomb exploded on the campus two weeks ago, but no casualty
report was given.
   Iranian women, shrouded in the black head-to-toe robes called
chadors, were not allowed onto the campus because strict Islamic
law requires them to be segregated. They sat in an enclosure some
distance away.
   Outside the campus, cartoon-like posters explained what to do in
case of an Iraqi poison gas attack.
   Beside the entrance was a transparent plastic ``war fund'' box
into which worshipers stuffed banknotes. Officials said one slipped
in a check for 400,000 rials, about $5,600.
</TEXT>
