<1ST_LINE>r a AM-One-ManStation 1stLd-Writethru a0651 04-01 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-One-Man Station, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0651,0694</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New England Legend To Give Up 24 Years Of One-Man Broadcasting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs the 16th & 17th grafs, beginning ``While he said,'' with
3 grafs to update with identity of new owner.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE JAHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLOUCESTER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 24 years as the disc jockey,
technician and owner of WVCA-FM, Simon Geller has sold his one-man
radio station for $1 million, saying that at age 68 he's ready for
a new life.
   When in a few months he hangs up the earphones for the last time
in his two-room apartment-studio, Geller plans to walk away from
this sleepy fishing community 25 miles north of Boston. Then he'll
finally pop the question to his sweetheart of 32 years.
   ``I've had 46 years in this miserable business and it's time to
get out,'' he said, when asked about his decision.
   His 3,000-watt classical music radio station has been on the air
every day, except when he shut down to run errands.
   It's an institution built on the single-minded dedication of a
man who won an 11-year battle against the Federal Communications
Commission and a powerful business group bent on takeover.
   It's also a focal point of 90,000 loyal listeners in a 35-mile
radius extending into Boston and New Hampshire, who have
contributed more than 90 percent of the money Geller needed since
WVCA-FM went on the air in 1964 as the Voice of Cape Ann.
   It took a bit of probing before Geller, a diabetic with
high-blood pressure, talked about his decision to sell.
   An insulin reaction in 1986 caused him to fall while walking
from one room to another in his apartment. He remained conscious,
but it took friends five hours to find and help him, while a
long-playing tape was unwinding on air.
   ``I'm 68 years old, and I don't know how much longer I'll live,
so I want to get things straightened out in case I should drop dead
next week,'' he said. ``The life expectancy is only 70 in this
country.''
   Also taking its toll is mental fatigue from his battle for
license renewal.
   The challenge was mounted in 1964 by Grandbanke Corp., a group
of New England station owners that wanted to take over his
frequency for a folk rock station.
   While only a few local businesses advertise on WVCA-FM, its
listening area is considered lucrative. Grandbanke argued that the
station's format violated FCC requirements that community interest,
news and public affairs be a part of programming.
   An FCC decision against Geller was reconsidered in 1984 on
orders of a federal appeals court, which pointed out that the
station had the support of Gloucester community leaders and
listeners. His license was renewed a year later.
   ``My license was safe until 1991, but I was afraid someone would
challenge me in 1991 and I would be in the same mess I was with
Grandbanke,'' Geller said.
   Geller's two cluttered rooms above a coin laundry are crowded
with a mixture of antiquated and new equipment, with a maze of
extension cords competing for space with unopened mail and
cardboard boxes. Order is imposed by neat rows of records and tapes
on shelves lining the walls.
   While he said new owner Doug Tanger, a Boston businessman, will
likely expand operations, Geller declined to discuss details of the
sale beyond disclosing that an application was filed with the FCC
this week.
   He said it will probably take three months for the FCC to
approve Tanger's application, allowing him to take over and
allowing Geller to walk out the door.
   Tanger owns stations WCLZ-AM and -FM in Portland, Maine, and
with his family has WQRS-FM in Detroit.
   Geller said a promise that the station will remain classical
permits him to look forward to the future with Carol Hill.
   He has publicly talked about proposing to his former bookkeeper
for years. But he remains coy about a date.
   ``I haven't discussed this with her and until I'm clear here I
cannot discuss it,'' he said. ``Let's wait until FCC approval.''
</TEXT>
