<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1432EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-SouthernDrought     04-01 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Southern Drought,0355</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Facing Fourth Serious Drought In Eight Years, Experts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia, Alabama and South Carolina are facing
their fourth serious drought in eight years, experts said Friday.
   ``If we don't get a dramatic increase in rainfall, we'll be
looking at water restrictions this summer,'' said David Word, chief
of water resource management for the Georgia Department of Natural
Resources.
   Lake Lanier in north Georgia and Lakes Hartwell and Thurmond on
the Georgia-South Carolina border are at lower levels than they
were at this point in the drought years of 1981, 1986 and 1987,
officials told reporters Friday in Atlanta.
   Likely effects of the drought include timber loss, reduced water
quality, stress on fish and ``water restrictions, if this continues
through the summer,'' said Pat Davis, chief of the Technical
Engineering Branch for the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers' Mobile
District.
   ``We're in the third (consecutive) year of greatly reduced
rainfall,'' Davis said. ``It's been persistently below normal
through the decade.''
   For the 1980s, much of the area is 12 percent below normal
rainfall _ the equivalent of an entire year without rain, he said.
Some parts of Georgia are 70 inches below normal for the decade.
   The area remains under a ``water shortage alert'' issued by the
corps last fall, and that could become a ``drought alert'' later
this month, officials said.
   Lake Lanier, which supplies water to metro Atlanta and is the
most visited lake in the Corps of Engineers system, stood Friday at
nine feet below its normal level.
   ``We have only about a 10 percent chance to fill the lake by
June 1,'' said Ed Burkett, chief of water management for the corps'
Mobile District. Corps officials in November reduced the amount of
water flowing from Lanier downstream into the Chattahoochee River,
in an attempt to conserve water in the lake.
   Despite a forecast for above-average rain for April to June,
Burkett said, the customary summer and fall drops in lake levels
would likely leave area lakes below normal levels.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
