<DOCNO> AP880401-0141 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1433EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Duty-FreeImports     04-01 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Duty-Free Imports,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Cuts Duty-Free Imports From Third World</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States announced Friday that
beginning July 1 it will eliminate duty-free imports on products
worth $1.1 billion in 1987, shipped here from 140 Third World
countries.
   A U.S. official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
decision would add $50 million to $100 million a year to the
tariffs collected by the United States. It will also provide
additional business to some U.S. producers by discouraging imports.
   Total U.S. imports under this system of ``generalized special
preferences,'' the biggest of its kind in the world, reached a
record $16.3 billion last year. It is designed to help poor
countries improve their production in about 3,000 different
products.
   ``As developing countries become increasingly competitive, we
are removing tariff preferences... for those products where
duty-free treatment is no longer warranted,'' said U.S. Trade
Representative Clayton Yeutter.
   Another $114 million worth of goods, previously cut from the
list, was reinstated.
   And $40 million worth of new products was added, from $17
million worth of fireworks to $3,911 worth of pickled beans. Hong
Kong will be the biggest beneficiary, but only until mid-1988, when
it is due to lose its duty-free privilege entirely.
   None of the exporting countries was removed from the list in
this annual review.
   Yeutter said five countries whose labor and human rights
situations had been challenged by labor unions and others will
remain eligible because of ``improvements in their practices.''
They are Taiwan, South Korea, Indonesia, Thailand and Turkey.
   The Central African Republic is still being reviewed.
   The trade bill approved Thursday by conferees of the Senate and
House would increase pressure on Third World countries on labor
issues. It grants the president power to retaliate against exports
of countries where the government refuses to give workers
internationally recognized rights, such as the right to form unions.
   Supporters of the bill argue that denying such rights gives
those countries an unfair trade advantage because it enables them
to keep wages down.
   The Reagan administration opposed the provision but Rep. Donald
J. Pease D-Ohio, its chief sponsor, said in an interview today it
has not threatened a presidential veto on that ground.
   Pease said such provisions are intended not to deprive poor
countries of trade but to give them an incentive to change their
labor laws.
   ``It's already happening in country after country,'' he added.
   Yeutter's office gave Thailand until Dec. 15 to comply with U.S.
conditions for protecting patents and copyrights. He has been asked
by business groups here to deny duty-free privileges to Thailand on
this ground.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
