<HEAD>Navy Probing Two Helicopter Crashes in Three Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHITING FIELD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators are trying to determine
if there was a connection between the crashes of two training
helicopters within three days, a spokeswoman said Friday.
   Neither the instructor pilot, Marine Capt. Steven Andrews, nor
his student, Navy Ensign Scott Jackson, were hurt when their TH-57
helicopter crashed Thursday, said Airman Audry Anderson.
   Two days earlier, Marine Capt. Thomas Lindblad, an instructor,
was slightly injured and his student, Marine 2nd Lt. Bradley Eid,
was unhurt when another TH-57 went down.
   The helicopters crashed at two outlying practice fields, but
photos show each wound up on its left side and with its two-bladed
main rotor ripped from the aircraft.
   The helicopters were assigned to two squadrons in Whiting's
Training Air Wing 5.
