<DOCNO> AP880401-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1445EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Fire     04-01 0772</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Fire,0794</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cultural Leader Deplores Cover-up in Library Fire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading cultural figure accused Communist Party
officials of ``upside-down glasnost'' for trying to cover up the
truth about a fire that destroyed or damaged millions of literary
treasures at a Leningrad library.
   State Cultural Fund chairman Dmitri Likhachev said party
officials ignored the plight of Soviet literature and failed to
preserve rare books that their elders managed to protect even from
the siege of Leningrad during World War II.
   The Feb. 14-15 blaze struck the Library of the U.S.S.R. Academy
of Sciences in Leningrad and destroyed or damaged more than 3
million books and periodicals, Likhachev said in an interview with
the weekly Moscow News and in an article he wrote in the weekly
publication Book Review.
   He said the fire, which raged for 19 hours, was a national
disaster made worse by official attempts to conceal it and
``became, truly, a Chernobyl of our culture.''
   The historian, writer and cultural activist said 400,000 books
were destroyed by fire and 2.7 million books and periodicals
damaged by water and moisture. A quarter of the library's unique
newspaper fund was destroyed, and many of the lost issues were the
last in existence, he said.
   The library, located in a 1920s building on Leningrad's
Vasiliyevsky Island, contained about 12 million books, manuscripts
and periodicals. Its collection was started in 1714, about a decade
after Peter the Great founded the city.
   ``It pains me to recall how books were saved during the blockade
of Leningrad,'' said Likhachev, 81, referring to the World War II
occupation when citizens spirited away rare books and other art
treasures to protect them from the Nazis. ``Now, in these peaceful
and happy times, books are dying. Incredible.''
   Likhachev said the fire could have been prevented if party and
government officials had heeded warnings about the dilapidated
condition of the nation's most prestigious book collections.
   Warnings of impending disaster had been published in the
state-run press, and party officials responded with promises that
crumbling libraries and museums will be taken care of.
   ``There grew up splendid buildings of district party committees
and regional executive committees ... in which those who had signed
those official replies discussed the problems of leisure,
deliberated on the declining thirst for books and the crisis of
moral integrity,'' Likhachev said.
   ``This upside-down glasnost is worse than keeping silent, for it
creates the illusion that things are being done and enables people
to make believe that the train is picking up speed when in fact it
is standing stock-still,'' he said, referring to Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of openness.
   The losses could have been minimized, he claimed, if the fire
had been properly extinguished instead of by the ``antediluvian
method'' of having 25 fire engines flood the building for 19 hours.
   He accused library management of trying to hide the extent of
the damage and the mishandling of the fire and said administrator
V.A. Filov and his assistant, V.P. Leonov, should be fired.
   Filov originally estimated damage at about $4,800, and promised
the library would reopen within a few days.
   The March 8 edition of the party newspaper Pravda said damage
was at least $480,000, but added that the figure was based on 1956
values and that some of the lost material was priceless.
   Filov and Leonov ``both acted, in the first days, according to
the `model' programmed by the mistakes of the Chernobyl catastrophe
_ they tried to belittle the cultural loss in the grossest
manner,'' Likhachev claimed.
   He was referring to Soviet authorities' initial attempts to hush
up the world's worst nuclear disaster, an April 1986 explosion at
the Chernobyl nuclear plant in which at least 31 people died and
millions were exposed to increased levels of radioactivity.
   ``A bulldozer was called, and huge piles of burned, dampened and
undamaged books were destroyed,'' Likhachev wrote. ``Library
workers were prohibited from saving books from this heap of ruins.
All this was in order to hide more quickly from the eyes of society
the size of the catastrophe.''
   Mold started growing on the water-damaged books within a week,
and only through the efforts of literature students and other
volunteers has serious work begun to salvage the water-logged
books, he said.
   Special driers have been brought in, absorbent paper has been
painstakingly applied between the pages of soaked books and great
stores of other damaged materials that rescuers could not get to
immediately have been frozen to preserve them during the interim.
   He criticized officials for failing to seek foreign help in
salvaging damaged books.
</TEXT>
