<2ND_LINE>AM-Ireland-Dance,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S., Canadian Winners at World Irish Dancing Championships</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALWAY, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States won a gold and silver
medal at the 19th World Irish Dancing Championships, which drew
more than 4,000 participants from nine countries.
   John Jennings, from The Golden School of Irish dancing in New
York, won the world title in the competition for 17- to 19-year-old
boys on Thursday night.
   Second place went to another New Yorker, Neill Reagan, of the
Inish Free dance school in Miller Place, according to official
results released by the Irish Dancing Commission.
   There were 19 teen-agers in the competition from Australia,
Scotland, Ireland, England, Wales, Canada and the United States.
   Canadian Ryan Carroll of the Butler School in Oakville, Ontario,
won second place in the competition for 15- to 17-year-old boys.
   The championships, which started March 26 and end Easter Sunday,
are being held in Galway for the third time.
   Several other Americans missed out on the top rankings but were
named overseas winners for achieving the best scores among foreign
participants.
   Jean Butler of The Golden School in New York was the overseas
winner in the competition for 16- and 17-year-old girls, getting a
special distinction for placing sixth among 82 entries.
   Julie Showaher of the Dennehy School in Oaklawn, Ill., was
overseas winner in the competition for 15- to 16-year-old girls,
and Collette Cremins from the same school was overseas winner in
the 11- to 12-year-old girls' competition.
   Paul Mayer of the Mayer School in Elmhurst, Ill., was overseas
winner in the 13- to 15-year-old boys' competition, and Erin Pender
of the Schade School in New York was overseas winner in the 14- to
15-year-old girls' competition.
   The overseas winner in the mixed dancing competition for 13- to
16-year-olds was the McGing School in Chicago.
