<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz     04-01 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz,0631</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Progress Reported on Proposed Move of F-16s to Italy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Italy's defense minister assured Secretary of State
George P. Shultz on Friday that the government is considering
seriously the possible transfer to Italy of F-16 jets being evicted
from Spain.
   But Defense Minister Valerio Zanone did not commit Italy to
accepting the fighters. He said the entire NATO alliance should be
involved in the decision.
   Shultz took up the issue of the F-16s with Zanone during a stop
in Rome before heading for the Middle East on Sunday to continue
efforts to spur Arab-Israeli peace talks.
   Italy is considered the prime candidate to take the 72
fighter-bombers of the U.S. 401st Tactical Fighter Wing, based in
Torrejon, Spain. In January, Washington bowed to a Spanish demand
to remove the planes within three years.
   In a communique issued after the talks, the Defense Ministry
said Zanone ``stressed the satisfactory progress of the study under
way to identify all elements necessary to a carefully pondered
decision, which will have to be made in concert with Parliament.''
   Asked at a news conference whether an accord in principle had
been reached on the F-16s, Zanone replied, ``I wouldn't say an
accord in principle. There is serious attention by the Italian
government to the problem.''
   His statements did not go far beyond those made in February
following talks in Rome with Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci.
   Zanone reiterated Italy's position that the F-16s must remain in
Europe to protect NATO's southern flank, but that a decision on
where they should be relocated and how to finance the move must be
decided by the entire Western alliance.
   ``There is a predisposition by Italy to study the possibility''
of accepting the F-16s, the minister told reporters.
   Shultz did not meet with reporters after the meeting with Zanone.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said the meeting with
Zanone was ``not in any sense an effort to make commitments'' on
the F-16s.
   Zanone said he and Shultz discussed the ``various possible''
sites in Italy where the F-16s could be based, but he declined to
identify them. Italian media have identified possible sites as the
bases of Gioia del Colle in southern Puglia, Decimomannu in
Sardinia, the present cruise missile base in Comiso, Sicily, and
the U.S. base in Aviana in northeastern Italy.
   Zanone, the lone Cabinet minister from the tiny Liberal Party,
noted that the issue will have to be faced by Italy's new
government. Premier Giovanni Goria resigned three weeks ago, and
fellow Christian Democrat Ciriaco de Mita is trying to form a new
five-party coalition.
   Some Italian politicians, including former premier Bettino
Craxi, a Socialist, have voiced concerns about the possible
relocation. The Communists and other opposition groups are firmly
opposed.
   Shultz met earlier Friday with President Francesco Cossiga and
Foreign Minister Giulio Andreotti.
   Speaking with reporters earlier on the plane taking him to Rome,
Shultz was cautiously upbeat about his new Middle East peace
mission. His trip last month failed to bring an agreement.
   ``I think we have a chance to see some motion,'' he said of his
shuttling to Israel, Jordan, Syria, Egypt and Saudi Arabia.
   Shultz said he felt especially positive about the role of
Jordan's King Hussein, describing him as a ``key player'' in the
peace process.
   ``I hope we can make some headway,'' he said.
   So far only Eygpt has endorsed the plan to have talks on
Palestinian self-rule begin on May 1.
   On Saturday, Shultz is to have a private audience with Pope John
Paul II. He also plans to attend the pope's Easter Mass on Sunday
before leaving for Jerusalem.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
