<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     04-01 0569</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0591</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When it came to the crunch, Eric
Erickson says he's proud to be a ``Chocolate City Man.''
   Erickson, 31, wrote a song to defend his birthplace in the
``Chocolate Wars'' between Burlington, the home of Nestle Food
Corp., and Hershey Foods Corp. of Hershey, Pa.
   The battle began when Burlington adopted the name ``Chocolate
City USA'' during the debut of a chocolate festival in May 1987.
   Nestle, the city's largest employer, embraced the idea. But
Hershey Foods protested when Burlington officials filed for
trademark protection of the adopted name and a logo bearing a
chocolate morsel. Hershey Foods claimed they bore too close a
resemblance to its trademarks, including the name ``Chocolate Town
USA'' and the Hershey kiss.
   ``A word of warning, Hershey _ and it's more than just a hunch.
Try and scare us with your `kiss of death' and you'll get the
Nestle's Crunch,'' Erickson sings.
   He also advises Hershey: ``Forget about the lawsuit _ you'll
never make it stick. You'd be better off to get a glass of milk and
have some Nestle's Quick.''
   ``The song really makes you feel proud of this city,'' said Jack
Berry, chocolate festival coordinator.
   Hershey Foods was closed Friday and officials could not be
reached for comment.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of University of Massachusetts
professors has embraced ``squash power'' to help the land-grant
university celebrate its 125th anniversary.
   The professors have stuffed a young Hubbard squash into a
foot-square Plexiglass chamber so the fruit can expand only in a
downward direction. Now, the giant squash is growing ever larger in
a campus greenhouse, compressing a set of springs connected to a
set of load cells connected to a balance beam.
   And on Charter Day, April 29, the contraption will be wheeled
out to the campus pond to demonstrate the power of the fruit by
hoisting a tractor.
   The Hubbard hijinks have historical precedent, said John W.
Denison, professor emeritus in the College of Food and Natural
Resources. The experiment was first performed at the institution in
1874 by its third president, Col. William S. Clark, a ``somewhat
flamboyant botanist,'' according to Denison.
   Before it expired, Clark's squash hoisted about 5,000 pounds
worth of anvils, anchors, drainpipes, barrels of sand and
``whatever else he found lying around,'' Denison said.
   ``We figure to do a bit better, maybe 30,000 pounds'' Denison
said Wednesday. ``They've been really babying that vine over in the
greenhouse. They even come in on weekends to feed it.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DONIPHAN, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Elementary school Principal Gail Thompson
may think twice before betting with her pupils again.
   Thompson challenged her Doniphan Elementary School pupils to
read 10,000 books from October through March as part of the ``Book
It!'' national reading program. If she lost, she promised to spend
four hours in a tub of oatmeal.
   The 200 youngsters met the goal, so the principal headed for the
porridge Thursday, clad in a 1920s style bathing outfit, checked
hat and goggles.
   ``Ohhh, this is awful,'' she said as she stuck her foot in the
cereal.
   One of the youngsters was worried about the principal's ordeal.
   ``It's OK, honey,'' Thompson told a pre-schooler. ``You don't
have to feel sorry for me. It's just fun. I asked for it.''
   The pupils also were given a special breakfast treat in honor of
Thompson's adventure. You guessed it, oatmeal.
</TEXT>
