<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1524EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade     04-01 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>White House Issues Veto Warning Over Sweeping Trade Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administation threatened a
presidential veto of the newly minted congressional trade
compromise Friday unless major changes are made when lawmakers come
back from their spring break.
   The administration says the president's hands would be tied
unreasonably by provisions in the legislation calling for import
curbs to retaliate for trade agreement violations.
   The compromise worked out by House and Senate negotiators
Thursday night would transfer authority to retaliate from the
president to the U.S. trade representative. But it would leave
waiver authority if the president thought the costs of import curbs
would outweigh the benefits.
   The measure also would impose restricitions on imports to punish
Toshiba Corp. of Japan and its Toshiba Machine Co. subsidiary for
the latter's role in the sale to the Soviets of computerized
equipment that helps make Soviet submarines more difficult to
detect.
   ``We still have grave reservations about several of the
provisions, including plant closings, Toshiba, presidential
authority and some of the mandatory retaliatory provisions,''
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters traveling with Reagan to
California for a 10-day vacation.
   The plant closing provision would require employers to provide
their employees with 60-day notice of plant closings and
large-scale layoffs.
   Lawmakers who drew up the compromise wrapped up most of their
work before heading for the airports to start their spring break.
But they left enough loose ends to cloud the picture.
   Farm lawmakers were still wrangling over details, and a
House-passed plan to require registration of foreign property
ownership in the United States still had lawmakers deadlocked. They
planned to tackle the issue again later.
   Renewed White House veto threats should put the spotlight on
Senate Finance Committee Chairman Lloyd Bentsen, D-Texas, who is
empowered under the rules to start action that could lead to a
so-called superconference meeting of lawmakers to perform radical
surgery.
   Fitzwater said such a meeting already was in the works.
   ``The superconference will meet after recess, and if substantial
changes aren't made by the superconference, the president's senior
advisers will recommend a veto,'' Fitzwater said.
   Earlier, U.S Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter said Congress
``jettisoned a lot of undesirable things'' in negotiations this
week.
   ``The question is whether they jettisoned enough,'' he said.
``And we need a couple of days to assess that.'' He said there
``certainly are some provisions in there of dubious merit.''
   Some lawmakers already were indicating they saw room for
revision.
   ``The bill is good strong market opening legislation,'' said
Sen. John C. Danforth, R-Mo., one of the conferees.
   ``I am convinced that the trade provisions which are the heart
of the bill could be signed into law if they were standing alone,''
he said. ``But they are not standing alone. Congress will have an
opportunity in mid-April to consider any changes needed to meet
remaining objections from the administration.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880401-0150 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1528EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Daedalus     04-01 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Daedalus,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Daedalus Pilots Put Off Record Flight Attempt Because of Winds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IRAKLION, Crete (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The inventors of a flying machine to be
used in an attempt to break the world distance record for
human-powered flight said Friday that strong winds may delay the
endeavor for another three days.
   ``I think it's virtually impossible at this point to fly
tomorrow ... but Monday, Tuesday it should be feasible,'' said
Steve K. Bussulari, a Massachusetts Institute of Technology
aerospace expert heading the Daedalus project.
   Gale winds up to 45 mph are preventing the 70-pound plane from
attempting the 74-mile flight from Crete to the island of
Santorini, also known as Thira.
   ``Essentially, the airplane is ready to go anytime, and the
pilot's ready to go. We're in a pattern waiting on the weather,''
John S. Langford, the project director, told reporters.
   The flight will also update the 3,500-year-old legend of the
inventor Daedalus, who escaped from Crete with his son, Icarus, on
wings he made from feathers and wax. Icarus crashed into the sea
and drowned after soaring so close to the sun that his wings
melted, but Daedalus flew safely across the Aegean.
   The Daedalus 88 aircraft will be pedaled in a five-hour flight
that requires dead calm or a light southerly tailwind.
   Five pilots _ four Americans and a Greek _ are taking turns on
standby for 48 hours at a stretch and cycling up to 90 miles daily
to stay in shape. There are four backup pilots in case something
goes wrong.
   ``I feel a little disappointed I won't be going but I've been
watching the weather and saw this delay coming,'' said Greg Zack,
26, a professional cyclist who was ready to fly Friday or Saturday.
   The three-year MIT project already has produced one world record
distance for human-powered flight of 37.2 miles. It was set by
Glenn Tremml, piloting a Daedalus prototype plane in circles around
Edwards Air Force Base in California in January 1987.
   But the straight-line world record still stands at 22 miles set
by Bryan Allen in 1979 flying across the English Channel.
   ``With the right wind, Daedalus 88 could probably go 100 miles,
but we'll be satisfied with a touchdown on Santorini,'' Langford
said.
   Langford said the 36-member team will wait until mid-May if
necessary to make the record flight.
   ``We've got funds for another six weeks and two backup planes
that we'd also be willing to lose in the attempt,'' he said.
   The graphite epoxy and plastic aircraft with a wingspan of 112
feet could break up if the pilot crashes into the sea.
   Greek navy vessels and a flotilla of inflatable crafts will
escort the Daedalus plane, which would fly just 15 feet above the
waves.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
