<2ND_LINE>AM-Irish,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Expresses Regret For Incident at IRA Funeral That Left 2 Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of attacking one
of two British soldiers who later were killed told police he was
sorry the incident occurred, according to testimony Friday.
   Anthony Gallagher, 17, appeared before Belfast Magistrates Court
charged with causing grievous bodily harm to Cpl. David Howes on
March 19. He was ordered to remain in jail until his next court
appearance April 22.
   Howes and Cpl. Derek Wood were beaten by a mob of mourners after
their car encountered an Irish Republican Army funeral procession
in a predominantly Roman Catholic district of west Belfast. They
later were shot to death.
   A detective with the Royal Ulster Constabulary, Northern
Ireland's police force, told the court that when police formally
charged Gallagher, he replied: ``I'm sorry it ever happened.''
   Gallagher is the fifth person charged in the incident.
   Two men have been charged with murder, a third was charged with
withholding information from police, and a fourth with trading a
pair of bloodstained slacks with a man believed to have been
involved in the murders.
   The outlawed, predominantly Catholic IRA has been fighting to
oust the British from Northern Ireland and to reunite the province
with the Republic of Ireland.
