<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1556EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Taxes-Scholarships     04-01 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taxes-Scholarships,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRS Promises Quick Refunds for Wrongly Taxed Student Incomes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service is promising
quick relief for students who are due refunds because they were
wrongly taxed on teaching or research stipends earned during
graduate school.
   In general, any pre-1987 stipend that meets three tests spelled
out by the agency in a 1975 ruling will be considered non-taxable,
the IRS said Friday. Students who apply for refunds of any
additional tax will get prompt attention, the agency said.
   The IRS announcement was aimed at clearing up confusion
resulting from the fact that courts have issued conflicting
decisions on the question. Some court rulings have been
considerably more stringent than the 1975 IRS policy, and some IRS
district offices have chosen to use the court decisions as a guide.
   As a result, thousands of students have been billed for back
taxes on their stipends. The IRS says there is no concerted drive
to audit the returns of graduate students, and says much of the
blame for the students' problem is because many colleges reported
their stipends as taxable income.
   A student who has paid additional taxes because a district IRS
office wrongly considered a stipend taxable should file an amended
return (Form 1040X) and ask for a refund, the IRS said. Those who
have received a bill but have not yet paid the tax should file for
an abatement.
   ``Taxpayers should clearly indicate on the form that the claim
is being filed for reconsideration of the teaching or research
stipend issue under Revenue Ruling 75-280,'' the IRS said.
   That ruling states that a stipend is non-taxable if:
   _The student was a degree candidate at the time the stipend was
earned.
   _The student performed research, teaching or other services that
were required for a degree.
   _Similar services were required of all candidates for the degree.
   If those tests are met, the IRS said, the stipend will be
considered non-taxable under the presumption that its primary
purpose was to further the student's education or training.
   The rule applies only to stipends paid before 1987. A new law
that took effect in 1987 specifically taxes such income.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
