<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BoozeandBowling     04-01 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Booze and Bowling,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women's League Is Out; Don't Drink Enough</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOUNT CLEMENS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Wednesday Night Ladies House
League says their bowling alley manager cares more about how many
beers they knock down than pins.
   The league has been ousted from its 6 p.m. time slot in favor of
a men's league _ who put more of a dent in a keg than the ladies.
   ``The women are out, the men are in because they can drink more
than us, ... that's the bottom line,'' league official Mary-Lou
Allen said Thursday. ``Drinking should not be a prerequisite for
bowling.''
   Jimmy Walker, manager of Fern Hill Golf and Country Club lanes
in this Detroit suburb, said he asked the 60 league members
Wednesday to switch to another time slot for their 30-week season
beginning next fall strictly for business reasons.
   ``Women's leagues water you do death,'' he said, bemoaning what
he says is their preference for water over more costly beverages.
``That's why most places don't cater to women on the first
(evening) shift. The bowling business is not strictly bowling.''
   He said the men's league taking the women's place next fall will
bring in $100 to $150 per night in addition to regular bowling
costs. The women sometimes spent as little as $40 a night, he said.
   And some leagues are worth still more.
   ``What would you do if you owned the business?'' he asked.
``We've got an AMVETS league in here that does $250 to $275 a
night, and they're all great guys.''
   The league isn't sure what it will do, but Carol Blossey,
outgoing president and a member of Mothers Against Drunk Driving,
said she plans to file a complaint with her organization.
   ``I have a beer once in a while, but I can't bowl well if I'm
drunk,'' said Blossey, who carries a 167 average. ``I feel we're
being discriminated against.''
</TEXT>
