<1ST_LINE>r a AM-EasterBunnies     04-01 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Easter Bunnies,0197</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Seattle's Zoo Not A Shelter For Unwanted Easter Pets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Woodland Park Zoo says it no longer has a
problem with people abandoning their rabbits after Easter since
word spread that zookeepers feed some of the unwanted pets to the
lions.
   Zoo spokesman Hank Klein said Friday that in years past the zoo
was overrun with rabbits. After Easter passed, some people found
that bunnies aren't as much fun in May as they were in March or
April.
   Abandoned rabbits damaged the zoo grounds and created other
problems, Klein said. Domestic rabbits can't survive on their own
and end up starving, getting run over by cars or eaten by owls and
hawks.
   The zoo now has a pest control officer who traps and kills
rabbits, adding them to the daily feed for lions, wolves and
cougars.
   ``There are not too many people that want cute little Thumper to
end up in the jaws of a lion,'' Klein said.
   ``It's not a good idea to surprise someone with a bunny,'' he
said. ``We encourage people to think very carefully before giving
any animal, especially as a surprise.''
</TEXT>
