<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PlasticBeauty     04-01 0410</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Plastic Beauty,0423</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Naming Of Plastic Surgery Expert For Miss San Diego Pageant Causes
Flap</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The naming of a plastic surgery consultant to
the Miss San Diego Pageant is drawing grimaces from state and
national pageant officials, but Stephen Grifka doesn't understand
what all the fuss is about.
   The Culver City doctor said cosmetic surgery is a legitimate
option for today's beauty queens.
   ``This is a competition,'' Grifka said. ``And in order to get
the competitive edge, they want to enhance themselves to the
maximum amount. I can't change a couch into a chair. But I can
certainly fluff up a pillow.''
   Dayna Waitley, executive director of the Miss San Diego Pageant,
appointed Grifka to the unpaid consulting position at the
recommendation of a mutal friend.
   In a Jan. 5 letter to Grifka, Waitley wrote that the expertise
of the doctor, who specializes in nose jobs, scar removal and
facelifts, could help contestants realize their full potential.
   The appointment brought a storm of criticism from other beauty
pageant officials.
   ``That's the last kind of person who would ever be involved with
the Miss America Pageant,'' Leonard C. Horn, chief executive
officer of the Miss America Pageant, said in an interview in
Friday's Los Angeles Times San Diego edition.
   ``We have consultants on hair and evening gowns, but to have a
consultant on plastic surgery seems a little strange,'' Horn said.
   Though Horn branded the idea as ``laughable,'' plastic surgery
is permitted under pageant rules. Indeed, there were reports
shortly after the 1982 contest that titlist Debra Sue Maffett had
undergone extensive cosmetic work.
   ``There is no chance in the world he would ever be associated
with us,'' said Robert Arnhym, chief executive officer of the Miss
California Pageant, which oversees the San Diego pageant and 41
other contests throughout the state.
   ``No one in the state of California has ever encouraged our
winners to have plastic surgery _ ever,'' Arnhym said.
   Grifka had no involvement in this year's pageant, which was held
March 19, Waitley said. She said she will ask the pageant's board
of directors to review the arrangement because of the protest.
   For his part, Grifka said he accepted the appointment with the
best of intentions and has no desire to bring negative publicity to
the pageant.
   ``These contests are not strictly a show of beauty,'' he said.
``If you attended a pageant you would be amazed at how talented
these girls are.''
</TEXT>
