<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Unrest     04-01 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Unrest,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Television Reports Strikes, Appeals for Order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet TV reported Friday that strikes have
paralyzed most industry in Stepanakert, the main city in a Caucasus
region that is at the center of an ethnic dispute.
   The nightly news program, ``Vremya,'' said construction was at a
standstill and delivery of goods to and from the city had been
disrupted.
   ``Public transport is virtually at a halt and many enterprises
are idle on account of the failure to turn out to work,'' it said.
   Reports by ``Vremya'' and the official news agency Tass appeared
aimed at convincing Armenians it is futile to press demands for
annexation of the Nagorno-Karabakh region, which was made part of
Azerbaijan in 1923.
   About 75 percent of the 157,000 residents are ethnic Armenians,
most of whom are Christian. Azeris, the indigenous population of
Azerbaijan, are predominantly Shiite Moslem.
   Farmers in Nagorno-Karabakh were shown on television hard at
work with spring planting. The news reader said the Akhtanak
collective farm had appealed for a return to normal in Stepanakert.
   Cameras panned deserted building sites and quiet streets in the
city while the narrator explained that most workers were staying
home.
   Stepanakert's industries have run up debts of ``several million
rubles,'' the report said. No more specific figure was provided.
   Most industrial activity stopped March 24 in protest of the
Communist Party leadership's refusal to attach Nagorno-Karabakh to
Soviet Armenia.
   Activists in Armenia and Nagorno-Karabakh began demonstrations
in mid-February demanding that Nagorno-Karabakh, slightly smaller
than Delaware, be made part of Armenia even though there is no
common border. The Kremlin refused and said protests were
``intolerable,'' although it announced a development program.
   The Armenian claims incited riots Feb. 28 in the Azerbaijan city
of Sumgait. Official reports said 32 people were killed and nearly
200 injured, and that about 400 were arrested for murder, rape,
looting and other crimes.
   Communist Party officials said the Nagorno-Karabakh development
plan would involve spending 400 million rubles _ $640 million at
the official exchange rate _ to improve housing, education,
Armenian-language literature and broadcasts, and other elements of
life in the region.
   Complaints that Nagorno-Karabakh was losing its traditional
Armenian character were among points cited by activists in their
demand for annexation.
   ``Vremya'' said the development plan will not be carried out if
the strike continues.
   ``The people of Stepanakert have long been renowned for their
good sense, their love of work, their skill,'' the news reader
said. ``Let them show all these qualities now in the present
difficult situation.''
   Security forces were deployed in Yerevan, the Armenian capital,
earlier in the week to guard against more disorder there, but it
was not clear from the Vremya footage whether similar measures were
being taken in Stepanakert.
   Telephone calls to the region were not answered Friday, even at
such facilities as railroad stations and newspaper offices.
   In its only dispatch on the matter Friday, Tass outlined legal
problems involved in addressing Armenian demands for annexation. It
said the legislatures of both republics would have to approve any
change in status and the national Supreme Soviet would have the
final say.
</TEXT>
