<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Unemployment Bjt   04-01 0690</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Unemployment, Bjt,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unemployment Rate Falls To Decade-Low 5.6 Percent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WASHINGTON _ (AP) _ The nation's unemployment rate fell to a new
decade-low 5.6 percent in March even though there were 306,000
fewer Americans at work than a month earlier, the government said
Friday.
   The drop from February's 5.7 percent rate was credited entirely
to a 455,000 decrease in the number of people in the labor force _
those either holding jobs or seeking work _ raising inflationary
alarms among some economists.
   ``It's just one month, but it indicates that wages are not high
enough to coax second earners out of the home any more,'' said
Roger Brinner, an analyst for Data Resources Inc., an economic
consulting firm in Lexington, Mass.
   ``If the labor force has stopped growing, then wage inflation
may be right around the corner, not now but possibly in early
1989,'' Brinner said. ``Higher wages might coax more people out of
the woodwork, but any increase in the standard of living will be
temporary because prices will soon catch up.''
   The number of Americans in the labor force dropped from
approximately 123.1 million to 122.6 million between February and
March, as the percentage of the population age 16 and over holding
or seeking jobs declined from an all-time record 66.3 percent to 66
percent.
   The government has been warning about a reduced rate of labor
force expansion for several years, based on declining birth rates
in the 1960s and early 1970s.
   And a big part of the full percentage point drop in a jobless
rate that stood at 6.6 percent in March 1987 was the fact that the
number of new jobs last year climbed by 3 million while the labor
force grew by only 2 million.
   ``Although women are continuing to enter the labor force in
large numbers, the rate of their increase has slowed,'' Labor
Statistics Commissioner Janet L. Norwood told the Joint Economic
Committee of Congress on Friday. ``The dramatic surge of women in
the labor force took place in the 1960s and 1970s.''
   While the lower unemployment rates are raising fears of renewed
inflation among some economists, there certainly was no evidence of
it on the wage front last month.
   Average wages in private industry rose just 2 cents an hour in
March to $9.20, just 3 percent above what they were a year earlier.
Consumer prices, meanwhile, have risen 3.9 percent in the same
period.
   ``The experience in the 1980s clearly shows that full employment
and a falling inflation rate are not incompatible,'' said Richard
Rahn, chief economist for the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. ``We have
reached the lowest unemployment rate in a decade without stoking
the fires of inflation.''
   Except for May 1979, when joblessness also was 5.6 percent,
March's rate is actually the lowest it has been since August 1974.
   Reagan administration officials were quick to pounce on the
figures to bolster their opposition to union-sought provisions in a
trade bill that would require companies to give workers 60 days
advance notice of layoffs.
   ``Sixty-four straight months of job creation and nearly 16
million new jobs is the product of a vibrant, innovative and
entrepreneurial economy,'' said Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin.
``Now is not the time to put on the brakes with anti-competitive,
anti-growth federal mandates on business.''
   Despite the fewer number of Americans at work, employer payrolls
showed an increase f 262,000 new jobs in March, according to a
separate survey by the department.
   Ms. Norwood explained that the payroll survey and the household
survey from which the unemployment rate is calculated have moved in
opposite directions before.
   ``Over the long run, however, the two surveys generally show
similar trends,'' she said, adding that the payroll survey is
probably a better indicator of what actually occured in March.
   But the news on the payroll survey wasn't entirely good either.
Factory jobs, after rising an average 40,000 each month since last
summer, fell by 1,000 in March, with small declines spread over 11
major industries.
   Of the new payroll jobs, 85,000 were in business and health care
services with another 80,000 in construction.
</TEXT>
