<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LorraineMotel     04-01 0509</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lorraine Motel,0525</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lorraine Tour Guide On Outside Now</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In happier times, she planted flowers for
the anniversary and directed tours of the small motel where Martin
Luther King Jr. died.
   But now, in the 20th year after his death, Jacqueline Smith
huddles on a sidewalk, wraps herself in plastic to keep off the
rain and tells anyone who'll listen how the slain civil rights
leader would not like plans to make The Lorraine Motel a museum.
   Miss Smith, 37, lived and worked at The Lorraine for 11 years
and helped organize annual gatherings there on the anniversary of
King's death.
   ``We would clean up and plant flowers, and how the crowd was
handled was up to me,'' she said.
   But Miss Smith was evicted March 2 and has no official role in
ceremonies set Monday for the 20th anniversary of King's death.
   ``I feel sad,'' she said. ``I'll miss talking with the people as
they go in the room.''
   Participants in memorial programs for the King anniversary plan
a march through town, ending at The Lorraine. After a wreath-laying
ceremony there, a combination march and motorcade billed as a
``poor peoples' pilgrimage'' will be launched from the motel for a
trek through Mississippi, Alabama and Georgia.
   The Lorraine, where King was staying while helping lead a
Memphis sanitation workers' strike, is to become a civil rights
museum.
   For past anniversaries, visitors could go to the room where King
stayed. Over the years, motel employees built a makeshift shrine in
the room.
   State officials closed The Lorraine in January and put a
chain-link fence around it, saying it was unsafe for habitation.
Miss Smith stayed on.
   After her forced eviction, she set up housekeeping on the
sidewalk.
   The motel is in a downtown district of warehouses and low-rent
apartments, but developers have begun in recent years to upgrade
property in the area in hopes of attracting middle-income renters.
   Miss Smith claims the $8.8 million museum will speed the
gentrification of the neighborhood.
   ``Dr. King would not want the poor people displaced,'' she said.
   The project for The Lorraine museum, financed by the state and
local governments, is largely due to the work of a citizens' group
which raised $140,000 to buy the motel at a foreclosure auction.
The museum is scheduled to open in 1991.
   D'Army Bailey, a Memphis lawyer and a prime mover behind the
project, said museum visitors will be surrounded by pictures and
sounds of civil rights marches of the 1960s.
   ``The museum will take you back to those times and do all we can
to recreate those feelings, the tensions of the moment,'' he said.
``When people come in and spend an hour or two and then walk out, I
think and hope that what walks out is going to be affected and
changed.''
   Bailey said it has taken almost 20 years for local government to
realize that The Lorraine should be preserved as an integral though
painful part of Memphis history.
</TEXT>
