<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ActivistSlain     04-01 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Activist Slain,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>District Attorney Asks Governor To Allow Him Unopposed Bid</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor running for judge in racially
troubled Robeson County on Friday asked the governor not to call a
special legislative session to let a minority candidate enter the
race after the slaying of a Lumbee Indian contender.
   District Attorney Joe Freeman Britt declared himself the
Democratic nominee for Superior Court judge. Britt, who is white
and would have faced Julian Pierce in the May 3 Democratic primary,
would automatically win the judgeship in November because there is
no Republican candidate.
   Britt met privately for an hour with Gov. Jim Martin a day after
supporters of Pierce asked the Republican governor for the special
session. Britt had no comment afterward except to say, ``You will
have to get your information from the governor's office.''
   Martin's chief of staff, Phil Kirk, said Britt had met with the
governor at Martin's request and had spoken ``very firmly'' against
a special session.
   ``He considers himself to be the nominee of the Democratic Party
for the ... judgeship,'' Kirk told reporters.
   Martin said he remained undecided and would discuss the matter
with advisers and legislators over the weekend. He said he hoped to
make a decision early next week.
   Pierce was shot to death last week in what authorities described
at first as a probable assassination. On Tuesday, they arrested a
young man and said a second suspect committed suicide, and
attributed Pierce's murder to a domestic dispute.
   Under state law, if a candidate dies more than 30 days after
filing for a primary has closed, his opponent wins. Pierce's
supporters want the law amended to allow a replacement candidate.
   The judgeship is one of nine created last year in districts
designed to enhance minorities' prospects for winning.
   Britt's supporters suggested that Britt was a minority candidate
since blacks and Indians make up 58 percent of the registered
voters in Robeson County, Kirk said. But he said that argument
``doesn't hold water'' because the Legislature intended for whites
to be outnumbered in the new districts.
   ``That's why they were created that way, to give minorities an
excellent chance to be elected,'' Kirk said.
</TEXT>
