<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HoneySupports     04-01 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honey Supports,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Support Price Down 6 Percent From Last Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The support price for 1988-crop honey will
average 59.1 cents per pound, down 6 percent from last year's
level, Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng announced Friday.
   Actual honey support prices will vary between about 48 cents to
62 cents per pound, depending on the color or class of honey
offered by producers, Lyng said. The price supports will be carried
out through loans on honey stored on or off the farm.
   Under the 1985 farm law, honey supports are being gradually
reduced. Last year's average loan rate was 63 cents per pound and
the 1986 rate was 64 cents.
   Lyng also said the 1988 program will retain the ``marketing
loan'' provision to help reduce inventories held as surplus by the
department's Commodity Credit Corp.
   In earlier years, producers could redeem their honey only by
paying off the full amount of the CCC loan, plus interest. They had
the option of not repaying the loan at all, allowing CCC to assume
ownership of the honey which had been offered as collateral.
   Consequently, because of large supplies and low market prices,
CCC inventories of forfeited honey increased rapidly.
   But since the 1985 law, a honey producer can take out a loan and
then repay it at the prevailing market rate. In effect, this allows
the beekeeper to sell honey to the government at a specified price
and then buy it back at a lower price.
   Currently, producers who obtained price support loans averaging
63 cents per pound for 1987 honey can pay off the loans at 34 to 40
cents per pound, depending on quality.
   Lyng said the lower buy-back rates ``will be established at
levels that will minimize loan forfeitures, reduce honey stocks and
storage costs, and maintain the competitiveness of domestic honey
in U.S. and export markets.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
