<DOCNO> AP880401-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1641EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HumorConference     04-01 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Humor Conference,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Humor Conference Opens On April Fool's Day With Nary A Gag</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WEST LAFAYETTE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The seventh National Conference on
Humor opened on April Fool's Day without so much as a gag,
practical joke or even a hint of buffoonery.
   The 70-odd scholars gathered Friday at Purdue University to
dissect the fragile body of humor. These humor anatomists
specialize in the brain more than the funnybone.
   ``This is serious business,'' said Purdue linguist Victor
Raskin, the conference chairman.
   How serious? Well, have you heard the one about, ``The Effects
of a Silent or Laughing Confederate and the Amplification or
Inhibition of Facial Reactions on Cartoon Funniness Evaluation?''
   Ball State University researchers Lambert Deckers and Daniel
Moore planned to deliver a paper on that topic during the three-day
conference.
   ``You don't have to be funny while you're presenting a paper,''
Raskin said.
   He knows the public is puzzled by the paradox of
``excrutiatingly boring'' research on a topic that is mirth itself.
   He learned that lesson the hard way, ducking ripe tomatoes and
rotten eggs hurled by the media after the first conference in the
1970s at Arizona State University.
   ``The media decided that the humor conference was supposed to be
hilarious,'' he said ruefully. ``So there was a full page report in
Time magazine on how boring it was, complete with a couple of
pictures of back-benchers dozing off during presentations.
   ``Well, we learned our lesson,'' he said.
   At the five conferences that followed at Arizona State,
reporters were invited to cover sessions featuring humorists and
dynamic public speakers, while the real work was carried out in
back rooms, he said.
   ``The media on the whole have been very happy with those
conferences ever since,'' he said.
   There is something funny going on here, though. The meeting is
called the WHIM conference, that's for Western Humor and Irony
Membership.
   And, for those not celebrating Passover on Friday night, the
program guide promised seating for ``an indefinite number of
people'' at a beer and pizza place down the block. On Sunday night,
a three-hour joke-telling contest was scheduled.
   But why do these academics _ linguists, psychologists,
anthropologists and sociologists _ do it?
   Raskin's answer is basically, ``Why not?''
   ``It's an important natural phenomenon,'' he said. ``It's a
human faculty, and we study all the other faculties. We study the
mind, we study emotions, we study our health and behavior. And
humor is part of all that.''
   While a comedian knows which material works, the professors want
to know why.
   ``You don't expect a gymnast or a figure skater to come up with
a scientific explanation on their failures or successes,'' said
Raskin. ``That's what we are for. We're trying to figure out what
makes humor work.
   ``I know of no reseachers who have any ambition to become
stand-up comedians,'' he said. ``Most of us are professors, and we
use a lot of humor in the classroom. But that's a matter of
survival. If you don't, the students doze off on you and this is
reflected in your teacher evaluations and salary raises.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880401-0169 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1641EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LiteraryAwards 1stLd-Writethru a0676 04-01 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Literary Awards, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0676,0224</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>16 Americans to Receive Literary Awards</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after the 4th to update with Holmes' death.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixteen Americans will receive literary awards
from the American Academy and Institute of Arts and Letters, the
academy announced Friday.
   In addition, the academy announced that Blake Morrison of London
will receive the E.M. Forster award, given to an English writer for
a stay in the United States.
   Nine of the 16 awards include $5,000 purses given to encourage
writers in their creative work.
   Those nine are William Barrett of North Tarrytown; David Bottoms
of Marietta, Ga.; Rosellen Brown of Houston, Texas; David Cope of
Grandville, Mich.; John Clellon Holmes of Old Saybrook, Conn.; John
McCormick of Princeton, N.J.; James Seay of Chapel Hill, N.C.;
William Weaver of Arezzo, Italy; and Norman Williams of North
Ferrisburgh, Vt.
   Holmes died Wednesday of cancer in Middletown, Conn., and the
prize money will go to his estate, the Academy said. Holmes had
been told of winning the prize.
   The other seven are Andrew Hudgins of Montgomery, Ala.; Kaye
Gibbons of Raleigh, N.C.; Edward Hirsch of Houston; Thomas McMahon
of Wellesley, Mass.; Andre Dubus of Haverhill, Mass.; Jonathan Evan
Maslow of Mobile, Ala., and Clement Greenberg of New York City.
   The awards will be given May 18.
</TEXT>
