<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IBP-Wages     04-01 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IBP-Wages,530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Sues Meatpacker on Overtime Pay</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government sued the nation's second
largest meatpacker Friday on a claim that it cheated tens of
thousands of workers out of millions of dollars in overtime pay at
10 packinghouses in Kansas, Iowa, Nebraska, Minnesota and Idaho.
   In a suit filed in Kansas City, Kan., the Labor Department
accused IBP Corp. of ``repeatedly and willfully'' violating laws
requiring employers to pay hourly workers one and one-half times
the normal wage for work beyond 40 hours a week.
   The suit seeks what the government claims is unpaid overtime
plus interest stretching back to April 1985 for between 20,000 and
70,000 current and former employees of the company.
   Government officials refused to specify how much the sought
damages might total, but one acknowledged that it will likely be in
the tens of millions of dollars.
   Attorneys for the United Food and Commercial Workers Union,
which is trying to organize some of the plants and initiated the
Labor Department's action, calculated the possible back pay awards
at between $20 million and $43 million.
   The suit is based on allegations that IBP workers were required
by the company to spend up to two hours a week putting on, taking
off and cleaning safety equipment and maintaining knives without
being paid for their labor.
   Based on hourly wages in the industry averaging $6 an hour, and
assuming each worker was denied about two hours of overtime a week,
the union calculated that each worker may be owed as much as $3,744
in back pay.
   Full-time employment at the 10 plants is slightly less than
9,000 according to company officials. However, meatpacking has one
of the highest job turnover rates of any industry in the country _
estimated by some at as much as 80 percent annually.
   Gary Mickelson, an IBP spokesman, said the company is
``confident the courts will find our policies entirely acceptable
and lawful.''
   He said IBP follows the same wage practices with regard to
maintaining safety equipment at its three unionized plants and its
11 non-union packinghouses. None of the unionized plants was
mentioned in the suit.
   ``It's the same procedure industrywide,'' Mickelson said. ``The
unions have negotiated away what the Labor Department thinks we
should be paying.''
   ``We find this action ironic,'' he added. ``On one hand our
company has been widely criticized as not doing enough to ensure
the safety of our employees. Now we're being sued for making sure
our employees take the time to wear the equipment necessary to
protect them on the job.''
   Last summer the Labor Department fined IBP $2.6 million for
alleged job safety and record violations at its flagship
packinghouse at Dakota City, Neb.
   The investigation leading up to that fine, which has been
appealed by the company, was prompted by another complaint that the
union filed with the government while engaged in a strike at the
Dakota City plant.
   The suit Friday alleged the wage law violations occurred at IBP
plants in Emporia and Holcomb, Kan.; Madison and West Point, Neb.;
Luverne, Minn.; Denison, Storm Lake, Council Bluffs and Columbus
Junction, Iowa; and Boise, Idaho.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880401-0171 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1647EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ArtsStruggle     04-01 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arts Struggle,0564</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orchestra Cancels Season, Ballet Troupe Collapses In Chicago</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The city's No. 2 symphony orchestra is canceling
the rest of its 1988 concert season because of money troubles, only
months after Chicago's ballet company disintegrated.
   The Orchestra of Illinois, a highly praised group observing its
10th anniversary this season, announced Thursday it is canceling
its remaining seven performances because of a $410,000 deficit in
its $650,000 budget.
   ``The situation is very serious,'' Linda G. Moore, the
orchestra's executive director, said in a Chicago Tribune
interview. ``Our cash-flow position has been bad for some time, and
it has gotten to the point where we literally don't have enough
money to pay our musicians.''
   Just four months earlier, the Chicago City Ballet, the city's
only classical ballet troupe, collapsed following an internal
dispute over artistic directorship that alienated its chief
financial supporter.
   But the two groups' failures do not necessarily cast a pall over
the performing arts in general, observers say.
   ``One organization's problems do not necessarily reflect the
community,'' said Matthew Raphaelson, director of the Chicago Music
Alliance, a service organization comprising 15 orchestras and
dozens of other music groups such as operas and chamber music
companies.
   ``We have 86 member organizations ... and many of them are doing
quite well,'' said Raphaelson. ``Many are having their best years.''
   The city also has been supporting 28 performing companies,
including the now-defunct Chicago City Ballet, said Lisa Tylke,
executive director of the Chicago Dance Arts Coalition, another
service organization.
   Dancers who lost jobs at Chicago City Ballet have followed its
former artistic director, Daniel Duell, in an attempt ``to rise
from the ashes'' with a new classical troupe called Ballet Chicago,
Ms. Tylke said.
   The troupe has given one fundraising performance in its own
behalf and is practicing for another in May.
   Gregory Mansfield, spokesman for the Illinois Arts Council, a
state agency that poured $2.2 million into performing arts last
year, said the failures of the orchestra and the ballet are the
only ones he is aware of in the state this year.
   Those failures may end up as springboards to healthier
organizations, he said.
   The Orchestra of Illinois has a record of artistic excellence
and could resolve its problems, he said. The orchestra's board has
ordered outside experts to analyze its financial affairs to see
what can be done, he said.
   ``The arts council feels that by stopping to re-evaluate, an
arts organization can often emerge actually better,'' Mansfield
said. ``And there are hundreds of arts organizations in Chicago
that are doing quite well, and I'm speaking of performing arts.''
   Raphaelson said setbacks for performing groups seem to generate
more fear than problems with business organizations.
   ``When it happens in the arts community, people seem to get more
nervous than if it were soft drinks or crackers,'' he said.
   He speculated that the reason is that arts groups depend more on
fund raising and benefactors, who may be unduly frightened by
negative signs.
   ``The solution, obviously, (for arts advocates) is to be ever
more outspoken in their support for the arts,'' he said. ``If that
fear is the reality, the problem is not so much a problem in the
industry as a problem of perception.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
