<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SocialSecurity     04-01 0122</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Social Security,120</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, Spain Agree To Eliminate Duplicate Taxation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States and Spanish governments have
agreed to eliminate duplicate coverage and taxation under the two
countries' Social Security systems, Social Security Commissioner
Dorcas R. Hardy announced Friday.
   Many U.S. citizens working in Spain for U.S employers now pay
Social Security contributions to both countries for the same work,
and the same applies to many Spanish nationals working in the
United States.
   Elimination of the overlapping requirements was effective Friday.
   Similar agreements were already in effect with Belgium, Canada,
Italy, Norway, Sweden, Switzerland, the United Kingdom and West
Germany. Agreements have been signed with France and the
Netherlands and are expected to become effective later this year.
</TEXT>
