<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Poll,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll Results Show 2-1 in Favor of Meese Quitting</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Meese Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fifty-five percent of those questioned said
Attorney General Edwin Meese III should resign his post, according
to a U.S. News & World Report poll released Friday.
   Only 21 percent of the respondents said Meese should stay in
office, the magazine said.
   Fifty percent of those who considered themselves politically
conservative said Meese should quit, while only 27 percent of all
conservatives believed he should stay, the magazine said.
   Forty-six percent of Republicans said Meese should go, compared
with only 28 percent who said he should continue. Sixty-one percent
of all Democrats and 54 percent of all independents should Meese
should quit.
   Meese, who has been under criminal investigation for 11 months,
has been under pressure in Congress this week to quit since two top
aides left the Justice Department. The aides said Meese's
continuing legal problems were hurting the department's operations
and image.
   The nationwide telephone poll of 1,004 adults, conducted by The
Roper Organization on Wednesday and Thursday, has a margin of error
of plus or minus four percentage points.
</TEXT>
