<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Robertson     04-01 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson To Spend Easter In Colorado</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBBIE NEWBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate Pat Robertson is
spending Easter weekend in Colorado trying to drum up support for
his dormant campaign.
   ``He will be making an appearance, encouraging people to go
vote'' in Colorado's caucuses on Monday night, Robertson state
campaign coordinator David Nelson said Friday.
   Robertson has conceded that he has virtually no chance of
winning the Republican nomination. But he plans to stay in the race
in hopes he can influence the GOP platform that will be drawn up at
the national convention.
   ``He wants to represent conservatives and Christians in the
formation of the platform so we can have a voice,'' Nelson said.
   In Colorado, Nelson hopes Robertson can win one-third to
one-half of the state's 36 GOP delegates.
   He said up to 10 phone bank operators are trying to persuade at
least 10,000 people to show up for the caucuses. ``Our goal would
be to have 15,000,'' he said.
   The former television evangelist's only strong showings have
come in caucus states, where organization and depth of support
count.
   Robertson's three-day schedule here includes talks to an
estimated 5,000 people in four Denver-area congregations on Easter
Sunday.
   Robertson summed up his version of the Easter message this way
during a rally in a Virginia Beach, Va., church last weekend:
``...Some of the press have been saying that in terms of my
candidacy that it is dead. What they don't know about is the
resurrection.''
   Nelson said Robertson wouldn't mix church and politics in his
talks, although Robertson's support has been derived primarily from
fundamentalist Christians.
   ``I don't think it's proper to go into a church and say, `Vote
for me.' I believe Pat respects the rules and regulations involving
churches and politics. He will just talk about how important it is
to be involved in the political process,'' he said.
</TEXT>
