<HEAD>Reporters Protest Telecast of Soccer Match During Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Television reporters, angered by the live telecast
of a soccer match during a journalists' strike, staged a
retaliatory walkout Friday that halted all newscasts by the
state-controlled RAI network.
   The National Journalists Union backed the 24-hour blackout of
televised news, calling RAI's behavior ``a severe attack against
the right to strike.''
   RAI telecast the exhibition soccer match between the national
teams of Italy and Yugoslavia on Thursday night, reportedly bowing
to pressure from sponsors who had invested about $300,000 in
advertising at the Yugoslav stadium.
   The telecast was without comment and viewers could hear only the
crowd noise.
   ``Ninety minutes of mute soccer on television,'' wrote the Milan
newspaper Corriere della Sera in a front-page story critical of
RAI's decision.
   Italian press and television journalists have been striking on
and off for weeks to protest a breakdown in negotiations for a new
labor contract.
   Italy's major newspapers will not print Saturday because of the
continuing strikes.
