<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ChallengerMedals     04-01 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Challenger Medals,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Relatives of Challenger Astronauts Given Flight Medals</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA flight medals honoring the seven astronauts
who died in the Challenger explosion more than two years ago were
given Friday to their families.
   The presentations were made during a ceremony a day after
hundreds of people gathered at a celebrity-packed tribute and
fund-raiser for the Challenger Center for Space Education.
   June Scobee, widow of Challenger commander Dick Scobee, said it
would have been a ``tremendous moment'' for the astronauts if they
had lived to receive the flight medals, along with framed
certificates acknowledging work in the space program.
   ``Their proudest moment was to be known as one of you (NASA),''
Mrs. Scobee said, choking back tears.
   ``We want to thank you,'' she added.
   ``The dream is alive,'' Mrs. Scobee said, apparently in
reference to the challenger center project. ``And it's becoming not
only a dream, but a reality.''
   Conceived and developed by family members of the crew, the
educational center will offer teachers and students the opportunity
to learn about space by participating in simulated space flights
and missions at the flagship center in Washington, D.C., and at
satellite learning centers around the country.
   Some $2.5 million has been raised for the center since the
Challenger explosion Jan. 28, 1986, when all seven astronauts died.
   Daniel C. Brandenstein, chief of the astronaut office at NASA's
Johnson Space Center, said the medals are given to those who have
``made significant contributions to the manned space program.''
   Those appearing Thursday night were The Fabulous Thunderbirds,
Melba Moore, Pia Zadora, Brooke Shields, actor Michael York, The
Houston Pops, and Michael Maguire and Brandy Brown, who are
starring on Broadway's ``Les Miserables.''
</TEXT>
