<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Neighbors-Kidnapping     04-01 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Neighbors-Kidnapping,0520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Angry Neighbors Track Down Honor Cadet in Reported Kidnapping</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military school student was hunted down
and held at gunpoint by neighbors convinced he had kidnapped a
4-year-old girl, officials said.
   Kenneth Widel Jr., 21, was jailed on a kidnapping charge and
released Friday on $2,500 bail. He said the child was going to show
him where an old girlfriend of his lived in a subdivision near
Orlando.
   Widel, a senior at The Citadel in South Carolina, was tracked
down Wednesday night by neighbors who were alerted by a 5-year-old
friend of the little girl. Widel's car was spotted, and a neighbor
stopped it and forced Widel to step out. The girl ran home.
   ``If words could kill, that guy would be dead,'' said the girl's
mother, Carolyn John-Nurse. ``When I was cussing him out, he said,
`I'm sorry, ma'm. I'm sorry, ma'm. I was just getting ready to
bring her back.'''
   Widel's attorney, Dan Perry, said Widel told his mother he had
six beers when he drove to Hunter's Creek to look for a woman he
knew only as Samantha. Widel stopped to ask whether the little girl
or her friend, Rachel Anne Newhart, 5, knew Samantha.
   The lawyer said the little girl told Widel she knew where
Samantha lived and volunteered to show him. She got into Widel's
car, and the other girl ran off, Perry said.
   After a while, according to Widel, the little girl decided she
wanted to go home. Widel took her back, and a band of neighbors
confronted him at gunpoint and accused him of being a child
molester, Perry said.
   ``It was a simple misunderstanding that I can understand,'' the
lawyer said. ``He obviously exercised poor judgment. He's a good
kid.''
   Deputies believed Rachel, a youngster with ``exceptional''
presence of mind, sheriff's spokesman Randy Means said Thursday.
She told her mother Widel yanked the little girl into the car.
   ``There is no reason to doubt the 5-year-old's story. It is
pretty much corroborated by the other little girl and neighbors who
were around,'' sheriff's spokesman Jim Solomons said. ``She
apparently didn't get in the car willingly.''
   Widel told police he didn't know Samantha's last name. Solomons
said no one named Samantha has come forward to substantiate Widel's
story.
   Widel, who is 45 days from receiving a degree in electrical
engineering, was on full scholarship until recently, said officials
at The Citadel, who refused to give out any other information.
   Widel's mother, Carol Widel of Kissimmee, said her son lost his
scholarship when his grades dropped.
   Of his arrest, she said, ``This is so far out of the ordinary
that I don't know what to think. ... I'm utterly dismayed. He has a
lot to contribute to society.''
   Solomons said no neighbors would be charged. ``You can't condone
it, but you can't condemn'' what they did, he said. ``It apparently
was the right thing to do in this case. It's not illegal to have a
firearm, and this guy stopped a first-degree felony.''
</TEXT>
