<HEAD>Iran Accuses Iraq of Another Chemical Attack</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with Iran saying it will cease
attacks; picks up 6th grar pvs, ``Associated Press ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Iran-Prayers Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN MARRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran said Friday a new Iraqi chemical
bomb attack on Kurdish villages killed 75 people and wounded more
than 100. It also said it accepted a U.N. call for a halt in the
deadly ``war of the cities.''
   The Iranians claim 5,000 civilians were killed and the same
number wounded in gas attacks two weeks ago.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Cyprus,
reported that Iran earlier fired fired seven missiles into Kirkuk,
Iraq's northern oil capital and Basra, a southern port city. Iraq
said many civilians were killed or wounded in Kirkuk.
   No Iraqi missile firings were reported. Iraq said Thursday it
would suspend attacks on Iranian cities for three days, beginning
at midnight, while Prime Minister Turgut Ozal of Turkey is visiting
Baghdad.
   Turkey has good relations with both Iran and Iraq, which have
been at war since September 1980, and Ozal has tried to mediate.
   Tehran radio said Friday that U.N. Secretary-General Javier
Perez de Cuellar asked Iran to stop attacking residential areas in
Iraq. The request came in a meeting in New York with Iran's acting
U.N. ambassador, Mohammad Ja'afar Mahallati, said the radio,
monitored by the British Broadcasting Corp.
   It quoted Mahallati as saying: ``In line with our usual policy,
Iran accepts this request. However, true to its usual ways, Iraq
will renew these attacks. Therefore, the U.N. secretary-general
must not confine himself to a mere request.''
   The statement appeared to represent a call for U.N. action to
force Iraq to end its attacks.
   Associated Press photographer Greg English reported from
Kurdistan that Iran's Revolutionary Guards were pushing westward
into the strategic region of Iraq as part of an offensive begun
March 16.
   A dispatch from Iran's Islamic Republic News Agency said Iranian
jet fighters flew seven sorties against Iraqi troop concentrations
in the region Friday, inflicting ``substantial casualties and
losses.''
   IRNA said Iraqi warplanes dropped bombs containing nerve and
mustard gases in the Qara Dagh region of northeast Iraq on March
21-26.
   It quoted sources among Iranian-backed Kurdish guerrillas as
identifying the villages affected as Susiyan, Doukan, Balakha,
Jafaran and Oliyan.
   There was no independent confirmation or comment from Iraq.
   Qara Dagh is 15 miles west of the front in the Kurdistan
mountains.
   Iran claims the thousands of casualties from chemical attacks
were caused March 16-17 in three towns captured by Iranian forces.
   Western correspondents who visited one of the towns, Halabja,
last week reported seeing hundreds of bodies unmarked by bullet or
shrapnel wounds. Hundreds more Iraqi Kurds with severe burns and
respiratory ailments, consistent with exposure to poison gas, have
been seen in Tehran hospitals.
   On Thursday, Iran claimed Iraqi warplanes dropped chemical bombs
on Marivan in northwest Iran, killing civilians.
   IRNA said missiles were fired Friday at Basra and at a
``military target'' in Kirkuk ``in retaliation for Iraqi missile
attacks on Iran's residential areas.''
   Iraq reported only one missile hitting Kirkuk, 80 miles west of
the battle zone in the Kurdistan mountains. The official Iraqi News
Agency said it exploded in a residential district, killing or
wounding ``many civilians, including women and children.''
   More than 250 missiles have been fired by both sides since the
latest ``war of the cities'' began Feb. 29, killing hundreds of
civilians.
   In the Kurdistan campaign, officers of Iranian Revolutionary
Guards said their forces had bottled up 5,000 Iraqi soldiers around
a hydroelectric dam on Lake Darbandikhan, 80 miles east of the
Kirkuk oil fields. The dam and power station provide most of the
region's electricity and some power to Baghdad.
   English, who was with Western correspondents flown to the battle
zone Thursday, quoted Revolutionary Guards commander Asgar Ahmadi
as saying his men were within five miles of the highway between the
provincial capital of Sulaymaniyah and Baghdad, 160 miles to the
southwest.
   Ahmadi claimed Sulaymaniyah was within range of Iranian
artillery.
   Sulaymaniyah, which has a population of 100,000, is northwest of
the Darbandikhan region, where the Iranians said several days ago
they had captured 540 square miles of territory.
   The Iranians claim to have killed or wounded 12,000 Iraqis,
captured more than 4,500 and destroyed more than 200 tanks and
armored vehicles.
   English reported from the Kurdish town of Dojaila, captured on
the second day of the offensive that he could hear artillery fire
to the west and it was clear ``the Iranians have made significant
gains.''
</TEXT>
