<HEAD>Transcript Of Meese News Conference</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a transcript of Attorney General Edwin
Meese III's news conference Friday.
   Good afternoon.
   I indicated yesterday, when we were at the FBI, that I would
meet with you in due course.
   And although my time is limited, I know that some of you,
perhaps all of you, are on deadline.
   I did want to make myself available before the end of the week
to take a few questions.
   Before doing so, I would like to announce that early next week,
we will be holding a press conference.
   Terry Eastland will let you know as to the details of that
conference.
   And at that time, I will have with me certain individuals who
will be filling key positions here in the department.
   Now, let me also say that I have been gratified by the action
and the statement issued earlier today by independent counsel James
McKay.
   In addition to that, my attorney, Nathan Lewin, has also
commented on it, and I would refer any questions you might have on
that subject to those two statements and to Mr. Lewin.
   As I have said on many occasions, the purpose of an independent
counsel is to review all allegations that may be outstanding and
that all of us should await the determinations of the independent
counsel.
   For that reason, I would certainly urge that there be no rush to
judgment, but I am gratified by the statement that has been issued
today.
   With that, I'll be glad to answer any questions. Yes?
   Q. Mr. Attorney General, people in and out of the department
have commented that the appearance of propriety is important as
propriety itself. And therefore, that a law enforcement officer who
is under investigation ought to step aside while that investigation
is under way. Can you tell us why you have not stepped aside, and
what message that sends to other law enforcement officers who may
find themselves in a similar position?
   A. Well, the purpose of the independent counsel process is to
enable people to go on about their duties and, at the same time, to
have an independent and fair evaluation of whatever allegations may
be pending.
   That's the process, that is the way it should work, and that's
the way it is working in this case.
   And therefore, there is no reason _ as a matter of fact, if a
person has to step aside merely on the basis of some allegation,
however false, then it would be easy for unscrupulous persons to
make allegations and therefore literally cause people to step aside
and move out of their offices.
   Q. Are Mr. Burns and Mr. Weld unscrupulous persons?
   A. I beg your pardon?
   Q. Are Mr. Burns and Mr. Weld unscrupulous persons?
   A. Are they unscrupulous persons? No.
   Q. Why did Mr. Burns and Mr. Weld resign?
   A. Well, they've already indicated that they are resigning to go
back into private practice.
   Let me say that there were some basic differences as to the
effect that recent events have had on the department.
   And beyond that, I think their resignations are going to have to
speak for themselves.
   Q. Were those recent events the investigations, sir?
   A. I beg your pardon?
   Q. Could you elaborate _
   A. I say, there was a difference as to the impact that recent
events had on the department.
   In part, they were the fact that there is an independent counsel
investigation, yes.
</TEXT>
