<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Kidnap,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lebanese Businessman Held Captive Outside London</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police charged a 31-year-old builder Friday with
conspiracy in the kidnapping of a Lebanese businessman, who escaped
unharmed two days earlier from a rural bungalow where he was held
for 24 hours.
   The kidnappers demanded 5 million Swiss francs ($3.7 million) as
ransom for Ramzi Ata Dalloul, Scotland Yard said. Dalloul, 52, is
head of RAD Projects and Developments, a management consulting firm.
   Dalloul's captors apparently did not know he had escaped and
made ransom calls to the man's home after he was gone, police said.
   Anti-terrorist detectives arrested a man who accompanied Dalloul
to his home in London's fashionable Kensington district Wednesday
night. Derek Stanley Bumbridge, 31, was charged Friday with
conspiring ``with persons unknown'' to kidnap Dalloul and was to
appear in court on Saturday.
   Scotland Yard would not comment on media reports that the man
was Dalloul's only guard and helped in the escape.
   Police said Dalloul believed at least five men were involved,
four Britons and one who spoke Arabic.
   He was seized Tuesday night after his car was rammed on the way
home from his office in London's West End, and driven for about 15
minutes before being bundled into the back of a white van and bound.
   Dalloul was taken to a bungalow in Tenterden, Kent, about 40
miles southeast of London, where he was handcuffed while one man
stood guard.
   The kidnappers telephoned Dalloul's wife, Saeda, late Tuesday
night demanding the ransom and she told Scotland Yard shortly
afterward.
   On Wednesday evening, the kidnappers again contacted Mrs.
Dalloul, repeating their demand and explaining the method of
payment, police said.
   Forty-five minutes later, Dalloul telephoned his wife to say he
had escaped and was on his way home, police said. He turned up
about two hours later.

</TEXT>
