<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pope     04-01 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pope,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pope Symbolically Retraces Path to Crucifixion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II, carrying a black wooden cross,
led a torchlight procession at the Colosseum Friday night that
symbolically retraced Christ's walk to his crucifixion.
   Tens of thousands of people gathered to watch the Via Crucis,
the Way of the Cross ritual that ends the saddest day of the Roman
Catholic year.
   John Paul began the walk inside the great arena, where tradition
says ancient Romans threw Christians to the lions. He proceeded up
cobblestone steps and ended on the edge of the Roman Forum, once
the meeting place of Rome's leaders.
   Thousands of people followed the service from behind barricades
marking the pope's path, reading from prayer booklets illuminated
by candlelight. Many added their voices to the chorus that chanted
the service.
   During the walk, John Paul pressed the 5-foot cross, which
weighed only a pound, to his forehead as he marked the 14 Stations
of the Cross that represent the physical torment and mockery Jesus
endured as he walked to his death.
   The stations include the three times Christ fell under the
weight of the cross, the placing of the crown of thorns and
whipping by jailers.
   John Paul, wearing a white skullcap and gold-trimmed cape over a
white cassock, was illuminated at the beginning of the procession
by torches placed in the Colosseum's arches.
   Descriptions of the various stations were read in Italian,
French, English, German, Spanish and Portuguese and in the pope's
native language, Polish.
   Vatican Radio and Italian state-run television carried the event
live. The television said it was transmitted to 27 countries on
five continents.
   Earlier Friday, the pontiff heard confessions from 11 pilgrims
and tourists in St. Peter's Basilica in keeping with a Good Friday
tradition he began in 1979, during his first Easter Week as pope.
   Several hundred people were waiting when he appeared in the
basilica shortly after noon and stepped into one of the hand-carved
mahogany confessional booths.
   For 70 minutes, he heard confessions from, among others, an
Italian family of three, a 59-year-old contractor from the
Netherlands and his daughter, and a 22-year-old student from
California.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
