<2ND_LINE>AM-Planes Collide,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>One Killed, Two Injured When Two Small Planes Collide in Flight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SATICOY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two small planes collided Friday and
crashed, killing one person and critically injuring another,
authorities said. One plane landed safely with four people aboard.
   ``We were climbing out toward the ocean. ... Then all of a
sudden there was a tremendous explosion. The windshield blew out,''
said Bob Bruce, 38, of Camarillo, pilot of plane that landed
safely. ``I looked over and there was another airplane that looked
like it was descending; on its way down.''
   Bruce's rented plane, a Cessna Sky Hawk, was damaged but landed
at Camarillo Airport. He suffered facial cuts when the windshield
shattered, said Ventura County Sheriff's Lt. Lou McCombs.
   A Cessna 172 crashed in a rural area 65 miles west of Los
Angeles, said Nona Makinson, operations manager at Camarillo
Airport. One man aboard that plane died and another was in
extremely critical condition, said spokeswoman Millie Schofield of
Ventura County Medical Center.
   Bruce, who has eight years of flying experience, said he was on
a sightseeing flight over the ocean when the collision occurred.
His passengers, including boys ages 4 and 5, were not hurt.
   The National Transportation and Safety Board was investigating
the crash.
</TEXT>
