<HEAD>Catholics, Protestants March For Peace</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Protestants and Roman Catholics marched together
through London, Dublin and Belfast on Good Friday and prayed for an
end to sectarian violence.
   Cardinal Basil Hume asked London marchers to pray for political
leaders of Britain, Northern Ireland and the Irish Republic who
seek an end to the strife.
   ``Today, as never before, healing is needed not only in
grief-stricken Ireland but here in the heart of London, since we
are sadly but inevitably part of the problem,'' he said.
   ``The violence has always been the work of the few at the
expense of the many who want nothing better than to live at peace
with their neighbors.''
   Referring to the latest killings in Northern Ireland, Hume said:
``For the sake of the future of our countries, there must be a
renewed attempt to build a better society. This is no time to match
violence with violence even in the face of real or perceived
injustice.''
   Thirteen people have been killed in the province since March 6,
when British soldiers killed three Irish Republican Army guerrillas
in Gibraltar.
   The mainly Catholic IRA is fighting to drive the British out of
Northern Ireland, where Protestants are a majority, and unite the
province with the Irish Republic.
   Archbishop of Canterbury Robert Runcie, spiritual leader of the
Church of England, sent a message of peace to the 200 people who
marched silently from the Catholic Westminster Cathedral to
Westminster Abbey.
   ``I pray that the people of Ireland and England will forgive
each other for the hurts and wrongs done in the past and find in
today's common action a deeper unity of spirit,'' he said.
   About 400 people marched through Belfast and 1,000 in the center
of Dublin.
   Northern Ireland police said three people were arrested in
Belfast after stones and eggs were thrown at people marching from
Falls Road, a Catholic district, to Shankill Road, a Protestant
stronghold.
   ``The incident was over very quickly,'' a spokesman said.
</TEXT>
