<HEAD>Jackson, Dukakis Lead in Texas Delegate Count</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson has maintained a slight advantage
over Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis among Texas Democratic
Convention delegates, who will pick 64 delegates to the party's
national convention.
   Presidential candidates have to compete twice for delegates from
Texas, once in the state's March 8 primary and again in a series of
caucuses and conventions which begin that day. While the primary
results governed allocation of 119 national delegates, another 64
were at stake through the caucuses.
   Dukakis, who won the primary, was lagging behind Jackson in
state convention delegates in a nearly complete count issued by the
party on Thursday.
   Of the 5,037 state delegates counted so far, Jackson led with
1,722, Dukakis had 1,666 and Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. had
915. Another 251 state convention delegates remain to be counted.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Houston May Hold First 1988 Presidential Debate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Houston may host the first of four scheduled
debates between the 1988 presidential nominees this fall, but Vice
President George Bush's campaign has not committed to participate
in it.
   Bush spokesman Pete Teeley said the vice president, the expected
GOP nominee, intends to debate the Democratic nominee, but only on
his terms and at a site chosen by the candidates, not the parties.
But he said Thursday it would be premature to discuss which cities
Bush, who calls Houston home, would consider.
   Since last July the Democratic and Republican national parties
have heavily promoted the series of debates and are scouting
potential sites.
   But Donald Ward, coordinator of the city's bid, said further
delay in an announcement of debate sites may force Houston to drop
its effort to host the event. This includes the release of 2,500
local hotel rooms and the third floor of the George R. Brown
Convention Center which have been held since October in
anticipation of the debate, he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Democrats Vow Big Push Against Larouche Backers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iowa Democratic Party leaders vowed
Friday to crush an attempt by political extremist Lyndon LaRouche's
supporters to use the party's mantle in the June primary, even if
it means urging voters to go Republican in some cases.
   ``To us, these people are political poison and we are going to
beat them,'' said party spokesman Phil Roeder.
   ``They apparently feel this is fertile ground, but we are going
to teach them a major lesson,'' said Joe Shanahan, who runs
legislative elections for the party.
   Their alarm grew out of the number of LaRouche supporters filing
nomination papers to run in the June 8 primary for legislative and
congressional seats. The party leaders said they identified 16
LaRouche backers who met Friday's filing deadline.
   LaRouche supporters could win the Democratic nomination in some
legislative districts because no other democrats are running.
   If that happens, Roeder said, ``we will encourage people to vote
against them.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Campaign Spending Up, Negative Advertising Down, FEC says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Groups and individuals are spending more money
overall on independent campaigns for congressional candidates, but
are spending less on negative ads, the Federal Election Commission
has found.
   A survey of 1985-86 election spending patterns revealed that
independent expenditures for House and Senate candidates was $9.3
million, up from $5.9 million in 1983-84.
   Independent expenditures, in which a person or group buys
advertising or otherwise campaigns for the candidate, are legal as
long as the person making the expenditure does not coordinate with
the candidate's campaign.
   In the 1986 congressional elections, independent expenditures
against congressional candidates totalled $1.3 million, compared to
$2.6 million in 1984.
   Independent expenditures in favor of candidates totalled $8
million, up from $3.3 million spent in the last election.
</TEXT>
