<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Meese 3rdLd-Writethru 1stadd 04-01 0709</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese, 3rd Ld-Writethru, 1st add,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHN: in Meese.''</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Meese received other good news Friday when Solicitor General
Charles Fried said he would remain at the Justice Department, even
though Fried reportedly urged Meese to resign earlier in the week.
   ``I have concluded that while I am able to lead'' the solicitor
general's office ``I should continue to do so,'' Fried said. The
New York Times reported that Fried had urged Meese to quit
Wednesday but that Meese had rejected the suggestion. Fried's
statement did not endorse Meese.
   The independent counsel said that if at the end of his
investigation there remains ``insufficient evidence to warrant a
prosecution as to these or any other matters'' he will issue a
report covering all the matters which have been under investigation.
   ``Based on the evidence developed to date, he (McKay) does not
intend to recommend that the grand jury return an indictment
against Meese as to the `Aqaba pipeline' matter or as to matters
relating to Mr. Meese's investments, including the so-called `Baby
Bells' matter,'' McKay's statement said.
   If he issues a report without obtaining an indictment, McKay
said he would ``refer all of those matters for review and action by
the appropriate administrative authorities,'' an apparent reference
to Office of Government Ethics procedures.
   The ethics office has put its investigation on hold of Meese's
initial failure to disclose investments in the ``Baby Bell''
companies pending McKay's probe, said deputy director Donald
Campbell.
   If that proceeding is revived, the office could move to have
Meese make a complete disclosure of those holdings, Campbell said.
   Nathan Lewin, one of Meese's lawyers representing him in the
criminal investigation, criticized what he called ``speculation and
uninformed judgments by others that have appeared in the media.''
   ``Today's announcement by the independent counsel should
encourage everyone to continue abiding by the process,'' Justice
Department spokesman Terry Eastland said. ``It is very important
for the rule of law that we allow the process that the Congress has
ordained by enacting the independent counsel statute to continue to
run its course.''
   McKay has been investigating whether Meese conspired with
Wallach and others to violate the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act in
connection with an alleged scheme to pay the Israeli government and
the country's Labor Party to protect a proposed $1 billion oil
pipeline from military attack by Israel.
   Four months after enlisting Meese's assistance on a $1 billion
Iraqi pipeline project, Wallach wrote the attorney general a memo
saying that a portion of up to $700 million from the pipeline would
be paid to the Israeli Labor Party of then-Israeli Prime Minister
Shimon Peres. The pipeline was never built.
   Wallach at the time was legal counsel to Swiss oilman Bruce
Rappaport, a partner in the project and a longtime close friend of
Peres.
   Meese has contended he never read the portion of Wallach's memo
referring to Labor Party payments, Rappaport says he never
suggested any such plan and Peres says he was never offered any
money.
   McKay also has been investigating Meese's ownership of stock in
companies created by the breakup of AT&T when he was in a position
to make policy affecting the telecommunications industry.
   Meese as attorney general met with executives of four of the
regional Bell Telephone companies at a time when he owned $14,000
worth of stock in the Baby Bells, raising conflict-of-interest
questions.
   At the time, the Bell companies were seeking a reversal of the
Justice Department's position opposing the Bells' expansion into
new areas of business. Meese ended up approving a reversal of the
department's position early in 1987 in accordance with the
companies' wishes.
   Meese says he had intended to sell the stock in 1985 but was
unable to do so because he had lost the stock certificates. On his
financial disclosure forms for 1985 and 1986, Meese listed the Bell
stocks as having been sold. The fact that he still owned them
wasn't uncovered until last summer, when pressure from Congress
forced the attorney general to disclose the details of his
financial holdings.
   In December, McKay's office issued a similar annnouncement
stating there was insufficient evidence at that time to bring
criminal charges against Meese in connection with his efforts to
help the scandal-plagued Wedtech Corp. get defense contracts.
</TEXT>
