<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-01 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0438</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>April Rain Turns To Snow Over The Southern Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A storm spread snow up to 10 inches of snow from the southern
Rockies to the southern Plains on Friday, and heavy rain ahead of
the storm raised a threat of flooding.
   Snow fell over the southeastern third of Colorado, the
northeastern half of New Mexico, the Texas Panhandle, the Oklahoma
Panhandle and western Kansas.
   There were reports of 10 inches of snow over sections of the
Texas Panhandle and 6 inches of snow at Ulysses, Kan., the National
Weather Service said.
   In Oklahoma, the range was from 5 inches near Boise City to 10
inches near Guymon. Amounts in Colorado were mostly around 3 inches
or less.
   The snow closed some highways in the Texas and Oklahoma
panhandles.
   Ahead of the snow, rain and thunderstorms extended from the
remainder of Kansas and Oklahoma into eastern Texas, producing
marble-size hail in Oklahoma. Ground in the southern half of the
Plains was already saturated and flash flood watches were posted
over northeastern and central Oklahoma and the southeastern quarter
of Kansas.
   The Caney River was expected to crest during the night at
Bartlesville, Okla., at about 3 feet above flood stage. The Neosho
River was expected to crest about 4 feet above flood stage Sunday
evening at Commerce, Okla., and Oswego, Kan.
   Showers extended across northeastern Texas, the lower two-thirds
of the Mississippi Valley, the Ohio Valley, the Tennessee Valley,
eastern Mississippi, Alabama, western Georgia, northern
Pennsylvania and southern New York state.
   Elsewhere, rain continued over the northern Oregon coast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 26
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 85 degrees at
Kingsville, Texas. The early morning low for the nation was zero at
Yellowstone National Park.
   For Saturday, rain and occasional thunderstorms were forecast
from New Jersey across Pennsylvania, the Ohio Valley and the
Tennessee Valley, from the northwestern half of Georgia across the
Florida Panhandle, Alabama, Mississippi and southeastern Louisiana,
and from Iowa across Missouri, northern Arkansas, the east-central
Plains, Illinois, southern Wisconsin and Lower Michigan. Scattered
rain was forecast over the northern Pacific Coast.
   Highs in the 40s and 50s were predicted over New England, the
Great Lakes, the upper Mississippi Valley, the central Plains,
Oklahoma, the Texas Panhandle and the southern Rockies, as well as
the Pacific Northwest; in the 80s over the Florida Peninsula,
southern Texas, central California and the desert Southwest, and in
the 60s and 70s over the remainder of the nation.
</TEXT>
