<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Orion-Fine     04-01 0521</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Orion-Fine,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FAA Orders $632,200 Civil Fine Against Orion Air</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Aviation Administration on Friday
ordered a $632,200 civil fine for numerous safety violations
against Orion Air, the cargo airline that is being sought out to
fly passengers in case of a strike at Eastern Airlines.
   The civil penalty stemmed from violations of federal aviation
regulations uncovered during an inspection of Orion Air's
operations a year ago. The FAA said the violations have since been
corrected, although the agency is still reviewing whether to allow
the airline to fly passengers.
   The North Carolina-based cargo airline became the object of
controversy in recent months after it entered into an agreement to
fly passengers on Eastern Airlines' routes if Eastern becomes the
target of a strike by machinists and pilots.
   Eastern's unions have charged that the tactic is a violation of
labor law. Earlier this week a federal judge ordered Eastern to
halt the training of non-union Orion pilots under the contract with
Eastern, putting the future of Eastern's plans with Orion Air into
doubt.
   The FAA said its fine stemmed from practices by Orion Air that
involved operating some aircraft that did not meet federal
airworthiness requirements and allowing pilots to fly too many
hours in violation of federal duty-time limits.
   For example, the agency said, an Orion Air Boeing 727 was found
to have flown 1,193 flights while violating an airworthiness
requirement involving the plane's mechanism that adjusts wing
slats. Slat position is critical in an aircraft's takeoff because
it affects lift.
   In another example cited by the FAA, some pilots of Orion Air
were found to have flown slightly more than 100 hours during a
single month. The FAA requires that no pilot fly more than 100
hours during a 30-day period and most commercial passenger airlines
schedule their pilots to no more than 70 to 75 hours per month.
   The FAA said in a statement that Orion Air, which has its
headquarters in Raleigh, N.C., ``moved quickly to correct the
deficiencies (discovered during the inspection) and is now in
compliance with the (federal) regulations.''
   A request that Orion Air be given a certificate to fly
passengers is still pending before the agency, said FAA spokesman
Fred Farrar.
   Few travelers likely have heard of Orion Air, which has 55 jet
aircraft and serves such air freight companies as United Parcel
Service, Emery Air Freight and Purolator.
   In an attempt to blunt the effects of a strike, Eastern earlier
this year disclosed that it was leasing 26 of its jets to Orion
Air. Eastern officials called the move ``insurance'' that would
allow the cargo airline to fly passengers on Eastern routes if
pilots honor a possible strike by Eastern's machinists.
   The FAA acknowledged during congressional hearings in February
that it found numerous safety violations at Orion Air during its
inspection in April and March, 1987.
   At the time, Orion officials acknowledged the violations, but
said that the problems had been corrected.
   Orion officials could not immediately be reached for comment on
the civil penalties announced by the FAA Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880401-0197 </DOCNO>
