<DOCNO> AP880401-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1820EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SAfrica-Protest     04-01 0325</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Protest,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hundreds Join March To Protest Crackdown</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DURBAN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clergyman carrying crosses led
hundreds of people on a silent march through downtown Durban Friday
to protest the white-led government's new restrictions on
anti-apartheid groups.
   In a separate development, police reported that a white
constable was fatally stabbed overnight by a group of blacks while
on foot patrol in Pinetown West, on the outskirts of Durban. No
details about the attack were released.
   Nearly 1,000 people participated in the march at dawn. Nineteen
people wore gags to symbolize restrictions that banned the
opposition newspaper New Nation and major organizations opposed to
apartheid, under which the black majority has no voice in national
affairs.
   ``Many voices which stand for justice are being silenced in our
country, and we commit ourselves to ensure that those voices may be
heard once again,'' said Miriam Cele of the Dependents' Conference,
which assists the families of detainees.
   Among those addressing the protesters at church services before
and after the march was Archie Gumede, co-president of the United
Democratic Front, South Africa's largest anti-apartheid coalition
and one of the groups banned from all activity in February.
   Gumede was issued an individual restriction order limiting his
political activities.
   Other speakers at the services were Roman Catholic Archbishop
Denis Hurley and the Rev. Stanley Mogoba, general secretary of the
Methodist Church.
   After the march, women from the Black Sash civil rights
organization planted crosses on the beach opposite regional army
headquarters to protest Monday's commando raid in Botswana in which
four people were killed.
   South Africa said the victims were guerrillas of the outlawed
African National Congress, the main guerrilla group fighting
apartheid. Botswana says three of those killed were Botswanan
citizens.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
