<2ND_LINE>BC-Meese Text, 3rd add,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHN: independent counsel.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Q. There are reports that first lady Nancy Reagan would like to
see you go. What can you tell us about your relations with Mrs.
Reagan?
   A. I have always had a very good relationship with Mrs. Reagan
and that still continues.
   Q. You say you've had strong support in Congress and yet
everything we've heard in the public record except for maybe one or
two senators who have supported you has been quite critical,
especially among Republicans who say that you are hurting the party
and you are doing a disservice to the president. Do you not feel
that in a political election year, perhaps you should step, if not
down, aside?
   A. I can only tell you what people have told me, and as I say,
they come from both sides of the aisle.
   Q. Are you troubled by what Senator Thurmond told you yesterday?
   A. No, Senator Thurmond was very helpful and I'm very
appreciative with my conversations with him.
   Q. Have any of these problems been caused by any mistakes of
your own? And if so, what is wrong?
   A. Well, again, I will be happy to talk about my own conduct in
detail, when the independent counsel inquiry is over.
   As a matter of fact, I'll be meeting with all of you at that
time and that's when I can answer those questions more fully.
   Q. Mr. Meese, in the general sense, you promised the Senate
Judiciary Committee _
   A. I'm sorry, I can't hear you _
   Q. You promised the Senate Judiciary Commmittee during your
confirmation hearings that you had learned a lesson from the Stein
inquiry and that you would be more sensitive to ethical questions
in the future. Do you feel in general without going into the
details of the investigation that you can't talk about, that you've
lived up to that promise?
   A. Yes. OK?
   Q. Some officials have said this week that you've been so
distracted by your problems that you spend only 10 minutes a week
on the war on drugs, that you haven't been available for meetings
to try to decide what to do about the McNally decision. Could you
comment on those perceptions?
   A. Yes, that's totally untrue.
   I would say that I devote a good portion of my time.
   First of all, virtually all my time during the work week and a
good portion of weekends is devoted to the business of the
department and the attention that I've given to the matters of
leading the Drug Policy Board occupies a good portion of my time,
probably somewhere between 30 and 50 percent of my time.
   Q. That's during the week.
   A. During the week, yes. Not on Sundays.
   Q. Sir, why isn't the public entitled to know why Mr. Burns and
Weld, who are public officials who quit for reasons which involve
public policy, why aren't they entitled to know what they told you
and what their concerns were?
   A. Because _ as has been my practice in all personnel matters, I
leave that up to the individuals themselves, and I do not go into
detail as to what they've told me in confidential conversations.
Yes?
   Q. Attorney general, would you tell us why Judge Adams is
reluctant to take the deputy's job?
   A. I don't know what you're talking about.
   I never comment on anything or anybody affirmatively,
negatively, affirm or deny as to any person unless and until we're
ready to make an announcement.
   Q. You said _
   A. Yes.
   Q. _ you said you were talking to people of quality. He is a
person of quality. Why is he saying no?
   A. I'm talking to a lot of people of quality.
   Hello?
   Q. Is it your intention to stay on the job until the end of the
administration?
   A. Well, again, I've told you before. I've never set either a
limit or a deadline, but it is certainly my intent to carry on my
duties as long as the president wants me to.
   I think that just about exhausts the questions.
   Thank you.
</TEXT>
