<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1825EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CometTheory     04-01 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Comet Theory,0673</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NASA Scientist Finds Evidence Earth Hit By Millions Of Tiny Comets
Annually</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A NASA scientist said Friday he found
new evidence supporting a controversial theory that millions of
small, dark, water-bearing comets strike Earth's atmosphere every
year.
   Other scientists remained skeptical, but physicist Clayne
Yeates, of NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory, said: ``I'm very
convinced that what I'm seeing is real. ... These objects would not
have been seen inadvertently during other searches. They're small,
they're dark and they're moving fast.''
   The theory was first proposed in 1986 by University of Iowa
physicist Louis Frank, who said Friday he was met with ``total
disbelief'' and ``lost a lot of friends'' because of it.
   ``I'm happy (about Yeates' observations), but it's been a long
two years,'' Frank said by telephone from Iowa City.
   A NASA news release called Frank's hypothesis ``one of the
decade's most controversial astronomical theories.''
   Frank proposed the theory after ultraviolet photographs of Earth
taken by the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's
Dynamics Explorer 1 spacecraft in 1981-86 revealed countless dark
spots that appeared to be tiny holes in Earth's atmosphere.
   Frank theorized that about 10 million comets, essentially
30-foot-diameter fluffy snowballs with a dark coating, plunge into
the atmosphere each year, forming holes then breaking up and
vaporizing.
   He hypothesized that during Earth's early history, billions of
the tiny comets would have provided enough water to fill all the
oceans.
   Yeates said his observations on the 36-inch Spacewatch Telescope
at Kitt Peak National Observatory in Arizona make him believe that
at least a million such comets hit the atmosphere annually at a
speed of 22,000 mph.
   The comets appeared as white streaks on enhanced telescope
images, said Yeates, who is deputy project scientist for the
planned 1989 launch of the Galileo space probe to Jupiter.
   ``I'm a little skeptical,'' said astronomer Anita Cochran, of
the University of Texas at Austin. ``He (Yeates) may be seeing
something, but to leap to 10-meter comets is a fairly large leap of
imagination.''
   Frank said a soon-to-be-published study, in which atmospheric
holes were recently observed by Sweden's Viking spacecraft, also
supports his theory.
   University of Michigan physicist and planetary scientist Thomas
Donahue said: ``I'm not going to say this sounds like confirmation
of Frank's comets or not. But it certainly is exciting.''
   About a year ago, Donahue used 1977 data from the Voyager 2
space probe to show that Earth's atmosphere contained an excess of
hydrogen atoms released from water vapor. He said the discovery
could be consistent with Frank's theory, but also could be
explained if the hydrogen was freed from 10 million times fewer
comets that were smaller, faster but much more active than those
postulated by Frank.
   The less abundant comets wouldn't provide enough water to fill
the oceans, Donahue said.
   ``I really am a bit skeptical'' of Yeates' observations, said
Brian Marsden, associate director for planetary sciences at the
Harvard-Smithsonian Center for Astrophysics in Cambridge, Mass.
   ``If they (comets) are as numerous as he's talking about, then
some of these should show up when the telescope is in more normal
operation, and they haven','' Marsden said.
   Frank replied that only two specialized telescopes in the
country, including Spacewatch, are capable of observing the comets.
   Cochran voiced the most common objection to Frank's theory: If
so many icy comets hit Earth's atmosphere, they also should strike
the moon, creating a lot of water vapor. Yet the moon has very
little water vapor.
   Yeates said his observations are consistent with Frank's theory
that the comets orbit the sun in the same direction as Earth, and
that they are very dark, reflecting only 2 percent of the sunlight
that hits them.
   Despite the large number of such comets, there is so much space
around Earth that they would strike any single spacecraft only once
every 100 million years, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
