<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Youth     04-01 0209</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Youth,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Establish Independent Youth Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Hungarian students has
established an independent youth group intended as an alternative
to the Communist youth organization KISZ, one of the students
reported Friday.
   ``The objective ... is to create a new autonomous and
independent youth organization for the politically active ...
reform-minded youth groups,'' said a statement issued by the group,
according to Miklos Andrasi.
   Andrasi, 25, a recent university graduate in economics, said by
telephone from Budapest that the group was formally established
Wednesday. He said it has 37 members so far and that it wants to
work for a ``new Hungary.''
   Andrasi said KISZ has been losing influence among the country's
youth. He said the new group, Fidesz _ the Alliance of Young
Democrats _ would accept Communist Party members.
   The group hoped to talk to representatives of KISZ soon about
the possibility of cooperating, he said, but it rejects the idea of
membership in both organizations.
   There have been increased calls in Hungary for more pluralism
and political reforms to accompany a strict austerity program that
Parliament adopted last September to help the country's stagnating
economy.
   The group's statement said Fidesz wanted Hungary to have a mixed
economy and democracy.
</TEXT>
