<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0717 04-01 0621</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0717,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Calls for Higher Farm Prices</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS name of county to St. Croix, instead of St. Clair,
in graf 7, bgng ``He's great''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EVANS WITT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMERY, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Jesse
Jackson called Friday for higher prices for farm products and said
most consumers can afford to ``pay a few more pennies for a glass
of milk or for a cone of ice cream or for a loaf of bread.''
   A crowd nearly the size of the entire population of this town
gathered on Bud and Faye Lee's farm to hear Jackson call for fair
farm prices, a move designed to capture the votes of the 2,500-plus
farmers who attended the rally.
   ``The fact is farmers deserve fair prices and workers deserve
fair wages and the rich must pay fair taxes,'' Jackson said on the
dairy farm outside of Amery, a town of 2,800. ``The reality is if
urban people are working, they can pay a few more pennies for a
glass of milk or for a cone of ice cream or for a loaf of bread.''
   The preacher-turned-politician campaigned for another full day
across Wisconsin in preparation for Tuesday's primary. Jackson is
locked in a tight race with Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
here, according to pre-primary polls.
   From the Lee farm, he headed to an Indian reservation near Green
Bay and to meet with union workers he stood with in a strike last
year.
   Farmers are a key part of the coalition that Jackson hopes will
give him another big-state victory, and the almost all-white crowd
in Amery suggested he is making some progress.
   ``He's great,'' said David Dittman, a farmer from St. Croix
County, Wis. ``He's the only one who has been standing up for the
family farm.''
   ``We don't have to invent a 30-second TV spot showing Jesse
Jackson with the people: he's been with the people over the
years,'' said Texas Agriculture Commissioner Jim Hightower, on hand
for the event.
   Jackson, standing on a hay wagon in front of dark blue grain
silos on the 600-acre dairy farm, returned to his religious roots
in his first event on Good Friday.
   ``While so many farmers have been driven under in Polk County,
and though there is so much pain all around us representing the
crucifixion ... there is a sense that the crucifixion is not going
to last much longer, somehow we are going to roll the stone away
and there is going to be renewal, resurrection, new hope ... as we
the people come together,'' he said.
   Jackson, saying he has stood with farmers for years, repeated
his support for the liberal Harkin-Gephardt family farm legislation
and said he backs higher milk price supports. He did not specify
what increase he would support.
   Jackson blamed middlemen in the food business and the government
for the farm problems and for increasing food prices.
   ``The farmer did not take advantage of the consumer, it was
ConAgra, Cargill and the barracudas that ate up the farmers,'' he
said, mentioning several large grain companies.
   ``The system has collapsed because you had good farmers and a
poor president,'' Jackson added.
   He accused the Reagan administration of misrepresenting the
situation with the dairy industry in order to cut spending on price
supports _ as it did in January. At the same time, he said the
administration was shutting down a free-cheese distribution program
_ a major outlet for surplus milk products.
   Jackson refered again to criticism of his lack of governmental
experience.
   ``There is a lot of talk now days about experience. Mine is in
leadership. ... Some officeholders are not leaders. And some
leaders are not officeholders,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
