<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Saudi     04-01 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Saudi,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Minister Says No Intention of Attacking Saudi Missiles</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli Cabinet minister said his country had no
intention of attacking medium-range missiles recently acquired by
Saudi Arabia.
   In an interview to be broadcast Saturday by the Arabic service
of Radio France International, Yitzhak Navon said:
   ``As a vice prime minister, I can state that Israel has no
intention of striking Saudi Arabia or any other country. And if it
is confirmed that these missiles threaten Israel, there are
diplomatic means to counter such a threat. Countries like Syria,
Iraq and Libya have missiles. Israel has not threatened them or
done anything else.''
   A French script of the interview was obtained by the Associated
Press.
   The Washington Post reported last month that the Israeli air
force had been conducting unusually intensive low-level bombing
practice runs. It quoted U.S. intelligence officials as saying the
runs could be in preparation for a pre-emptive strike at the
missiles.
   President Reagan warned Israel a week ago against attacking the
CSS-2 missiles the Saudis purchased from China.
   It is believed the missiles have a range of 1,000 miles _
capable of reaching Israel.
   Navon is minister of education and culture and a member of
Foreign Minister Shimon Peres' Labor Party. Peres is deputy prime
minister and Navon is one of several vice prime ministers in the
Cabinet.
</TEXT>
