<HEAD>Amnesty International Delegation Visits Cuban Prisons</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A delegation from Amnesty International, the
London-based human rights organization, is in Cuba on a
fact-finding mission and has met with prison inmates, according to
Cuba's Prensa Latina news agency. In a dispatch monitored in Mexico
City, the agency said Amnesty representatives arrived in Cuba on
March 24 and on Thursday inspected the Boniato prison in Santiago
de Cuba, 430 miles southeast of Havana. It said the visitors spoke
with inmates.
   Prensa Latina said Ian Martin, director of the organization's
department for the Americas, heads the Amnesty team. It quoted
Martin as saying the prison visit was ``very special, directly
related to our work.'' The agency said the Amnesty group also met
convicts in other Cuban prisons, but gave no details.
   The group also met with members of the government's judicial
tribunals and officials of the federal prosecutor's office, Prensa
Latina reported.
   It said the Amnesty visit came at the invitation of Vice
President Carlos Gonzalez Perez. The dispatch did not say how many
people were in the Amnesty group or give other details.
