<HEAD>Feds Seize Truckloads Of Paraphernalia</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stephan cq in 2nd graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Christmas stockings stuffed with
cocaine paraphernalia were among $5 million worth of merchandise
seized from a company, authorities said Friday.
   Company owner Stephan Pesce, 31, of Massapequa was charged under
a 1987 federal law making it illegal to sell or transport drug
items across state lines and to foreign countries, said U.S.
Attorney Andrew J. Maloney of Brooklyn.
   Customs agents searched Main Street Distributors Inc. in
Hauppauge on Thursday and carted off two truckloads of merchandise,
Maloney said. Much of the drug paraphernalia was imported from
Taiwan or Japan, he said.
   The Christmas stockings, sealed with a picture of a smiling
Santa Claus and a ``Merry Christmas'' greeting, contained a mirror,
razor blade, a metal tube, a small glass container and a cocaine
spoon, authorities said.
   Pesce could receive up to three years in jail and up to $1
million in fines if convicted.
</TEXT>
