<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1852EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Turkey-Kurds     04-01 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Turkey-Kurds,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Twenty Kurds Die in Gunbattle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MARDIN, Turkey (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty suspected Kurdish guerrillas were
killed in a shootout Friday with security forces in southeastern
Turkey, the state radio said.
   It was the highest number of rebels slain in a single battle
since the Kurdish insurgency began in August 1984, it said.
   The radio said the guerrillas opened fire after they were
surrounded by security forces and told to surrender. Two soldiers
were also killed in the fight, which took place near the village of
Kadirli in Nusaybin township, the radio said.
   The report quoted the the regional governor's office as saying
two other soldiers were wounded.
   In addition to the battle casualties, a major was killed and
five soldiers were injured when the helicopter taking them to the
zone crashed, according to the report. It did not say what might
have caused the crash.
   Most of the rebels in the area belong to an organization that
seeks to establish a Marxist Kurdish state in southeastern and
eastern Turkey.
   More than 700 civilians and military personnel and 700 Kurdish
insurgents have been killed in violence related to the revolt since
1984.
   Ethnic Kurds make up about one-fifth of Turkey's population of
52 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
