<1ST_LINE>r a AM-People-Edwards 2ndLd-Writethru a0708 04-01 0379</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-People-Edwards, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0708,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doug Edwards' Last Day at CBS</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2nd graf, Friday ``CBS..., with 1 graf to fix wording;
subs 4th graf, Edwards last..., with 1 graf to UPDATE with final
radio broadcast.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Douglas Edwards, who was the nation's first
nightly TV anchorman, preceding Walter Cronkite in the job at CBS,
had his last day at the network on Friday after 46 years.
   Friday's midday ``CBS Newsbreak'' was his last television
appearance for CBS.
   He concluded it with a personal statement: ``And so ends the
chapter of almost 46 years as this reporter moves on along the
journey. A deep bow of gratitude, love and respect to the men and
women of CBS News and to the company for which they stand. To you
out there, thank you for honoring me with your presence in my
audience, and most of all for your voices, your most sweet voices.
Douglas Edwards, CBS News New York.''
   Edwards' last radio broadcast was Friday night. At its close,
CBS News vice president Joe Dembo wished Edwards ``goodbye and
Godspeed,'' and CBS Evening News anchorman Dan Rather saluted him
as ``one of the founding fathers'' of broadcast journalism.
   President Reagan sent a congratulatory letter calling Edwards a
``consummate professional.''
   ``Over the years, countless men and women have turned to you for
the news, especially in time of crisis, and have felt reassured
that they are `getting it straight' when they hear the the voice of
Douglas Edwards. I can't think of any greater tribute to a
journalist than that,'' said Reagan's letter.
   Edwards joined CBS Radio in 1942, joining Edward R. Murrow's
staff in London towards the end of World War II. Later, he served
as Paris bureau chief.
   When CBS launched its evening news show in 1948, then-CBS
President Frank Stanton tapped Edwards to anchor it and called it
``Douglas Edwards with the News.''
   NBC followed with ``Camel News Caravan,'' and ABC later launched
a nightly news show with John Daly.
   Edwards stayed in the job for 14 years, until the show became
the ``CBS Evening News'' and Cronkite took over as anchor.
   Edwards, 70, plans to move to Sarasota, Fla. He will continue
lecturing on broadcast journalism and start work on a book.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
