<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1903EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-FerryStrike     04-01 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ferry Strike,0235</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Channel Ferry Talks Break Off, Lines Grow At Dover</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks between striking seamen and P and O European
Ferries broke down on Good Friday, the first day of the Easter
weekend, and no further talks were scheduled, government mediator
Dennis Boyd said.
   P and O is one of the main ferry services across the English
Channel. At Dover, where the line's seamen have been off the job
for two months, about 3,800 frustrated tourists were stuck in a
line of more than 100 buses, an equal number of cars and 500 trucks.
   P and O chairman Peter Ford issued a statement to those waiting
at Dover: ``I have nothing but apologies and regret for the people
who have been disrupted. I remain convinced we will achieve a
solution to this dispute, which I believe is being prolonged
unnecessarily by people who are not trying to solve it.''
   Tourists who had ferry reservatons for Calais faced delays of up
to 12 hours and truck drivers could be waiting even longer, said
Paul Youden of the Dover Harbor Board. Buses at the end of the line
were given estimates of 24 hours.
   The strike has halted all P and O ferries in Dover but other
vessels were operating from the port. About 2,300 seamen are
striking over the line's plans to cut 400 jobs and introduce new
shifts.
</TEXT>
