<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1903EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UgandanPriestess     04-01 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ugandan Priestess,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebel Ugandan Priestess Freed From Kenyan Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Ugandan rebel leader and voodoo
priestess who anointed her troops with oils to protect them from
bullets was turned over to United Nations authorities after three
months in prison, a Kenyan government official said Friday.
   Alice Lakwena, who fled to Kenya after Ugandan troops
slaughtered her army, was turned over to the U.N. high commissioner
for refugees, according to a high-ranking Kenyan government
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   New Vision, the Ugandan government newspaper, reported Friday
that Ms. Lakwena was seeking political asylum through the United
Nations.
   The Kenya government jailed Ms. Lakwena and seven of her Holy
Spirit Movement followers in December on charges of entering the
country illegally. Kenya had said it would turn the rebel leader
over to the Ugandan government after she completed her a four-month
sentence.
   But Ms. Lakwena appealed and the Kenyan High Court ruled Feb. 11
that the minister in charge of immigration should decide on whether
to return her to Uganda. New Vision said Kenya had decided not to
extradite Ms. Lakwena but did not give a source for its report.
   Ms. Lakwena, believed to be 28, was born to an Anglican
clergyman and his wife in northern Uganda.
   She began her crusade against the government of President Yoweri
Museveni in early 1987, claiming she was guided by a spirit
demanding his ouster. She was known to followers as ``Mama Alice.''
   She raised a battalion of followers numbering as many as 15,000
and told them she had magical powers to protect them. But
government troops crushed her army, which fought with sticks and
stones, late last year.
   There was no word on her jailed followers Friday and no official
Kenyan statement on her release. The U.N. refugee office in Nairobi
was closed for Good Friday and calls to representatives' homes went
unanswered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
