<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1905EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Women     04-01 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Women,0426</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women Union Officials Decry Inequality</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The top women officials of labor federations in
seven cities issued a statement Friday complaining that women on
the job received unequal treatment and demanding a public debate on
the issue.
   ``We call upon the media, economic and theoretical communities,
leaders at all levels of the (Communist) party and government ...
and all men and women workers to air their own views and actively
join in a discussion,'' the seven women said in the statement,
published on the front page of the newspaper Workers' Daily.
   Their statement, drafted at a meeting in Beijing, was especially
critical of what they said was a growing tendency to fire women
once they have children.
   Many enterprises also have done away with maternity leave and
other ``women's benefits'' in order to cut costs now that companies
are being held responsible for their own profits and losses.
   ``Some people believe that when a woman becomes pregnant and has
a child it is a private matter and becomes a burden for the
enterprise,'' the statement said. ``But others believe women carry
two heavy loads, of helping produce material goods for society and
perpetutating the human race, and this contribution deserves social
recognition and special protection.''
   Women were regarded as inferior in traditional China's rigid
social hierarchy but are promised equal treatment in Communist
China's constitution.
   In reality, they hold few high government or party posts and
have little social influence. Most still bear the full burden of
household chores and child-rearing while also working full-time in
the fields or in factories.
   Political and economic reforms, including decentralization of
authority and emphasis on profit-and-loss, have eroded the few
guarantees of access to higher education, jobs and political
representation for women.
   Official media have carried dozens of reports in the past year
of women being denied jobs or fired because of their sex. A recent
All-China Federation of Trade Unions survey found that 64 percent
of all workers being laid off in factory reorganizations were women.
   The statement by the seven labor leaders blamed the lingering
influence of ``old thinking'' and the failure of enterprises to
find practical solutions to problems faced by women workers with
children.
   ``If these problems are not solved, not only will it harm the
enthusiasm of women workers, but it will have impact on the
progress of (economic) reform,'' said the seven, who head the
women's sections of Beijing, Luoyang, Wuhan, Chongqing, Nantong,
Handan and Liuzhou municipal labor federations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880401-0221 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1903EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0659 04-01 0883</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,850</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Says Reagan Administration Permits a Corporate Mania</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADD 7grafs to UPDATE with Dukakis' comments on Meese</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RACINE, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis, looking for
support among union voters, said Friday the Reagan administration
has permitted a corporate ``merger mania'' that has cost a
half-million workers their jobs and weakened America.
   Dukakis injected a strain of populism into his presidential
campaign as he spoke to labor audiences in Wisconsin, where he is
locked in what polls suggest is a close race with rival Democrat
Jesse Jackson.
   ``Wall Street pirates and corporate hit teams aren't the model
for a new America,'' Dukakis said.
   The Massachusetts governor spoke to about 500 people crowded
into the Racine Labor Center, a meeting place for various union
locals, where he criticized Attorney General Edwin Meese III and
blamed the administration for what he described as a ``takeover
epidemic'' among giant companies that enrich the corporate raiders
and put workers out of their jobs.
   ``If we're serious about winning the battle for our economic
future, we've got to get control of the merger and acquisition
binge that's gobbling up capital, tearing corporations apart like
erector sets, making millions of dollars for a few ... and leaving
the average working men and women of America holding the bag,'' he
said.
   Dukakis' audience was mostly retired and active union members in
Racine, from auto, tractor and other manufacturing plants in a area
where unemployment is reported to be more than 8 percent. Later he
was speaking to displaced workers in Green Bay and visiting a farm
near Wausau in northern Wisconsin.
   Dukakis' populist-tinged speech came as his campaign began a new
television ad in Wisconsin attacking the Reagan administration and
depicting farm foreclosures and homeless families.
   He is battling Jackson _ whose own populist appeal has made him
a close second to Dukakis in the delegate race _ in next Tuesday's
Wisconsin primary. After his loss to Jackson in Michigan, Dukakis
needs a victory in Wisconsin. Also running are Sens. Albert Gore
Jr. of Tennessee, who has been attacking big corporations in
television ads in this state, and Paul Simon of Illinois.
   Under criticism from some Democrats for a bland style, Dukakis
has unveiled new campaign speeches in an effort to sharpen his
message, even as aides maintain he is not changing his style or
approach in reaction to opponents.
   Dukakis cited figures showing more than 12,000 corporations have
changed hands in the last five years and that 15 takeover bids of
$1 billion or more have been made in the past 12 weeks.
   ``And what have we got to show for it?'' he asked ``Massive
corporate debt. Lower quality products. Workers thrown into the
streets. A less competitive America. And the profits these people
make are unbelievable.
   ``Altogether we've seen a half-million workers lose their jobs
as a result of merger mania in recent years,'' he said, citing
layoffs and plant closings in Eau Claire, La Crosse, Cudahy and
Milwaukee, Wis.
   He blamed the administration's Labor Department and National
Labor Relations Board, saying they ``won't stand up for the
American worker.'' And, he said, ``We've got an attorney general
who couldn't tell the difference between antitrust and antifreeze,
an antitrus division (of the Justice Department) that hasn't been
heard from in years.''
   Dukakis said that because the administration has permitted
``this takeover epidemic ... the Japanese must be laughing at us
all the way to the bank.''
   At a union hall in Green Bay, Dukakis criticized Meese, who has
been under criminal investigation for 11 months.
   ``This guy in the Justice Department is spending so much time
defending himself he can't do his job.''
   Suggesting Reagan should fire Meese, Dukakis said: ``One of the
jobs of a chief executive ... is not only you hire people but
occasionally you fire them.''
   Meese came under heavy fire in Congress this week after two of
his top aides quit the Justice Department, saying Meese's
continuing legal problems were hurting department function and its
image.
   But Meese got a boost Friday in Washington when independent
counsel James McKay announced he had found insufficient evidence to
date to warrant indicting Meese in connection with a $1 billion
Iraqi pipeline plan or a possible conflict of interest involving
his telephone company stock.
   Dukakis avoided mention of his Democratic rivals but, taking
questions from the audience at the Green Bay Labor Temple, said he
viewed Bush's claim to aspire to be ``the education president''
this way: ``With a large laugh.''
   ``Cutting and slashing student loans, destroying our commitment
to education, I don't see it,'' Dukakis said. ``What's he for? ...
It'll be quite a conversion.''
   He took a swipe at Education Secretary William J. Bennett,
saying: ``He's the exception to the rule that an education is good
for you.''
   Dukakis met with leaders of the National Farmers' Union, a group
representing family farmers, at a dairy farm near Wausau. Standing
with farmers in front of a dairy barn after their meeting, Dukakis
said he backed ``reasonable price supports'' for milk as well as
``reasonable'' controls on supply _ but did not say what those
levels would be.
   Union president Lee Swenson said Dukakis offered ``a very
receptive ear'' to farm concerns.
</TEXT>
