<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Terrorists     04-01 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Terrorists,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Reduces Prison Terms Of Two Jewish Underground Members</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Jewish men imprisoned for armed attacks on
Arabs in the occupied land West Bank were ordered freed Friday in a
Passover holiday gesture by President Chaim Herzog.
   Ira Rappaport was pardoned with four months remaining on his
sentence and Yitzhak Geniram still had 2{ months on his term, said
Ami Gluska, a spokesman for Herzog.
   ``This is really a holiday present,'' Rappaport's wife, Orit,
told Israel radio. ``We are very happy and every day Ira spends
with us is a present.''
   Gluska said the two had been pardoned in part because they
expressed regret for their actions. ``There is a general trend to
reduce sentences in the framework of the 40th year of the state,''
he said on Israel radio. Israel was founded in 1948.
   Rappaport and Geniram were convicted of belonging to a Jewish
terror ring that carried out attacks on Arabs in the occupied West
Bank of the Jordan River earlier in the 1980s. Members of the
group, called ``The Jewish Underground,'' were apprehended between
April 1984 and December 1986.
   The New York-born Rappaport was convicted of attaching a bomb in
June 1980 to the car of a former mayor of Nablus, Bassam Shakaa,
who lost his legs in the explosion.
   Rappaport was sentenced to four years in jail, but the court
suspended 1{ years of the sentence, taking into account ``personal
circumstances.''
   Rappaport came to Israel in the 1970s and was a founder of
Shiloh, a Jewish settlement in the West Bank.
   Geniram, a founder of the right-wing Gush Emunim settlement
movement, was sentenced to four years in jail and three years on
probation after being convicted of manslaughter and attempted
manslaughter.
   The court ruled he loaned his car to attackers who killed three
Arab students at the Hebron Islamic College and wounded 30 in a
July 1983 attack.
   He also was convicted of helping gather explosives for a June
1980 attack on Arab mayors in the West Bank and was involved in a
plot to blow up Moslem mosques on the holy Temple Mount in
Jerusalem.
</TEXT>
