<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--RayInterview     04-01 0153</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Ray Interview,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>James Earl Ray Says He'd Trade Places with Hostages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After nearly two decades in prison for the
assassination of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., James Earl Ray
says he would trade places with the hostages in Lebanon.
   ``I'm primarily interested in getting out of jail. I'll take my
chances over there,'' the 60-year-old Alton native told the Alton
Telegraph in a recent telephone interview.
   Ray is being held in Tennessee's Brushy Mountain State Prison on
a 99-year sentence for the April 4, 1968, slaying of King. Ray
pleaded guilty but maintains he did so only under pressure and is
innocent.
   Ray said he does not think about how he will be remembered.
   ``It's been a long time. After a while you get to think about
other things,'' he said. ``I work in the laundry now. You don't get
up and think about it everyday.''
</TEXT>
