<DOCNO> AP880401-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1946EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Salvador-Elections     04-01 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Salvador-Elections,0514</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Electoral Tribunal Announces Assembly Election Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The right-wing Nationalist
Republican Alliance won exactly half of the 60 legislative assembly
seats in elections held on March 20, election officials announced
Friday.
   The Central Elections Council said the alliance, known by its
Spanish acronym Arena, won 30 seats but fell short of an absolute
majority.f the elections council and a director
of the governing Christian Democratic Party, said the Christian
Democrats won 23 seats and the conservative National Conciliation
Party seven.
   Arena earlier claimed the party won up to 35 seats. Local media
had projected the party would win 33-34 seats.
   In the new assembly, National Conciliation legislators could
form a voting bloc with the centrist Christian Democrats and make
passage of legislation by either Arena or the Christian Democrats
difficult.
   Samayoa said the results present an ``interesting situation
because no party will predominate and will have to have
negotiations.''
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte's Christian Democrats held 33
seats in the previous assembly and Arena 13.
   Arena founder Roberto d'Aubuisson said his party would petition
the council to have the election results annulled. If that was
rejected, Arena would take its case to the Supreme Court,
d'Aubuisson said.
   Alfredo Cristiani, Arena's president, had said on March 23 that
the Christian Demcorats were manipulating the vote count to deprive
his party of a parliamentary majority. ``We cannot let these
shameless individuals steal our legislators,'' he said.
   In an interview on local television Wednesday, Cristiani said
``The people are being defrauded. This could explode at any moment,
something difficult to stop (could) occur.''
   D'Aubuisson had said three days after the balloting, ``We don't
want to promote violence. But we want to play clean and they won't
let us.''
   The National Association for Private Enterprise had declared
earlier it would call a general strike if the elections council did
not report an Arena victory.
   Samayoa said Friday Arena would have to accept the final results
and ``re-evaluate its positions.''
   Arena leaders withdrew from the vote-counting process Tuesday
night and removed their representative from the elections council.
   One representative from each of the three major political
parties is allowed to sit on the elections panel. Two votes are
enough to approve any decision.
   Francisco Merino, the Arena representative, withdrew Tuesday and
claimed the other panel members were trying to make a ``game of the
vote tallies in order to change the results of the elections.''
   In a recent interview with The Associated Press, Samayoa
rejected the allegations of fraud and said it ``only exists in the
mind of those who have manipulated information about the results in
their favor.''
   While a computer count of votes for mayors in 262 municipalities
was incomplete, Samayoa said Friday Arena had won 178 of the races.
</TEXT>
