<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1947EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-JapanFoodstuffs     04-01 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Japan Foodstuffs,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan to Seek Compromise on Beef, Oranges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese officials said Friday they intend to
continue seeking a compromise over U.S. demands for an end to their
country's import quotas on U.S. beef and oranges.
   Agriculture Minister Takashi Sato said despite the breakdown of
negotiations, his government would continue to discuss the issue
through diplomatic channels. He also told reporters he was ready to
return to Washington when necessary. The minister was scheduled to
leave Saturday for Tokyo.
   Sato met briefly Friday with Allen Wallis, U.S. undersecretary
of state for economic affairs. Their talk was described, however,
as a courtesy call rather than resumption of the foodstuff
negotiations with the office of the U.S. trade representative that
ended in deadlock Thursday night.
   U.S. officials said the next step will be next Friday in Geneva,
where the United States will urge the council of GATT, the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, to convene a panel to declare the
Japanese quotas illegal under international trading rules.
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter, who negotiated with
Sato, declared after the talks he was ``deeply disappointed that
the Japanese did not come forward with their proposal to liberalize
trade on beef and citrus.'' Japanese officials termed the U.S.
demand for total elimination of the quotas covered by an expired
four-year agreement unrealistic but declined to say whether they
had offered a timetable for the elimination.
</TEXT>
