<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Storm     04-01 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Storm,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wintry Storm Blankets Panhandle With Snow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMARILLO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A spring blizzard hit the Texas and
Oklahoma panhandles on Friday, stranding motorists and knocking out
power in areas.
   As much as 6 inches of snow blanketed some areas and up to 20
inches were expected from the strong storm system that moved out of
the southern Rockies across northeastern New Mexico, the National
Weather Service said.
   ``They're going to have a white Easter there,'' said weather
service forecaster Larry Mooney in Norman, Okla., referring to a
blizzard warning posted for the Oklahoma Panhandle.
   Mary Anne Burdo, a Highway Patrol dispatcher at Guymon, Okla.,
where a foot of snow had fallen by late Friday afternoon, said
westernmost Cimmaron County ``is completely shut down.''
   ``We have a lot of stranded motorists in town and on the
highways,'' said police dispatcher Susie Simmons in Dalhart, in
northwest Texas. She said a lot of the travelers were on their way
to ski resorts.
   ``I guess they can cross-country ski here,'' she said.
   At least two major highways were closed, U.S. 87 through Dalhart
and U.S. 287 north of Stratford, because of blowing snow, the
Department of Public Safety said.
   Winds of up to 30 mph caused power outages from West Amarillo to
Dumas, authorities said.
   Thunderstorms, some producing hail, also rumbled across Texas
and Oklahoma Friday.
   The weather service issued a flood and flash flood watch for
much of southeast Texas, including metropolitan Houston, Galveston,
Beaumont and Port Arthur.
</TEXT>
