<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 2001EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Taiwan-Scientist     04-01 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Taiwan-Scientist,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Taiwan Confirms Missing Nuclear Scientist Is in U.S.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The defense minister on Friday said a
missing nuclear scientist, who allegedly gatherered information for
the CIA about purported plans by Taiwan to make nuclear weapons, is
in the United States.
   Defense Minister Cheng Wei-yuan said Col. Chang Hsien-yi, former
deputy director of the state-run Nuclear Energy Research Center,
may have gone to America for a better job or because of ``his lack
of confidence.'' He did not elaborate.
   ``We are not sure of the motive,'' Cheng told the legislature.
   He said Chang had telephoned and written friends in Taiwan from
the United States but he did not know where the scientist was
staying.
   Chang vanished in January and the government issued a warrant
for his arrest. Local newspapers claimed Chang worked for the CIA
and left the country with information about a government nuclear
weapons development program. They did not cite sources.
   Taiwan's Nationalist Chinese government has said it does not
have nuclear arms. The issue is sensitive because communist China
has said production of atomic weapons in Taiwan would be a
justified cause for invading the island, which the communist
leaders view as a renegade province.
   China has exploded its own nuclear devices.
   The American Institute in Taiwan, which handles diplomatic
matters in the absence of official U.S.-Taiwan relations, has said
it does not know Chang's whereabouts.
   A poll published Friday indicated Taiwanese are about evenly
divided over whether the government should make nuclear bombs.
   The United Evening News survey also indicated that most people
in Taiwan believe the country has the capability to make such
weapons.
   It reported 35 percent of 767 people polled by telephone said
Taiwan should make nuclear weapons and 34 percent were opposed,
with the rest undecided.
   About 58 percent believed Taiwan has the ability to develop such
weapons, it said.
   The poll was conducted last month and had a margin of error of
3.5 percentage points, according to United Evening News.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
