<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Koch-Jackson     04-01 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koch-Jackson,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koch Says Jackson, If Elected, Would Bankrupt America In Three
Weeks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Jesse Jackson is elected president and ``did
everything he said he wanted to do,'' the nation would be bankrupt
in three weeks ``based on all the social programs we would be
putting into effect,'' Mayor Edward I. Koch said Friday.
   However, because of party loyalty and because ``he'd be better''
than the likely GOP nominee George Bush, the Democratic mayor said
he would vote for Jackson if the Democrats nominate him at their
convention in Atlanta.
   ``I have said I would be stuck with whoever comes out of that
convention,'' Koch said.
   Reacting to Koch's remarks, Jerry Austin, manager of Jackson's
campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination, said the mayor
has ``solidified his position in the national exaggeration hall of
fame.''
   Koch told reporters that ``I think this country would be
ill-served to have Jesse Jackson'' in the White House.
   ``I think that in three weeks, based on all the social programs
we would be putting into effect (under Jackson), if you did
everything he said he wanted to do, we'd be in bankruptcy. People
know that's pie in the sky,'' Koch said.
   Koch added that ``he wants to disarm us'' and is ``on the wrong
side of every issue I know of with two exceptions: drugs _ he's
great in opposition to drugs _ and he's great in talking about the
need for family responsibility and particularly as it relates to
education.''
   The mayor also said that Jackson's standards are ``not my
standards. So I have said that it's very bad to contemplate having
Jackson being president.''
   Stanley Hill, co-chairman of Jackson's New York campaign, said:
``It's obvious that Mayor Koch is being very divisive in the city.
Once again, it is not helping the city.''
   While he termed the mayor's remarks unfortunate, Hill added:
``I'm not going to even try to reach his level of negative
campaigning.''
   Koch also said some people claim that criticism of Jackson might
be based on race, but he maintained that the black candidate's
positions on the issues are just as open to comment as those of
white candidates.
   ``He should be held accountable like any white candidate. Not
different. Exactly the same,'' he said.
   But, the mayor said, if Jackson is nominated, Jackson would win
Koch's vote in the presidential election ``for two reasons: party
loyalty _ and I have said I would be stuck with whoever comes out
of that convention. And the other is: he'd be better than Bush,''
the vice president, who is far ahead in this year's GOP
presidential race.
</TEXT>
