<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Britain-Soviet     04-01 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Soviet,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain, Soviet Union Initial Nuclear Safety Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain and the Soviet Union have agreed to
exchange information on nuclear safety, including the disclosure of
nuclear accidents, the government's Health and Safety Executive
announced late Friday.
   The agreement was initialed Thursday by British officials and
top Soviet nuclear safety experts.
   A government spokeswoman, speaking anonymously in keeping with
British government custom, said the agreement was wide-ranging and
covered the exchange of information on operating, building,
commissioning and decommissioning nuclear installations.
   The two countries agreed to exchange information on nuclear
accidents and any major release of radioactive material, she said.
The Soviet Union was criticized for its delay in reporting the
April 1986 explosion and fire at the Chernobyl nuclear plant, which
killed 31 Soviets and spread a cloud of radioactivity around the
world.
   The four Soviet officials met top officials at the Energy
Department and toured the Hinkley Point Magnox nuclear plant in
southwest England during a four-day visit to Britain. They have
returned to Moscow.
</TEXT>
