<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Britain-Nuclear,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thousands March on British Atomic Research Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Veterans of Britain's first ``Ban the Bomb''
movement 30 years ago, including former Labor Party leader Michael
Foot, marched Friday in front of thousands of demonstrators walking
toward a nuclear facility.
   Organizers said about 5,000 people participated in an
anti-nuclear rally Friday at Hyde Park in London. Thousands of
other protesters were expected to join the demonstrators on their
52-mile march that is to end Monday with another rally at the
Aldermaston nuclear base in Berkshire.
   The base houses the government's atomic weapons research center.
   Organizers said some protestors at the Hyde Park rally were
children of the demonstrators 30 years ago.
   Foot said Friday's protest was aimed at current problems. ``This
has nothing to do with nostalgia,'' he said. ``This march is a sign
that the campaign will go on until nuclear weapons are wiped off
the face of the galaxy.''
</TEXT>
