<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 2030EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Minister-Slaying     04-01 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Minister-Slaying,0384</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Charged In Contract-Killing Of Minister's Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSCUMBIA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister hired three men to kill his
wife for $1,000 each, then shot himself to death as suspicion
focused on him, authorities said Friday in announcing the arrests
of the alleged killers.
   The Rev. Charles Sennett, 45, apparently borrowed the $3,000
from his girlfriend for the March 18 stabbing of Elizabeth Sennett,
45, at the couple's ransacked rural home, said Colbert County
Sheriff Buddy Aldridge.
   Kenneth Eugene Smith, 22, and John Forrest Parker, 19, both of
Florence, were charged with capital murder Thursday, and Billy Gray
Williams, 21, also of Florence, was charged with conspiracy to
commit murder, Aldridge said.
   They were being held without bail.
   Sennett killed himself in front of his son's home March 25.
   ``We had interrogated him earlier in the day and ... told him he
was a suspect and informed his family he was,'' said Aldridge. ``We
had set up a polygraph test for the following Tuesday.''
   The sheriff said Sennett approached Williams ``about hurting
someone,'' and Williams hired Smith and Parker to carry out the
slaying.
   Smith and Parker ransacked the Sennett home and took a videotape
player and other items to make the crime look like a burglary, the
sheriff said.
   The minister of the Sheffield Church of Christ had told police
he returned home to find his wife stabbed and unconscious on the
floor, investigators said. She never regained consciousness and
died that night in surgery.
   Aldridge said Sennett, in shooting himself to death, left a note
saying ``he had never hurt his wife and that he had gotten in with
some bad guys.''
   The sheriff said that police have not pinpointed a motive in the
killing but that minister had admitted having a girlfriend.
   The woman told police Sennett borrowed $3,000 to ``pay on a
note,'' the sheriff said, ``but he would not account to us what he
had done with the money.'' The woman, whom authorities declined to
identify, was not charged.
   The suspects told officers they threw the weapons used in the
slaying _ a hunting knife, a fireplace poker and a cane _ into a
pond outside the Sennett home, Aldridge said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
