<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Obit-Jordan     04-01 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Jordan,0218</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jim Jordan, Radio's Fibber McGee, Dead At 91</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Jordan, who delighted radio audiences for
decades as the well-meaning but bumbling Fibber McGee in the
classic show ``Fibber McGee and Molly,'' died Friday. He was 91.
   Jordan had been hospitalized for about a week after a fall at
his home, said a family friend who declined to be identified.
   ``Fibber McGee and Molly'' was on the air for the NBC radio
network from 1935 to 1960 and was the top-rated show in the country
for seven of those years.
   It was the source of such familiar routines as McGee's
overstuffed closet, which always unloaded mercilessly on Jordan's
character whenever it was opened. Even McGee's address, 79 Wistful
Vista, became a place on the American cultural roadmap.
   ``Even though he had become very frail, his mind and his humor
were as fresh as ever,'' said Lenore Kingston, a vice president for
Pacific Pioneer Broadcasters. ``We all adored him.''
   Like the couple in the ``Fibber McGee and Molly'' scripts, the
stars of the show were married. Jim and Marian Jordan came to radio
out of vaudeville to formulate the comedy with writer Don Quinn.
   Mrs. Jordan died of cancer in 1961.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880401-0234 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 2058EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Afghanistan     04-01 0317</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Afghanistan,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Mediator Meets Separately With U.S., Soviet Envoys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. mediator Diego Cordovez on Friday held
separate meetings with Soviet special envoy Nikolay Kozyrev and
U.S. diplomat Robert Peck in his efforts to secure an Afghanistan
peace settlement.
   The superpowers could sign as guarantors if an accord is reached.
   Peck, a deputy assistant secretary of state, and Kozyrev have
been following the U.N.-sponsored indirect negotiations between
Afghanistan and Pakistan since the latest round began March 2 and
have routinely met with Cordovez.
   Pakistan acts on behalf of Afghanistan's Moslem guerrillas, who
have fought to topple the pro-Soviet government in Kabul for more
than eight years.
   Peck declined to say what impact, if any, a proposal by
Secretary of State George P. Shultz had on the talks.
   ``I'm not really able to talk about the details of the diplomacy
at the present time,'' he told reporters at the Geneva U.N. office
where the talks are being held.
   Shultz suggested Thursday that Moscow could keep arming Marxist
forces in Afghanistan after an estimated 115,000 Soviet troops
withdraw, provided the United States can maintain supplies to the
Afghan guerrillas.
   Washington said in the past it would not guarantee a settlement
unless the Soviet Union agreed to stop supporting the Afghan
governmewnt at the same time the United States ended aid to the
guerrillas.
   Soviet officials rejected that as attempted interference in
Soviet-Afghan relations and claimed America had raised a
last-minute obstacle at the U.N. talks.
   But Peck said: ``We're continuing to work very hard and we'll
stay here until we get an agreement. We should be able to put
something together.''
   Formal negotations are to resume Monday, but U.N. officials have
left open the possibility of continuing diplomatic contacts over
the weekend.
   The Soviets sent troops into Afghanistan in December 1979 to
help the government battle the rebels who were gaining control of
many areas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
