<DOCNO> AP880401-0235 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 2102EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mozambique-Zimbabwe     04-01 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mozambique-Zimbabwe,0200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zimbabweans Aid Mozambique Forces In Guerrilla Raids</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAPUTO, Mozambique (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zimbabwean forces joined Mozambican
soldiers in attacks that destroyed three major guerrilla bases in
southern Mozambique this month, the army announced Friday.
   The national news agency, AIM, said it was the first
confirmation of Zimbabwean participation in the 12-year-old civil
war between Marxist government forces and the Mozambique National
Resistance, which the government says is South African-backed.
   Zimbabwean forces have been in neighboring Mozambique for
several years, helping to guard the Limpopo Railway line which runs
for over 300 miles from the border to the port of Maputo.
   Zimbabwean and Mozambican railway workers are repairing the
track, which will give Zimbabwe a second outlet to the sea. The
other line, to the port of Beira, functions well, said AIM. It also
is guarded by Zimbabweans.
   AIM quoted a spokesman for the general staff of the Mozambican
armed forces as saying the joint force attacked the bases of
Chiconjo, Maginge and Nhahombe in Gaza province during the second
half of March, killing 260 bandits.
   There have been several reports of Mozambican guerrillas raiding
villages in Zimbabwe since that country sent troops into Mozambique.
</TEXT>
