<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SatelliteRescue     04-01 0294</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Satellite Rescue,280</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NOAA Team Helps Save Indian Satellite</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A team of federal experts at an Alaskan space
communications center helped to rescue an ailing Indian satellite
that was out of control earlier this month, a U.S. official said
Thursday.
   Larry Heacock, director of satellite operations for the National
Oceanographic and Atmospheric Administration, said the Indian
satellite, called IRS1A, was launched by a Soviet rocket on March
17 and placed into an orbit of about 560 miles.
   Satellite controllers in Germany, he said, discovered that the
IRS1A was unable to focus a guidance sensor on the Earth, a
sighting it was to use for an accurate orientation. As a result,
the craft was unstable and could not be controlled properly.
   Heacock said the satellite passed over the NOAA satellite
communications station in Fairbanks, Alaska six times every 24
hours.
   The German Space Agency, which was operating the satellite for
India, asked the NOAA station to take and send data to IRS1A.
   ``Each time it went by, NOAA took data and sent it to the German
space agency,'' said Heacock.
   Using this data, the Germans were able to properly orient IRS1A.
   ``The satellite is now normal,'' said Heacock.
   The IRS1A is to be used by the Indians to gather remote sensing
data. It was placed in a near-polar orbit which enables it to scan
the whole Earth once every 22 days.
   Heacock said the normal operation of the Fairbanks NOAA station
is to collect signals from the NOAA 9 and 10 weather satellites.
   For the Indian satellite, the NOAA engineers used a spare
antenna, and India paid the agency about $200,000 for the work,
Heacock said.
   The NOAA station earlier performed data collection for a French
remote sensing satellite called SPOT.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
