<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Reagan-Mint     04-01 0321</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Reagan-Mint,310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mint To Buy Coin Materials From Foreign Countries As Needed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan directed Treasury Secretary
James A. Baker III on Thursday to buy materials for U.S. coins from
foreign countries when required by international agreement, despite
a ``Buy America'' provision enacted by Congress.
   In a statement issued as he signed a reauthorization bill for
the Bureau of the Mint, Reagan noted that the legislation requires
preference for U.S. producers and suppliers over those in any
country that has its own protectionist measures governing
procurement for coinage.
   ``This requirement, standing alone, conflicts with certain of
our nation's international obligations,'' he said.
   Under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, for example,
the United States agreed to require the Mint to give equal
treatment to the products and supplies of other countries that are
signatories of the agreement.
   Some countries did not designate their mints as covered by this
agreement, but may have designated other agencies that the United
States elected not to have covered, the president said.
   Thus, he said, the preference provided in the bill ``could be
viewed by our trading partners as violating our obligations.''
   Canada did not designate its mint as covered by the agreement,
but Canada and the United States recently signed a free trade
agreement which is now being considered by Congress. The president
said following the preference provided in the bill ``could also
bring into question our obligations'' under the U.S.-Canadian trade
agreement.
   The president said it was fortunate that the bill would permit
the secretary of the treasury to waive the Buy America provision
when he found that it would be inconsistent with the public
interest or the cost would be unreasonable.
   ``The public interest of the United States includes adhering to
our international obligations, and these obligations should be
taken into account by the secretary of the treasury in making
procurements'' affected by the bill, the president said.
</TEXT>
