<DOCNO> AP880401-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0031EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BankDeregulation     04-01 0586</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Deregulation,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Proponents Encouraged By Senate Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House advocates of granting banks broad new
securities powers said Thursday their efforts have been given a big
boost by overwhelming passage of legislation in the Senate.
   ``We're on the move,'' said Rep. Stephen Neal, D-N.C., who plans
to offer a bill mirroring the Senate measure when the House Banking
Committee meets next month to consider the issue.
   The Senate voted 94-2 late Wednesday to allow bank holding
companies to underwrite and sell mortgage-backed securities,
commercial paper and municipal revenue bonds.
   It would permit underwriting of corporate bonds and mutual funds
six months after enactment by both houses of Congress and signature
by President Reagan, who favors the bill.
   ``I think ... the vote in the Senate shows a very broad-based,
liberal-conservative, bipartisan base for this kind of change,''
Neal said.
   But those pushing a more cautious approach say the Senate action
may have little effect, pointing out that a Senate deregulation
effort in 1984 died in the House for lack of support.
   ``Four years ago the Senate voted 89-4 for a bill that never
came out of the House. I'm not sure what influence it has now,''
said Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y. He said he believes provisions in
the Senate bill safeguarding federally insured deposits from the
risk of securities activities are too weak.
   Schumer is backing a bill drafted by House Banking Committee
Chairman Fernand J. St Germain, D-R.I. It would grant banks only a
few securities powers _ commercial paper, mortgage revenue bonds
and asset-backed securities _ and place more restrictions on banks.
   The Senate bill substantially lifts limits on banks in place
since 1933 when the Glass-Steagall Act separated commercial from
investment banking in the belief that bank involvement in
securities helped fuel the speculative binge that ended in the 1929
stock market crash and the bank failures of the 1930s.
   Proponents of change say developments in the financial system,
particularly in the last decade, threaten the ability of banks to
compete. Securities firms, for instance, offer bank-like services
such as commercial paper and money market mutual funds. They argue
that sufficient safeguards can be put in place to prevent the
abuses of the 1920s.
   The Senate measure requires a separate vote in 1991 before bank
holding companies could underwrite corporate stock, the most
lucrative securities activity.
   Rep. Edward J. Markey, D-Mass., whose Energy and Commerce
subcommittee on finance has partial jurisdiction over the issue,
called passage of the Senate bill a positive step, but said the
House will devote its attention to ``developing strong and
resilient firewalls'' between banking and securities activities.
   Consumer groups on Thursday praised provisions in the bill _
unrelated to securities _ aimed at benefiting bank customers.
   ``We're very excited,'' said Peggy Miller of the Consumer
Federation of America
   One section prohibits lenders from unilaterally changing the
pay-back and other terms of home equity loans. It requires lenders
to warn borrowers that they could lose their house if they fail to
pay and imposes other disclosure requirements.
   Another provision bars misleading savings and checking account
advertisements and requires banks to disclose the interest rate,
fees and other information.
   The bill would also require banks to prove they are meeting the
needs of poor citizens and neighborhoods before getting permission
to exercise the new powers.
   And, it directs banks to cooperate if state laws require them to
mail material to customers inviting them to join state financial
consumer organizations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
