<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Police-Homosexuals     04-01 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Police-Homosexuals,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Officers Arrest Single Men Who Wander Into Secluded Areas of Park</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special police detail is using an obscure
ordinance against walking in the bushes to arrest suspected
homosexuals in a city park.
   An official of the American Civil Liberties Union said Thursday
the tactic is discriminatory and probably illegal.
   Police said they see it as a way to clear Langford Park of
homosexuals who meet there. A city study concluded that the
boardwalks that wind through the forested park have become a
hangout for homosexuals and male prostitutes.
   Plainclothes officers on the special detail walk the wooden
boardwalks and wait for men to walk into the bushes and sheltered
spots.
   The law against walking in the bushes is part of a catch-all
loitering ordinance. It is not posted in the park.
   One 35-year-old man who did not want to be identified said he
was sitting in an open area of the park listening to a radio when
two uniformed officers demanded to see his identification and asked
if he had ever been arrested.
   They wanted to know why he was in a city park 10 minutes from
his home and if he was married, he said. ``They asked me if I was a
homosexual. Twice,'' the man said.
   He said the officers threatened to arrest him if they saw him
``walking aimlessly'' or spending more time there than they
believed was proper.
   ``How do you walk with purpose in a park?'' Ron Ross, president
of the local chapter of the ACLU, asked Thursday. ``Police are
using unposted laws and are creating their own criteria for arrest,
like `walking aimlessly.'''
   ``The innocent person doesn't have a chance,'' Ross said,
arguing that police have created a situation in which no single men
are innocent.
   Officers arrest suspected homosexuals on whatever charge they
can when they are unable to prove the men are prostitutes, said
police Capt. Duane McGray.
   The tactic has been used for more than a year because it is
difficult to make prostitution arrests, he said.
   Robert Stabile, 37, was picked up while strolling through the
foliage last week. He was jailed on a charge of prohibited
activity, although police could simply have issued him a notice to
appear in court and let him go home.
   ``I wasn't doing anything. I was just walking,'' Stabile
complained. ``They said I was out there too long.''
   The arrest report said a plainclothes officer on the special
detail saw Stabile ``walk into the bushes off of the park path. The
subject walked throughout the wooded area. I then arrested him for
prohibited activity in the park.''
   Stabile could serve 60 days in jail and pay up to a $500 fine if
convicted.
   Ross said the police practice is ``discriminatory, definitely
discriminatory, especially in a city park that is supposed to be
for the benefit of all citizens.
   ``It is outrageous to discriminate against a certain class of
people _ rather, who they suspect to be members of a certain class
of people,'' Ross said.
   Police attorney John Ross, who is not related to the ACLU
president, said anyone who claims that the law is being selectively
enforced has to prove it.
   ``The burden is on them to actually show that there are names
and addresses of people we have not arrested,'' he said.
</TEXT>
