<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Communists     04-01 0425</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Communists,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Communist Party Takes Blame For Hungary's Woes, Calls For Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party said Thursday it
was to blame for Hungary's economic woes and proposed reforms in
party elections including secret ballots and multi-candidate slates.
   A draft policy statement published Thursday by Nepszabadsag, the
Hungarian Communist Party daily newspaper, said the party had
failed to assess ``the impact of world economic changes on the
Hungarian economy,'' causing an economic crisis.
   The statement, a rare public admission of a mistake by a
governing communist party, added: ``The Central Committee and its
executive organs, the government and its institutions are
responsible for all this.''
   The draft is to serve as an outline of discussions at a national
party conference opening May 20 to review the Communists' role in
the changing society.
   The party draft said Hungarian leaders recognized ``belatedly''
that economic growth could not come without more economic and
political changes.
   The statement advocated a new system of party elections to be
implemented before the next congress in 1990.
   ``The practice of nominating more candidates should widen and
secret elections be held at all levels,'' the draft said.
   A 1986 party resolution setting a two-term limit on some lesser
party posts should be extended to cover regional party secretaries
as well, the draft said.
   The document also noted the party ``should not assume the scope
of tasks of the state and social organizations'' and pull back from
daily administration.
   The policy statement did not say whether the conference would
include a discussion on replacing Janos Kadar, the 75-year-old
Communist Party leader who has held power since 1956.
   But an unsigned editorial in the economics weekly Figyeloe said
Thursday that ``important decisions'' on personnel questions were
expected at the conference.
   The party meeting must create a new political system capable of
forging consensus among Hungarians of different opinions and
interests, Figyeloe said.
   Hungary borrowed heavily in the 1970s to build up heavy
industry. Now, its 10.6 million people are burdened with a gross
hard-currency debt of $16 billion, the highest per capita in the
Soviet bloc.
   As part of a government austerity program that took effect Jan.
1, Hungary became the first East bloc country to impose personal
income taxes. The government also said prices are to rise at least
15 percent this year.
   The austerity program is the work of Prime Minister Karoly
Grosz, 57, who took over the government in July and is seen as a
possible successor to Kadar.
   The last party congress was held in March 1985.
</TEXT>
