<2ND_LINE>AM-Mummy Found,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Widow Pleads Guilty to Forgery in Mummy Case; Dentist Pleads
Innocent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALESBURG, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who concealed her husband's death
for eight years and tended the corpse as if he were alive pleaded
guilty Thursday to two felony forgery charges related to the death.
   A former Chicago-area dentist accused of assisting her in the
forgery pleaded innocent.
   Carole Stevens, 42, of Knoxville entered the plea in Knox County
Circuit Court. Judge Harry Bulkeley placed her on two years'
probation and sentenced her to 12 days in jail, for which she
received credit for 12 days served.
   Bulkeley also ordered Mrs. Stevens to undergo psychiatric
treatment. She could have received up to five years in prison and a
$10,000 fine.
   Mrs. Stevens was charged with fabricating a power of attorney
for her dead husband in 1984 and using it to refinance a home
mortgage.
   Her alleged accomplice, Richard G. Kunce, 56, a former Aurora
dentist who was a guest in the Stevens house, was charged with
signing his name as a witness.
   In February, Mrs. Stevens and Kunce pleaded guilty to
misdemeanor charges of failing to report the 1979 death of Carl L.
Stevens, a diabetic who authorities say died shortly after he
joined a holistic health cult and stopped taking his daily insulin
shots.
   Mrs. Stevens was placed on a year's probation on the misdemeanor
charge. Kunce has asked a judge to withdraw his guilty plea.
   Stevens' withered corpse was found Jan. 29 on a bed in the home,
where officials said his widow, a registered nurse, had cared for
the body daily for the past eight years, changing its clothes and
moving it from room to room.
   Mrs. Stevens' children, ages 17 and 14, are in foster care
receiving psychiatric treatment.
   In a separate case, Mrs. Stevenson on Thursday admitted to child
neglect for allowing her children to live with their father's
mummified remains for eight years.
   She was granted permission to continue seeing her children under
supervision pending a decision on whether she will retain custody.
   Kunce also awaits a court appearance on a felony charge of
cruelty to children for allegedly teaching the Stevens children
``black magic and suicide'' and for allowing them to live in the
same house with the corpse.
   If convicted on the cruelty charge, he could receive up to three
years in prison and a $10,000 fine.
