<2ND_LINE>AM-Balloonists, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0697,0308</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Balloonists Cancel Attempt To Circle Earth</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 6th graf: Petrehn, 52 .... with 1 graf to DELETE
extraneous words.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MENDOZA, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two American balloonists on Thursday
called off their plans to circle the Earth non-stop in two weeks or
less, saying $100,000 worth of helium leaked out of one of their
balloons.
   They said they hoped to try again next year.
   Col. Rowland Smith, 50, said a patch in one balloon ripped
Wednesday as the two 360-foot-high balloons were being inflated at
El Plumerillo Air Base outside Mendoza, 660 miles west of Buenos
Aires.
   Smith and project organizer John Petrehn, of Topeka, Kan., said
about $2.5 million had been spent in transportation, materials and
personnel for the double-decker balloon flight.
   ``Technically it's impossible to attempt to fly around the
world'' this year, a disappointed Smith said at a brief news
conference. He said they hoped to try next year.
   Petrehn, 52, is a businessman, while Smith is a former Vietnam
War pilot and a Kansas-based pilot for Trans World Airlines. The
balloonists had hoped to do what no one else has: circle the Earth
around the 45-degree parallel in the Southern Hemisphere.
   They planned to follow the 45th parallel for about 17,545 miles,
traveling southeast from Mendoza, crossing the Atlantic and Indian
Oceans and New Zealand's Campbell Island, then cross the Pacific
until Chile, dropping over the Andes to return to Mendoza in nine
to 14 days.
   They hoped to travel at speeds up to 60 knots an hour, following
the prevailing eastern winds at altitudes of up to 30,000 feet in a
pressurized radar-equipped polyethlene gondola three yards by two
yards wide.
   The longest manned balloon flight was in 1981, when the Double
Eagle V crossed the Pacific for about 5,000 miles.
</TEXT>
