<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica     04-01 0402</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Bans All Outdoor Political Gatherings For Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government on Thursday
banned all outdoor meetings for a year, except those involving
sporting events or funerals.
   Justice Minister Kobie Coetsee announced the order under terms
of the Internal Security Act, which prohibits a wide range of
activities. It takes effect Friday and will be in force through
March 31, 1989.
   Under national emergency regulations already in effect, outdoor
rallies are illegal unless approved by a magistrate or Law and
Order Minister Adriaan Vlok.
   It was not immediately clear if the latest order expanded
government authority to restrict rallies.
   Magistrates still will have the power to consider exceptions to
the ban.
   The order appears aimed at nationwide municipal elections
scheduled for all race groups in October. By restricting rallies to
indoors, the government apparantly seeks to limit the size of
crowds and reduce the potential for violence.
   It is the latest move in recent government crackdowns aimed at
limiting political activity.
   Last week, a judge, acting on a government request, banned an
outdoor rally by the Afrikaner Resistance Movement, a
white-supremacist paramilitary organization. The group eventually
met indoors.
   On Feb. 24, the government banned 18 leading black
anti-apartheid groups from participating in political activity.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
   Also Thursday, Minister of Constitutional Development Chris
Heunis said residents of the small black township of Oukasie,
outside the northeastern city of Brits, must be resettled in
keeping with government policy.
   Heunis said Monday in Parliament the government would not try to
relocate the remaining 8,000 residents.
   He said Thursday his statement was misinterpreted. He reiterated
government policy that Oukasie remained officially abolished and
residents would be moved to Lethlabile, a newly established
township 15 miles away. But he said it would not be done by
``force.''
   Heunis abolished Oukasie by decree in October 1986, but only
about 5,000 residents moved to Lethlabile. Oukasie residents
repeatedly have said they prefer their old homes and have no
intention of moving.
   The government says the cost of upgrading Oukasie would be
``astronomical.'' Oukasie residents say the government wants them
out because the township has expanded to within 250 yards of a
white suburb in Brits.
</TEXT>
