<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SchoolsClosing     04-01 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Schools Closing,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>District School Board Votes To Furlough All Employees For Up To
One Week</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The District of Columbia school board,
claiming budget shortfalls, voted Thursday to furlough all
employees for one to seven days.
   The board also voted to cut some summer school sessions, reduce
purchases, and institute a hiring freeze because of a $15 million
gap in the fiscal year 1988 supplemental budget, according to
acting school superintendent Alfred Jenkins.
   Furloughing all city school employees for up to seven days could
save the school district $8.1 million in pay and other costs,
Jenkins said.
   ``I don't feel very good about it at all,'' Jenkins said. ``I
only know the reality is we just don't have the money. We have to
make plans for any eventuality.''
   Jenkins said the school board did not decide whether the
furloughs would take place on consecutive days, or whether they
would be spread out between now and Sept. 30, the end of the 1988
budget year.
   City council member Hilda Mason, who chairs the council's
education and libraries panel, said she did not know whether the
school district would run into accreditation problems if schools
were closed.
   One possibility is that the furloughs would come during the
summer, when most students aren't in school, while another scenario
is that the temporary layoffs could be staggered in order to keep
schools open, Mason said.
   Council chairman David Clarke called the school board's decision
``the height of irresponsibility,'' and said that the council has
approved a total of $37.7 million in additional school spending for
fiscal years 1988 and 1989.
   The school board requested an additional $25.1 million in the
1988 budget supplement, but the council approved only $10 million
of that request.
   Including the supplemental increases, the 22,000-pupil school
system will receive $579.5 million in the 1988 budget year.
</TEXT>
