<1ST_LINE>r a AM-StudentJabbings     04-01 0242</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Student Jabbings,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students, Teacher to be Tested For AIDS After Pupil Jabbed Them</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTERLY, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 25 high school students and a
teacher are being tested for AIDS after a 16-year-old jabbed them
with a surgical instrument taken from a biology classroom, the
principal said Thursday.
   ``There is no indication that anyone was sick with anything, but
it's better to be safe than sorry,'' said Albert Ferraro Jr.,
principal at Westerly High School.
   Ferraro said the student, who was not identified, jabbed a
teacher in the side and drew blood Monday with a lancet, a
two-edged, pointed device used to prick the skin for blood samples.
   About 25 students reported Monday and Tuesday that they had been
poked as well, and a police officer who frisked the boy in the
school office Monday came in contact with the lancet in the
teen-ager's pocket, Ferraro said.
   The student was suspended for 10 days Monday after the teacher,
whom Ferraro would not identify, filed assault charges.
   The teacher, police officer and students were given tetanus and
hepatitis shots at Westerly Hospital on Monday and Tuesday, Ferraro
said.
   On Wednesday, he said, the students began returning to the
hospital, where their blood was being drawn and sent to the state
Department of Health for the AIDS test. The results can take up to
two weeks, a hospital spokeswoman said.
   Ferraro said he recommended the testing after talking to the
school doctor.
</TEXT>
