<1ST_LINE>r a AM-NoriegaLawyer     04-01 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Noriega Lawyer,0252</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Lawyer Warns Client U.S. Could Kidnap Him For Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American attorney for Gen. Manuel Antonio
Noriega said Thursday he has advised the Panamanian leader to be
wary of possible attempts to kidnap him and bring him to trial on
drug charges in the United States.
   Neal Sonnett of Miami said he based his advice on history _
citing previous U.S. kidnappings of fugitives _ and the refusal
recently of Elliott Abrams, assistant secretary of state, to rule
out any option for removing Noriega.
   The lawyer said a kidnapping attempt would not necessarily come
while Noriega is in Panama. It could come as the general sought
refuge in another country, he said.
   ``I don't know that the United States would send marshals, armed
guards or troops to snatch him from Panama,'' Sonnett said.
   He said he would ``insist not just on a (U.S.) promise not to
extradite but also on a guarantee of safe passage'' if Noriega
leaves Panama.
   Noriega, the military power behind the civilian government, has
been indicted on drug and racketeering charges in Miami and Tampa.
   U.S. State Department spokesman Rudy Boone on Thursday refused
to comment on Sonnett's suggestion that kidnapping was a U.S.
option.
   Sonnett cited the U.S. decision in 1985 to force down a plane in
Sicily that was transporting four accused Palestinian hijackers as
``an indication of the length to which the United States will go to
secure a fugitive.''
</TEXT>
