<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HorseFraud     04-01 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Horse Fraud,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Horse Trader Pleads Guilty In Bid To Defraud Insurance Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A horse trainer Thursday admitted taking part
in a scheme to collect $81,000 in insurance by sending eight horses
to their death over a cliff.
   Bobby Griffin, 45, of Lufkin, Texas, pleaded guilty along with
Leonard Keith Autterson, 48, of Lakeside, Calif., to conspiracy to
defraud an insurance company.
   Each faces up to five years in prison at sentencing May 23, but
Assistant U.S. Attorney Patrick Coughlin said he will recommend
probation. Both men have agreed to testify at the trial of four
co-defendants, Coughlin said.
   The staged truck accident occurred in 1983 off Interstate 8 near
Jacumba, about 70 miles east of San Diego. Seven horses died at the
scene; the eighth horse was destroyed.
   Coughlin said Griffin was listed as the buyer of the horses
because the alleged conspirators needed the name of someone in the
horse business to make the accident look legitimate.
   ``I was supposed to get $10,000 to use my name as the
contractor,'' Griffin told U.S. District Judge Gordon Thompson Jr.
   ``They were supposed to be selling them to me and ship them to
Texas. I didn't put it together; I just agreed to it,'' said
Griffin. He said he did not get any of the money.
   Autterson told Thompson he was offered $7,500 by another
co-defendant to drive the horses off a cliff.
   ``Did you cause the accident?'' asked Thompson.
   ``I drove the truck up to the cliff and made sure the horses
were in it,'' he answered.
</TEXT>
