<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LaRoucheTrial     04-01 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-LaRouche Trial,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>LaRouche Launches Attack On Bush</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Political extremist Lyndon LaRouche said Thursday
the defense at his conspiracy trial would show that Vice President
George Bush condoned infiltration and harassment of LaRouche groups.
   ``Vice President George Bush is going to be dropped into this
trial,'' LaRouche said without offering evidence to support this
allegations. ``This is no longer a credit card case. This is the
George Bush-Oliver North case.''
   LaRouche is on trial on federal charges he conspired to obstruct
a grand jury investigation into alleged credit card fraud by his
1984 presidential campaign.
   His remarks Thursday were his first since defense lawyers gained
access to government documents discussing alleged infiltration of
LaRouche groups by FBI and CIA operatives.
   According to trial testimony, the documents do not mention Bush,
but LaRouche said the vice president had to be aware of the alleged
infiltration because he presided over an interagency panel that
discussed intelligence matters.
   Prosecutors contend intelligence operatives quoted in the
documents lied in claiming to have been asked by the FBI and CIA to
infiltrate LaRouche groups.
   But LaRouche said the documents proved his contention that the
Reagan administration plotted to ruin him because he refused to
support the president's Contra-aid program.
   LaRouche said the defense also would prove that Bush, contrary
to his public statements, had a central role in the shipment of
arms to Iran and the diversion of the profits to the Contra rebels
in Nicaragua.
   ``The people who are running the operations are accountable to
him,'' said LaRouche, who espouses theories of world conspiracies
and has accused prominent world leaders of being Soviet agents.
   The vice president's office did not return telephone calls from
The Associated Press.
   Testimony in the trial of LaRouche, six aides and five LaRouche
political organizations has been halted while a judge holds
hearings on defense allegations that prosecutors withheld evidence
of infiltration of LaRouche groups.
   The hearings are expected to continue at least through next week.
   Bush's office and numerous federal agencies have been ordered to
search their files for references to LaRouche, a candidate for the
Democratic presidential nomination.
</TEXT>
