<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TotCommitted     04-01 0243</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tot Committed,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Says He Had No Choice But To Commit Toddler To State
Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge said Thursday he had no alternative
when he sent a 4{-year-old boy to a state mental hospital.
   Authorities said the child is apparently the youngest ever
committed in Maryland.
   ``There was a lack of any other resources under the
circumstances,'' Montgomery County Juvenile Court Judge Douglas
Moore said in a telephone interview from Rockville. He said the boy
was committed Tuesday evening.
   The child was receiving individual attention at the Springfield
Hospital Center in Sykesville, said Mike Golden, spokesman for the
Department of Health and Mental Hygiene.
   The action stemmed from an investigation by the county
Department of Social Services into charges that the boy had been
neglected, said J.C. Shay, spokesman for the state Department of
Human Resources.
   ``This is an emergency placement, until we can find something
better,'' Shay said. ``The boy needs in-patient psychiatric care.''
   Officials could not remember any child that young ever before
being committed in Maryland, said Dr. Henry Harbin, director of the
state Mental Hygiene Administration.
   Winifred DePalma, an attorney with the Maryland Disability Law
Center, called the move ``mind-boggling.''
   ``I have never heard of them committing a child that young,''
she said. ``They have no facilities for a child that age. There are
some very emotionally disturbed youths in the adolescent unit. In
no case should a 4-year-old child ever be committed there.''
</TEXT>
