<1ST_LINE>a e AM-APArts:CommonPursuit Adv05   04-01 0634</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AP Arts: Common Pursuit, Adv 05,0648</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv05</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tue AMs, April 5 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>``Common Pursuit'' Gets Second London Chance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A flop London play that became a surprise New York
hit is having its second shot at local success as a result of its
long off-Broadway run.
   ``Whatever happens to it now, it's a much better piece,''
playwright Simon Gray said of his play ``The Common Pursuit,''
which opens a commercial London engagement April 7 at the Phoenix
Theater.
   The play, which looks at the lapsed ideals of six graduates of
Cambridge University over a 15-year-period, bowed to mixed reviews
and disappointing houses four years ago at West London's
not-for-profit Lyric, Hammersmith Theater.
   Hopes of transferring that production to the West End, London's
Broadway, were never realized. It took the play's subsequent
success off-Broadway, where it began an acclaimed 10-month run at
the Promenade Theater in October 1986, to secure its present West
End engagement.
   Co-producer John McQuiggan said the play has been transformed
from its original London run. ``I don't think anyone wants to dwell
on 1984,'' he said. ``My feeling is this is a brand-new
production.''
   McQuiggan produced the play on his own in New York and is
co-producing it in London with Howard Panter's Independent
Theatrical Productions.
   Capitalized at $295,000, roughly the same as its off-Broadway
cost, the play will break even in the West End at 40 percent
capacity, McQuiggan said, meaning it could recoup its investment
after five weeks if business is good. In New York, it broke even at
52 percent of capacity and recouped after 13 weeks, he said.
   Playwright Harold Pinter directed the initial London production,
which local critics found too narrowly focused a look at the
well-educated elite of Britain's publishing and academic
communities.
   New York critics, however, responded warmly to the literacy of
the play and its rueful, compelling plot. In addition, Gray said
they didn't bother to speculate on the real-life prototypes for his
on-stage characters.
   ``People realized there wasn't anything to know except what was
on the stage,'' Gray, a Cambridge graduate, said of the New York
audience. ``It's part of the general imbecility of theater critics
in England that they thought the real-life parallels were worth
discussing.''
   Gray said three separate American productions of the play _ in
Los Angeles, New Haven, Conn., and New York _ enabled him to do the
necessary rewrites.
   ``I had always felt dissatisfied with the text,'' said the
playwright. ``Now, it's the same skeleton but with, I hope, more
flesh.''
   Gray's previous New York and London hits include ``Butley,''
``Otherwise Engaged'' and ``Quartermaine's Terms.''
   The West End production uses the same revolving oak set by David
Jenkins that won acclaim off-Broadway. But its cast is younger than
in previous productions and heavily weighted with such British
comics as Rik Mayall, Stephen Fry and John Sessions.
   ``I'm now absolutely certain that the cast has to be young,''
said Gray, whose play requires the actors to age from their early
20s to mid-30s.
   But he said the present line-up did not represent a bid for
increased commercialism.
   ``The comics aren't doing stand-up routines; they are acting,''
he said. ``The audience comes to see people who've made them laugh
on TV, and they stay to grasp the whole experience.''
   Gray's previous experiences with this play have already produced
two memoirs: ``An Unnatural Pursuit, and Other Pieces'' and ``How's
That for Telling Them, Fat Lady?,'' which is to be published in
Britain next month.
   Has Gray now closed the book on his play at last?
   ``Oh God, yes,'' he said. ``I think I've done all I can humanly
do to make the play work, and if it doesn't, it doesn't.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tue AMs, April 5</NOTE>
