<1ST_LINE>s i BC-BritishRichMan Adv10   04-01 0981</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-British Rich Man, Adv 10,1006</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 10 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Britain's John Moores Got Rich on Pennies</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GRAHAM HEATHCOTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Moores has amassed a fortune from other
people's pennies.
   The bricklayer's son who started out at 14 as a Post Office
messenger is reckoned by some to be the richest person in Britain
after Queen Elizabeth II, who knighted him in 1980.
   He did it by offering the soccer pools _ football pools, they're
called here _ to a public dreaming of escape from the 1930s
depression. Today, having expanded into mail-order shopping and
chain stores, he is personally worth about $3 billion, according to
the British journal, Money Magazine, and the Guinness Book of
Records.
   Now 92 years old, he lives quietly in Formby outside Liverpool,
not far from his birthplace, and has not spoken to reporters for
two years. The last time Moores was heard from, in an interview
with The Guardian newspaper, he said: ``I don't pretend to be very
clever. I don't seem to have any outstanding quality. I count
myself enormously lucky.''
   At 82, he told the British Broadcasting Corp. he didn't know how
much money he had, never carried any and often went weeks without
buying anything.
   ``A rich man doesn't sit on bags of gold,'' he said. ``I'm often
overdrawn at the bank because I don't leave my money there. I can
earn much more than the 8 or 9 percent the bank pays by investing
elsewhere.''
   His success story began in 1924 at his kitchen table, where he
devised a lottery based on the results of soccer games. His family
and two of his workmates at the Commercial Cable Co. invested a
total of 150 pounds, then worth $720.
   They called their business Littlewoods, after an aunt of that
name, to avoid being fired from their jobs for moonlighting.
   Littlewoods Pools earned just 8 pounds ($38.40) its first year,
and the partners opted out. So Moores roped in relatives to help
check coupons on Sunday mornings.
   Bettors had to guess at a penny a try which eight games would
result in ties in national league soccer matches. Moores didn't
invent soccer pools, but he elaborated them and offered the biggest
prizes. By 1932, when one-seventh of the British work force was
jobless, he was a millionaire.
   The chances of winning even a small prize are 80-1, but some 8
million people today fill in a weekly coupon, and hundreds win
something.
   Littlewoods cagily says the odds against winning a big prize
cannot be calculated because there are too many imponderables. But
the Guinness Book of Records says the odds for selecting eight ties
from 55 games in one line are 1,217,566,350 to 1.
   In 1950, Moores set a prize limit of 75,000 pounds (then
$210,000), saying that was ``ample money to fulfill all the dreams
and ambitions of ordinary people.''
   But rivals and inflation later forced him to scrap the limit,
and this past July truck driver Jimmy Anderson collected the
British record pools win of 1,339,358 pounds (then $2.14 million)
for a stake of 40 pence (64 cents).
   He picked the 8 scoreless games from a list of 58.
   ``I didn't know what to do with it,'' Anderson said three months
later. ``All I bought in the first two weeks was a box of frozen
prawns.'' He got bored not having to get out of bed for work at 3
a.m., and bought a delivery truck to go into business for himself.
   The three big pools companies, Littlewoods, Vernons and Zetters,
pulled in the equivalent of $956 million last year, Littlewoods
taking 75 percent. The companies paid out $262 million to winners
and $406 million in taxes. Expenses totaled $286 million.
   Winners are not required to pay taxes on the sum they receive,
but they must pay them on such things as interest on bank accounts
or dividends earned from stocks purchased with the prize money.
   After making his first million, Moores expanded into mail-order
shopping in 1932 and launched his Littlewoods Stores chain in 1936.
He now employs 41,000 people and owns 108 stores.
   Moores recalled to The Guardian that he started his mail order
business with ``no buyers, no catalogue, no anything.'' He cut
illustrations out of magazines, assembled a menswear range and
again called on his family for help. Then he went to see Montgomery
Ward and Sears Roebuck in the United States.
   ``I found that if I said thank you and praised them, they would
give me almost anything,'' he said. ``I got a lot of new ideas from
them. I learned a lot from America and I admire the Americans.''
   His mother, he said, taught him the value of money by adding a
halfpenny (2 cents) for every 3 pennies (12 cents) he saved in
pocket money.
   Short and white-haired, he lives in the seclusion of an
Italianate villa and drives a Rolls-Royce. He and brother Cecil,
82, who runs the pools, are known in Liverpool as ``the uncles.''
   He married Ruby Knowles, a cafe waitress, in 1923, and their
four children have followed him into the business. His wife died in
1965.
   He is president for life of Littlewoods Organization PLC, and
lists sports and travel among his pastimes. He loves to paint, and
in 1957 he founded the John Moores Liverpool Exhibition, a biennial
contest to promote young painters. His knighthood was for services
to art, not business.
   Moores gives about a half million pounds (nearly $1 million) a
year to charity.
   ``It's for me to help the weak and poor,'' he said in his BBC
interview.
   ``A man in a swamp can only be helped by a man with his feet on
dry ground. I'm strong enough to pull him out.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 10</NOTE>
