<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WeekendTV-OscarShow Adv08-10   04-01 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-Oscar Show, Adv 08-10,0712</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv08-10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, April 8-10 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Oscar's Writers on Strike, the Show Goes On</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The producer of the 60th annual
Academy Awards show hopes big box office translates into better
Nielsen ratings for the show, which has lost viewers in recent
years.
   Last year's show, produced by Samuel Goldwyn Jr. and directed by
Marty Passetta, stemmed Oscar's long-term Nielsen ratings
hemorrhaging, albeit by a fraction of a rating point.
   The 1987 show earned a 27.5 rating, just above the 1986 rating
of 27.3, the worst in the history of the Academy Awards show and
the bottom of a slide that began early in the decade. The A.C.
Nielson Co. rating is a percentage of total U.S. homes with
televisions.
   Goldwyn, who is producing Monday's awards show as well, is
banking on the box-office popularity of this year's nominees.
   Goldwyn says he studied more than 20 years of televised Academy
Awards shows, and ``the thing I noticed is that when the movies are
popular, the show does well.''
   The Academy's nominees in recent years have performed in
critically acclaimed but not widely seen movies, such as four of
the 1986 best-picture nominees, ``Hannah and Her Sisters,'' ``The
Mission,'' ``A Room With A View'' and ``Children of a Lesser God.''
The big winner was ``Platoon.''
   This year, covering films from 1987, the nominees come from
movies that got wide attention and sold millions of tickets:
``Fatal Attraction,'' with more than $100 million in ticket sales,
has six nominations; ``Moonstruck'' also has six nominations, and
``Broadcast News'' has seven.
   Nominees for acting awards this year include Robin Williams for
best actor in ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' Cher for best actress in
``Moonstruck,'' Sean Connery for best supporting actor in ``The
Untouchables,'' and Anne Archer as best supporting actress for
``Fatal Attraction.''
   And the Academy has something to celebrate this year _ itself.
   Douglass M. Stewart Jr. is editing film sequences to review 60
years of Oscar presentations.
   ``The `Oscar Memories' film, with Richard Dreyfuss narrating,
has a lot of pieces of film many haven't seen for many years,''
Goldwyn said. ``It shows the evolution from a small dinner party to
an event watched by a billion people.''
   There will also be a parade of performers from each of the 59
previous best-picture films, from Buddy Rogers of ``Wings,'' the
1927-28 winner, to Charlie Sheen for ``Platoon.''
   A review of the career of writer-director Billy Wilder also is
scheduled, with clips from his films including ``Sunset
Boulevard,'' ``Some Like It Hot'' and ``The Apartment.'' The
six-time Oscar winner will receive the Academy's Irving Thalberg
Award for lifetime achievement.
   There is the usual impressive list of stellar presenters,
including Connery making his first appearance at the ceremony, as
well as two-time Oscar winner Olivia de Havilland.
   Other presenters will include Cher, Daryl Hannah, Steve Martin,
Chevy Chase, Robin Williams, Glenn Close, Audrey Hepburn, Paul
Newman, Gregory Peck and Michael Douglas.
   Goldwyn said he hopes to improve on his record by keeping the
show focused. Running overtime is a perennial problem for the
broadcast.
   ``The biggest thing was dropping the musical numbers not generic
to film, and the vague tributes,'' he said in an interview. ``If
you keep the show generic to film and what the evening is about ...
the audience will stay with it.''
   Like last year, a blinking red light will warn winners to wind
it up after 45 seconds of acceptance patter.
   Although some Oscar shows haven't looked like it, they do go by
a script. The presenters don't make it up as they go along. But
they may have to this year.
   The Writers Guild of America went on strike March 7 and rejected
an appeal from the Motion Picture of Academy Arts and Sciences to
grant an exemption, so work on the almost completed script stopped.
   However, the Academy wrote to the Guild at the end of March
seeking to negotiate a separate contract that would allow
scriptwriters Mel Shavelson, Jack Rose and Ernest Lehman to finish.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, April 8-10</NOTE>
</DOC>
