<DOCNO> AP880401-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1833EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WeekendTV-Moody Adv15-17   04-01 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-Moody, Adv 15-17,0838</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv15-17</NOTE>
<HEAD>For Weekend Editions, April 15-17, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lynn Moody Developing New Character on `Knots Landing'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Georg in 11th graf, bgn, On `Roots'..., is correct</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lynn Moody says the thing that excited her
about joining CBS' ``Knots Landing'' was not the racial
breakthrough but the opportunity to develop a character.
   ``This is the first role I've had that I can develop and work
on,'' she said of her role as Patricia Williams on the hit
prime-time soap opera. She previously has starred in sitcoms and
was in ``Roots'' and its sequel.
   Though they are the only black regular characters on a
prime-time soap, little is made of the fact that Moody and Larry
Riley, who plays her husband, are black. The producers believe that
makes a better statement than having race as an issue in the
stories.
   ``It's exciting, and it's a role that suits me so well,'' Moody
said. ``I like the soap opera formula. I like the idea of building
a character who's exciting and challenging. She's a bright lady,
but she has a lot of problems. She has problems with her family,
with her career and with her neighbors. But she has no problems
because she's black. They're all human problems.
   ``When they first talked about bringing in a new family, I don't
know if they were to be white or black,'' she said. ``I don't know
what the talk was before they decided on us. I know they were
losing some important characters and there was a house available in
the cul-de-sac.''
   The vacancy in the Lorimar show came when Laura Avery, played by
Constance McCashin, died in the 200th episode. Her bequest to Karen
(Michele Lee) asked that her house be rented to a family ``she'd
love to have next door.''
   The new family, who joined the show in January, also underwent a
transformation of sorts. They were rather mysterious, at times even
obsessive, until it was revealed last month they were in a witness
protection program living under assumed names.
   Moody's character had been the witness to a major crime and is
actually a neurologist, not a bank teller. Her husband had been a
police detective and was bitter at having to give up his career.
That, of course, created a lot of tension between them.
   ``I found out my name was really Nela Stewart Sollars,'' Moody
said. ``I told the writers I hated the name Williams. They put it
in the script, which made it more personal. But now it makes sense
they would pick a common name to hide under.''
   Moody said that despite her problems, the character is not angry
nor hostile. ``She's warm and sensuous. I love playing a role with
all these dimensions. Usually you don't get all these sides
exposed. I can't wait to find out what problems I'll have next
year. I've never been an independent woman who has all these
layers. It's great to be able to slam doors and be dramatic.''
   On ``Roots'' and ``Roots: The Next Generations,'' Moody played
Irene Harvey, the great-grandmother of author Alex Haley. She was
married to Tom Harvey, played by Georg Stanford Brown.
   ``Irene was very colorful,'' she said. ``She collected flowers
and dyed clothing. She had a lot of Indian blood in her. The slaves
sometimes ran away and lived with the Indians.''
   One of the first roles she ever played was that of a slave in an
eighth-grade school play in Evanston, Ill. ``The times were
different then,'' she recalled. ``There were no roles for black
girls. Then I played a slave and I got teased by my friends. In
high school there were no roles for me. The schools were integrated
but there were a lot of restrictions.''
   She was on ``Soap'' for two seasons as the love interest to Ted
Wass. ``We had a lot of bi-racial jokes,'' she said. ``It wasn't
daring but it was fun and I got to work with a lot of brilliant
people.''
   Her other series were ``E-R,'' which lasted only briefly, and
``That's My Mama.''
   Moody, who is single, spends much of her time working for Save
the Whales International. She's on the advisory board, which is
based in Lahaina, Hawaii.
   ``I helped rescue a pink dolphin in the Amazon,'' she said. ``I
helped organize the effort. They were endangered by the
construction of a dam. We're trying to convince people in Brazil to
encourage people to come see the dolphins, not to kill them. In
Hawaii, whale watching alone brings in $10 million a year.''
   Moody has been a guest on many network episodic shows and
starred in such movies as ``Lost in London,'' ``Wait Till Your
Mother Gets Home,'' ``Goldie and the Boxer,'' ``Some Kind of
Hero,'' ``White Dog'' and ``Las Vegas Lady.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, April 15-17</NOTE>
