<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The suspense over who will end up with Federated
Department Stores Inc. remained unbroken as the retailer's board
put off deciding whether to remain betrothed to R.H. Macy & Co.
Inc. or switch affections to Campeau Corp.
   The company's board of directors postponed the decision at least
until Friday after Macy presented a new, $6.73 billion takeover
offer Thursday morning. Campeau is offering $6.62 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. reached an agreement
with rival bidder Whirlpool Corp., allowing it to proceed unopposed
with a $507.6 million offer to acquire Roper Corp.
   GE spokesman George Jamison said Thursday the Connecticut-based
company's offer of $54 per share would be extended until 5 p.m.
Monday. Whirlpool simultaneously announced it was terminating its
$50-per-share offer.
   The battle to acquire Roper, an appliance and lawn equipment
manufacturer based in Augusta, Ga., began last November.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The price of Resorts International Inc. stock
slumped as Donald Trump, who holds 88 percent of the company's
voting power, withdrew his bid to take the hotel-casino operator
private and indicated he would block a higher, rival offer by
entertainer Merv Griffin.
   Resorts' Class A stock fell by $1.62{ per share to $28.87{
Thursday in trading on the American Stock Exchange.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Supreme Court justice has set aside an
appeals court ruling that had cleared the way for the merger of the
photofinishing operations of Eastman Kodak Co. and Fuqua Industries
Inc.
   Officials of the companies involved in the dispute disagreed
Thursday over whether the ruling by Justice Byron R. White would
force the merger to be dissolved, at least temporarily.
   The deal created the nation's largest wholesale photofinishing
operation.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropicana Products Inc. has obtained a
court order barring a departed key engineer from divulging ``trade
secrets and secret processes'' to rival Minute Maid.
   Tropicana contends when engineer Richard A. Hamilton left last
week he expressed an ``intense dislike of Tropicana and stated he
would `get' the company.''
   Hamilton began work Monday with Minute Maid, a subsidary of
Coca-Cola Foods.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NASA officials say two of the three ``more
attractive sites'' for a $1 billion plant to build the next
generation of space shuttle rocket boosters are on government
property in Mississippi.
   The third is near Cape Canaveral, Fla., where shuttles are
launched, NASA said Thursday.
   NASA officials said they expect a site to be selected before
requests are issued in June for proposals to build and operate the
plant.
