<TEXT>
   The Italian government has agreed to explore
possible collaboration in building the ``super collider'' atom
smasher planned by the Energy Department, Energy Secretary John
Herrington says.
   Italy has not agreed to contribute to the cost of the $4.4
billion installation, but collaboration could still lead to
savings, officials said Thursday.
   Italy has a distinguished history in advanced physics research
going back to nuclear pioneer Enrico Fermi in the 1930s.
