   The chairman of the Senate Banking Committee
has proposed creation of a regulatory committee to oversee the
nation's financial markets in the wake of the October stock market
crash.
   The bill, sponsored by Sen. William Proxmire, D-Wis., is being
pushed by former New Jersey Sen. Nicholas Brady, who headed a
presidential task force that studied the crash.
   The bill creates an Intermarket Coordination Committee composed
of the chairmen of the Federal Reserve, Securities and Exchange
Commission and the Commodity Futures Trading Commission, officials
said Thursday.
