<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     04-01 0204</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0212</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil trading has turned slow and lackluster with
the approach of the holiday weekend.
   Oil prices were mixed Thursday in dull trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange. Futures contracts for crude oil were unchanged
to marginally higher, while heating oil contracts declined and
gasoline was mixed.
   Contracts for May delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the
benchmark U.S. crude, settled on the exchange at $17.08 per
42-gallon barrel, unchanged from Wednesday's close.
   Among refined products, the April contract for wholesale heating
oil fell 0.45 cent a gallon to 48.15 cents. Unleaded gasoline for
April delivery edged up by 0.02 cent a gallon to 48.67 cents.
   ``There was no action; it was just dead,'' said Chris McCormack,
a futures broker for investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   The Mercantile Exchange is closed Friday in observance of the
Good Friday holiday. McCormack noted that the bulk of the limited
activity stemmed from traders balancing out their positions in
advance of the weekend.
   Market participants are looking ahead to an upcoming meeting of
the pricing committee of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries. The session is due to start on April 9 in
Vienna, Austria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
