<DOCNO> AP880401-0296 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0210EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Koppers Bjt   04-01 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koppers, Bjt,0697</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beazer, Koppers Trade Barbs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British industrialist Brian Beazer says
Koppers Co. is trying to confuse its employees and Pittsburgh
supporters over his $1.7 billion takeover offer. Koppers says
Beazer is the one confused.
   ``Koppers management has diverted attention to irrelevant
subjects such as the role of our financial advisers ... but they
have never responded to the key questions,'' Beazer PLC, the
construction and building materials company, said Thursday in
newspaper advertisements.
   ``We have asked Koppers management again and again to sit down
and discuss our proposal,'' the ad said. ``Instead, they have
mounted a massive campaign of disinformation, creating panic and
confusion among Koppers employees and the Pittsburgh community.''
   Koppers Vice President J. Roger Beidler, responding to the ad at
a news conference, said Beazer has misconstrued Koppers' profit
margins and employment trends.
   Koppers again criticized Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. for being
an equity partner with Beazer in BNS Inc., the company formed to
launch the $60-per-share takeover.
   The investment bank overstepped the traditional role to become a
corporate raider, Beidler said.
   Shearson has said it is merely helping finance the tender offer.
   U.S. Sen. John Heinz, meanwhile, failed Wednesday to amend a
banking bill with language to bar another Beazer backer, National
Westminster Bank PLC, from its role as an equity partner in BNS,
said Richard Bryers, an aide to Heinz. But the senator won a
promise from Banking Committee Chairman William Proxmire to hold
hearings in April on the Heinz measure as separate legislation, the
aide said.
   At a news conference called by U.S. Rep. Doug Walgren, D-Pa.,
Robert A. Papariella, 38, said he resigned his job as a vice
president of investments in Shearson's Pittsburgh office in protest
of the firm's role in the Koppers takeover attempt.
   Papariella, repeating claims made by Koppers and its allies,
including Heinz, said Shearson stands to make $150 million or more
in fees on the takeover.
   Shearson spokesman Michael O'Neill said the figure is
inaccurate, but he declined to offer a specific figure.
   Beidler, meanwhile, said Beazer was mistaken when he claimed
recently he could improve Koppers' profit margins in construction
materials from 10 percent to the industry average of 20 percent.
   Beidler said Beazer misconstrued companywide margins for those
of one segment. Koppers' margins in sand and gravel exceed 20
percent, and margins in crushed stone are near 20 percent, he said.
   ``He's going to find very little room ... to achieve that kind
of improvement,'' Beidler said at a news conference. ``Koppers has
been running the business as well or better than most companies.''
   Beazer's ad tried to dispel fears expressed by Koppers and its
allies that a takeover could elmininate 1,100 Pittsburgh-area jobs
and sap the local economy of an estimated $232 million per year.
   ``All Beazer companies have retained their local offices,'' the
ad said. mentioning Gifford-Hill in Dallas, Squires in Charlotte,
N.C.; Cohn Communities in Atlanta; Phillips Builders in Nashville,
Tenn.; Tidewater Construction Co. in Norfolk, Va.; and FK Co. in
Farmington, N.M.
   The ad said employment at Koppers has declined from 18,000 to
1,000, while employment at Beazer has grown from 4,000 to 18,000 in
the past five years.
   Beidler said Koppers eliminated about 9,700 jobs through asset
sales and attrition but added about 6,000 through growth in its
businesses. Employment declined from 14,500 in 1983 to 10,700 in
1987, he said.
   Beazer said Koppers' efforts to find a white knight could lead
to consequences worse that Beazer's plan to sell the chemical
businesses if it gains control.
   ``Remember, it was `white knight' Chevron that emptied the Gulf
Building,'' Beazer said.
   Opponents of the Beazer bid, including federal, state and local
elected officials, say they don't want the landmark Koppers
Building in Pittsburgh to be emptied as Gulf Corp.'s headquarters
were after T. Boone Pickens drove the oil company into a merger
with Chevron.
   ``Every company we've acquired has improved its performance and
profitability, with corresponding growth in opportunities and
benefits for employees,'' Beazer said.
</TEXT>
