<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     04-01 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Motionless In Moribund Trading; Remains At 6-Year Low
Against Pound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was virtually motionless in foreign
exchange trading in Europe today as activity wound down to a bare
minimum ahead of the Easter weekend. The U.S. currency remained at
a 6-year low against the pound.
   With most Asian and European markets closed for Good Friday and
with corporate clients standing on the sidelines, foreign exchange
rooms that were open were mostly idle, traders said.
   The only European foreign exchange markets open today were those
in Luxembourg, France and Italy, ``but they are all lying low,''
one trader in Milan said. ``There is absolutely no direction at all.
   Gold markets in London, Zurich and Hong Kong were closed.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar closed at 124.10 yen, down 0.40 yen from Thursday despite
some light intervention by the Bank of Japan, dealers said. Later
in Europe, the dollar was quoted at 124.05 yen.
   Other dollar rates in Europe at midmorning, compared with late
Thursday's rates, included: 1.6558 West German marks, up from
1.6555; 1.3613 Swiss francs, down from 1.3635; 5.6250 French
francs, up from 5.6130; 1.8630 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8575;
1,228.00 Italian lire, down from 1,229.50; and 1.2347 Canadian
dollars, up from 1.2339.
   The British pound was quoted at $1.8885 _ a six-year high for
the second day in a row _ compared with $1.8878 Thursday.
</TEXT>
