<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0741EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ColumbiaRecord     04-01 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Columbia Record,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Columbia's Afternoon Newspaper Ceases Publication</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Columbia Record, the capital city's
afternoon newspaper for 91 years, ceases publication with today's
edition.
   ``We will add 10,000 papers to the press run,'' Acting Managing
Editor Bunny Richardson said Thursday. ``Employees want them,
people in the street want them and we've had people calling us who
are not subscribers asking us where they can get a copy.
   ``There will be a lot of reminiscing in it from old Record
staffers. They have the same feeling that we have here now: the
camaraderie, the feeling of family, the feistiness of a small
newspaper.''
   The demise of the Record was announced Jan. 20 by Publisher Ben
R. Morris, who said the readers and advertisers of the area can be
served better by concentrating resources in a single daily
newspaper, The State.
   ``There will be other news in the Record other than its ceasing
publication,'' Ms. Richardson said. ``We still have to put out a
newspaper and that will keep us from feeling sad.''
   The Record staff will be merged with that of The State. Both
newspapers are owned by the Knight-Ridder newspaper group.
</TEXT>
