<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Roper Bjt   04-01 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>^PM-Roper, Bjt,0433</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GE To Proceed Unopposed With Offer For Roper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The battle to acquire Roper Corp. appeared
to be over with the announcement that Whirlpool Corp. was ending
its bid, allowing General Electric Co. to proceed unopposed with a
$507.6 million offer.
   A spokesman for GE said the Fairfield, Conn.-based company would
extend its offer until 5 p.m. Monday. But Robert Cook, chairman of
Augusta-based Roper, indicated he expected the deal to go through
quickly and smoothly.
   ``I'd say it's over,'' Cook said. ``We had alrady told our
stockholders to tender to GE two days ago.''
   GE and Whirlpool said early Thursday that negotiations were
continuing over their rival bids for Roper, a manufacturer of
appliances and lawn equipment.
   But the companies announced Thursday night that Whirlpool was
terminating its $50-per-share offer for Roper.
   GE is offering Roper $54 per share.
   According to the GE announcement, GE will be free to acquire
Roper and its manufacturing capacity for kitchen ranges and lawn
equipment. Whirlpool obtains rights to the Roper name for major
appliances.
   GE will supply Whirlpool with electric and gas ranges for the
Roper brand for at least two years under the agreement.
   Also, Whirlpool will relinquish its $37.50 per share option on
1.6 million Roper shares upon the completion of GE's tender offer.
And the companies agreed to various commercial relationships in
which GE will sell to Whirlpool certain industrial components and
materials.
   The battle to acquire Roper began last November, and led to a
series of lawsuits charging, among other things, that Roper and
Whirlpool engaged in activities designed to hinder GE's ability to
bid competitively for the Augusta company.
   Thursday's agreement called for the withdrawal of all lawsuits
upon the completion of GE's tender offer.
   ``For GE, the Roper factories and Roper's strong Sears
relationship makes this an important niche acquisition that will
significantly strengthen our appliance business in an increasingly
competitive global market,'' said Roger W. Schipke, GE senior vice
president in charge of the company's appliance business.
   ``Gaining the Roper brand name was one of Whirlpool's key
strategic objectives in pursuing this acquisition,'' said David R.
Whitwam, chairman, president and chief executive officer of Benton
Harbor, Mich.-based Whirlpool.
   ``With our complementary KitchenAid, Whirlpool and Roper brands,
Whirlpool plans to compete vigorously in all segments of the major
home appliance market,'' Whitwam said.
   ``The amicable settlement is beneficial to both parties, and is
the foundation for a strong, expanded supplier relationship with
Whirlpool,'' GE's Schipke said.
</TEXT>
