<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FoodstuffsReax     04-01 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Foodstuffs Reax,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Feel Anger, Regret On Breakdown Of Beef, Citrus Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Japan Foodstuffs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials reacted with regret and anger today after
talks between Agriculture Minister Takashi Sato and U.S. officials
failed to produce an agreement on Japan's restricted imports of
beef and citrus fruits.
   Sato began three days of talks in Washington on Tuesday in hopes
of renegotiating a four-year bilateral agreement setting quotas on
U.S. beef and citrus exports to Japan. No progress was made, and
the accord expired Thursday.
   Shintaro Abe, secretary-general of the governing Liberal
Democratic Party, told reporters, ``I am disappointed the talks
ended with differences between the positions of the two countries
still too great, but Sato did his best.''
   Sato's delegation ``made efforts to explain the situation in
Japan, but could not regrettably come to an agreement,'' said a
Foreign Ministry spokesman.
   In Washington, U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter said
the United States requested an emergency meeting next week of the
General Agreement on Tarrifs and Trade, where it will ask that a
panel be formed to review U.S. complaints. GATT is an international
body for settling trade disputes.
   Sato is scheduled to return Sunday to Japan, according to an
Agriculture Ministry official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Mitsugu Horiuchi, chairman of the powerful Central Union of
Agricultural Cooperatives, issued a strong statement accusing the
United States of refusing to hear out Japan.
   ``Though the situation making it impossible for Japan to
liberalize its market for imported beef and citrus fruits was
repeatedly expressed during the talks, the United States government
refused to listen and continued to one-sidedly push for total
liberalization or a decision by GATT,'' the statement said.
   Horuchi said his organization would continue to urge the
government to maintain beef and citrus quotas, saying ``this is the
concensus of Japan's 5.5 million farmers.''
   Japan has insisted in past talks with the United States that a
liberalized market for beef and citrus imports would have a
detrimental effect on domestic producers and lead to unemployment.
   But the United States has demanded Japan remove its quotas and
has refused to negotiate unless Japan proposed a timetable for
liberalization, something Japan has yet to do.
</TEXT>
