<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 0939EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-HuttonProbe     04-01 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hutton Probe,0490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hutton To Plead Guilty To Felony Counts For Money Laundering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   E.F. Hutton & Co. says it will plead
guilty to up to three felony counts and pay a fine for money
laundering _ some which was conducted for organized crime figures _
at its Providence branch.
   The company revealed details of a pending agreement with the
U.S. Justice Department and the U.S. Attorney's office in Rhode
Island in a mandatory quarterly report to the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
   Federal authorities have been investigating allegations that
Hutton, which was acquired last year by Shearson Lehman Brothers
Inc., failed to report cash transactions over $10,000 conducted by
its Providence branch as required by law.
   U.S. Attorney Lincoln C. Almond said some of the $1.2 million in
transactions involved were for organized crime figures, while
others were for ``legitimate'' businessmen trying to hide income
from the IRS.
   Almond revealed a week ago his office and the Justice
Department's New England Organized Crime Strike Force were
negotiating a guilty plea in the case.
   Almond and John Voorhees, attorney in charge of the strike
force's Providence office, declined to comment on the SEC report,
which was filed on Wednesday.
   Companies are required to report to the SEC any activities that
could affect their status as licensed investment dealers.
   Under SEC rules, a felony conviction could result in the total
suspension of business. But a spokesman for Shearson Lehman Hutton
Inc. in New York said Thursday the company expects to receive
waivers from the SEC that will allow it to continue operating.
   In its SEC report, Hutton said the investigation will result in
criminal charges, as opposed to civil penalties that could be
imposed under federal law.
   The company said it will plead guilty to ``no more than three''
felony counts'' and that the allegations ``will result in a fine
being imposed in an amount yet to be determined.''
   Most of the illegal transactions involved Stephen Fusco, a
Hutton broker who died of cancer in December 1985. Fusco allegedly
helped customers break large sums of money into amounts less than
$10,000 that were then deposited into their accounts. The scheme is
known as structuring.
   Most of the abuses ``took place during 1982 and 1983, and none
occurred later than August 1984,'' the company told the SEC.
   Michael O'Neill, a spokesman for Shearson Lehman Hutton, said
Thursday that the company does not expect any ``adverse impact on
the business.''
   Last October, the SEC found that Hutton had violated provisions
of the SEC law and rules relating to financial record keeeping and
reporting of currency transactions.
   As a result of the findings, Hutton was censured and directed to
report to the SEC on policies and procedures regarding the receipt
of cash deposits and to adopt surveillance procedures to monitor
deposits of multiple bank checks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
