<DOCNO> AP880401-0305 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1004EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-UAW-ContestedElection     04-01 0354</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UAW-Contested Election,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dissident Movement Has Chance at UAW Executive Board in New
Election</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dissident movement within the United Auto
Workers will have another chance to elect one of its members to the
UAW's powerful executive board in a new regional election ordered
by a federal judge.
   Candidate Jerry Tucker lost a June 1986, election against
incumbent Region 5 Director Kenneth Worley by two-tenths of a vote
and protested that the election was tainted by discrepancies.
   On Wednesday, U.S. District Judge Richard Suhrheinrich in
Detroit ordered a new election in the eight-state region, which
covers 80,000 active and laid-off workers in 68 local unions in
Missouri, Kansas, Oklahoma, Arkansas, Louisiana, Texas, Colorado
and New Mexico.
   Tucker and Worley again will compete in the election, which
could be held in 60 to 90 days. A third candidate also reportedly
may enter the race.
   As director of Region 5, the winner will sit with other regional
directors and top union officers on the UAW's core decision-making
body.
   The dissident faction, which calls itself New Directions, seeks
more participation by the rank-and-file in decisions affecting the
1 million-member union and want more open debate about the UAW's
general direction and philosophy.
   Tucker said he is most disturbed by the reluctance of union
leaders, including UAW President Owen Bieber, to allow the
democratic participation by the rank-and-file as provided under the
union's constitution.
   Suhrheinrich also ordered new elections for the region's
approximately 300 convention delegates. The UAW can appeal the
order, but it cannot by law halt the election, set up by the
Department of Labor, which had brought the case.
   UAW officials who asked not to be identified said the union
would appeal if it believed the decision set a precedent that was
harmful to the UAW.
   The Labor Department brought three suits against the UAW,
charging 27 illegal delegates voted in the election, Worley
illegally used union money for his campaign and Tucker was fired
illegally in May 1986 after announcing his candidacy.
   Worley did not return phone calls from The Associated Press on
Thursday.
</TEXT>
