<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CitrusSecrets     04-01 0346</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Citrus Secrets,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tropicana Goes To Court to Ensure Top Foe Doesn't Get Juice
Secrets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRADENTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropicana Products Inc. has obtained a
court order in an attempt to ensure that Minute Maid, its top
citrus-juice competitor, doesn't learn trade secrets from an
engineer who switched companies.
   In court documents Tropicana claims Richard A. Hamilton left
last week after 3{-years employment, expressing an ``intense
dislike of Tropicana'' and vowing to ``get'' the company.
   Hamilton began work Monday with Minute Maid, a subsidary of
Coca-Cola Foods, Alice Brink, a spokeswoman at Coca-Cola Foods in
Houston, said Thursday. A judge on Tuesday granted Tropicana's
request to bar Hamilton from divulging ``trade secrets or secret
processes.''
   ``We take this matter very seriously ... It was intended to make
sure (Coca-Cola) cannot get our proprietary secrets,'' said Steven
B. Gold, Tropicana vice president and general counsel.
   Tropicana is considered top in the rapidly growing market for
ready-to-serve citrus juices, with Minute Maid second.
   It would cause ``last and irreparable harm to Tropicana,'' if
Hamilton were to disclose what he knows to Minute Maid _ ``which is
attempting to develop a commercial pasteurized orange juice
product,'' Tropicana said in its court papers.
   Tropicana officials maintain Hamilton told them he was joining
Ardmore Farms, a small, non-competitive juice processor in DeLand.
   Tropicana said its concern was ``heightened when shortly after
leaving Tropicana, (it) discovered that, contrary to his earlier
representations, Hamilton had in fact accepted a position with
Coca-Cola.''
   Before he quit Tropicana, Hamilton told company officials that
Minute Maid representatives had contacted him by telephone at home
and at work ``in an attempt to obtain confidential information
concerning Tropicana's processes,'' court documents contend.
   But Ms. Brink said any attempt to get proprietary information
are ``definitely against our policy.''
   The company told Hamilton in writing not to divulge ``anything
which would breach the confidentiality agreement he signed with
Tropicana. We ask our employees to sign a similar agreement,'' she
said.
   Last month, Seagram Co. Ltd. agreed to buy Tropicana from its
parent, Beatrice U.S. Food Corp. for $1.2 billion.
</TEXT>
