<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unemployment Rate Drops to 5.6 Percent; Construction Spending Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after lede with February construction report;
picks up 2nd graf pvs, While the ....</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A sharp decline in the size of the American labor force last
month sent the civilian unemployment rate to 5.6 percent, its
lowest level since 1979, the government said today.
   Construction spending fell 0.3 percent in February, held back by
weakness in the residential sector, the Commerce Department said in
another report.
   The third consecutive monthly decline in construction spending
reflected the adverse effects of the new tax law and high vacancy
rates for apartments and office buildings.
   While the number of people at work in March dropped by 306,000,
those either holding jobs or looking for them fell by 445,000, the
Labor Department reported.
   The 0.1 percentage point drop from February's 5.7 percent
jobless rate reflected a decrease of 137,000 _ to 6.8 million _ in
the number of workers listed as unemployed.
   Janet L. Norwood, the commissioner of labor statistics, said a
slowdown in the expansion of the labor force is beginning to be
reflected in unemployment rates, which had, until last month, been
dropping more on the basis of job growth.
   On Thursday, the financial markets gave a mixed performance in
quiet pre-holiday trading, with stock prices modestly higher, the
dollar losing some ground and interest rates holding steady.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 9.94 to 1,988.06,
finishing the week with a gain of 9.11 points. Six issues increased
in value for every five that fell on the New York Stock Exchange.
   In foreign exchange, the dollar headed narrowly lower against
all key currencies while the rising pound continued to take center
stage in trading.
   The dollar hit its lowest level against the pound since January
1982 in London. It cost $1.8878 to buy one pound, more expensive
than $1.8790 late Wednesday. Later, in New York, one pound cost
$1.8874, up from $1.8780.
   In the credit markets, bond prices and interest rates were
narrowly mixed, although the Treausury's bellwether 30-year issue
managed to end the week with a gain of [ point, or $1.25 per $1,000
face amount. The bond's yield, which moves inversely to its price,
slipped to 8.74 percent from 8.76 percent.
   Analysts said traders were reluctant to carry big positions
Thursday ahead of the Easter and Passover holiday weekend,
especially with the unemployment report due.
   Both the stock and bond markets will be closed today. Many
currency dealers did not plan to trade today, while others said
they would work only half a day.
</TEXT>
