<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1107EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-IRS-Panama     04-01 0178</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-IRS-Panama,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRS Says Tax Payments to Delvalle Government will qualify for Tax
Credit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Internal Revenue Service said today that
American corporations' tax payments to the Delvalle government of
Panama will qualify for the U.S. foreign tax credit.
   The announcement cleared the way for U.S. firms that operate in
Panama to pay taxes into a special account at the Federal Reserve
Bank of New York without jeopardizing the tax credit. The credit is
designed to avoid taxation of the same dollar of income by the
United States and a foreign country.
   The action cuts off a source of cash to the financially strapped
regime of Manuel Antonio Noriega in Panama. The Reagan
administration has expressed concern that a recent infusion of
cash, some of it from U.S. corporate tax payments, may have
temporarily strengthened the hold of Noriega.
   The United States recognizes Eric Arturo Delvalle as president.
Delvalle issued a decree on March 25 directing that income taxes
due the government of Panama be paid only to a New York Federal
Reserve Bank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
