<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Federated 1stLd-Writethru   04-01 0723</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Federated, 1st Ld-Writethru,0749</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cliffhanger Continues as Federated Board Puts Off Decision</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates with 7 grafs with meeting under way, no word when
decision will be announced, picks up 7th graf, For the ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE M. ROSENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The board of Federated Department Stores Inc.
resumed its deliberations today on whether to continue the
retailer's alliance with R.H. Macy & Co. or agree to a buyout by
Campeau Corp.
   The board was meeting in New York, but Federated spokesman Jim
Sluzewski said he had no details about the talks or when an
announcement would be made.
   Sluzewski said the board would meet ``as late as they need to.''
   The board was believed to be considering a $6.73 billion
takeover offer from Macy and a $6.62 billion bid from Campeau.
However, it was possible that higher offers also were on the table.
   The directors had been expected to reach a decision on which
offer to back following an all-day meeting Wednesday. However, they
agreed to continue their talks after Macy submitted a higher bid on
Thursday.
   Wall Street analysts said that even if a decision were announced
today, they did not expect the 2-month-old battle for the nation's
fifth-largest retailer to end soon.
   ``Macy's has a slight edge, but I don't think that it's over,''
Walter Loeb, a retail industry analyst with Morgan Stanley & Co.,
said Thursday. ``There'll be more discussions and more legal
wrangling.''
   For the first time since it announced its cash-and-stock bid a
month ago, Macy placed a value on the stock end of its bid and also
offered shareholders the option of taking all cash for their
shares, Federated said in a statement.
   Macy offered $78.92 a share in cash for 80 percent of
Federated's 89.5 million outstanding shares, and said it would pay
$60 in cash or exchange five shares in the merged company,
Macy's-Federated Inc., for each remaining Federated share. That
would give the deal an aggregate value of $75.14 a share.
   Macy's latest offer superseded a $6.61 billion bid presented at
Wednesday's meeting.
   In its latest bid, Campeau said it would pay $74 a share for
approximately 80 percent of Federated's shares, and the same amount
for the remaining 20 percent after a merger, Federated said.
   Wall Street analysts had said Macy would be forced to put a
value on the securities portion of its offer to compete with
Campeau. Many investors, including arbitragers who hold a sizable
portion of Federated stock, had been leaning toward the certainty
of Campeau's all-cash offer.
   Federated had reached a merger agreement with Macy on March 2
but reopened the bidding after Campeau raised its offer last week.
   Investors pushed up the price of Federated stock Thursday, but
it held below either of the latest offers, rising $2.62{ a share to
$72.87{ on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Before the meeting, Campeau had taken its bid directly to
Federated's stockholders, in a two-step, all-cash tender offer
totaling $6.53 billion.
   Macy was offering $5.4 billion in cash plus stock in the new
company. Analysts valued that offer at $6.3 billion overall.
   The fight for Federated began Jan. 25, when Campeau offered $4.2
billion to buy the retailer, which rejected the offer as inadequate.
   Campeau raised its bid, but Federated spurned the Canadian
company's advances until the end of February, when the retailer
agreed to negotiate with Campeau.
   But as the Federated board was to meet to review that proposal,
the Macy bid surfaced, and on March 2, Federated and Macy announced
they had reached a merger agreement.
   Court battles over Federated's ``poison pill'' takeover defense
ensued, and both suitors continued to raise their offers until the
Federated board called for ``final bids'' to be presented Wednesday.
   If Federated's board endorses the latest Macy bid, the battle
will return to court, where the poison pill would again be an issue.
   The pill would make a takeover attempt more expensive by
allowing the retailer's shareholders to buy more company stock at a
discount, unless Federated's management supported the bid.
   Federated's divisions include Bloomingdale's, Burdine's,
Filene's, Foley's, Lazarus and Rich's department stores.
   Macy owns nearly 100 department and specialty stores.
   Campeau, which started in real estate development in Canada,
moved into the U.S. retail market at the end of 1986 by acquiring
Allied Stores Corp.
</TEXT>
