<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Hance-OPEC     04-01 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Hance-OPEC,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>RRC Member Meeting Oil Cartel President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Railroad Commissioner Kent Hance says he
will meet the president of the OPEC cartel in London Monday to
discuss the world energy situation and need for stable petroleum
prices.
   Hance said he also will urge that the Railroad Commission gain
observer status at OPEC meetings and that crude oil prices be
stabilized in the range of $18 to $24 per barrel.
   The president of OPEC, Minister Rilwanu Lukman of Nigeria, will
participate in the meeting to discuss ``the world energy situation
and options for the stabilization of oil prices,'' Hance said.
   He said he has been working through diplomatic channels since
last fall to achieve observer status for the commission at meetings
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   ``A line of communication with OPEC is of importance to Texas
and the nation,'' Hance said Thursday. ``At the present time, the
OPEC cartel sets the price, and we have no input.''
   The designation means that non-OPEC members can attend meetings
but can't vote. OPEC ministers can exclude observers from their
meetings as they choose.
   Oil cartel founders used the railroad commission as their model
when OPEC was formed in 1960 because ``Texas is one of the largest
non-OPEC producers in the world,'' Hance said.
   Lukman scheduled a meeting of OPEC`s pricing committee for April
9 in Vienna.
   Texas Railroad Commission was established in 1891 to prevent
abuses and discrimination in freight and passenger tariffs on
railroads, but its powers were later broadened to include
regulation of oil and gas production.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
