<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1421EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyCommodities Adv02-03   04-01 0806</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Commodities, Adv 02-03,0833</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 03</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions April 2-3</NOTE>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Set To Rally, Analysts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Market watchers expect soybean futures to open
with a bang Monday, following a pair of government reports that
indicate supplies could become extremely tight later this year.
   And they says a quick, strong rally is the only thing that could
encourage more soybean planting and perhaps lessen the crunch.
   Corn-and-soybean growers have until April 15 to decide whether
to opt for the security of corn price-support payments _ and the
accompanying requirement that they idle 20 percent of their land _
or take their chances on the open market.
   Higher futures prices for new-crop soybeans would induce more
farmers to choose the latter course and grow soybeans on those
acres that would otherwise lie idle, analysts said.
   Market-watchers were predicting three months ago that prices for
1988 soybeans could climb as high as $7 a bushel, the highest level
in four years.
   Thursday's Agriculture Department reports on spring planting
intentions and U.S. grain stocks reaffirmed that view.
   ``The general mentality of the market has been an expectation of
over $7 beans on November futures, probably $7.20, which would
result in $7 cash in most parts of the country,'' said David
Bartholomew, an assistant vice president of Merrill Lynch Futures
Inc.
   But after Thursday's reports ``$7 almost sounds conservative,''
he said. ``I think they're going to set prices higher after seeing
these figures.''
   Cathy Leow, assistant vice president of Thomson McKinnon
Securities Inc., predicted a sharp rise in soybean futures prices
on Monday and said the November contract could reach $7.30 a bushel
by April 15. November beans settled Thursday at $6.71 a bushel on
the Chicago Board of Trade, which closed out a work week shortened
by the observance of Good Friday.
   ``We may go 30 to 60 cents higher from these levels, with 60
being the upper limit,'' she said.
   But, she added, ``I don't think you need to get quite as high as
$7.30 basis November'' to encourage more soybean planting.
   The planting intentions report, based on surveys conducted in
March, said farmers planned to plant 58 million acres of soybeans,
up 1 percent from last year but still the second lowest acreage
since 1976 and below the average pre-report estimate of about 59
million acres.
   ``The market has been rallying all year in an effort to get
additional supplies for next year and boost farmer plantings,'' Ms.
Leow said. ``This report shows the market hasn't done its job and
prices have to move higher.''
   The soybean stocks report was even more surprising. The USDA
reported soybean stocks at 1.15 billion bushels, down 14 percent
from March 1, 1987. The market had expected the number to be about
30 million bushels higher.
   The relatively low number suggests soybean stocks on Aug. 31,
the end of the current marketing year, will also be lower than had
been expected, Ms. Leow said.
   ``When you combine the less-than-expected acreage with a
smaller-than-expected carryout, you're looking at a very, very
tight supply situation for next year,'' she said.
   ``If weather is even marginally below average, supplies are
going to be extremely tight. I think the market will want to do
something about that.''
   Thursday's reports on corn and cotton planting intentions also
were seen as bullish for futures prices. The wheat numbers were
construed as neutral for futures prices.
   Here are some commodity price trends during the past week:
   Grain and soybean futures turned in a mixed performance on the
Chicago Board of Trade.
   Wheat for delivery in May settled Thursday at $2.99\ a bushel,
down from $3.05 the previous Friday; May corn was unchanged at
$2.09} a bushel; May oats fell to $1.61{ a bushel from $1.68}; and
March soybeans advanced to $6.53{ a bushel from $6.48{.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Live cattle for delivery in April settled Thursday at 74.90
cents a pound, down from 74.92 cents; March feeder cattle advanced
to 82.77 cents a pound from 82.72 cents; April hogs fell to 45.52
cents a pound from 46.25 cents; and May pork bellies retreated to
56.12 cents a pound from 57.37 cents.
   Precious metals moved higher on the Commodity Exchange in New
York.
   Gold for delivery in April settled at $454.40 a troy ounce,
compared with $453.30; and May silver advanced to $6.785 a troy
ounce from $6.715.
   Energy futures were higher on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil for delivery in May settled at
$17.08 a barrel, compared with $17.03; April heating oil advanced
to 48.15 cents a gallon from 47.78 cents; and April unleaded
gasoline rose to 48.67 cents a gallon from 47.94 cents.
</TEXT>
