<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-01 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls in Shortened Domestic Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede: LONDON</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell in domestic trading Friday after
steadying in Europe as traders quit early to get a head start on
the holiday weekend.
   Gold markets were closed.
   Activity was lackluster, with market participants reluctant to
take on positions ahead of the Passover and Easter weekend. Trading
virtually halted in New York at around noon.
   Dealers said the central banks continue to monitor market
activity. Should the banks come into the market in support of the
dollar next week, ``there is the potential for a technical
rebound,'' said Stephen Flanagan, an assistant vice president at
Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co.
   Many market participants are anticipating dollar-selling by the
Japanese as their new fiscal year gets under way.
   Most European and Asian centers were closed for Good Friday. But
the dollar managed to hold fairly steady in what little dealings
took place.
   Markets in Italy, France and Luxembourg, but dealers were idle
most of the day, traders said.
   ``They are all lying low,'' said one trader in Milan. ``There is
absolutely no direction at all.
   Gold markets in New York, London, Zurich and Hong Kong were
closed.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar closed at 124.10 yen, down 0.40 yen from Thursday despite
some light intervention by the Bank of Japan, dealers said.
   Later in Europe, the dollar was quoted at 124.20 yen. In New
York the dollar finished at 123.90 yen, down from 124.35 yen on
Thursday.
   The British pound was quoted at $1.8895 _ a six-year high for
the second day in a row _ compared with $1.8878 Thursday. In New
York it cost $1.8905 to buy one pound, more expensive than
Thursday's 1.8874.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday, included: 1.6555 West German marks, down from 1.6575;
1.36425 Swiss francs, down from 1.3650; 5.6155 French francs, down
from 5.6170, and 1.23455 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2354.
   Other dollar rates in Europe late afternoon Friday, compared
with late Thursday, were: 1.6565 West German marks, up from 1.6555;
1.3650 Swiss francs, up from 1.3635; 5.6270 French francs, up from
5.6130; 1.8595 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8575; 1,228.75 Italian
lire, down from 1,229.50 and 1.2335 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2339.
</TEXT>
