<1ST_LINE>r f AM-RailBankruptcy     04-01 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rail Bankruptcy,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chicago, Missouri & Western Files for Bankruptcy Protection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chicago, Missouri & Western Railway Co. filed
for federal bankruptcy-court protection Friday, citing a burdensome
debt despite recent improvement in operations.
   There will be no disruption of service while the railroad awaits
court appointment of a trustee to oversee operations and determine
the company's best course, said Dave Barr, acting chief executive
officer of Venango River Corp., the CM&W's Chicago-based holding
company.
   The CM&W listed debts of $131.8 million and assets of $103.5
million in its filing for Chapter 11 protection from creditors.
   ``It's our intention to continue to operate in the normal course
of business while we seek to reorganize and emerge a viable
operation,'' Barr said.
   He said operating expenses and revenues were close to the
``break-even level in the last few months.''
   But servicing the debt incurred by the railroad was an
increasing financial burden, Barr said.
   CM&W operates freight service on the 632-mile line between
Kansas City, Mo., and Joliet, with trackage rights extending the
final 40 miles into Chicago. It also operates the Amtrak passenger
line between Joliet and St. Louis.
   A second Venango railroad, the Chicago South Shore and South
Bend railway, is not affected by the filing, Barr said.
   In February, CM&W and Venango filed a federal lawsuit accusing
the Illinois Central Gulf Railroad, the CM&W line's previous owner,
and its parent company, IC Industries. The lawsuit contends traffic
on the railroad failed to reach levels anticipated when the line
was purchased in April 1987.
</TEXT>
