<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CrabSeason 1stLd-Writethru   04-01 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crab Season, 1st Ld-Writethru,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crab Season Looks Promising on Opening Day</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds:CORRECTS typos grafs 2,14</NOTE>
<DATELINE>KENT ISLAND, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hunt for the blue crab, the
Chesapeake Bay's most valuable and abundant seafood, opened Friday
with predictions by watermen and scientists for a strong harvest
this year.
   Last year's catch was average, said William Sieling, chief of
seafood marketing for the Maryland Department of Agriculture. The
1985 and 1986 seasons were better.
   But this year, people on Smith Island, where the crabs show up
first, say the crop of small crabs on the bottom was good last
fall, said L. Eugene Cronin, blue crab researcher and consultant
for the state Department of Natural Resources.
   Those crabs mature through the winter and migrate up the bay.
``That's the most promising sign I've heard,'' Cronin said Friday.
   However, predicting the size of the catch is harder than
predicting where the crabs are during any given week, he said.
   This early in the season, crabs run in the lower bay. By May or
June they should be running farther north in the Annapolis area.
   Maryland watermen, anxious to make up for the poor oyster
season, are setting crab pots in the lower Chesapeake and at
Seaside, near Ocean City.
   Crabs are also more expensive this time of year. Packers are
paying watermen $60 to $65 a bushel and selling crabs by the dozen.
   Bert Kappel of Annapolis Seafood Market said he has been selling
North Carolina crabs all winter for $15 a dozen. By summer, crab
feasts likely will be more affordable at $30 to $40 a bushel.
   The demand for crabs traditionally runs from Memorial Day
weekend to Labor Day weekend.
   The crab harvest season usually creates jobs for about 19,000
people and generates $80 million to $90 million for the area
economy, Cronin said.
   State officials laid the groundwork to keep the blue crab from
going the way of the oyster at a crab workshop last fall, Cronin
said.
   Workshop participants compiled a report listing problems that
needed to be addressed to protect the blue crab, which seems less
vulnerable to pollution because it spawns at the mouth of the bay,
he said.
   The report recommended ways to:
   _Minimize crab waste.
   _Distribute the catch between commercial and recreational
interests and between Maryland and Virginia.
   _Better measure the crab population.
   The report is part of a state plan to develop a baywide crab
management plan to be completed by July 1989 as part of the
Chesapeake Bay Agreement between the states.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
