<1ST_LINE>r f AM-VAMortgageRates     04-01 0238</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-VA Mortgage Rates,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>VA Raising Maximum Interest Rate to 10 Percent</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: also running on general news wires</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Veterans Administration said Friday it was
raising its maximum interest rate for federally backed VA home
mortgages by one-half percentage point to 10 percent.
   The VA said it was making the change, which will take effect
Sunday, to reflect recent increases in interest rates in financial
markets.
   In the past 12 months, the VA rate has been changed seven times,
fluctuating between 9.5 percent and 11 percent. The last change was
Feb. 1, when the rate was lowered a full percentage point from 10.5
percent to 9.5 percent.
   The Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp. said Friday that the
national average for 30-year conventional mortgages, those without
government guarantees, rose above 10 percent for the first time
since late January. The national average rate was 10.05 percent, up
from 9.99 percent the previous week.
   The VA said that effective Sunday a variety of other mortgage
rates will also rise by one-half percentage point. Graduated
payment mortgages will increase to 10.25 percent, home improvement
loans will rise to 11.5 percent and loans for mobile homes will
increase to 12.5 percent.
   The VA rates apply to new loans, not existing ones. VA mortgages
peaked at 17.5 percent in September 1981 before beginning a decline
whih reached a low for this decade of 8.5 percent in early 1987.
</TEXT>
