<1ST_LINE>r f AM-LogExport     04-01 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Log Export,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Raw Log Export Bill Picks Up Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill to let states regulate exports of raw
logs cut on state lands gained key support Friday from several
Northwest lawmakers, including the chairman of the House panel with
jurisdiction over the measure.
   ``Log exports are creating a crisis for Northwest mills,'' said
Rep. Peter DeFazio, D-Ore., who introduced the measure almost a
year ago.
   DeFazio said the new support, especially that of Washington
Democratic Rep. Don Bonker, ``shows a growing determination in the
Northwest to get serious about log exports.''
   The measure is pending before the House Foreign Affairs
Committee's subcommittee on international economic policy and
trade, which Bonker chairs.
   ``Log exports benefit certain parts of the industry, but
processing those logs at home would provide thousands of jobs and a
stronger domestic economy,'' Bonker said in endorsing the bill. ``I
think we're foolish if we don't maximize the economic benefits
which come from our natural resources.''
   Other new co-sponsors of the bill include Democrats Al Swift of
Washington and Les AuCoin of Oregon and Republican Rod Chandler of
Washington.
   DeFazio said he was ``confident'' action would be taken on his
measure as soon as Congress deal with the omnibus trade bill.
Congress is expected to vote on the trade bill shortly after it
returns from its Easter break.
   Oregon, Alaska and Califfrnia had restricted exports of
unprocessed logs harvested on state lands until a 1984 U.S. Supreme
Court decision struck down the Alaska ban.
   The court ruled that Congress had not specifically delegated
such authority to the states.
   DeFazio's bill would grant the states such authority, strictly
limiting it to logs harvested from state owned or administered land.
   About 80 percent of the logs cut on Washington state lands and
about half of those harvested on Oregon lands in 1987 were shipped
without being processed.
   Raw log exports from the Northwest totaled roughly 3 billion
board feet in 1987.
   DeFazio said that the U.S. Forest Service estimated that 27,000
jobs are created from every 1 billion board feet of timber milled.
   ``Last year, that translated into 81,000 jobs _ unfortunately,
those jobs are all oversees,'' said DeFazio.
   In addition, some Northwest mill owners earlier this year blamed
a layoffs at their facilities on a shortage of logs resulting from
exports to Japan, South Korea and other Asian countries.
   Northwest timber industry groups are generally split over the
measure depending on whether their members are log exporters or
they have milling and processing operations.
   Among those who support the measure are the Western Forest
Industries Association of Portland, the Northwest Timber
Association of Eugene and Northwest Independent Forest
Manufacturers headquartered in Tacoma.
   Opponents include the Pacific Rim Traders Association, whose
members include Weyerhaeuser, Georgia Pacific Corp., International
Paper and publicly-owned ports in Portland, Astoria, Newport and
Coos Bay.
   The measure has also drawn support from several Northwest and
national environmental groups, including the National Audubon
Society and the Washington Environmental Council.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880401-0332 </DOCNO>
