<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Shrimpers     04-01 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shrimpers,0462</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Low Price Keeps Shrimpers at Dock</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Coast shrimpers staged an informal
strike on the first day of their season Friday to protest low
prices resulting from abundant supplies of last year's catch.
   ``The boats are not out right now and this is opening day, so it
appears we have a strike situation until they get the price worked
out,'' said Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife shrimp biologist
Neil Richmond. ``It's real interesting, because there is not an
organized association, but you're not real popular if you got out
now. You'd be a strike breaker.''
   Richmond said shrimp fishermen were staying in port up and down
the West Coast while they haggle with packers over a price.
   Shrimpers were asking for at least 50 cents a pound, while
processors were offering only 40 cents, said Scott Adams, plant
manager at Hallmark Fisheries, the largest processor on the Oregon
Coast.
   Last year's price averaged 68 cents a pound, with a high of 80
cents in May brought on by strong demand.
   Adams said a huge inventory of last year's catch was driving
down wholesale prices from $4.75 a pound last summer to a current
level of $3.60 a pound.
   ``Just about every processor on the coast has shrimp left from
last year,'' he said.
   Between 1 million and 2 million pounds remained in cold storage
from last year's Oregon catch of 45 million pounds, the third
highest on record, according to the Oregon Department of Fish and
Wildlife.
   Processors may begin selling their stocks at $2.99 a pound to
clear current inventories and any dockside price higher than 40
cents a pound would make inventory reductions difficult, Adams said.
   ``You can't afford to buy a product if you can't make any
money,'' Adams said. ``I understand the fishermen and I'd like to
see them get what they got last year, but we can't afford it.''
   Adams said processors probably would sit back and wait to see
what happens with the market value and shrimping conditions.
   In Astoria, Point Adams Packing Co. General Manager Tom Libby
said the current price of 40 cents a pound wasn't enough to entice
fishermen to sea.
   ``I don't know of anyone who is holding out at that price
locally,'' he said.
   In Newport, state biologist Marc Saelens said it wasn't unusual
for the shrimp fleet to stay in port the first few days of the
season as the price was negotiated. The season runs through October.
   Richmond said shrimp should be at least as abundant as last
year, resulting in an increased effort by shrimpers, once the price
is worked out.
</TEXT>
