<2ND_LINE>AM-FDA-Drink Mixes, 1st Ld-Writethru,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>FDA Says Products May Be Contaminated With Salmonella Bacteria</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 3rd graf bgng ``The FDA ... '' to reflect FDA revision
to at least seven cases of illness; also moved on general news
wires.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Food and Drug Administration warned
consumers Friday not to use Nutrien and Vitalite powdered drink
mixes because they may be contaminated with Salmonella bacteria.
   Both products are nutritional supplements marketed as powdered
drink mixes by Sunrider International of Torrance, Calif.
   The FDA reported there have been at least seven cases of illness
associated with the products.
   It said Sunrider has agreed to begin a nationwide recall, but
has not supplied the agency with specific distribution information.
   The warning applies to all sizes and flavors of Vitalite diet
drink mixes and all flavors of Nutrien drink mixes.
   The FDA said Sunrider markets its products nationally through
more than 37,000 independent distributors _ generally individuals
who sell them door-to-door or among friends.
   The full product name for Nutrien is ``Nutrien Whole Food
Concentrate.'' It is sold in flavors such as Pina Colada, Mandarin
Orange, Ambrosial Almond, Brisky Lemon and Positively Plain, the
FDA said. The Vitalite Weight Management product is marketed as a
meal substituting for a conventional breakfast, lunch or dinner.
   Salmonella bacteria ca cause nausea, fever, headache, diarrhea
and vomiting in healthy adults. It can be fatal to infants and to
elderly or debilitated individuals, the FDA said.
   The agency said tests detected Salmonella in a soybean powder
extract used in the Sunrider products and in some samples of
finished products.
</TEXT>
