<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CorporateGiveaway     04-01 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Corporate Giveaway,0393</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>McDonald's, General Motors and Sears Launch Huge Giveaway
Promotion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   McDonald's Corp., General Motors Corp. and Sears,
Roebuck & Co., the largest U.S. companies in their respective
fields, linked hands Friday not in monopoly, but in Monopoly.
   In what has been called one of the biggest giveaway promotions
ever, the three corporate giants are offering Oldsmobiles,
children's clothing, cash and food to winners in a game based on
Monopoly.
   Business analysts said the campaign, based on McDonald's
successful 1986 Monopoly promotion, will allow GM to pitch the 1988
Oldsmobile Cutlass Supreme to young adult customers of McDonald's.
It also will help Sears promote a line of children's clothing
developed last year in conjunction with McDonald's.
   Company officials declined to say how much the promotion would
be worth, but a report in an automotive trade magazine several
months ago said it would be a joint venture of at least $100
million. The copyright story in the Jan. 25 issue of Automative
News described the McDonald's-GM link, but did not mention Sears.
   ``I can confirm that we're part of it,'' a spokesman for
Chicago-based Sears said when advance word of the promotion leaked
out.
   McDonald's is based in Oak Brook, a Chicago suburb.
   McDonald's customers who play the game will be given paper
facsimiles of the Monopoly game board, and can collect cards
representing various Monopoly properties at any McDonald's
restaurant.
   Automotive News reported that Detroit-based GM would contribute
500 Oldmobile Cutlass Supremes as prizes in the game, as well as
cash prizes.
   The New York Times reported that Sears was expected to
contribute prizes from its Sears McKids children clothing, a line
decorated with pictures of McDonald's cartoon characters.
   The joint effort ``is not suprising in the sense that we think
of those three as large mass-marketing organizations,'' said Sidney
J. Levy, chairman of the marketing department at Northwestern
University's J.L. Kellogg School of Management.
   ``They are all-American names sharing an interest in a very
large public,'' Levy said. ``McDonald's, nevertheless, seems to
represent a little more working-class, a little more teen-age, a
little more casual idea than I would associate with Oldsmobile or
even Sears, because I had the impression that Sears was trying to
upgrade.''
   The game began Friday at McDonald's restaurants nationwide.
</TEXT>
