<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1847EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-IBMAnniversary 2ndLd-Writethru   04-01 0996</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IBM Anniversary, 2nd Ld-Writethru,1029</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On First Birthday, IBM's New PC Is About To Have Company</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-8, ``I don't ... particular patents., with 2
grafs to UPDATE with IBM changing again to say it makes patent
licenses generally available; picks up 9th graf, Clone makers ....</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year old on Saturday, IBM's new line of
personal computers will soon have some unwelcome company. Big
Blue's rivals are about to send in the clones.
   The imminent arrival of compatible computers has given the
world's largest computer company the difficult choice of whether to
fight them all the way or give them room to grow.
   The question penetrates to the heart of International Business
Machines Corp., and many observers believe it has sparked a debate
within the company.
   Being the only company making a Personal System-2 for the past
year has allowed IBM to run up healthy profit margins, recoup some
of its investment and reassert control over corporate accounts.
   But some customers have been reluctant to buy a Personal
System-2 until they know whether it will catch on as a standard.
And it may not catch on as a standard if IBM is the only company
making it.
   Some big corporate customers, wanting a second source for the
PS-2, have been urging IBM to license other companies to make
compatible machines.
   There seems to be confusion even with IBM on its willingness to
issue patent licenses to potential PS-2 clone makers.
   One spokesman said Friday, ``I don't see why we would ever want
to do that. ... That would be just the same as giving them the
store.'' Later, another said that in fact, IBM makes licenses
available to anyone under reasonable terms and conditions. But
clone makers still have to avoid infringing on IBM's copyrights on
the PS-2.
   Clone makers forced down prices and stole market share when they
knocked off IBM's first line of personal computers. But they also
helped IBM by expanding the overall market, of which IBM got a
healthy chunk.
   In any case, the moment of truth is approaching quickly.
   Tandy Corp. has called an April 21 meeting for ``the unveiling
of a revolutionary invention of major significance.'' A
well-traveled rumor is that it will be a PS-2 clone.
   Chips and Technologies Inc. and Adaptec Inc. have created sets
of chips that will allow clone makers to build PS-2 look-alikes.
They demonstrated a working model this past week.
   Even Compaq Computer Corp. of Houston, which makes premium PCs
based on the old standard, admitted last year it is hedging its
bets by working in the back shop on a PS-2 compatible.
   Alone in the market, IBM shipped 1.5 million of its new computer
line through the end of January.
   The sales boosted IBM's share of the worldwide personal computer
market to 13 percent last year in terms of units sold, up from 12.2
percent in 1986 and not far from the peak of 13.9 percent in 1985,
estimates Dataquest Inc. of San Jose, Calif.
   The PS-2 has gotten some negative press lately, including an
article in the Wall Street Journal that compared its mysterious
Micro Channel Architecture to the overblown secret ingredient in a
can of cleanser.
   Most computer analysts say the Micro Channel Architecture is
more than an audacious marketing gambit. It only seems that way now
because software developers have not had time to develop any
important programs that take advantage of its power, said Dataquest
analyst Peter Teige.
   ``By 1990 or 1991, I personally believe the old PC bus (data
pathway) will be considered very archaic,'' said John Xenakis, a
consultant and writer based in Framingham, Mass.
   The emergence of PS-2 clones does not entirely depend on IBM.
Theoretically, computers developed independently could be
compatible with the PS-2 without infringing on any IBM copyrights
or patents, the company says.
   But without IBM's blessing, many customers would be reluctant to
buy clones for fear that they would not be fully compatible or
would be at risk of a legal challenge.
   In short, IBM can squelch the clones if it chooses to do so.
Even if the compatibles turn out to be perfectly legal, the costs
of a protracted lawsuit by IBM could wipe out some small companies.
   IBM could simultaneously stimulate and control the PS-2 market
by selectively selling sets of chips or issuing licenses to clone
makers, said John McCarthy, a director at Forrester Research Inc.
in Cambridge, Mass. But he doubts IBM will do so.
   ``It's kind of a circling-the-wagons mentality,'' McCarthy said.
   Other observers are more willing to believe that IBM will take
it easy on the cloners. Chips and Technologies, in San Jose,
Calif., says its own discussions with IBM about licensing have been
``positive and non-adversarial.''
   Dataquest's Teige said IBM could recoup its investment in the
PS-2 through royalties and license fees from clones, while
continuing to introduce new models that would keep it a step ahead
of the compatibles.
   ``I don't think they want to monopolize the market,'' Teige said.
   Customers' desire for PS-2 clones is partly psychological, said
John Xenakis, a consultant and writer in Framingham, Mass.
   ``What would kind of give me personally a green light to buy the
IBM is if everybody's cloning it and it'll become an industry
standard and I won't become stuck with a lemon,'' he said. ``I do
believe that IBM understands that strategy.''
   IBM will issue licenses selectively, predicted Bill Langenes, an
analyst with Creative Strategies International in Santa Clara,
Calif.
   Ironically, IBM's original personal computer in 1981 helped
legitimize computing on the desktop, a revolution in the office
that is eating into IBM's traditional mainframe and minicomputer
business.
   IBM contends there is still plenty for big machines to do, but
clearly they are a shrinking portion of the total market.
   ``The PC may ultimately be IBM's undoing. They've created the
monster that's going to eat the parent,'' McCarthy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880401-0336 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1907EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-ICL-SmithKline     04-01 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ICL-SmithKline,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corning Drops Bid For ICL</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corning Glass Works, which had previously
reached an agreement to buy a Tennessee clinical testing firm,
bowed out of a bidding war Friday with SmithKline Beckman for the
company.
   The pharmaceutical giant SmithKline's latest offer for
International Clinical Laboratories Inc. was $37 per share, or
nearly $400 million, for all the outstanding shares. Corning's last
offer had been $35 a share.
   Corning said it had purchased 3 million shares of the
approximately 10 million outstanding shares of ICL stock at their
original offer of $26 per share. Corning has agreed to sell those
shares to SmithKline at $37 per share.
   ``ICL is a fine company, but our management and board made a
firm and final decision about ICL's potential value to Corning,''
James R. Houghton, Corning's chairman and chief executive officer,
said in a prepared statement.
   SmithKline's $37 per share offer expires at midnight EDT on
April 20.
   ``Our offer to acquire ICL is in concert with our corporate
strategy of leadership in health care and life sciences. Clinical
laboratory services is one of our key businesses, growing fast in
both sales and earnings,'' Henry Wendt, SmithKline chairman and
chief executive officer, said in a press release.
   ICL, based in Nashville, runs 13 major clinical testing
laboratories mainly in the South and West. ICL had sales of $205.5
million for the fiscal year ending Aug. 31, 1987, compared with
$168.7 million a year earlier.
   Through a subsidiary, King of Prussia-based SmithKline
BioScience Laboratories Inc., SmithKline is the country's largest
provider of clinical testing services.
   On March 8, ICL agreed to be acquired by Corning for about $260
million or $26 a share. Before the deal could be consumated,
however, SmithKline offered $32 a share.
   Corning challenged the offer with a $35 per share bid on Monday
and SmithKline countered hours later with the $37 offer.
   The agreement announced Friday between SmithKline and Corning
also resolves possible claims between the two parties, Corning said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
