<DOCNO> AP880401-0337 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-01-88 1916EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-EconomyRdp     04-01 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0374</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Construction Spending, Unemployment Rate Down</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In a pair of new economic reports, the government says the
nation's unemployment rate fell in March and construction spending
slipped in February.
   The financial markets' reaction to the reports won't be apparent
for a few days, however, because the U.S. stock and bond markets
were closed Friday to mark the start of the Easter and Passover
holidays.
   Some light trading was reported in the foreign exchange markets,
where the dollar fell in the United States after steadying in
Europe.
   The unemployment rate fell to 5.6 percent from 5.7 percent in
February even though there were 360,000 fewer Americans at work
than a month earlier, the Labor Department said.
   The unemployment rate is at the lowest level since it was 5.6
percent in May 1979.
   The rate decline was credited entirely to a 455,000 decrease in
those in the labor force _ which includes those either holding jobs
or seeking work.
   Employer payrolls rose by 262,000 new jobs in March, according
to a separate government survey.
   Factory jobs, which have risen an average 40,000 each month
since last summer, fell by 1,000 in March. Of the new payroll jobs,
85,000 were in business and health care services with another
80,000 in construction.
   The 0.3 percent decline in construction spending in February
reflected weakness in the housing sector.
   The Commerce Department said that construction spending declined
to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $391.5 billion in February
following a 2.8 percent drop in January.
   In addition, the department revised the December figure to show
a small decline of $100 million instead of a 0.4 percent increase.
   The February decline pushed construction spending 2.5 percent
below where it was a year earlier. Analysts are forecasting further
cutbacks in 1988 because of high vacancy rates in apartments and
office buildings.
   Residential construction fell by 1.1 percent in February to an
annual rate of $188.1 billion, while non-residential construction
posted a 1.2 percent increase to an annual rate of $92 billion.
   Public construction edged up 0.4 percent in February to an
annual rate of $74.7 billion.
</TEXT>
