<1ST_LINE>r f AM-US-Sugar     04-01 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Sugar,0440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Sugar Planting to Expand, Threatening Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. sugar beet growers plan to increase their
plantings, a move the Sweetener Users Association said on Thursday
may reduce imports again.
   The U.S. Department of Agriculture reports that a survey in
March indicated that sugar beet growers intend to plant 1.29
million acres, an increase of 1.6 percent.
   ``If sugarcane growers in Florida, Hawaii, Louisiana and Texas
follow suit, higher domestic sugar production would force the fifth
consecutive reduction in U.S. sugar import quotas,'' the
association said in a statement.
   Calculation of quotas is mandated by existing U.S. law.
   Tom Hammer, the president of the association, added:
   ``This is bad news for many of our Caribbean, Latin American,
Asian and African trading partners who have seen their sugar sales
drop from from 2.2 billion dollars to just under 400 million since
1981.''
   The Dominican Republic has the biggest import quota, followed by
the Philippines.
   Last December President Ronald Reagan's administration reduced
the quota to 750,000 tons, compared with 5 million tons in 1981.
The action was the fifth reduction in a row and brought imports to
the lowest point in 113 years. There were strong protests from the
governments of sugar-exporting countries.
   ``Unless the legislation is changed, the trends will continue,''
U.S. Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng predicted then.
   Lyng said in January that the administration would like to kill
the sugar program as enacted by Congress. It keeps prices high in
the United States for the benefit of domestic farmers, at the
expense of countries which traditionally export it to the United
States.
   Legislators from urban areas have put forward a plan to cut the
U.S. price and increase imports, saying price support for U.S.
sugar benefits only 10,000 growers and costs U.S. consumers $3
billion a year. They have had little response from other membes of
Congress sympathetic to farm interests.
   Last month the Agriculture Department raised its estimate of
world production for the 1987-8 season by 1 percent to 101.9
million metric tons, 900,000 tons less than than last season's crop.
   The Sweetener Users Association said U.S. sugar beet farmers
last year indicated that they planned a 1.3 percent increase in
acreage but actually planted 3.1 percent more, resulting in a
record U.S. output of nearly 4 million tons.
   Partly because of the high price of beet and cane sugar,
sweeteners made from corn and other products have been taking a
larger share of the U.S. market. Consumption of sugar has been
declimning.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
