<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WorldBank-Argentina     04-01 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-World Bank-Argentina,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World Bank Lends $400 Million to Argentina</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World Bank approved a $400 million loan
package Thursday to financially troubled Argentina and its banks.
   Funds from the 15-year low interest loan will be released in two
stages. The first half will become available immediately, with the
release of the final $200 million contingent on the success of
Argentina's economic recovery.
   The World Bank said it made the loan to encourage deposits and
confidence in the Argentine banking system, improve the
distribution of credit and reduce its cost.
   This action comes after a $317 million loan from the
International Monetary Fund two weeks ago. The IMF loan, which was
also conditional on reductions in the government deficit, was
designed to trigger a release of funds by private banks.
   Argentina is the Third World's third largest debtor, after
Brazil and Mexico, with a total debt estimated at $50 billion, of
which $3.5 billion is owed to the IMF.
   Argentina's situation is complicated by inflation that reached
175 percent last year and appears headed in the same direction for
1988.
</TEXT>
