<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Dravo-Westinghouse     04-01 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dravo-Westinghouse,0198</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks With Westinghouse Halted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dravo Corp. says negotiations to sell its
waste-to-energy business to Westinghouse Electric Corp. have been
halted.
   The move will ``enable both companies to explore alternative
options to achieving their respective objectives,'' said Thomas J.
Ward, Dravo's acting chief executive officer.
   The business ultimately could go to Westinghouse, Ward said, but
the sale ``is now more likely to involve one of the potential
buyers who expressed interest prior to the reaching of the
preliminary agreement with Westinghouse.''
   Dravo officials also said the company has executed a letter of
intent to sell its interests in geothermal energy production in
California to a joint venture organization formed by Bonneville
Pacific Corp. of San Jose, Calif., and Calpine Corp. of Salt Lake
City.
   Included in the planned sale are Dravo's geothermal power
generation facility and a contract for the future supply of power
from a planned second unit, the company said Thursday.
   Terms of the sale were not disclosed.
   ``The sale of our stake in geothermal operations complements the
divestiture actions now under way involving Dravo's other
engineering and construction businesses,'' Ward said.
</TEXT>
