<1ST_LINE>r f BC-WorldsofWonder     04-01 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Worlds of Wonder,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Company Founder Kingsborough Quits</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREMONT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Donald Kingsborough, chairman and founder
of Worlds of Wonder Inc., agreed to leave the debt-saddled toy
maker as part of its bankruptcy terms, the company announced
Thursday.
   The agreement involves banks and unsecured creditors and has
bankruptcy court approval, WOW said.
   The new management team includes president and chief operating
officer Angelo Pezzani and Stephen J. Hopkins as chief executive
officer. Hopkins is executive vice president of Nightingale &
Associates Inc., a New Canaan, Conn.-based management consulting
company.
   Kingsborough, who said earlier in March that he had no intention
of stepping down, has not disclosed his plans. The company said he
would be available to assist the new chief executive officer.
   ``With the bank's support and toy specialists on the management
team, I believe that Worlds of Wonder Inc. is entering a new era
which will inspire retailer and vendor confidence and active
participation,'' he said in a press release.
   ``Now the company can get on with what it does best _ creating
and marketing innovative toys with exceptional play value,'' he
said.
   WOW said the new arrangements call for a business and operating
plan to be presented to the banks and unsecured creditors for
approval, with financing then being negotiated.
   The high-tech toy manufacturer owes creditors about $260 million
and has missed $3.6 million in interest payments to bondholders. It
lost $186.9 million in the quarter ending Dec. 31, and the stock
has plunged from $29 a share after it went public in June 1986 to
$1.31\, up 12{ cents Thursday in over-the-counter trading.
   Kingsborough, 41, a former executive with Atari Corp., founded
WOW in March 1985 and turned it into one of the fastest-growing
startup companies ever on the strength of enormous success with the
Teddy Ruxpin talking bear and the game Lazer Tag. It fell victim to
overexpansion and slumping sales and filed for Chapter 11
bankruptcy protection last December.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
